<html><head><title>Seminars - Welcome to the Seminar</title></head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0><BLOCKQUOTE><h2>Welcome to the Workshop!</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>
<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

Over the next few weeks, lawyers on 
<A HREF="http://www.counsel.com/about.htm">LEXIS&#174 Counsel Connect<font
size=-2><tt>(TM)</tt></font></A>, the largest online communications network for
lawyers are participating in a special workshop devoted to a discussion of what
makes a good employee handbook. You are invited to "listen in" on the discussion
here, and <a href=/download/seminars/form2.html>submit proposed
questions</a> to the participants. Here is the introduction to the seminar as
posted online for the lawyers on Counsel Connect:<p>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 08:54:02 1996<br>
Subject: Welcome to the Workshop<p>

Welcome to our latest workshop -- The Ultimate Employee Handbook! As the
name suggests, over the next three weeks, we will explore what goes into
a well-constructed employee handbook. We will start by considering what
should -- and what should not -- be included in a handbook, and why. We
will then move on to discuss particular handbook language.<p>

Of course, we do not expect agreement on all of the elements that make
up the "Ultimate" employee handbook. In fact, one thing our panelists
will probably agree on is that there is no, single model for the "best"
employee handbook. This is definitely not an area where "one size fits
all." A large, multinational company is likely to have different needs
from a small company. It is our hope, however, that some common elements
will emerge that will help our audience craft useful handbooks for their
clients.<p>

We have put together an excellent panel of experts on the subject of
employee handbooks. But like other seminars on Counsel Connect,
audience participation is encouraged.<p>

There is one major difference between this workshop, and other seminars
you may have taken part in on Counsel Connect that you should be
aware of: The transcript of this workshop will be posted daily to the
Small Business Law Center on the Court TV Law Center on the Internet's
World Wide Web. What this means is that if you make a comment in this
workshop, it will be available not only to Counsel Connect
members, but also to any one who visits the Small Business Law Center on
the Web. <I>We recognize that there may be some comments that you would
like to make that you would prefer be made anonymously -- at least for
the public transcript we place on the Internet</i>. If so, simply
indicate in your message that you want any personal identifying
information stripped from your comment before we post it to the Court TV
web site. If you have any questions about this, please call me
(800-455-4354) or <A HREF="mailto:claporte@counsel.com">email me</a>,
and I will try to answer. I also welcome any comments you may have.<p>

We're glad to have you aboard, and we hope you enjoy the workshop.<p>

<hr><p align=center><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p> <P><I>To look up the email address of
the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.

</P></I></BLOCKQUOTE><P ALIGN=CENTER><br><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif"><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="All Materials Copyright CourtTV 1995. All Rights Reserved. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML>
