<html><head><title>Seminars - Meet the Panelists</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Meet the Panelists</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 20:18:16 1996<br>
Subject: Meet the Panelists<p>

We have collected a wonderful group of panelists for our workshop. Their
names, and a brief description of their backgrounds follows:<p> 



<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:tbanksnn@counsel.com">Ted Banks</a></strong> is
currently Associate General Counsel at Kraft Foods, Inc., in Northfield,
Illinois, having joined the Kraft Law Department in 1976. At Kraft, Mr.
Banks is involved in antitrust law, public policy coordination, mergers
& acquisitions, preventive law, and solid waste/recycling. He also
supervises the automation systems for the Kraft Law Department. Mr.
Banks has written numerous articles on antitrust and automation
subjects, and is a frequent speaker at CLE programs. He has supervised
dozens of major corporate transactions and lawsuits, including the
recently concluded (in Kraft's favor) antitrust challenge to Kraft's
acquisition of the Nabisco ready-to-eat cereal business. Mr. Banks is a
graduate of Beloit College and the University of Denver College of Law.
Mr. Banks is also co-moderator of Counsel Connect's Antitrust Law
discussion group.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:mbaskin0@counsel.com">Maurice
Baskin</a></strong> is a partner with the Washington, D.C. law firm of
Venable, Baetjer, Howard & Civiletti, LLP, and focuses exclusively on
labor and employment law counseling and litigation, representing
management. He has been the editor of Venable's model employee handbook
(marketed to firm clients and beyond) for the last five years. He is
also the author of "The Value of Employee Handbook Disclaimers in
Employment Litigation" (LLJ 1991), and other handbook-related articles.
Mr. Baskin is a member of the Labor Lawyers Advisory Committee of the
National Association of Manufacturers, the Labor Relations Committee of
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, and the Legal Section Council of the
American Society of Association Executives. Mr. Baskin is co-moderator
of Counsel Connect's national Labor and Employment Law Discussion
Group.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:tgosseli@counsel.com">Tom Gosselin</a></strong>,
is a partner in the San Francisco office of Pahl & Gosselin, where he
specializes in labor and employment law. He represents management in
both federal and state court on wrongful discharge, whistle-blowing,
breach of employment agreement, discrimination, harassment charges and
other employment related litigation. He is also actively involved on the
preventative side, and frequently conducts in-house training for clients
on sexual harassment, workplace violence, wrongful termination, and the
ADA and FMLA. Mr. Gosselin is admitted to the California and District of
Columbia bars. He is a Judge Pro Tem for the Santa Clara County and
Almeda County Superior Courts and, in addition to numerous bar section
memberships, is a member of Stanford Law School's Executive Program.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:sgrodin0@counsel.com">Sharon
Grodin</a></strong> is a partner at Corbett & Kane, in Emeryville,
California. Her practice emphasizes personnel policies, client training,
and preventive advice. She also has experience representing clients in
discrimination, harassment, and wrongful discharge litigation and in
resolving clients' disputes through mediation. Ms. Grodin was the
1994-1995 chair of the California State Bar's Labor and Employment Law
Section, and has served on its Executive Committee since 1991. She has
served as a member of the Editorial Board of the California Labor &
Employment Law Quarterly, and as an associate editor of the publication
for several years. Ms. Grodin was graduated from Brown University and
received her law degree from Temple University, where she was associate
editor of the Temple Law Quarterly.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:lhoguet0@counsel.com">Laura Hoguet</a></strong>
is a graduate of University of Chicago Law School, class of 1967. She
joined the New York law firm of White & Case in 1967 as an associate,
and became a partner in the Litigation Department there in 1974. She has
recently announced her departure from White & Case, effective February
2, 1996 to form a new firm, Hoguet Newman & Regal, with two other
litigators. The new firm will conduct a general litigation practice in
New York "which means, in this time we live in, that we will do a lot of
employment law and litigation." She has been active in the employment
field for many years, usually advising employers but also negotiating
agreements, severances etc. for a large number of executives. Ms. Hoguet
is co-moderator of Counsel Connect's national Labor and Employment
discussion group.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:jkeyes00@counsel.com">Judith Keyes</a></strong>
is a partner at Corbett & Kane, in Emeryville, California. She is known
for her ability to find practical solutions to difficult employment
problems and for litigating difficult cases. She is an Early Neutral
Evaluator and Mediator for the U. S. District Court in San Francisco.
She is active in the American Bar Association Sections on Labor and
Employment Law and International Law, and is on the Executive Committee
of the Bar Association of San Francisco's Labor and Employment Law
Section. She is the 1996 President-Elect of the Alameda County Bar
Association and was a charter member of the Northern California Chapter
of the Association of Attorney Mediators. Ms. Keyes earned her law
degree at Boalt Hall School of Law, University of California, Berkeley,
where she was associate editor of the California Law Review and from
which she was graduated Order of the Coif. Before joining the firm, Ms.
Keyes was a field attorney for the San Francisco Regional Office of the
National Labor Relations Board. While on sabbatical leave from Corbett &
Kane in 1986-1987, she was a visiting professor at Suffolk University
Law School, Boston, teaching labor law and evidence.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:mmasla00@counsel.com">Mike Maslanka</a></strong>
is a partner at Clark, West, Keller, Butler, and Ellis, where he
represents management in all aspects of labor and employment law. He is
the editor of the <I>Texas Employment Law Letter</i> to which over 2,000
Texas employers subscribe. He is also the author of the recently
published Texas Employer's Guide to Employee Policy Handbooks, and is
currently writing the supplement to a book for Warren, Gorham, &
Lamont's on employee handbooks and policies. He was the Institute
Director for the State Bar of Texas' first ever CLE seminar on employee
policies called "A Strategic Approach to Drafting and Implementing
Employee Policies." Mr. Maslanka is also moderator of LEXIS Counsel
Connect's Texas Labor and Employment discussion group.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:cmerri01@counsel.com">Charles
Merrill</a></strong> is a partner in the Newark, New Jersey office of
McCarter & English, where he chairs the firm's Computer & High Tech
Practice Group, which is involved in the entire spectrum of information
law practice, both transactional and litigation. Since the earliest days
of Counsel Connect in early 1993, he has served as the moderator
of the Counsel Connect E-Mail and Electronic Commerce Forum, which
has evolved into a place to explore cloverleafs feverishly under
construction where the information superhighway intersects with
traditional neighborhoods. In his practice and ABA activity, and as a
frequent speaker and writer, he is deeply involved with the legal
problems of security (privacy as well as authentication of identity) on
the Internet, and public key encryption technology as the linchpin to
the galloping transition from a paper-based to a digital world. The
Ultimate Employee Handbook of the 1990s must deal with such subjects.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:jmorales@counsel.com">Jerry
Morales</a></strong>, a partner at Snell & Wilmer L.L.P., practices in
the areas of employment, employee benefits and international law. He is
an active member of the Labor and International Sections of the American
Bar Association, the National Law Center for Inter- American Free Trade
and of the Latin American/Carribean Group of Lex Mundi. Mr. Morales
earned his MBA and J.D. Degrees from Tulane University.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:drameynn@counsel.com">Drucilla Stender
Ramey</a></strong> graduated magna cum laude from Harvard University and
then from Yale Law School. She has chaired the San Francisco Commission
on the Status of Women and the ACLU of Northern California. Ms. Ramey
was a civil rights lawyer specializing on gender and race/national
origin discrimination in employment and education at MALDEF (on whose
national board she currently serves) and in private practice. For the
last decade, Ms. Ramey has served as the Executive Director and General
Counsel of the Bar Association of San Francisco, which operates with a
$4 million budget and a staff of 75, where she has produced a number of
nationally distributed videotapes, model policies, programs and reports
in the areas of hiring and retention of women, minority attorneys,
attorneys with disabilities, and gay men and lesbians. A member of the
California and Connecticut bars, Ms. Ramey was an associate professor of
law at Golden Gate University prior to her current post and has won
numerous awards, including the American Jewish Committee Judge Learned
Hand Human Relations Award and the National Lawyers Guild Annual Award,
and the California Women Lawyers' 1992 Award as Outstanding Woman Lawyer
in California. Ms. Ramey has published extensively in labor and
employment issues.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:aweitzma@counsel.com">Allan
Weitzman</a></strong>. After twenty-one years in Proskauer Rose Goetz &
Mendelsohn's New York City headquarters, Mr. Weitzman moved to its Boca
Raton, Florida office in 1995 to head the labor and employment law
practice there. Although his practice is multi-faceted, most of the time
he is either litigating in state or federal court (at the trial and
appellate levels), representing employers before administrative agencies
responsible for the enforcement of the numerous antidiscrimination laws
and before the National Labor Relations Board, negotiating collective
bargaining agreements or arbitrating contract disputes. In addition, Mr.
Weitzman has provided valuable day-to-day and crisis advice to clients
in a wide range of businesses, including the securities industry, health
care institutions, television networks, maritime industry, a public
utility, a major sports and entertainment arena, manufacturing
facilities, construction industry and public education. On any given
day, the scope of his practice could include personnel policy planning,
sexual harassment, avoiding litigation when terminating employees, union
election campaigns and employee benefit plans. Mr. Weitzman was the
co-editor of Proskauer's three-volume work published in 1992 entitled
<I>New York Employment Law</i>. In August 1994, he became a Business Watch
columnist on labor and employment law topics for <I>The National Law
Journal</i>. He is also the Editor-In-Chief of a bi-monthly journal
entitled <I>HR Advisor -- Legal & Practical Guidance</i>. Last fall, Mr.
Weitzman had been part of the course faculty for Federal Publication
programs on the ADA and FMLA in New York, Washington and Boca Raton. His
course will be given again this spring in New York, Chicago and San
Francisco. Mr. Weitzman is a graduate of Cornell University's School of
Industrial and Labor Relations, and the Cornell Law School, where he was
an Editor of the Cornell Law Review, graduated with distinction and was
a member of The Order of the Coif.<p>

<STRONG><A HREF="mailto:pzeughau@counsel.com">Peter
Zeughauser</a></strong> is a principal in ClientFocus, a Newport Beach,
California consulting firm. ClientFocus conducts law firm client
relationship assessments and consults to law firms on client
competitions and the structuring of alternative fee arrangements. Before
forming ClientFocus in 1995, Mr. Zeughauser was Senior Vice President
and General Counsel of the Irvine Company, where he practiced for
fifteen years. He is former Chairman of the American Corporate Counsel
Association and a Fellow of the College of Law Practice Management. He
is a frequent speaker at law firm retreats and continuing legal
education programs. Mr. Zeughauser is moderator of LEXIS Counsel
Connect's Inside/Outside Relationships discussion group.<p>

