<html><head><title>Seminars - Why have a handbook?</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Why have a handbook?</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 08:57:05 1996<br>
Subject: Why have a handbook?<p>

Last Append: Sun Jan 21 22:57:06 1996<p>

We are about to spend the next three weeks discussing what should
be contained in a good employee handbook or employee policy
manual. As we begin, I would like to ask our panelists why they
think it is a good idea for employers to go to the effort to
create a written employee handbook. Are there good reasons to
have one and not-so-good reasons, and are these reasons important
for lawyers to communicate when advising clients about handbooks?
Does anyone think there is a threshold company size, below which
a handbook is unnecessary?<p>

<hr>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br> 
Date: Mon Jan 15 15:47:09 1996<br>
Subject: Why have a handbook?<p>

Businesses that try to improve the quality of their products find
out that one of the key impediments to success is the lack of
good communications. Much of the work of the "TQM" (quality)
consultants consists of figuring ways to improve communications
about a business process. One example of the importance of
communications is in the area of employee relations. Employees
perform best when they know what is expected of them, when they
are given the tools to succeed, and when they know the
compensation and benefits to which they are entitled. Therefore,
any communications tool that helps facilitate this process can be
valuable. An employee handbook can serve as a reference document
for basic information about the employer, and for procedural
information about how certain issues are handled (e.g., medical
claims). It can also be a resource for a small bit of educational
information (e.g., certain legal obligations imposed by
securities laws regarding insider trading). It is always a
dynamic document, being changed from time to time to reflect
changes in the company. Educational experts tell us that
effective communication requires a variety of inputs--in other
words, a handbook by itself is not going to fulfill all employee
communication needs. However, the employee handbook can be
effective as part of an employee orientation process that
includes oral presentations and employee activity.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Laura Hoguet -- Hoguet Newman Regal - New York<br>
Date: Mon, 15 Jan 96 20:43:33 EST<br>
Subject: Why have a handbook?<p>

Some companies have handbooks because they think the books are an
effective way of communicating information to employees. Some
companies think handbooks are not a good way of communicating
with employees (people don't read them, most of the stuff in them
is obvious or can be communicated orally or on the bulletin
board, etc.), and some companies are just so new and/or small
(under 75-100 people, I'd say) that there isn't much point in
taking the time to develop a handbook. A lot of HR [Human
Resources] people, of course, take for granted that there should
be a handbook. I think whether or not there should be a book
ought to depend on the HR thinking of the company, i.e. the
business culture -- is there information that needs to be
communicated, and is the handbook a good way to do it? The other
driver of handbooks is lawyers, who think of the handbook as a
good place to disclaim legal obligations to employees and at the
same time proclaim the company's "law" or rules that will be
applied to employees. It would not be necessary, in order to
disclaim obligations, to have a handbook -- one could write
employees yearly letters formally disclaiming the intent to
create contractual obligations, etc. It is convenient, though, to
do it in a handbook.<p> 

There is often tension between the business cultural objective of
a handbook and its legal goal. The business people want to make
sweeping statements of ideals or aspiration, to sell the company
to its employees, only to find themselves liable for making
promises they disclaim a legal duty to keep. It is very hard, I
find, to explain the lawyers' point of view to the business
people or to make the lawyers understand that the business people
have a real need to make their cultural statement. No wonder
handbooks produce so much litigation.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Tue Jan 16 21:09:03 1996<br>
Subject: Handbook Goals<p>

I recall the time when handbooks were mostly pitched as a device to make
unions "unnecessary." Poor communications were (and are) an important
factor in unionization, so anything that promoted better communications,
i.e., handbooks, helped promote a union free environment. Handbooks also
initially were promoted as bolstering employees' feelings of "security,"
until the court decisions of the 1970's and 1980's punished employers
who did too good a job of making employees feel "secure." Now, although
communications continues to be an important goal, fewer companies are
worried about unions, and more are worried about being hoisted on their
own handbooks. We have found that properly drafted handbooks can
actually help reduce the amount of litigation and can still promote good
communications. Those should be the primary goals of a company handbook
these days, in that order.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 09:35:59 1996<br> 
Subject: 75-100 employee lower limit?<p> 

I'm surprised, Laura, that you think a company with fewer than 75
employees may forego the expense/effort required to create a good
handbook. With so many federal regulations triggered when a company
reaches 50 employees, I thought any company over that number ought to
have a handbook.<p>

- Cloyd<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 18:28:02 1996<br> 
Subject: Small Employers <p>

I'm a big proponent of handbooks for small employers -- in which I'd
include employers with as few as five employees. Cloyd is right in
suggesting that to the extent size of the employer defines potential
liability under particular employment laws, size is one logical way to
identify which employers need employee handbooks. It's not the only
consideration, however. In some ways, small employers face even greater
challenges of communication and of providing supportive evidence in
litigation than do larger employers. Often the supervisor is an
entrepreneur wearing many hats, with little time or talent for
consistent employee communication or training, and often there is no
system of documentation for anything except revenue and expenses. A
handbook properly used can be an important supplement and guide for that
client. On the other hand, Laura Hoguet is right that not every small
employer will use a handbook properly or to best advantage; in such a
case it might be a waste of time (and even potentially harmful) to
develop a handbook.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br> 
Date: Wed Jan 17 18:40:54 1996<br>
Subject: Goal- Problem Solving<p>

In addition to the Handbook Goals others have noted, a good employee
handbook should identify, realistically and convincingly, avenues of
communication and problem solving for complicated situations. We can't
cover all the really hard supervision problems with admonitions in the
handbook (or they wouldn't be really hard problems), but we can make
sure employees and supervisors know how they are expected to communicate
constructively about such problems.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 01:22:01 1996<br>
Subject: Why have a handbook?<p>

I may be stating the obvious here: but employers (especially small
employers) should not feel that a handbook is the <I>ONLY</i> way to
communicate with employees. In my experience, handbooks may not be
effective means of communication. They are forgotten over time, or
supplanted by intervening memos or by intervening events. There is
little more deadly than a handbook that has been forgotten -- and when
that has happened, I'd say the employer should eliminate the handbook,
substituting, say, a list of benefits (e.g., vacation accrual, holiday
entitlement) and leaving it at that.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 22:57:06 1996<br>
Subject: Why have a handbook?<p>

I feel that even very small outfits need to have some document that sets
forth the framework that governs hours, benefits, and the other matters
usually covered by an employee handbook. For one thing, the smaller the
company, the less likely there is to be an employee charged with truly
keeping track of and communicating these things.<p> 

<hr><p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your question or
comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email address of the lawyers
participating in this discussion, use our online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
