<html><head><title>Seminars - Employee Handbook Basic Elements</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Employee Handbook Basic Elements</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 08:57:44 1996<br>
Subject: Common Elements?<p>

Last Append: Tue Jan 16 20:55:00 1996<p>

Are there basic elements that all employee handbooks should have?
If so, what are they?<p>

<hr>

Appended by: Allan H Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 12:31:53 1996<br> 
Subject: THE BASICS<p>

Here's a basic outline for the essentials:<p><OL>

<LI>A disclaimer to make sure that the handbook does not create a
contract or implied contract.<p> 

<LI>A statement of the employer's commitment to equal employment
opportunity, including sexual (and other) harassment policies and
complaint procedures.<p>

<LI>A description of the employer's rules, regulations and
procedures.<p>

<LI>A description of policies designed to help employees,
including FMLA[Family and Medical Leave Act].<p>

<LI>Guidelines for termination of employment.<p>

<LI>State and local legal requirements.</ol><p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Tue Jan 16 20:55:00 1996<br>
Subject: More basics<p>

While I generally agree with the set of basics just set forth, I
would add the following:<p><OL>

<LI>There should be a series of disclaimers which clarify what the
handbook does and does not do (discussed elsewhere in more detail).<p>

<LI>A list of employee benefits.<p>

<LI>An acknowledgement of receipt, possibly in different
forms for incumbent employees and new hires.<p>

<LI>Wherever possible, reservation of discretion or flexibility on the
part of management to deal with different employees differently.</ol><p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your question or
comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email address of the lawyers
participating in this discussion, use our online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
