<html><head><title>Seminar - The Ultimate Employee Handbook</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF"
VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>What are the Pitfalls?</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 08:58:22 1996<br>
Subject: What are the Pitfalls?<p>

Last Append: Sun Jan 21 18:30:01 1996<p>

What are some pitfalls that writers of employee handbooks can
fall into? How can they be avoided?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Allan H Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 12:18:06 1996<br>
Subject: Too Much Legalese<p>

As an employee communications vehicle, too much legalese in a
handbook can be a distraction to the message. If an attorney
drafts the handbook, have the human resources people critique the
document to evaluate whether the lawyers have gone too far. You
might even try out a draft on a cross-sample of rank and file
employees.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br> 
Date: Mon Jan 15 15:54:19 1996<br>
Subject: What are the Pitfalls?<p>

A handbook that goes unread does not provide much value.
Therefore it should be only as long as necessary to get the job
done (i.e., as short as possible), and it must be written in
clear, normal English (or whatever language is appropriate to the
work force). As noted above, lawyers are not always the best
authors for this purpose. A professional writer should be
utilized for any document like this that will have wide
distribution.<p>

The other common pitfall of an employee handbook is the failure to
clearly specify that the document is intended as a reference source and
not as a contract of employment. There is lots of litigation over
"promises" made in employee handbooks that use careless language which
seem to create an employment contract rather than an 
<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/workplace/660.html">
at will relationship</a>. The language must be chosen with care, and
state and federal law must be considered as the policies to be
communicated in the employee handbook are developed.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Robert Zielinski -- Ross & Hardies - Chicago<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 15:54:50 1996 <br>
Subject: Additional pitfalls and avoidance<p>

A constant problem with employee handbooks that I see is the
tendency to uncritically cut and paste a company's handbook
together from other employer models. Frequently the borrowed
material is out of date or while sensible for its original user
makes no sense in the current employer's context. Another thing I
usually recommend is to have a sunset provision that causes a
policy to expire at a specified date in the future unless it is
specifically reaffirmed. This way one can avoid getting caught by
policies that everyone has forgotten even exist.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br> 
Date: Tue Jan 16 17:04:48 1996<br>
Subject: Chilling Morale<P>

I think another difficult call is in tech areas involving use of email,
computers, voicemail, etc.<p>

How can employers protect themselves from exposure for liability, yet
avoid policies so onerous that employees' creativity and/or morale is
stifled, or alternatively, the policies are uniformly ignored?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Tue Jan 16 21:21:27 1996<br>
Subject: Pitfalls<p>

<OL>
<LI>Overpromising: setting standards which supervisors cannot always meet
or saddling the company with working conditions which changed
circumstances no longer permit.<p>

<LI>Inconsistency between sections, which
is often a function of...<p>

<LI>Poor organization, often the result of the slapping together of
different models referred to above, but with the extra pitfall of no one
knowing exactly what the handbook contains until a plaintiffs lawyer
points out multiple or confusing promises which have been made.<p>

<LI>Inadequate disclaimers: I should note that I disagree
somewhat with those who seek less legalese in handbooks. My first goal
for a handbook is that it help to reduce litigation; the second goal is
good communication, in that order (see my post on a separate thread).
This is matter of degree -- the good handbook really should accomplish
both objectives and should certainly be readable -- but if it becomes
exhibit A in a lawsuit against the company nobody is very happy with the
HR person who made sure the employees were able to understand and read
the handbook.</ol><p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Laura Hoguet -- Hoguet Newman Regal - New York<br>
Date: Tue, 16 Jan 96 21:38:27 EST<br>
Subject: What are the Pitfalls<p>

"Less Is More" would be a good rule for handbooks -- too much detail
makes problems. Rather than have an enormously complex rule book, it
makes sense to keep the book as short and plain English as possible--
and have a detailed book, if necessary, for internal use of HR [Human
Resources] administrators. This one ought to say on every page, in a
footer, that it is not distributed to employees and is not to be relied
on as a policy statement. I noticed Maurice's comment that the
handbook's first objective ought to be legal protection of employer.
Does everyone agree with this? Is the legalization of HR a fait
accompli? How do HR people feel about this?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Allan Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 12:10:05 1996<BR>
Subject: Legalese and Computers<p>

To avoid litigation, I agree with Maurice that legalese is
necessary -- but limited to those portions that are designed to protect
the employer, such as the disclaimer and the employee receipt. In the
sections dealing with vacations, etc., legalese can be a turnoff to
employees and should be avoided or at least toned-down.<p>

In response to Monica's concern about the chilling effect of a computer
use policy, I do not have a problem with allowing employees to use their
computers for term papers or for the preparation of announcements for
charitable events -- provided that prior supervisory approval is given.
(The 
<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/weitzlb1.html">
sample policy</a> I submitted covers this.)<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Tom Gosselin -- Pahl & Gosselin - San Francisco<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 18:29:04 1996<br>
Subject: Exempt-non-exempt<br>

Employers creating one handbook to cover both exempt and non-exempt
employees must be careful to distinguish policies that do not apply to
both employee categories. For example, policies concerning "tardiness"
or "time cards" do not apply to exempt employees. [For a discussion of
the difference between exempt and non-exempt employees, See this <A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/survival/work/123.html"> Legal
Help File</a> from the Court TV Survival Guide.] One way of handling this
issue is to include a general statement at the beginning of the handbook
that "except where otherwise provided, the handbook applies to both
exempt and non-exempt employees." Where a policy applies only to one
category of employee, the policy can so indicate, e.g. "For non-exempt
employees only."<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 18:50:38 1996<br>
Subject: Wishful Thinking<p>

Wishful thinking on the part of the handbook drafter is a tremendous
potential pitfall. As with any employer-employee communication, if the
handbook does not reflect accurately the workplace it purports to
describe and guide, the handbook will be useless or worse. The most
productive and challenging question I can ask in the course of a
handbook review is, "How does this really work?"<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 19:21:35 1996<br>
Subject: Chilling Morale<p>

Regarding electronic media, there's too much focus right now on the
medium, and too little on the message. Hurting employee morale by
providing guidance on the use of these media is a short-term concern. In
another few years, we will be used to business conventions about the use
of e-mail, voice mail, the Internet, etc. The business conventions will
flow from the same sense that most of us have now in using the telephone
or writing a letter in the workplace:<p><OL>

<LI>If it's personal, it should rarely be done in the workplace;<p>

<LI>Anything done in the workplace presents a greater risk that it will
not be treated as private by the employer;<p>

<LI>If personal use costs money (as with long-distance calls, use of
copiers, etc.), you should pay for it;<p>

<LI>If it's potentially offensive to others in the workplace, keep it
out of the workplace;<p>

<LI>If your use of the employer's communications media is potentially
embarassing or harmful to the employer, don't be surprised if your
employer wants to find out about it and wants you to stop.</ol><p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 08:56:26 1996<br>
Subject: Plain Language<p>

Your five principles outlined above appear to me (not an employment law
specialist) to be good examples of plain language principles that might
be incorporated in a handbook. Have you used them before? <p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 14:24:58 1996<br>
Subject: Plain Language <p>

I can count on one hand the number of clients I've met who would be
comfortable with a handbook which states principles as baldly as I have
done in my earlier post, because most employers (especially HR people)
are so used to handbook-speak that they feel the need to see something
that looks more "corporate" and familiar. My favorite chalIenge is to
make it plain, and still fit the client's particular style. I do use
materials for supervisory training which read just like my earlier post,
because I get to do training in _my_ style.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 14:33:10 1996<br>
Subject: Exempt-non-exempt<p>

Slightly different topic: A remarkable number of workplaces still use
the terms "salaried" and "hourly" in a way which indicates, in that
culture, that there are status differences between classifications of
nonexempt employees. These verbal habits persist even though the
employer is aware that the terms have no legal significance in a
wage/hour analysis, and even though the terms are potentially confusing.
I say: let them maintain their culture, but make sure there is very
explicit language in the handbook which distinguishes "salaried" and
"hourly" from "exempt" and "nonexempt." (Also, the use of these terms is
a good clue that hours-worked documentation for nonexempt employees may
need tightening up in that workplace.)<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jerry Morales -- Snell & Wilmer - Phoenix <br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 16:55:58 1996 <br>
Subject: pitfalls<p>

If the handbook is in a loose leave format, it is easier to make
modifications and distribute them. One problem I have encountered is
that while we have a receipt that the employee received the handbook in
199x we do not have proof that he received the changes made to various
policies. The receipts for the changes may become as important as the
initial receipt. This problem can be resolved with a tear-off receipt
system with the immediate supervisors being responsible to collect the
receipts and turn them over to hr only once all employees in the
department have signed. It is a pain but if the objective is to minimize
risk it is a worthwhile task.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 02:59:20 1996<br>
Subject: annual re-signing?<p>

(not resigning)  ;-)<p>

Is there any value in having employees sign their employee manual on an
annual basis? Or having a form that the employee signs as part of an
annual review process, acknowledging that s/he has read revisions during
the year? Or is that getting too bureaucratic??<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: David L Haron -- Frank & Stefani - Troy<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 12:19:37 1996<br>
Subject: disciplinary language<p>

Virtually all employment today is At Will, of course. However, many
handbooks contain language threatening "disciplinary action" <I>including
termination</i> for violation of various rules and regulations, etc..
There are many cases in which the conflict between the latter provisions
and at will language is raised in support of a wrongful discharge claim.
While the courts seem to be considering the at will language to avoid
any implication of just cause employment arising from the quoted
language, I wonder what purpose is served by including such language and
whether it is better to just state the prohibited conduct and to leave
it at that..<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 09:44:10 1996<br>
Subject:  annual re-signing?<p>

Are the administrative and bureaucratic headaches and concerns of having
employees re-sign annually eliminated by having the handbook on-line
accessible to all employees? It would then be a "living" document with
revisions and additions apparent (or called out from time to time). Does
this raise a different set of concerns?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 11:27:46 1996<br>
Subject: annual re-signing?<p>

There's value in documenting that an employee has been reminded of the
rules. I suspect there's less value in a routine re-signing for the
purpose of establishing consent. Two problems often occur: 1) the
employee testifies convincingly that the re-signing is routine and
meaningless, or not voluntary, and 2) an employee who has been annoyed
by some feature of the handbook may make an annual event of refusing to
sign.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 12:45:55 1996<br>
Subject: What are the Pitfalls?<p>

Monica makes a good point. I think we're about to enter the 2nd
generation of these policies, going from the "don't expect privacy in
e-mail" phase to the "here's what it's for" (or NOT for) phase. That's
much harder to articulate. The old fashioned telephone model (not to be
used for personal business except in emergencies) just doesn't wash for
e-mail, especially in the creative environment, as Monica says. Another
point re: pitfalls (related to the "don't make promises you can't [or
won't] keep" admonition is this. Employers tend to see handbooks as
something akin to recruiting devices -- as thought if the handbook is
inviting (warm, fuzzy) enough, it will somehow mollify employees, or
make them happier, or something. This is potentially problematic when
the employer is attempting to read the policies narrowly, or to use them
as defining.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 18:30:01 1996<br>
Subject: Annual resigning<p>

Sharon raises an important question -- what do you do with the employee
who refuses to resign for a given year? If the employer does not fire
her, that can be used to argue that she was no longer an employee at
will. If she is fired, the argument is that she was entitled to some
sort of protection which was violated by the termination. However, it
seems clear that the refusal cannot simply be ignored.<p>

<hr><p>

