<html><head><title>Seminar - The Ultimate Employee Handbook</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Fun and a Theme [Are Generally Missing]</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Mon Jan 15 19:01:01 1996<br>
Subject: fun and a theme<p>

Last Append: Sun Jan 21 22:51:11 1996<p>

[Fun and a theme] are the two things missing from most handbooks.
Think about your high school yearbook. The very thought of
opening it up and looking at a picture of myself from 20 years
ago leaves me cold. I think most employees would rather look at
the old yearbook than pick up an employee handbook.<p> 

Here are a couple of thoughts: First, some progressive companies
borrow a concept from the restaurant industry which says that
people eat with their eyes before they eat with their mouths.
Same with handbooks. If it looks foreboding than the employee is
not going to pick it up and use it as a reference guide. For
instance, the Wild Oats Community market has a handbook, printed
on paper. The color of the handbook is warm and inviting. It
makes you want to pick it up. Also, the print size on the inside
is "user friendly." The sections are set off in large bold type
and the formatting is varied, which makes it easier to read.<p>

Second, most handbooks lack a sense of fun. To return to
Wildoats: One of their benefits is the payment of $200.00 to a
new father or mother. Instead of just putting it in the handbook,
the handbook says: "It is important that Wild Oat staff members
reproduce themselves so that we will have new managers for the
next century!" I know this is not for everyone, but the point
is well taken: However written, the handbook should make the
employee want to read on.<p>

Third, handbooks which lack a theme miss an opportunity to
inculcate the employee with the company's view of the
employer/employee relationship. The sense of entitlement which
many employees have can, I think, be watered down with the right
handbook language. By way of example, I've seen a handbook, which
in the table of contents organizes topics under two general
headings: "What You Can Expect From (the company)" and then "What
(the company) Expects From You." To return to Wild Oats, their
handbook is broken down to "Responsibility to Our Customers";
"Responsibility to Our Staff"; "Responsibility to Our Community";
and "Responsibility to the Bottom Line." It's this sense of a
shared commitment and of mutual responsibility that is lacking
in many handbooks. The bottom line: A handbook should be
<I>more</i> than a compilation of policies.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - Newark<br>
Date: Tue Jan 16 00:34:03 1996<br>
Subject: Creative Use of the Intranet<p>

The first electronic brief in HTML (Hypertext Markup Language -
the hotlinks used on the Internet's World Wide Web) has been
filed in the U.S. Supreme Court, eliciting an enthusiastic
response from Justice O'Connor.<p>

Can the first electronic employee manual (published in HTML on
the Company's private "Intranet"), be far off? The advantage of
HTML is that you can insert a hotlink every time there is a
reference to another part of the document (such as a defined term
of art or a footnote) or to another document (such as a list of
persons who can answer questions), or to perform functions (such
as a database query or the popup of an e-mail menu).<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 18:19:14 1996<br>
Subject: electronic manual<p>

I think this might work well where there are employees who work out of
their homes. I'm not sure it could work in other contexts.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 01:25:29 1996<br>
Subject: fun and a theme<p>

I know of a company in Silicon Valley that has it's own internal home
page -- with icons employees can "click" for information about leave
entitlement, vacation scheduling etc. The home page can be updated
daily; is interactive (so questions can be fielded), etc. It seems to
work well, and, to me, to be a great idea. Why not?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 22:51:11 1996<br>
Subject: electronic manauals<p>

I think that electronic handbooks are great, and agree that links to
other parts would be terrific. In fact, the possibilites are especially
exciting in light of the advent of, e.g., video. For example, in the
diversity area, our bar ass'n. has produced all kinds of model policies,
videotapes, Goals and Timetables, including detailed examples of how
inexpensive accommodation of even very severe disabilities can be, etc.,
and these can help in employee sensitivity training simply by their
being easily accessible through the employee manual. There are obvious
problems in making sure that all old material is truly "deleted" (which
is said to be less than a sure thing), that the manaual is accessible
only to the firm's employees, and that new additions have been run by
counsel, etc., but on balance, I think it would be a great advance.<p>

<hr><p>

