<html><head><title>Seminar - The Ultimate Employee Handbook</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF"
VLINK="#FF0005"> <IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0> <BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Disclaimers</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington, DC<br>
Date: Tue Jan 16 21:41:34 1996<br>
Subject: Disclaimers<p>

Latest Append: Thu Jan 25 11:12:58 1996<p>

Everyone knows the handbook should disclaim that it is a contract, but
there are really a series of disclaimers or "clarifiers" which every
employee handbook should contain, preferably on the first page. (Indeed,
courts in New Jersey and Maryland have insisted that the disclaimers be
given considerable prominence in order to have any effect). As too many
employers give short shrift to the need for <I>multiple</i> disclaimers,
here is a starter list of those which the handbook should absolutely
have:<p><OL>

<LI>Not a contract, express or implied. (Must be bold-faced in
Maryland.)<p>

<LI>Does not alter the <A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/workplace/660.html"> "at
will"</a> relationship or guarantee employment for any definite period
of time.<p>

<LI>Who the handbook does and does not apply to.<p>

<LI>Supercedes any previous handbook or unwritten policies.<p>

<LI>Cannot be modified except in writing, by the President.<p>

<LI>May be changed or revoked unilaterally by the Company at any
time.<p>

<LI>Is not all-inclusive, but offers general guidelines only.</ol><p>

There are others, which apply to specific provisions, but these should
all be up front, or else the company faces unnecessary legal
exposure.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 12:12:36 1996<br> 
Subject: Jerry Morales' Disclaimer<p>

I have just posted another 
<AHREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/disclib1.html">
disclaimer, from panelist Jerry Morales</a>, into the discussion
library. MB<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Allan Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 12:21:26 1996<p>
Subject: Receipts<p>

I like to see most of Maurice's disclaimer elements replicated in the
signed employee receipt.<p>

In addition, I think the disclaimer itself should state that the terms
of written insurance policies control over the brief summary of employee
benefits described in the handbook.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 19:21:02 1996<br> 
Subject: employment application <p>

A disclaimer should also appear in the employment application. It's just
amazing how often a plaintiff will claim that,yes, he signed the
disclaimer in the handbook but before that he was promised such and such
while going through the application process. Also, companies, when
hiring executives, often neglect to have them fill out an application or
receipt of a handbook. Of course,<I>all</i> applicants who do not have
an employment contract must be required to complete an application
(sorry, a resume alone just won't do) and sign off on the handbook.
Although we as lawyers consider these matters self-evident, many
companies -- especially those in one which is going through rapid growth
-- do not cross their t's and dot their i's in this regard.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Carol Mulac -- Parker-Hannifin - Cleveland<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 11:27:44 1996<br>
Subject: Disclaimers<p>

When it comes to employee handbooks, an employer simply cannot have its
cake and eat it, too. Specificity in policy and procedure may be
interpreted as a contract by a court, and so the need for disclaimers.
But this must be balanced against the desirability of good employee
relations, especially in a non-union location which is hoping to remain
so. While a friendly disclaimer may be riskier in court, there is a lot
to be said for not antaganozing your workforce. Consider a statement
which reminds employees that the realtionship with the employer is by
its nature mutual - just as an employee is free to quit, the employer
may also end the employment relationship at any time.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br> 
Date: Sun Jan 21 23:04:15 1996<br>
Subject: what about partners?<p> 

I am curious -- to what degree are partners subject to any kind of
employee manual? Are they bound only by the partnership agreement, many
of which contain woefully little in the area of discrimination? In
general, what, exactly, do most partnership agreements contain and how
should they be changed to catch up with the Real World?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: William Sailer -- Gray Cary Ware - San Diego<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 00:18:10 1996<br>
Subject: Disclaimers<p>

As noted in another thread, the California Supreme Court recently
decided the <I>Scott v. PG&E</i> case, holding that despite at-will
language, a contract not to discipline without good cause could be
implied-in-fact based upon a company's "positive discipline" policy. How
would the <I>Scott</i> case change the handbook disclaimer - is it
enough to simply disclaim any contractual nature of the handbook or
company policies/practices? Should the employer specifically reserve the
right to discipline at-will? If so, should the employer also retain the
right to do other changes to the workplace (e.g. benefits,
reorganization, etc)? If all this is included, the disclaimer starts
getting pretty long. What about simply putting a "management rights"
clause in the disclaimer, reserving sole discretion in the employer on
issues of wages, hours and working conditions?<p>

Any thoughts?<p>

<hr><p>

From: Hope Pomerantz -- Williams Caliri - Wayne<br>
Date: Thu Jan 25 11:12:58 1996<br>
Subject: Jerry Morales' Disclaimer<p>

This is a good disclaimer. However, we have found, at least in New
Jersey, that despite the at-will language in the disclaimer, there
should still be another separate "AT-WILL" disclaimer inserted in the
front of the manual, standing alone,. In our courts, this seems to be
the only way of further ensuring success at the summary judgment level
if a case is brought, and lends itself to summary disposition.<p>

<hr><p>

