<html><head><title>Seminar - The Ultimate Employee Handbook</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Employee Receipt</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Tue Jan 16 17:21:49 1996<br>
Subject: employee receipt<p>

Lastest Append: Wed Jan 24 08:47:19 1996<p>

One area of importance is how the handbook is implemented in the
workforce. it can be a terrific piece of work, but if it is not
implemented properly it will land with a thud. A couple of ideas:<p><OL>

<LI>Have the employee in the acknowlegment state that not only has he
read the acknowledgment stating that he got it and that he is an
employee 
<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/workplace/660.html">at
will</a>, but also put in there that he will read the policies within
one week of their receipt and ask his or her supervisor about any points
that he or she does not understand.<p>

<LI>One of our clients has a new hire orientation check list. The
checklist covers a three month span(which is the length of the
orientation period). On a monthly basis a supervisor reviews portions of
the manual with the employee together with other employment issues.
There is then a checklist to show the supervisor went over the issues
with the employee. the supervisor has to <I>print</i> his or her name(this
makes it easier later on to find out who covered it with the employee).
The idea is that a person can swallow just so much information at any
one sitting.<p>

<LI>Disney world has an interesting concept. They figure a new employee
could care less about a bunch of policies the first day on the job. So
what they do <I>first</i> thing is show the employee where he punches
in; where his work station will be; where to park his car; and how he
gets his paycheck etc. The idea is that when you do this first the
employee can concentrate on the employee handbook stuff. Otherwise the
employee is thinking about this mundane <STRONG>BUT TO THE EMPLOYEE THE
MOST IMPORTANT STUFF</strong> while an hr [human resources] guy is
droning on about policies.</ol><p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br> 
Date: Tue Jan 16 21:27:04 1996<br> 
Subject: Acknowledgements<p>

Depending upon the employer's situation, we have offered different
receipt forms for new hires and existing employees. The latter form may
say simply that the employee has received the handbook and understands
that it is his reponsibility to read it, while the new employees get the
form containing all the "at will" stuff. Some first-time companies have
run into trouble with their existing employees when they confront them
with the detailed acknowledgement form, whereas new hires will sign
anything. The cases are mixed on how much value the acknowledgement form
alone has anyway.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville <br>
Date: Wed Jan 17 18:00:16 1996<br>
Subject: employee receipt<p>

Another pleasant and effective method used by one of our clients: once a
year, employees in a department get together for cookies and handbook
reading for about an hour. They split the handbook into manageable
portions, read to themselves, and employees (and supervisors) comment
and ask questions of the group, as questions occur to them. This method
has improved the value of the handbook tremendously, both legally and
practically, and has inspired some interesting discussions which
prompted changes to the handbook.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 08:58:21 1996<br> 
Subject: Counsel Presence Required?<p>

The group session on the handbook sounds interesting, Sharon. But it
also might be dangerous if the employer started to "explain" what a
particular section of the handbook "means." I'd be leery of suggesting
this procedure to a client without insisting that counsel be present. Am
I being overly cautious?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 13:59:23 1996<br>
Subject: Counsel Presence Required?<p>

If an attorney's presence is required in order to guard against oral
interpretations of the handbook by a supervisor, then the handbook has
not been well written and the supervisor has not been adequately
trained. I think a handbook is near to useless if it does not enable the
supervisor to use it as a guide, and if it does not empower a supervisor
to supervise and communicate directly with employees. In the
group-discussion situation I've described, notes are taken about
questions asked and answered, and some of those questions and answers
are reviewed later with an attorney to evaluate whether the handbook
should be clarified. I also recommend an attorney-run training session
with supervisors, which combines an orientation to the handbook with a
refresher on legal issues.<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Scott Wollaston -- Rolm Systems - Santa Clara <br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 14:52:03 1996<br>
Subject: employee receipt<p>

We have a raging debate among the lawyers and the HR staff and
management. Can the handbook be put on line? Printing is very expensive,
updates are hard to do, etc. However, how do you ensure everyone sees
it, reads and understands it and, most importantly, agrees to the
policies (including At-Will)?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 18:12:44 1996<br>
Subject: registered mail<p>

I suppose you can send stuff by e-mail that is registered (at least you
can here on Counsel Connect). But the problem is that at a summary
judgment hearing or at a trial you need to hit a judge or jury over the
head, and nothing quite works like a big blow up with the plaintiff's
signature.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 16:03:21 1996<br>
Subject: Group Handbook meetings<p>

I'm intrigued by the notion of monthly meetings to discuss the handbook.
How is the "employment at will" language explained? Does management
really tell people that they can get canned any time we feel like it,
whether we have a valid reason to do so or not? If not, I see a real
danger of testimony that the boss told us at the meeting that this
language meant that we would not be fired unless management had a good
reason for doing so. A handbookis either a device for raising morale or
a legal protection arrangement. If it is the latter, the meeting will
seriously diminish its utility.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Louis Storrow -- Louis A. Storrow - Carlsbad<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 14:13:57 1996<br>
Subject: monthly meeting thumbs down<p>

I too see a problem with the staff meeting where the handbook is
discussed. If the handbook is so well written, why do we need a meeting?
And, when a hypothetical question comes up, any answer the supervisor
gives becomes a footnote to the book, without benefit of counsel. As an
attorney paid to be a nervous nelly, I don't like it...<p> 

-- Lou Storrow<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 16:12:55 1996<br>
Subject: a variation<p>

One idea of an employee meeting on a handbook is what one of my clients
does which is to have a 10 or 15 minute meeting every other week to
cover certain items(i.e. safety,new production goals etc.). When
something of an operational nature isn't on the agenda, they will cover
an item in the handbook -- such as policynagainst harassment, EEO
committment etc. When the lawsuit is filed, this all comes in as
background evidence that they just don't write something up, and forget
about it.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 18:13:31 1996<br>
Subject: What about discipline? <p>

The discussions are helpful in regard to the harassment policy and EEO,
I guess, but they should never, never, never include a discussion of
disclipline policy. And if the supervisors are told they are not to
discuss discipline, the meetings can be counterproductive. No meetings,
I vote.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 18:39:43 1996<br>
Subject:  Online Handbook<p>

Regarding Scott's earlier question about having the handbook online, I
think more and more companies will do that as they go paperless. Online
versions also have the advantage of being easier to amend and
disseminate to employees. And, if the handbook is not meant to be an
employment agreement but simply a document that affirms the statutory
presumption of at-will employment, the need for a signature per se
indicating agreement may not be as great, as long as the handbook's
existence and accessibility to employees online is publicized widely and
regularly.<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 11:16:23 1996<br>
Subject: Track Usage?<p>

Do you think that the usage of this online handbook should be tracked?
Should an employee's views of various handbook internal web pages be
catalogued? Should the employee sign-in to the handbook when viewing
it?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Scott Wollaston -- Rolm Systems - Santa Clara<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 14:31:40 1996<br>
Subject: employee receipt<p>

One of the key problems with an on-line only (put aside for the moment
what you do for new employees) is access to the manual. If all
employees, including the night janitor, have a terminal on their desk
(assuming they have a desk) you might be able to show receipt. We are
thinking of having kiosks spread around so all employees can access the
manual.<p> 

One other problem is going to be keeping up with updates. While it is
never good to have a printed manual that is out of date because of
changes that never effectively get distributed to all employees, I can
see keeping track of revisions will be a nightmare. Companies these days
are not managing the "details" very well. Unless a librarian of some
sort keeps track of revisions, it would well be very difficult to
establish in a lawsuit what a particular policy was if it had been
changed at any time during the life of the manual.<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 20:36:11 1996<br>
Subject:  employee receipt<p>

It is true that a systems administrator needs to keep track of changes
in the online handbook. Over the years as major and minor edits are made
it could be difficult if not impossible to take a snapshot view of the
policies at a particular point in time. A revision history at the front
of the online handbook might be worthwhile.<p> 

As far as electronic records that an employee reviewed the policies
while employed, I suppose that is technologically possible, and perhaps
worth pursuing if it becomes an issue in litigation. A lot depends on
the culture of the company. In any event it seems to me the more
important thing is that it is made available to employees and they are
so told.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - Newark<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 08:47:19 1996<br>
Subject: Online Handbook Technology<p>

I agree with Ted that online handbooks are likely to become popular.
I'll go farther and predict that they will become a "killer app" as
firms and companies migrate more and more of their internal
communication to the company Intranet (that's InTRAnet, not InTERnet).
The techniques of HTML "hotlinks" to display other material at the click
of a pointer, when combined with the user-friendly possibilities of
animation and communication and query techniques of Java applets
embedded in the document, strike me as offering human resources an
exciting chance to combine both an individual help desk and the group
"cookie session" mentioned earlier, with a perfect audit trail of what
questions were asked and what answers were given.<p> 

The technological infrastructure for legal support of the online
handbook is important. Judging from the products presented at the RSA
Data Security Conference last week, I'd say that the technology is all
there, with rollout of implementation ready to follow the demand
promptly. The key ingredients I see are:<p><OL>

<LI>robust digital signatures of employees, using public key crypto
techniques which provide non-repudiation as to <STRONG>WHO</strong>
received the document, and <STRONG>WHAT</strong> version of the document
was received;<p>

<LI>trusted third-party time-stamping services which identify in a
non-repudiatable fashion <STRONG>WHAT VERSION</strong> of the
referencing document (i.e., the top page) was received, and
<STRONG>WHEN</strong> it was received, and <STRONG>WHAT VERSION</strong>
of the referenced documents were located at the other end of the
hotlinks at the same time the top page was received.</ol><p> 

To provide strong non-repudiation of the employee's digital signature,
the discussion of commercial key escrow in the 

<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/merrill1.html">

"Employee E-MailEncryption"</a> thread should be considered. If
commercial key escrow is implemented on the company's system, it is
extremely important that only the <I>session keys</i> for each
individual message are escrowed, and not the employee's permanent
<I>private key</i> in the public key cryptosystem. If the employee can
argue that the employer's escrow system could possibly have allowed the
employer to spoof his digital signature, the elegant legal
non-repudiability of the employee's digital signature disappears. There
is no comparable problem with the leading time-date stamp technology
(Surety Technologies), which does not require cryptographic keys at
all.<p>

For those interested, some of these concepts are treated in the October
95 draft of the ABA Information Security Committee (Section of Science
and Technology) Digital Signature Guidelines, and continue to be
explored in detail in the Counsel Connect "E-Mail and Electronic
Commerce Forum", which you'll find under DISCUSS, then under National
and International, then under Computers and Technology.<p>

<hr><p>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit
your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email
address of the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our online directory of
attorneys, <a href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.

