<html><head><title>Seminar - The Ultimate Employee Handbook</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Antitrust Compliance Policy?</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 12:49:29 1996<br>
Subject: Antitrust Compliance Policy<p>

Last Append: Thu Feb  1 22:23:45 1996<p>

Does anyone [else] think that an antitrust compliance policy
should be part of the typical employee handbook? Or is this
something that just belongs in the management realms?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jerry Morales -- Snell & Wilmer - Phoenix<br> 
Date: Thu Jan 18 16:59:20 1996<br>
Subject: anti-trust <p>

I would leave this to the management realm. There [are] enough
topics that need to be included.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Laura Hoguet -- Hoguet Newman Regal - New York<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 21:16:52 1996<br>
Subject: Antitrust Compliance Policy<p> 

There is one area where antitrust compliance belongs in an employee
handbook, and that is price fixing in companies where employees have the
opportunity to have communications with competitors that could create
this problem. It doesn't have to be a big deal: "Agreements between
producers of competing products to fix prices are illegal. Employees may
not discuss the pricing of our products with competitors. If you are
present at any discussion with competitors at which prices are
discussed, contact the General Counsel immediately to discuss the
matter." This could help the company someday show that it had done what
it could to make its employees aware of the law so if they broke it [it]
wasn't the company's idea. The same principle applies to securities law
compliance and insider trading.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 11:39:54 1996<br> 
Subject: Trade Associations<p>


I think I would go a bit further than just talking about price fixing. I
would caution my employees about their activities with trade
associations. I might cover the concept of the illegal group boycott,
for example. But again, this is probably not for all employees, and
might be covered in a separate Corporate Antitrust Policy distributed to
managers.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 23:23:54 1996<br>
Subject: Antitrust Compliance Policy<p>

There are two separate questions:<p>

What kind of antitrust message should be in the employee message? What
kind of antitrust compliance policy should be in effect?<p>

The employee handbook should probably have a condensed antitrust
compliance message, with emphasis on the criminal violations. It should
reference the more detailed antitrust policy (which should be given to
all employees).<p> 

There should be an antitrust policy that provides for compliance with
all applicable antitrust and similar laws. This would cover the obvious
criminal violations, and then should cover the civil violations with an
emphasis on the types of situations that relate to the company's
business. For a company selling consumer products, a Robinson-Patman
compliance policy is very important. For a company providing consulting
services, it is less important.<p> 

In addition, there may be certain antitrust laws (e.g., things relating
to acquisitions) that should be focused on appropriate segments of
management.<p> 

Antitrust is just one of the key legal considerations that should be
covered in an employee handbook. All of the relevant federal criminal
statutes should be covered in the handbook, along with reference to more
detailed policy statements, and procedures for contacting the Law
Department. The subject should be reviewed and reinforced during the
employee orientation program. A videotaped message from a senior exec
emphasizing the company's commitment to legal compliance would also be a
good idea.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 22:23:45 1996<br>
Subject: Legal Compliance<p>

Employees should get legal compliance policies covering the following
subjects:<p><UL>

<LI>Antitrust Law
<LI>Securities Law (insider trading)
<LI>Employment Law<br> 
<LI>Contracts
<LI>Use of the Law Department
<LI>Privilege and confidentiality
<LI>Unsolicited Ideas
<LI>Trademarks, tradenames, servicemarks
<LI>Trade Secrets
<LI>Service of process
<LI>government investigations
<LI>Record retention, record creation
<LI>Business entertainment and gifts (giving and receiving)
<LI>Political Contributions
<LI>Lobbying
<LI>Copyright, work for hire 
<LI>Conflicts of Interest 
<LI>Computer Software
<LI>Reporting of Wrongdoing 
<LI>Industry specific laws (e.g., commitment to pure food, honest
advertisements)</ul><p>

All of this can be put in the employee handbook or in some other
publication(s) that goes to the employee. It needs to be reinforced with
some sort of training.<p>

