<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Sick Leave -- Substance Abuse</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Kirk Brown -- Law Office - Pueblo<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 16:19:57 1996<br>
Subject: Sick leave-substance abuse<p>

Last Append: Sat Jan 20 11:57:02 1996<p>

Any suggestions for policies regarding "sick leave" policies? Obviously
personnel managers want to discourage (or exclude) "sick leave" for
alcohol or other substance abuse (meaning the employee "calls in sick "
because he or she is "under the influence").<p> 

Given that an employee is entitled to leave for treatment,
hospitalization, or meeting attendance under the ADA [Americans with
Disabilities Act], FMLA [Family and Medical Leave Act], and the
Rehabilitation Act, there must be some way to word a policy that does
not take adverse action against a person with a record of a disability
or a perceived disability and yet gives the employer some leverage in
dealing with an employee who calls in (generally with little notice)
hungover or under the influence.<p>

Perhaps a generic "excused absense" vs. "unexcused absence" policy with
notice requirements stated for each?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Melissa McMorries -- Atty-M McMorries - Atlanta<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 21:41:07 1996<br>
Subject: Sick leave-substance abuse<p>

My understanding of the ADA on alcohol and substance abuse is that the
condition is recognized as a disability <I>provided that the employee is
not actively pursuing his or her addiction</i>. In other words, if the
employee is pursuing a treatment or other recovery program, ADA
protections applies; if the employee is actively using alcohol or drugs,
ADA protections do not apply. A sick call for a hangover or for being
under the influence would necessarily indicate that the employee was not
following the prescribed treatment or recovery program. It follows then
that normal disciplinary policies would apply for an unexcused absence.
While relapse is common, particularly early on in a treatment program,
most, if not all, treatment counselors would encourage an employer to
take disciplinary action for relapse behavior. Otherwise, the employer
is engaging in "enabling" behavior, which can impede an employee's
recovery.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Robert Zielinski -- Ross & Hardies - Chicago<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 23:10:39 1996<br>
Subject: Sick leave-substance abuse<p>

One method is to attack the behaviors around the attendance problem
rather than the lack of attendnace itself. For example, one might
punish heavily for failure to call-in to report absence or tardiness, a
misbehavior that is frequent associated with attendance abusers.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 16:24:58 1996<br>
Subject: Posted to the Website<p> 

[The following comment was submitted by a visitor to the workshop "echo"
on the Court TV Small Business Law Center. See the thread "Welcome to
the Workshop" for more information, or visit the site on the Web at:
http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/]<p>

NAME=William Adams<br>
COMPANY=Feldman, Waldman & Kline<br>
EMAIL=WFAdams@Prodigy.com<br>

QUESTION=One good way to control abuse of a company's sick-leave policy
is to merge vacation and sick leave into one interchangeable policy. For
example, if a company offers 10 days of vacation and 10 days of sick
leave, a flexible time off policy of equivalent value would permit 15
days off for any reason. Thus, it no longer matters whether the employee
is sick or on vacation. Further, employees who use excessive sick leave
will have less available vacation. After companies adopt such a program,
sick days are cut dramatically. For those who wonder why 15 days of
flexible time off can be considered equivalent to 10 sick days plus 10
vacation days, there is an explanation that must be supplied to the
employees. Most employees use only 2-3 legitimate sick days per year.
For them, there will be an increase in vacation time. An employer should
let those who abuse the present sick leave policy do their own math as
to whether they are better off or not, but the most they can lose is
five days of sick leave, even if they take the maximum every year. I
hope this is helpful.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 11:57:02 1996<br>
Subject: Sick leave-substance abuse<p> 

I agree with Robert Zielinski that it may be more effective to look at
how behaviors are affecting work, rather than merely looking at them as
a problem of sick leave abuse. I'd take it a step further, though. For
example, instead of using sick leave or calling in late, the same
hungover employee might show up at work and be useless. Unless there is
some special protection for the employee's condition, what's really
irking the employer at this point is that the employee has not
aknowledged a responsibility to avoid diminishing his or her ability to
do good work. This is a performance issue, and can be addressed without
a focus on specific infractions like tardiness or call-in rules.<p>

<hr><p>

