<H2>Computer Network Policies</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 08:54:33 1996<br>
Subject: Computer Network Policies<p>

Last Append: Fri Jan 19 12:05:48 1996<p>

Given that we're holding this workshop in cyberspace, and the
danger of chilling employee morale through computer and
telecommunications equipment use policies has been raised, I
think it's time to start a separate thread on this issue.<p>

Sharon Grodin has suggested that the old paradigms covering the
nature of the workplace can be adapted to cover new
technologies.<p>

On the other hand, there seems little doubt that people who are
unfamiliar with how the technology actually works may be at sea
when it comes to issues such as privacy/permanency of e-mail
systems.<p>

Obtaining information from online services and then distributing
that information on an internal company communications system may
easily lead to unintended copyright violations.<p>

Chas. Merrill will likely explain his views on whether an
employer should forbid the use of strong encryption on a company
LAN. Or is this really a business policy issue, as opposed to a
legal question?<p>

So, I think we need a separate thread to address how handbooks
should be updated to reflect the impact of new technologies.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 14:16:47 1996<br>
Subject: Computer Network Policies<p>

I'd love an explanation why the risk of copyright infringement is
greater if the medium is network distribution of material found
on the Internet, rather than, for example, photocopying the same
material from a book and routing or mailing it. The only factors
I can think of are 1) the electronic medium is faster so you
don't have as much time to worry about it before you do it, and
2) people aren't educated to understand that the electronic
distribution method amounts to the same thing as the more manual
method. It seems to me that a very little training--and yes,
maybe some handbook language--would solve this problem without
making it a thorny legal issue. (I'll be waiting in my horsedrawn
carriage for responses to this.)<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 14:40:42 1996<br>
Subject: A few more factors<p>

I'd say you've hit the big ones -- lack of education and speed.
To those I'd add: 1) When one copies electronic documents, they
can more easily lose there identifying characteristics than when
one photcopies a page; and 2) When one copies documents at a
photocopy machine, one knows exactly how many copies one is
making, and is aware of the reams of paper flowing through the
machine, whereas when I unleash a copy in a networked
environment, how many copies have I made?<p>

By the way, it's interesting that you use the photocopy machine
as an example of <I>old</i> technology (from the horse and buggy
era)!<g><p>

- Cloyd<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 12:05:48 1996<br>
Subject: Privacy<p>

Perhaps more important than the copyright aspect of computer network use
in the workplace, is communicating with employees about the use of the
company's email network, and what they should expect with regard to the
privacy of their email. Most experts I have spoken with about this
advise that their client employers specifically state that email on the
company systems is subject to monitoring without warning.<p>

<hr><p>

