<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Written Employment Contracts</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Peter MacLaren -- Law Offices - San Jose<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 20:39:00 1996<br>
Subject: Written employment contracts<p>

Last Append: Mon Jan 29 14:09:46 1996<p>

The legal problem that the proposed disclaimers and employee receipts
are attempting to resolve is whether an implied agreement not to
terminate without cause can be inferred from the handbook and/or other
employee documents. The most effective way to avoid the problem
altogether is to require each employee to execute a written employment
agreement stating that employment is <A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/workplace/660.html">
at-will</a> and that any progressive discipline procedures that the
employer may employ to improve the performance of an employee are
discretionary and do not constitute a waiver or limitation of the
at-will employment relationship. If the contract has an integration
clause, most courts will refuse to consider parole evidence that
contradicts the contract's at-will provision and will rule, as a matter
of law, that termination with or without cause does not give rise to an
action for breach of contract. The handbook/receipt provisions stating
that employment is at-will sometimes get similar treatment and sometimes
are merely held to be elements for the jury to consider in determining
whether an implied employment agreement existed, Given the availability
of word processing, the administrative cost of preparing written
employment contracts would appear to be far outweighed by the expense of
litigating handbook provisions.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 01:29:28 1996<br>
Subject: Employment contracts<p>

I agree with you. I'm surprised at how often employers shy away from
contracts, because they think they will be locked in -- when the
opposite can be true. I would be curious, though, to hear what others
think about the adhesion contract notion, when the contract is standard,
and all employees are required to sign. I understand that conceptually
this is no different from a handbook (which is adhesive, standard,
etc.), but I wonder whether the courts might not construe a mandatory,
uniform contract for lower level employees to be repugnant, in some
way.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 09:01:39 1996<br>
Subject: Written employment contracts<p>

Peter, could you give us the language you use for your integration
clause?<p>

Is there any cause to be concerned that if an employee signed a
contract, and then later received a new, written employee handbook, that
this might be found to be a written alteration of the original
contract?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 15:53:59 1996<br>
Subject: Fixed term contract<p>

I would go even further and give every employee a contract for a fixed
term of one year, with an option in either party to terminate the
contract on notice. I would also provide that the employer will pay the
employee a modest sum (say $1,000) if it elects to terminate. That may
create some emotional distress for some clients, but in the long run
they would be money ahead. What's the big deal about making everyone
employees at will? It sounds bad and it accomplishes little that a one
year contract would not.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 20:09:09 1996<br>
Subject: Flexibility<p>

Most of our clients seem to prefer not to have formal contracts with
each of their employees, and one of the purposes of the disclaimers in a
handbook is to avoid creating one. (As noted elsewhere, that is only one
of the purposes). Our experience is that properly worded disclaimers
give the employer greater flexibility than contracts do, and they have
worked to avoid litigation while preserving the good communications
aspects of handbooks. While definite term (i.e., one-year) agreements
make sense for some employees, and indeed are often used, they don't
seem to suit all, or even most employment situations, as well as the at
will concept.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 09:27:08 1996<br>
Subject:  Written employment contracts<p>

With regards to the earlier question whether an agreement at hire
stating the relationship to be at will could be construed as an adhesion
contract, I would think that in order to be unenforceable on that ground
it would also have to contain unconscionable terms, and merely stating
the statutory presumption of at will employment applies would not meet
that test.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 12:51:07 1996<br>
Subject: Written employment contracts<p>

I think your point is well taken, Theodore. The follow up question for
me is whether a mandatory arbitration provision (a fair and square one,
using -- say -- AAA [American Arbitration Association] rules, damages
according to law, "conscionable" time limits, etc.) would make it
unconscionable. Perhaps the answer is more likely to be no if it's
limited to claims of breach of contract; more likely to be yes, if it
attempts to incorporate discrimination claims -- but then, if that's the
answer, most employers would probably say, "Why bother?" And I'd have to
agree they were right.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael Caldwell -- DeLong Caldwell - Atlanta<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 13:15:02 1996<br>
Subject: Written employment contracts<p>

This idea sounds attractive, notwithstanding Maurice's clients'
preferences. But what if the employer needs to change an employment
policy for the company, or institute a new benefit, or create a new rule
or procedure to deal with a new exigency? Could these be accommodated
in a rather static employment contract, even with a one year term? 

<A HREF="mailto:mcaldw02@counsel.com">Michael A. Caldwell</a><br>

DeLong, Caldwell & Wisebram, L.L.C.<br>
Suite 1770 Resurgens Plaza<br>
945 East Paces Ferry Road N.E.<br>
Atlanta, GA. 30326<br>
(404)842-0555<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 18:25:24 1996<br>
Subject: Fixed term<p>

A fixed term contract could specify only the employment term and leave
other conditions subject to change, so long as the changes are uniform
and without discrimination. The only downside I can see is that the
employer is required to pay money to cancel the contract before the year
ends, and that is cheap insurance in my book. From a flexibility
standpoint, except for the cost, it is the same as an "at will"
contract.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Matthew Vega -- Sirote & Permutt - Birmingham<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 12:13:17 1996<br>
Subject: When disclaimers not enough<p> 

A recent Alabama Supreme Court case, <I>Amoco Fabrics and Fibers
Company, Inc. v. Robert Hilson</i>, 1995 WL 502999 (Aug. 25, 1995)
illustrates how the best disclaimer language in the world is not enough.
The Court affirmed the trial court's summary judgment in favor of the
employees and half-a-million dollar judgment on a breach of contract
claim that relied on Amoco's vacation pay policy. The Court held the
policy gave rise to a unilateral contract even though the Handbook
contained an express disclaimer of contractual liability. Reason? Amoco
made a crucial change to the policy through a memorandum and
announcement but did not modify the original vacation pay policy itself.
Accordingly, the Court refused to recognize the change and held that the
language in the handbook's original policy was sufficient to constitute
an offer to create a binding unilateral contract.<p> 

This prompts two questions and/or suggestions:<p><OL>

<LI>isn't it crucial that disclaimer language be incorporated throughout
a handbook, or will an isolated introductory statement or About This
Manual policy suffice?<p>

<LI>handbooks should be issued in a loose-leaf format to permit changes
by the issuance of new pages for insertion (many employers like nice
little type-set booklets but 3 months later when they want to change the
policy they are unwillingly to go through the added expense of
reprinting its employee handbooks and think a addendum or memorandum
will suffice).</ol><p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 17:32:35 1996<br>
Subject: Severance<p>

Neil, I'm not sure this option really "costs" anything other than the
equivalent of a reasonable severance pay policy. If an at-will employee
is terminated for misconduct, an employer wouldn't pay severance, and I
assume you would not require an employer termininating [for misconduct]
one of your basic contract employees to pay the "liquidated damages"
provision -- or would you?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Peter MacLaren -- Law Offices - San Jose<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 12:24:36 1996<br>
Subject: Written employment contracts<p>

The issue of adhesion merely provides that ambiguous language will be
construed against the drafter of the document. Most courts will hold
that a provision stating that employment is "at-will" and explaining
that either party has the right to terminate the employment relationship
at any time without cause or notice, is not ambiguous. Even if the court
admits evidence to "explain" the ambiguity, the parol evidence rule
prohibits an interpretation that contradicts the plain language of the
contract.<p> 

The language in an integration clause in an employment contract does not
need to differ from language used in other types of contracts. The
clause should state that the agreement is intended to be the final and
complete expression of the agreement between the parties, to supercede
all prior written, oral, an implied agreements, negotiations and
understandings, that no party is relying on any statement or promise not
contained in the agreement, and that any modification must be in writing
and executed by the parties.<p> 

It is true that employees can attempt to offer evidence of subsequent
agreements to the contract, though this problem is partially solved by
the "modifications must be in writing and signed" provision of the
integration clause. The contract can provide that the handbook or other
personnel documents are merely advisory, can be bypassed at the
discretion of the employer, and that were a contradiction exists, the
contract will control. In termination cases, the key dispute will be
progressive discipline policies. If the written contract states that the
procedures are discretionary and failure to utilize such procedures does
not constitute a breach of the agreement, the employee will have
difficulty by-passing the language of the contract.<p> 

The best contracts that I've seen are updated each year as part of the
review process. This keeps any of the information, such as salary,
position, or supervisor from becoming obsolete. Each subsequent contract
supercedes anything that happened during the prior year. So judges would
view execution of five successive contracts containing at-will
provisions as more persuasive evidence of at-will employment than a
single five year contract. One problem with a fixed term of contract is
that if the company forgets to renew it, the court is going to look to
conduct after the period ended to evaluate the rights of the parties.<p>

In my opinion, Employers who believe that a handbook offers greater
"flexibility" than a fully integrated written at-will employment
contract are missing the point. By failing to specify, unequivocally, in
a binding contract that employment is at-will, employers invite
litigation concerning the terms of employment. Some judges will grant
summary judgment, some will not. A written contract, with an attorneys
fees clause, will dissuade most plaintiff's attorneys from bringing the
case in the first place. A written at-will employment contract will
vastly simplify the preparation of the motion for summary and will
greatly increase the likelihood that the motion will be granted.<p> 

The employment contract does not have to specify every term of
employment. Benefits can be specified by addendum or the documents that
contain the terms of employee benefits can be specifically incorporated
by reference.<p> 

Most California courts will uphold arbitration clauses. The State courts
generally do not hesitate to enforce broad clauses such as the NASD "all
matters arising out of employment" to require arbitration of
discrimnation and other statutory claims. The Ninth Circuit uses a
"knowing agreement to arbitrate" standard that merely requires that the
arbitration clause make it clear that statutory discrimination claims
are included. A clear description of the types of causes of action that
are subject to arbitration will frequently be enforced.<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 23:20:06 1996<br>
Subject:  Written contracts<p>

While I fully agree with Peter's recommendation on written agreements, I
have to wonder how many employers actually take that step. I suppose
much depends on the characteristics of the employer and industry, e.g.
is it a mature company with employees who expect to stay until they
retire, or is it a startup where it is the norm and expectation that
employees will come and go. Also, what has been the history of
litigation with former employees?<p> 

I expect that in many companies there would be resistance to the idea of
annual contracts for one or more of the following reasons:<p><OL>

<LI>it dumps cold water on the romance phase of the employment
relationship;<p>

<LI>it is too legalistic;<p>

<LI>it adds to administrative burdens to have annual agreements or
renewals; and/or (often unstated)<p>

<LI>it is not our primary goal to make life easier for the
lawyers.</ol><p>

It is with these realities in mind that a well-drafted handbook plays an
important role in the relationship.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 18:36:29 1996<br>
Subject: fixed or at will<p>

I agree with the wonderful notion that fixed contracts "pour cold water
on the romance aspect of the relationship". But it is the promises
motivated by "romance" that gets the employer in trouble, the same as in
the matrimonial context.<p> 

I would pay severance to the employee that the employe[r] thought it
terminated for misconduct. Sometimes the employer is wrong and sometimes
it is right but can't prove it. Paying everyone saves money in the long
run.<p>

You can write your at-will contracts any way you want, but I don't think
there is any way you can keep the disgruntled ex-employee out of court
claiming public policy, implied covenant of good faith or some other
cockamamie theory. If the people get some sort of termination pay, the
employer starts off looking fair-minded. I like to grab the high ground
early.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Peter MacLaren -- Law Offices - San Jose<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 22:00:31 1996<br>
Subject: Written employment contracts<p>

The majority of the Silicon Valley employers that I have dealt with do
not have formal written employment contracts, but lots of Silicon Valley
firms put an at-will clause in their offer letters and require that new
employees countersign the letter. Some of the offer letters contain
abbreviated integration clauses. The at-will-clause-in-offer-letter
approach does not appear to hinder the romance stage of the relationship
because everyone believes the relationship will last forever.<p> 

When a breach of implied contract or implied covenant case is brought,
the employer argues that whatever at-will clauses exist, whether in the
employment application, the offer letter, the employee handbook, the
receipt for the employee handbook, the stock option agreement, are
controlling. The employee argues that the clauses are merely one of the
factors affecting "the reasonable expectation of continued employment."
Some judges grant summary judgment on nothing more than a handbook
at-will clause. Other judges require more.<p> 

If the employee has executed the document containing the at-will
language, the employer will argue that the document is an employment
contract that is at least partially integrated on the issue of
termination and the chances that summary judgment will be granted
increase substantially. If the document actually purports to be an
employment offer or employment agreement, as opposed to an employment
application or handbook receipt, and contains an integration clause,
summary judgment becomes fairly certain. If a an employer has a standard
contract containing a prevailing party attorneys' fee provision, then a
contract based law suit is unlikely, and if an action is brought, the
summary judgment motion will be extremely short and the employer will
probably be awarded fees pursuant to the contract.<p> 

When mergers take place, some Silicon Valley employers have the
employees of the acquired firm countersign form "offer letters" that
offer a position with the merged entity, with same job title, duties,
and salary provided by the prior employer, and which contain an at-will
provision and integration clause. If the employees are concerned about
layoffs, they do not hesitate to sign the letter.<p>

Management acceptance would probably improve if the contracts appear to
primarily address business concerns such as non-compete/severance
agreements to salesmen or proprietary information/invention agreements
to engineers and scientists. The perceived need for such procedures
would probably deflect some resistance.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jeffrey Bernfeld -- Spire Corporation - Bedford<br>
Date: Mon Jan 29 14:09:46 1996<br>
Subject: Something for nothing<p> 

I may have read this thread a little [too] quickly, but my immediate
reaction is that universal employment contracts is an intriguing idea,
but not one that I could see implementing at any co. with which I am
familiar.<p>

I don't know a single company that has its act together enough to keep
renewing the contracts annually or updating them regularly to account
for changed circumstances (e.g. promotions). And if you don't renew, it
seems to me that you've created the worst sort of negative implication.
Worse, if you've relied on the contract at the expense of the at will
language typical of a handbook, you may be really letting yourself in
for trouble. Conversely, if you have the handbook language, it seems a bit
belt & suspender-y.<p>

I also can't see handing this document labeled "contract" to about-to-be
employees, having them read it, and having them come to the
understanding that even though it says "contract", which they understand
to mean something like "binding commitment", what it really commits to
is no commitment. "Romance" or not, I don't think it's a good thing to
start a relationship by appearing to try to pull a fast one. Let me
hasten to add that I am not suggesting that that is the intent, but it
seems to me like a reasonable conclusion for an employee to reach. In
our industry, employees expect to sign nondisclosure agreements, and
many understand that they need to sign noncomps [non-compete
agreements]. Beyond that, a "contract" is viewed as the kind of benefit
only the bigwigs get to protect themselves if they get the axe. To label
a document a "contract" and have it provide the opposite (more or less)
just seems like a red flag.<p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your
question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the
email address of the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our
online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.</I></P>
