<html><head><title>Seminar - The Ultimate Employee Handbook</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Sexual Harassment Nuances</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 22:02:48 1996<br>
Subject: Sexual Harassment Nuances<p>

Last Append: Sun Jan 21 23:09:19 1996<p>

We've all heard so much about sexual harassment litigation -- and
after <I>Weeks v. Baker & McKenzie</i> case, et al., I suspect
companies are far more sophisticated about establishing policies
to prevent abuse.<p>

But where are the nuances? What remains problematic, and how can
handbooks address these issues. For example, take a look at 
<A  HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/romantic.html">
Allan Weitzman's policy on "Romance" in the workplace</a>.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 01:13:24 1996<br>
Subject: Sexual Harassment Nuances<p> 

One nuance concerns the employer's <STRONG>NOT</strong> stating, at the
conclusion of the no-harassment policy, that disciplinary action will be
taken against the harasser "if harassment is found to have occurred." If
the policy so states, there is an argument that the employer is
constrained from taking disciplinary action if something short of
harassment is found to have occurred, that is, inappropriate behavior
that may not quite cross the line to being full-blown harassment. Or, if
the employer does take disciplinary action following a harassment
investigation, the "victim" can argue that there must have been illegal
harassment (for which the employer may be strictly liable, at least in
California). The solution: conclude the policy in the employee handbook
by stating that discipline will be taken "if harassment or other
inappropriate conduct is found to have occurred."<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 01:11:07 1996<br>
Subject: Sexual Harassment Nuances<p>

As Executive Director of a large urban bar and a former civil rights
litigator, I must say that I continue to be surprised that large, well,
<I>most</i> legal employers continue to have great difficulty dealing
with partners, particularly rainmakers, who engage in sexual harassment.
They may well have policies that deal with it in great detail, but in
general I think that the emphasis on the bottom line, together with the
influx of laterals and exit of some "elder statesmen" who may have
exerted some real beneficent influence in some firms -- has created a
climate where sexual harassment by partners, especially the sort of
"shark" litigators in their mid-40's, is very poorly dealt with. Many
management lawyers point out that unless that partnership writes into
the partnership agreement that a partner can be ousted for harassment
(and by far less than the 90+% it took under the Baker & McKenzie
partnership agreement) and otherwise put real economic sanctions in for
partners who harass, the problem will not get a great deal better. It's
interesting, and hardly surprising to note that the California State Bar
Survey of Women Lawyers several years ago found that harassment
decreases as the percentage of women in the firm increases. All the more
disheartening, then, to see the recent studies that show that the
percentages of women partners in firms have stalled and they remain, at
best, at the penultimate ranks.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Tom Gosselin -- Pahl & Gosselin - San Francisco<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 12:42:35 1996<br>
Subject: Sexual Harassment Nuances<p> 

Another nuance of no harassment policies is that an employer's
responsibilities to prevent harassment (at least in California) extend
beyond the employer's own employees. Thus, an employer's no harassment
policy should extend to actions by clients, vendors, customers and the
like. In addition, some no harassment policies unnecessarily limit the
reporting olbigations to harassment that is actually experienced by an
employee. We take the position that employees should report harassment
that they experience <STRONG>OR WITNESS</strong>. The importance of this
requirement is heightened if the witnessing employee is a supervisor, as
the employer is deemed to have "knowledge" of harassment commensurate
with the knowledge of its supervisory employees.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Robert Zielinski -- Ross & Hardies - Chicago<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 22:36:30 1996<br>
Subject: requiring informers on sex harassment<p> 

I would be leery of a policy which too greatly encouraged non-targets of
harassing behavior to make formal complaints. After all if the conduct
is consensual or welcome, a complaint and followup could be viewed as an
invasion of privacy by the employer, particularly in a privacy happy
state like California.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 09:17:19 1996<br>
Subject:  Sexual Harassment Nuances<p> 

Judith's earlier comment is well taken. It is very easy, not only in the
harassment portion of the handbook, but in other areas as well, to use
legal phrases as shortcut definitions. The problem is exacerbated if
these phrases find their way into investigative reports -- they could be
read as admissions by the employer. Although courts have ruled that an
employer can impose stricter standards of conduct on employees than the
law requires, such that prohibited "harassment" subject to discipline
under the handbook need not amount to a violation of Title VII, see
<I>Chalmers v. Quaker Oats</i> (7th Cir.), having to explain that to a
judge or jury could be avoided.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Sharon Grodin -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 11:41:33 1996<br>
Subject: Sexual Harassment Nuances<p>

In reply to Robert Zielinski's comment on investigating potentially
consensual behavior following a tip by others, I say, better safe
(checking it out) than sorry. The employer can be discreet by not
seeking to know more than is required to satisfy legitimate workplace
concerns. Even if the conduct is mutually consensual, the fact that it
has drawn attention by others in the workplace is some reason for the
employer to be concerned. Even in California.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 23:09:19 1996<br>
Subject: Sexual Harassment Nuances<p>

I'd be interested to know what you-all think of legislation currently
pending in Sacramento which would extend the employer's responsibility
with respect ot sexual harassment to include independent contractors.
This issue will be brought before our Board of Directors quite soon.<p>

<hr><p>

