<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>No Solicitation</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Jerry Morales -- Snell & Wilmer - Phoenix<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 17:31:26 1996<br>
Subject: No Solicitation<p>

Last Append: Sun Jan 21 12:31:58 1996<p>

What about no solicitation/no distribution/no displays policies?
Did you see the 6th Cir[cuit] decision in <I> NLRB v. Mead </i>
1/16 dlr? Can the employer protect himself here?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 01:16:31 1996<br>
Subject: no solicitation<p>

Surely you mean himself or herself.<p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 03:00:55 1996<br>
Subject: samples in library<p>

Jerry has graciously contributed a 
<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/solicit.html">
sample policy</a> -- check out the seminar library.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jerry Morales -- Snell & Wilmer - Phoenix<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 10:51:15 1996<br>
Subject: no solicitation<p>

actually i meant itself.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 00:37:48 1996<br>
Subject: touche<p>

sorry, dru -- but i think jerry "got 'cha"<p>

<g><p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 13:22:18 1996<br>
Subject: Policies<p>

Returning to the original question, we have always cautioned employers
that the vagaries of NLRB [National Labor Relations Board] and court
pronouncements on solicitation rules create certain unavoidable risks in
drafting any written policy on this issue. Nevertheless, for at least
the last 10 years, the Board has been fairly consistent on the "working
time" (for solicitation by employees) and "working areas" (for
distribution) formulation and our model policy on these points has had
no difficulty. The <I>Mead</i> case dealt with a slightly different
issue -- buttons and t-shirts -- on which the NLRB has developed
different rules prohibiting total bans, and which the employer there
tried unsuccessfully to get away with. We do not recommend publishing
policies which contradict NLRB law. Another area where the rules are
still a little unsettled is the prohibition of soliciting by
non-employees, post-Lechmere, at least for some employers who have
special access issues, and for other employers who want to discriminate
in favor of selected (usually charitable) solicitors.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 23:14:09 1996<br>
Subject:  no solicitation<p>

So how does an employer provide in its policies for access for
charitable or community organizations without opening up its facilities
to everyone?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 12:31:58 1996<br>
Subject: United Way Ghosts<p>

Ted, thanks for raising this issue. I think it's still quite thorny.<p>

In the '70s and early '80s, back before the shenanigans of its
now-exiled leader Wm. Aramony finally hit mainstream press, United Way
used <I>unbelievable</i> tactics to get exclusive rights to solicit at
worksites -- esp. large corporate sites. Many other major charities --
including the Am Heart Assn and Am Cancer Society -- were effectively
shut out of many worksites.<p>

I know it's better now, but the question remains: how does an employer
"do good" by allowing on-site solitications or payroll deductions,
without "doing harm" by overt or subtle pressure on employees to
contribute, and/or by shutting everybody out or only supporting
"establishment" charities? (e.g., When I was a graduate student working
three jobs to stay in school, and working as a cashier at a major
supermarket chain, my supervisor <I>intensely</i> pressured me to
contribute my "fair share" so his dept. would have "100%.")<p>

One solution that has emerged that I think works well is "employer
matches" to employee donations. It is less coersive, and can be
structured so that the employer and employee have much more choice.<p>

And this is just anecdotal, but I sense that, at least in smaller
companies, priority is given to charities where employees are actively
volunteering. Should that be a criteria? And I also see companies taking
on charitable projects as a company -- where everybody dives in and does
more than just write checks. Maybe a "cafeteria" plan of several choices
is the way to go -- but is that impractical? Hard to administer?<p> 

<hr><p>



