<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Duty of Loyalty</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Jerry Morales -- Snell & Wilmer - Phoenix<br>
Date: Thu Jan 18 17:35:07 1996<br>
Subject: duty of loyalty<p>

Last Append: Thu Jan 25 11:30:21 1996<p>

Should the handbook include an explanation of the employee's duty
to the employer before and after the employment?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 23:35:09 1996<br>
Subject: duty of loyalty<p>

There are several "loyalty" issues that should be covered: No conflicts
of interest, No insider trading, At employment there should be a
confidentiality agreement signed, and the employee should be reminded of
the importance of maintaining confidential information in confidence
during and after employment. It is also appropriate to do some
education about not inadvertently revealing trade secrets to competitors
or the press.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Thu Jan 25 09:17:39 1996<br>
Subject: Loyalty <p>

Jerry's question raises an issue arising out of the Supreme Court's
<I>Town & Country</i> decision which found paid union organizers to be
"employees," and put off questions of what constitutes a conflict of
interest in the context of union organizing. The Court decision arguably
allows employers to enforce a duty of loyalty, but employers are left
entirely at sea as to what that means or how they can enforce it. <I>See
also Willmar Electric v. NLRB</i> (D.C. Cir. 1993). The safest approach
would be to define the duty using the traditional types of policies set
forth in the preceding comment, particularly where it can be shown that
such policies are commonplace in firms who are unconcerned about union
organizing. Some of the nastier tactics being used by union salts,
however, may not be fully covered by such policies, and it is unclear
what the NLRB will tolerate. For example, whether employers can insist
that employees not solicit co-workers to quit (believe it or not) is an
issue now pending before the Board. The IBEW manual frankly states that
one of their goals is to drive non-union employers out of the market,
yet the Board policy implicitly requires employers to ignore this
"disloyal" objective when confronted with an IBEW organizer/applicant.
Until the after-effects of T&C are more settled, employers confronted
with salting must draft any loyalty policy with extreme care, and I have
not seen any such specific policy tested in this context.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jerry Morales -- Snell & Wilmer - Phoenix<br>
Date: Thu Jan 25 11:30:21 1996<br>
Subject: duty of loyalty<p>

With respect to solicitation to other employees to quit and or go to a
competitor see <I>Mccallister v. Kastella</i>, 1992 WL 14653 and
<I>Augut v. Aegis</i>, 565 N.E. 2d 415 dealing with employees breach of
fiduciary duties owed to their employers by attempting to "cripple the
employer or former employer". In the case of salters would the NLRA
[National Labor Relations Act] preempt state law?<p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A 
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit 
your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email
address of the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our online directory of
attorneys, <a href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.</I></P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
