<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Probationary Periods</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 20:28:05 1996<br>
Subject: Probationary Periods<p>

Last Append: Fri Jan 26 18:50:47 1996<p>

How about that hardy perennial, the probationary period? Are you
for or against having them in the handbook. Our view is that the
employer gets some mileage out of them, and most employees and
EEO agents seem to understand that a short service employee has
less ability to complain about a discharge in general, and
particularly if there is a clearly stated probationary
requirement. At the same time, we make clear that completion of
the probation (introductory period, whatever) does not alter the
employee's
<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/workplace/660.html">
at will</a> status, which strikes some people as
inconsistent, but it seems to work. Perhaps as important, but
often overlooked, is a provision that the probation can be
extended at the discretion of the employer (so employees who get
past the "magic" day before the supervisor remembers to terminate
them cannot claim to have escaped probation). In the same vein,
and again overlooked, is that any review requirements imposed on
supervisors should be left open to more frequent or less frequent
occurrences than specified, because supervisors seem to never
meet the timetables specified in the handbook.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 12:57:50 1996<br>
Subject: Probationary Periods<p>

I think the bigger problem with probationary periods is the false
expectation they create. First, with employees, who think that if
they're off probation, it means something, regardless of the
disclaimer re: at-will. (And, I'd have to say, they would seem to
have a point: what <I>is</i> the difference between probation and
non-probation? Yes, of course, something about benefits and about
notice, but does it have any substantive significance? If not,
then why the label "probation"?) Second, with supervisors. They
<I>can't</i> terminate even probationary employees at whim; there are
EEO protections, as well as privacy protections, whistleblower
protections, public policy protections, implied contract
protections, etc. Supervisors tend to be sloppier with
probationary terminations because they think they can do it
freely, when in fact, they can't. It seems to me the EEOC (or
whoever) is just as understanding if the employer says, "This
brand new employee (only with us 3 months) just didn't seem to be
working out," as if the employer says, "This 'probationary'
employee just didn't seem to be working out."<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 13:46:31 1996<br>
Subject: orientation<p>

I think it was Mark Twain who said that when in doubt, resort to
the truth. Here, I think the truth is that the word "orientation"
fits the purpose of a "probationary period" without building in
any expectations that things will be different after the period
is over.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael Caldwell -- DeLong Caldwell - Atlanta <BR>
Date: Sun Jan 21 13:09:36 1996 <BR>
Subject: Probationary Periods <P>

I agree that "probationary period" conveys the wrong meaning to
employees and supervisors. I have my clients tell their employees
that they're always on probation -- in the sense that they always
have to prove their value to the department and the company on
the job -- just like their supervisors and managers, and
ultimately the Company have to prove their respective values to
the ultimate consumer of their seer vices. At the same time
orientation periods are of some use, if employees understand that
there are no commitments before or after the orientation period
ends. But then what is the significance of orientation? The
employee can always quit without prior notice if he or she finds
the job unpalatable. And, so long as the employer has made the
employee's "at will" status clear from the outset (like on the
employment application and in the opening paragraphs of the
handbook), the employer can still terminate an employee who
doesn't work out.<p>

<A HREF="mailto:mcaldw02@counsel.com">Michael A. Caldwell</a><br>
DeLong, Caldwell & Wisebram, L.L.C.<br>
Suite 1770 Resurgens Plaza<br>
945 East Paces Ferry Road N.E.<br>
Atlanta, GA. 30326<br>
(404)842-0555<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 16:06:20 1996<br>
Subject: it's psychological<p>

When someone first comes to work, they like the idea of a period
where they feel they can get their sea legs. Otherwise, you are
right that there is no legal purpose to the period. Perhaps
employers should rethink whether they should have such a
period.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 18:20:32 1996<br>
Subject: Familiarization not probation<p>

I recognize that employers have an emotional need to have an
introductory period for the new worker and the bosses to get to
know each other. However, calling it "probation" is sure death if
the employer wants to claim that the workers are employees at
will. You can try to satisfy the employers by calling the period
a "familiarization period" in which the employer and the employee
are getting to know each other, without hinting that the
employee's job security increases in any way after the initial
period comes to an end. I was able to sell this theory to my
clients while I was in practice, but that was awhile ago.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San
Francisco<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 23:28:28 1996<br>
Subject: Probationary Periods<p>

This leads into the thicket of "employee evaluation". I'd be interested
how you feel this should best be handled--what works and what doesn't,
and whether you actually practice in your own workplace what you preach
to your clients.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 12:11:46 1996<br>
Subject: Model Language<p>

I don't think we have a model "Probationary Period" clause in the
Workshop Library yet. Would a proponent of such policies like to step
forward with a sample? Thanks in advance.<p>

- Cloyd<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Matthew Vega -- Sirote & Permutt - Birmingham<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 21:36:47 1996<br>
Subject: Probationary Periods<p>

We advise clients to refer to the probationary period as an
"introductory period" to avoid application of state law cases (Alabama)
which have held that the term "probationary" suggests if the employee
survives the period he or she is "off probation" and therefore entitled
to "something more" (i.e., implied contract or promise of continued
employment).<p> 

We mention the introductory period in three places in an employee
handbook:<p><OL>

<LI>In the Employment Classification policy to distinguish regular
full-time employees and regular part-time employees from full-time or
part-time employees still in their introductory period who may not be
entitled to the same benefits;<p>

<LI>a separate Introductory Period policy with the double talk
disclaimer language I admit is confusing but deem crucial to defend
against the cases mentioned above (the company reserves the right to
terminate the employment relationship at-will before or after successful
completion of the introductory period); and<p>

<LI>In each benefit policy which differentiates the level of benefit
based on employment status. I will try to put models of these three
policies in the model section.</ol><p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Laura Hoguet -- Hoguet Newman Regal - New York<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 21:49:37 1996<br>
Subject: Probationary Periods<p>

For years I conscientiously removed probationary periods from clients'
draft manuals. Then I came to realize that, whatever the legal angles,
the idea of a trial period does have meaning in the workplace and people
generally understand that when you take a job, you are on probation
until they decide whether they want you. Also, benfits often don't
start, and vacation doesn't accrue, for some initial period. Now I try
to give clients the alternatives and, if they choose keep a probationary
period, accept their choice with a good grace.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 22:35:43 1996<br>
Subject: Model<p>

I will be happy to send Monica a copy of our language, which actually
uses the term "provisional" or "introductory" period, which doesn't make
any difference as far as I'm concerned. I second what Laura just said.
It may not be completely logical, but the probationary period has value,
so why not use it (with the proper qualifications mentioned above).<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 09:45:49 1996<br>
Subject: It's the Expectation!<p>

I still think the answer to Maurice's question is the false sense of
security on the part of management, false expectation on the part of the
post-probationary employee that probation (or privisional or
familiarization or orientation) periods create. Re: Dru's question about
performance evaluations: do you mean during the probationary period? If
not: (and to answer your easier question), yes, we at Corbett & Kane do
have a performance evaluation program for all but partners, that is, for
associates, support staff, legal assistants and administrators. And for
the most part, we try hard to practice what we preach, and sometimes we
even succeed!<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 18:50:47 1996<br>
Subject: What is probation?<p>

Bottom line in my view is that if the employer has a "probationary
period", the employee gains additional job security on completion of
probation than he or she had previously. That is certainly what
employees expect, and if they don't get it, they get upset and go see
lawyers. If the employer is not willing to give a greater degree of job
security (and that need be all the way to "good cause"), it should call
the introductory period something else.<p>

<hr><p>

