<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Reference Checks</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sat Jan 20 23:32:20 1996<br>
Subject: Reference Checks<p>

Last Append: Sun Jan 28 20:10:51 1996<p>

In light of cases such as the <I>Randi M. v. Livingston School
District</i> (Ca.) and the <I>Jerner v. Allstate Insurance</i>
(Fla.) cases, where the courts allowed misrepresentation claims
to proceed against former employers who did not fully disclose
misconduct of individuals they gave glowing references, what
should an employer provide in its handbook on this subject? Is it
still worth checking references when it is highly probable that
nothing meaningful will be learned? Should an employer continue
to give references? What ground rules should it follow?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 18:08:03 1996<br>
Subject: references<p>

Sad to say, but prudent employers have no choice other than to
give "references" that merely confirm that a person was employed
by them from date A to date B, period. They should not even
indicate whether the employee resigned or was terminated or
retired or whatever. Here in Missouri, there is a Service Letter
Statute that makes the employer state the reason that the
employee was terminated, but that is a rare situation.<p> 

I see no reason why the subject of references to future employers
should be mentioned in the employee handbook at all, but I could
be talked out of that view if someone else came up with a good
reason.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 23:22:38 1996<br>
Subject: Reference Checks<p> 

This is one of those areas where the reality simply doesn't comport with
the theory. In hiring someone, as we all know, telephone references
quite often reveal truly important things that dramatically alter an
otherwise rosy picture created by a resume, written letters of
recommendation and even an interview. Therefore, as an employer, I find
reference checks to be critical, and that most employers continue to be
astonishingly frank. Even when not frank, the tone of voice, the sort of
non-verbal communication of <STRONG>PROBLEM</strong> seems to come out
loud and clear. On the other side of the issue is the problem when you
are called for a reference by a good friend, say the Executive Director
of some struggling race discrimination non-profit who is hiring for a
critical position and who is truly relying on your word and to whom it
feels simply untenable to give the standard response. How is the
situation changed if the applicant has included named references on a
resume, or given them to you orally upon request?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Robert Zielinski -- Ross & Hardies - Chicago<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 18:11:39 1996<br>
Subject: Reference Checks<p>

One means which can be used to combat this problem is for the hiring
employer to require that the applicant sign a waiver of defamation type
liablity in favor of the employer from whom the reference will be
requested. While there are some problems in releasing the reference
from a liability that hasn't yet occurred, it can workinsome states and
with careful drafting. This doesn't directly solve the issue of
potential liability to third parites for "negligent reference" but if
you can truly tell all, maybe that problem recedes. Short of such a
system, it seems the safest thing to do is simply not give references at
all.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 01:08:27 1996<br>
Subject: Reference Checks<p>

I've toyed with the thought of giving departing employees a menu of
choices. That is, to tell the employee what the Company will say
regardless of whether or not the employee wants it released (e.g., dates
of employment, last position held), and then to give the employee (in
writing) the option of having the company release certain additional
information, such as the last performance rating. Of course, for this,
the employee would have to sign an authorization to release the
additional information. Then, when the reference request comes in (in
writing, of course, or else nothing is provided), the employer releases
the menu of choices (the menu itself, with the boxes checked or not
checked), and the information to be released. If the employee is
terminated for something serious (threats of violence, harassment,
embezzlement), that information would be provided regardless of the
employee's menu selection. If what's released is the truth (this
<I>IS</i> why the employee was fired), and the employee is advised of
the fact that this information will be released (so there are no
surprises), and the information is released only upon proper request (so
no invasion of privacy), what's the realistic risk? (Even in California,
where we do, after all, have a qualified privilege?)<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Hope Pomerantz -- Williams Caliri - Wayne<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 10:00:48 1996<br>
Subject: Reference Checks<p>

We ask our departing employees to sign a form which authorizes us to
give a reference to a potential future employer. If they fail to elect
or sign the form, we give nothing more than the standard information
regarding their dates of hire and termination, salary, position, etc.
The reference problem has become a thorny one. However, one possibility
is to ask the third-party who is requesting a substantive reference to
have the potential employee sign a waiver so that you can speak
honestly, albeit carefully. We have done this in the past, and it has
been successful.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 18:46:19 1996<br>
Subject: Good waivers?<p>

Do you all really think that those waivers that the employee/applicant
signs when hunting for a new job and under pressure to provide a
reference will be respected by a court? They look like they were signed
under duress to me.<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Sun Jan 28 13:09:22 1996<br>
Subject: Reference Checks<p>

Regardless of the merits of a reference policy, and we generally favor
the "neutral" reference in all but the most unusual cases, the question
for this panel should be what, if anything the handbook should say about
it. The Venable model proposes to say nothing unless the employer is
required to give references by applicable state law, because the
handbook is for employees, not those who (by definition) are former
employees. In addition, a statement that only neutral references will be
given can create problems if a supervisor violates the policy. Having
said that a reference policy is not necessary, we have drafted or
approved carefully worded policies for some clients who prefer to say
something on the subject. The policies can serve the limited purpose of
putting employees on notice that their employer accepts no obligation to
provide them with references, or state that a release from the employee
will be required, etc.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sun Jan 28 20:10:51 1996<br>
Subject:  Reference Checks<p>

While the advisability of discussing the employer's views of references
in the handbook might be argued, for the reasons stated above, some
employers include them to advise managers of its expectations, and to
have something these managers can point to when they decline to give
references. That said, it certainly could be contained in a manager's
handbook or in formal HR policies.<p>

<hr><p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your
question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email address of
the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
