<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Handbook Versus Goals</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br>
Date: Fri Jan 19 02:53:27 1996<br>
Subject: Handbooks v. Goals<p>

Last Append:Sun Jan 21 22:43:27 1996<p>

Many companies have adopted strong policies against
discrimination on the basis of race, sex, etc...<p>

And many employers have pledged to actively increase opptys for
women, minorities, gays, disabled, etc...<p>

What should be in <I>handbooks</i> and what should be
<I>goals</i> or philosophies articlulated elsewhere.<p>
For example, many SF [San Francisco] employers have adopted the
Bar Assn. of SF's minority goals and timetables. Do these belong
in employee handbooks -- or outside -- and why?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 22:43:27 1996<br>
Subject: Handbooks v. Goals<p>

I know a great deal more about the "goals" approach than about personnel
manuals per se, but our bar association spends a huge amount of time
trying to persuade firms to adopt concrete policies and goals which are
intended to make for an environment more hospitable and conducive to
diversity. I suppose that the two approaches should increasingly
intersect. For example, in the sexual orientation area, a set of
aspirational goals adopted and sent out to our 400 sponsor firms and
corp. law depts. included extention of bereavement and sick leave, as
well as health care coverage, to cover domestic partners, as well as a
series of policies about "family" attendance at firm social events,
recognition of holidays that are significant to the gay/lesbian
community, firm payment of dues of gay/lesbian bar ass'ns and the like.
Very recently, a great many firms in San Francisco have jumped on the
bandwagon of a few earlier pioneers in providing domestic partner
ins[urance] coverage, and their insistence on including this has abruptly
changed the climate for health insurance companies offerring it (in part
because their experience in offering it to large public employers has
proven to be de minimis). Obviously, once non-discrimination takes the
form of a tangible employee benefit in an organization, it must properly
be in the personnel manual, but less tangible hortatory or aspirational
matters are rarely found beyond the required non-discrimination jargon. I
should note, though, that even though the tangible, concrete policies in
the manual should include part-time policies for childcare, eldercare,
and/or whatever else the firm may provide in this regard, it is my
impression that even firms which have publicly stated that they have
adopted our bar's 
<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/altwork.html">
Model Flexible Worktime Policy</a> have not necessarily
put it into their manual, and, therefore, most people in the firm don't
know about it, which may or may not be why it's not there. (the guts of
the policy is to provide for a presumption for part time work, at pro
rata pay, for BOTH partners and associates, without going off the
partnership track). Our bar's Goals and Timetables for Minority Hiring
and Advancement might well go in as examples of efforts the firm has
made in aid of its commitment to non-discrimination. I know the firms
use their signing up to the Goals (and 100 of them did) in their
promotional literature in law school recruitment.<p>

<hr><p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your
question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email address of
the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
