<html><head><title>The Ultimate Employee Handbook</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>[What is the Correct] Level of Detail in Policies?</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Admin Todd Thomas -- Brouse & McDowell<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 14:01:05 1996<br>
Subject: Level of Detail in Policies<p>

Last Append: Tue Jan 23 21:49:46 1996<p>

When writing policies, is less better than providing extensive
detail? I fear either being too vague, or limiting coverage of
policies to only situations specified in a policy.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Sun Jan 21 16:39:39 1996<br>
Subject: this is a tension...<p>

in all hanbooks. However, I take the view -- sort of like the
thesis in the book <I>The Death of Common Sense</i> -- that
general principles are bettter than trying to anticipate each and
every situation which might arise.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br> 
Date: Sun Jan 21 18:10:37 1996<br> 
Subject: that depends....<p>

On some matters, such as vacation policy or sick leave, I believe
that extensive detail is both necessary and appropriate. On
discipline policy, which is where the employer can get into
trouble, prudence would dictate only general statements.<p>

<hr><p>


Appended by: Matthew Vega -- Sirote & Permutt - Birmingham<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 21:49:46 1996<br>
Subject: Level of Detail in Policies<p>

I agree simple is best...however handbooks written like executive
summaries tend to cut corners, leaving out crucial disclaimer language.
Shorter is not always clearer. Contingencies should be anticipated in
advance to ensure consistent and fair application of policies
(especially with regard to leave policies, and hours of work policies).
The handbook should be detailed enough that the employer does not have
to prepare a second administrative manual to implement the policy
(centralizing company policy is invaluable). The only exception I can
think of to this rule is benefit policies (quick reference to insurance
booklets, etc. is appropriate in an employee handbook I think). Another
place I think the shorter the better is the Employee Obligations section
of the handbook. Disciplinary policies and General Workplace Rules of
Conduct policies should not attempt to be exhaustive but should provide
enough detail and examples to be useful while at the same time
preserving the discretion of management (i.e. progressive discipline not
a formal grievance procedure, don't lock management into a specific
disciplinary actions for a specific act of misconduct).<p> 

<hr><p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your
question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p>
<P><I>To look up the email address of
the lawyers participating in this discussion, use
our online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer
Search</a>.

</P></I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><br>
