<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Wrongful Demotion - Scott v. PG&E</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 13:54:36 1996<br>
Subject: Wrongful Demotion-Scott v. PG&E<p>

Last Append: Mon Jan 22 16:35:19 1996<p>

<H4>[The following comment was submitted by a visitor to the workshop
"echo" on the Court TV Small Business Law Center. See the thread
"Welcome to the Workshop" for more information, or visit the site
on the Web at: http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/]</h4>

NAME=Paul W. Hicks<br>
TITLE=Mgr., Human Resource Services<br>
EMAIL=pwhfny@napanet.net<br>
COMPANY=Payroll Masters<p>

QUESTION=Please comment on <I>Scott v. [Pacific Gas &
Electric</i>, 904 P.2d 834 (Cal. 1995)] and liability [for]
wrongful *demotion* based on an implied-in-fact contract.<p>

Thank You<br>
Paul W. Hicks<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 16:35:19 1996<br>
Subject: Scott meaning<p>

In Scott, as I recall, the employer specifically mentioned
"demotion" in its handbook as a form of discipline. Thus, it got
caught up in the "good cause" requirements.<p> 

The troublesome issue is whether any discipline short of
discharge should be judicially reviewable. Scott said all
discipline could be attacked in court, and I believe that is a
very bad result.<p>

<hr><p>
