<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Domestic Partner Benefits</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 15:22:03 1996<br>
Subject: Domestic Partner Benefits<p>

Last Append: Wed Jan 24 01:14:52 1996<p>

Dru Ramey has provided us with an excellent <A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/domestic.html">
Model Domestic Partner Health Benefits policy</a> that can be
found in the Workshop library. Today, I received the following
message from the BENEFITS-L listserv mailing list on the
Internet:<p>

<hr>

From: Marzec Mark E Internet<br> 
Date: Mon, 22 Jan 96 15:06:49 EST<br> 
Subject: HEALTH BENEFITS FOR EMPLOYEE'S DOMESTIC PARTNER
ARE TAXABLE TO EMPLOYEE.<p>

Has anyone else seen the private letter ruling (LTR 9603011)
released last Friday (1/19/96) in which the Service has ruled that
health benefits provided to an employee's domestic partner, who
does not qualify as a spouse under state law or as a dependent
under section 152(a), will be taxable as wages to the
employee?<p>

This would appear to give problems to companies who have
implemented such benefits nationwide.<p>

Senders Internet Address benefits-l@frank.mtsu.edu<p>

<hr>

Does anyone think, in light of this ruling, that any
handbook that includes a domestic partners health benefits
description should be redrafted to reflect the anticipated tax
consequences of the plan?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 01:14:52 1996<br>
Subject: Domestic Partner Benefits<p>

Our Bar has considered that issue, and we assumed that the benefit would
be taxable. It, therefore, came before our Board as to whether our model
policy should include language indicating that it might well be taxable
and that some employers have opted to pay additional salary to the
employee in question so as to achieve full economic parity with married
employees. However, one general counsel of a very large bank and several
members of large firm management committees objected to inclusion of
such language, maintaining that this would put very large employers in
an untenable situation, that there are all kinds of inequities in the
tax laws that have an impact on employees and, therefore, that this is a
slippery slope. The Board ultimtely deferred to this position, though a
substantial minority did not concur. I should note that BASF itself coun
not, until recently get its insurer to pay for domestic partner coverage
for BASF staff members, so we paid the employees in question an amount
representing the premium for the individual policy AND an additional
amount representing the tax hit on that.<p>

<hr><p>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A 
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit 
your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email
address of the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our online directory of
attorneys, <a href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.</I></P>
