<html><head><title> The Ultimate Employee Handbook</title> </head> <BODY
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005"> <IMG
SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0> <BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Employee E-Mail Encryption</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - New Jersey<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 12:45:57 1996<br>
Subject: Employee E-Mail Encryption<p>

Last Append: Thu Jan 25 07:45:20 1996<p>

At Cloyd's suggestion, I'd like to start a new thread on the subject of
how the employer should address the issue of employee encryption of
e-mail on the Company LAN, when writing the Employee Handbook's chapter
on Company E-Mail (and VoiceMail) policy.<p> 

This question is only partially inspired by my attendance at the RSA
Data Security Conference (on encryption) last week in San Francisco.
Clients have been raising this issue for over a year now.<p> 

The scenario would arise in the context of a fairly typical e-mail
policy, namely: The LAN is the property of the company, to be used
primarily for company purposes, and only incidentally for personal
purposes, to the extent consistent with company purposes.<p> 

The policy would then go on to rebut the expectation of privacy with
respect to stored e-mail messages, warning that employees should not
entrust personal confidences to the LAN, and that the employer retains
the full right to monitor stored (but not to intercept) e-mail messages
(and voicemail messages), as permitted by 18 U.S.C. 2701(c)(1).<p> 

At that point, let's assume the policy goes silent, and omits to specify
whether the employees are permitted to use private systems of encryption
on the LAN. Some employees then begin chatting back and forth with their
private copies of RSA or PGP, and similarly encrypted messages to and
from external e-mail addresses begin to appear.<p> 

What concerns should the Company have, and what solutions might be
proposed by you the Ultimate Handbook advisor?<p> 

Let's simply the question by assuming that the Company is in the private
sector, and in an industry unrelated to law enforcement, defense or
national security.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - Newark<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 08:52:48 1996<br>
Subject: E-Mail Address<p>

Here's my e-mail address, which I forgot to include:<p>
<A HREF="mailto:5338481@mcimail.com">5338481@mcimail.com</a><p>
Chas Merrill, McCarter & English, Newark NJ<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 09:31:33 1996<br>
Subject: Just forbid it?<p>

Is there any reason an employer should not just forbid the unauthorized
use of encryption? While such a policy might fly in the face of a
company's corporate culture, concept of retaining the right to monitor
email is meaningless if the company can't decrypt the email.<p> 

"Authorized use" might be defined to include any use so long as the
employee has escrowed his encryption key with the company. But
enforcement of such a policy might be difficult.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods<br>
Date: Mon, 22 Jan 96 20:59<br>
Subject: Employee E-Mail Encryption<p>

If the encrypted material is discovered, I assume that the policy would
then be modified to specifically say that no employee may place
encrypted material on a company computer unless specifically authorized
to do so.<p> 

A rule prohibiting all personal use would cover this situation, but I
think that such a policy would be viewed as unreasonable. On the other
hand, a policy allowing "reasonable" use of company computing assets for
personal use is subject to abuse. Nonetheless, I would opt for a policy
allowing for reasonable personal use that does not interference with job
performance, with the caveat that all material placed on the computer
must be readable by the company and may be read by the company.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - Newark<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 23:01:54 1996<br>
Subject: Commercial Key Escrow<p>

Although I am a fan of cryptography, I agree with both Cloyd Laporte and
Ted Banks, that it is generally too risky for a Company to allow
employees to use robust encryption on the Company system, unless there
is some mechanism for the Company to have authorized access to the
decryption key.<p> 

A document or message encrypted for privacy with industrial-strength
public-key crypto such as PGP or RSA is gone virtually <I>forever</i> if
the decryption key is not available. Some of the nightmares are:<p><OL> 

<LI>the employee uses her own key-pair to encrypt company info, and
loses her decrypting private key;<p> 

<LI>the employee sends company info to another employee, encrypted with
the public key of the other employee, and that other employee loses his
private key;<p> 

<LI>encrypted messages with attached encrypted documents are discovered,
addressed to suspicious external addresses where there might be interest
in trade secrets, and the sending employee fails or refuses to furnish
the key;<p> 

<LI>disgruntled or at-risk employee systematically encrypts company info
with an ace-in-the-hole blackmail motive;<p> 

<LI>Company is served with valid subpoena or court order for company
data which is unrecoverably encrypted by an employee who is dead, fired,
or recalcitrant.</ol><p> 

Some problems with a flat prohibition policy arise from the company's
legitimate need for secure electronic communication and transmission of
electronic documents, with the currently insecure Internet the only
available company channel, and what to do when senior management decides
that the prohibition on encryption does not apply to senior
management.<p> 

An emerging technological compromise which bears close watching is the
concept of "commercial key escrow," which is analogous to the hated
"Clipper Chip" Escrow Encryption Standard proposed by the Clinton
Administration on April 16, 1993, but with important differences:<p><OL>

<LI>the Company rather than the government holds the escrowed keys;<p> 

<LI>the due process rules for release of escrow are decided by the
Company rather than the Government;<p> 

<LI>the encryption algorithms are the Company's choice, not the
Government's Skipjack algorithm;<p> 

<LI>unlike Clipper, which escrowed the <I>permanent</i> private keys of
the device/user and compromised that private key for all past and future
messages using that key, the commercial scheme escrows only the
<I>session key</i> of each message, which compromises only that message,
not past or future messages.</ol><p> 

With such commercial key escrow technology installed, the e-mail policy
would provide that no encryption will be permitted, except the
encryption officially endorsed and supported by the company with the
escrow feature. The official escrowed cryptosystem would be readily
available to any employee in a position to need legitimate security for
company info.<p> 

Without such technology, the company e-mail policy should probably
resemble the laws of France and Russia, which provide basically that
encryption shall not be used without advance approval and deposit of the
decryption keys with the security establishment. If permission is
granted, the encryption encountered on the LAN will need to be
constantly tested with the deposited keys, to control the problem of
undetected change of keys. This scenario is decidedly awkward, and it is
probably unwise, in the absence of a controlled commercial key escrow
scheme, to allow any encryption whatsoever on the Company's system.<p> 

<hr><p>



Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 10:13:27 1996<br>
Subject: Enforcement<p>

I agree having a policy requiring employees to use the company's
commercial key escrow system would help address some of the problems you
have outlined (Care to draft a sample one for our Handbook Library?). I
also think such a policy might help a company escape a "spoliation"
argument if it is unable to comply with a subpoena because an employee
has used unauthorized encryption techniques.<p> 

But I still see a major problem with enforcement. How does the
commercial system let the company monitor compliance? Does somebody (or
some software) have to examine every file on the server to ensure that
it is encrypted only with the authorized commercial escrow software?
What if I, the disgruntled employee, first encrypt with my personal copy
of PGP, and then re-encrypt with the commercial key escrow?!<p> 

At some point, you have to trust your employees and accept that you are
vulnerable.<p> 

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - Newark<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 12:10:08 1996<br>
Subject: Enforcement<p>

The sample language regarding encryption is pretty brief, and will look
a little lonely all by itself in the library. Following my summary of a
typical e-mail policy in the first posting in this thread, It's to the
effect of: "Thou shalt not use any encryption on the Company's system
with express prior written permission, and strict compliance with the
terms of such prior written permission." The style and tone will depend
on the Corporate Culture and level of technology, as will the content of
the permission, if it is ever given.<p> 

Cloyd, these enforcement questions are not unique to the online
encrypted environment. How do you know your employees are not secretly
destroying company data? How do you know that your employees are not
shipping out trade secrets written on their underwear?<p> 

It sure helps to have a clear statement that such activity is not
permitted, which helps guide the vast majority of your employees who are
honest and loyal, but may be receiving confusing signals in the absence
of a clear e-mail policy saying that departure will be rewarded by
discipline or dismissal.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - Newark<br>
Date: Thu Jan 25 07:45:20 1996<br>
Subject: Samp Pol Employee Encryption <p>

As my sample policy language for employee encryption, I hereby
incorporate by reference as a starting point, the excellent "Electronic
Media and Services: Scope of Use" E-mail policy by Margaret Philips of
DHL Systems, Inc., with this paragraph 2.5 in place of the existing
paragraph 2.5:<p>

"2.5 In order to ensure the company's continuous access to information
on the company's system, no employee shall use personal hardware or
software to encrypt any e-mail or voicemail, or any other data stored in
or communicated by the company's system of electronic media, except in
accordance with express prior written permission from the company's
management."<p> 

I fear that if there is an attempt to spell out in the general policy
the circumstances and precautions warranting permission, it will
inevitably have loopholes and will need to be changed too often. General
rules for escrowing keys can be developed more easily in developing
sub-rules for certain classes of employees.<p>

If permission is granted to use truly robust public key encryption
algorithms such as 128-bit PGP or RSA, the private keys need to be
furnished in electronic form along with the pass phrase required for the
employee's operation of her private key, and the permission should make
it clear that management intends to spotcheck messages continuously to
make sure that the private key has not been superseded by another
public/private key pair.<p> 

The really bad news is that having the *private key of the sender* will
not decipher two-party messages because messages are encrypted for
privacy by using the *public key of the recipient* and decrypted by
using the *private key of the recipient*. So messages sent to
non-employees will need to be prohibited, and messages sent to employees
will need to prohibited unless the *recipient* has provided his private
key!! In two party messages the private key of the sender is used to
digitally *sign* messages, and there is almost never a legitimate reason
for the company to be able to digitally impersonate an employee. The
private key of the sender is most useful to control one-party encryption
of stored data.<p>

As discussed above in this thread, the only really effective method of
allowing robust public key crypto on the system and ensuring company
access is a company sponsored system of commercial key escrow of the
*session* key for each message, not the permanent private keys. Such a
system is now being marketed by Trusted Information Systems.<p>

<hr><p>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your
question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the
email address of the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our
online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.</I></P>
