<html><head><title> The Ultimate Employee Handbook Seminar</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Union Organizers -- Employees</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Jerry Morales -- Snell & Wilmer - Phoenix<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 12:55:36 1996<br>
Subject: union organizers-employees<p>

Last Append: Fri Jan 26 15:41:29 1996<p>

Does [the recent Supreme Court case] <I>Town and Country</i> render policies
which prohibit employees to be employed by another employer
unlawful?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Mon Jan 22 16:37:54 1996<br>
Subject: union organizers<p>

The Supreme Court tried to decide <I>Town and Country</i> narrowly,
limiting it only to a holding that union organizers can be "employees"
the same as everyone else. That being so, I believe there is still room
to argue that they are subject to the same prohibitions against other
employment as everyone else. Interesting question.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 09:47:32 1996<br>
Subject: More on Unions<p>

While we're on the topic of Unions, Panelist Maurice Baskin has provided
some sample anti-union handbook language for non-unionized companies.
<I>See <A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/unions.html"> A
Few Words About Unions</a></i> in the workshop library. Does anyone feel
that this language is inappropriate?<p>

My guess is that employers would like to put it in, and suggesting it
probably endears a lawyer to clients. But surely an employee is not
going to be swayed on the question of joining a union by language in a
handbook. And if a dispute later arises about whether an employer has
engaged in unfair labor practices, I would not like to have such a
document introduced in evidence.<p>



<hr><p>

Appended by: Richard U. Stubbs, Jr. -- Skoler Abbott - Springfield<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 17:10:07 1996<br>
Subject: Employer free speech<p>

This is still America and an employer has a right to give its general
opinion about unionization. If Section 8(c) of the NLRA means anything,
it's should give a company the right --without fear of a ULP--to voice a
non-threatening opinion that employees do not need a union. I have not
read Maurice's model statement, but I have no doubt he has tailored it
to state the point in a defensible manner.<p> 

On the proposition that employees don't give squat about what an
employer thinks about unions: I'm not sure that's true. I know of
several workplaces where employees signed authorization cards without
any idea that this might rub their employer the wrong way. The
non-union-and-proud-of-it statement may, subconsciously, convince some
employees that supporting a union is disloyal to a somewhat likeable
boss.<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 22:48:05 1996<br>
Subject: Unions<p>

Since you asked --<p>

We actually provide two options, one a one-paragraph, generally worded
statement and the other a detailed discussion of unions, and I would say
that most of our clients choose the third option of saying nothing.
Regrettably, our experience has been that some employees, when
confronted by card-signing activity, indeed allow themselves to be
pressured into signing a union card on the basis of a misguided belief
that the employer "doesn't care" about the issue one way or the other --
based on the employer's silence. Having the employer's view (protected
by 8(c) of the Act as noted above) expressed in the handbook may avoid
that circumstance. A legal point -- employers must be careful in their
acknowledgement forms not to impose a requirement that the employees
"adhere" to everything in the handbook, because the NLRB held a couple
of years ago that such a requirement, in the context of a policy on
unions, was unlawfully coercive.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Drucilla Stender Ramey -- Bar Assoc. of S.F. - San Francisco<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 01:26:52 1996<br>
Subject: union organizers-employees<p>

I think that regardless of the language in which this kind of thing is
couched, most employees would feel the "chill", whether intended by the
employer or not. Regardless of how the employee felt about unions in
general or about some particular union situation which happens to be
developing, I think the chilling effect of such language might go well
beyond the question of unions and more broadly chill the
employee-employer relationship as a whole.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Richard U. Stubbs, Jr. -- Skoler Abbott - Springfield<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 15:41:29 1996<br>
Subject: Feeling the "chill"<p>

Frankly, if an otherwise non-threatening statement against unions tends
to "chill" some skittish employees anyway, so much the better for the
employer.<p>

<hr>

