<H2>Whistle Blower Language</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 17:00:01 1996<br>
Subject: Whistleblower Language?<p>

Last Append: Tue Jan 23 23:15:05 1996<p>

Does anyone include a "whistle blower" policy in a handbook? Does it
make sense to have a written policy about complaining about company
behavior to governmental/regulatory agencies? What would such a policy
look like?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Tue Jan 23 23:15:05 1996<br>
Subject:  Whistleblower Language?<p>

A number of companies, including defense employers, have anonymous
"hotlines" they encourage employees to call to report ethics violations
or illegal acts. Beyond that, I would think an open door complaint
policy, coupled with a no-retaliation commitment by the employer, would
accomplish the same result.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Thu Jan 25 15:16:37 1996<br>
Subject: New Library File<p>

Gloria Ju, Associate Editor at the Alexander Hamilton Institute, Inc,
provided us with some <A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/whistlju.html"> Whistle
Blower handbook language</a> from her companies publication, <I>Employee
Handbook Audit.</i> You can find it in our workshop library.<p>


<hr><p>

