<H2>Arbitration [Clauses]</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br> 
Date: Wed Jan 24 16:08:30 1996<br> 
Subject: Arbitration<p>

Last Append: Sat Feb  3 20:56:19 1996<p>

Should not the handbook have a clause providing a grievance procedure
leading to mandatory arbitration for any claims of handbook violation?
Whether or not the handbook is filled with disclaimers, arbitration
provides an avenue for the disgruntled employee that is private and
relatively inexpensive. I think it should be a feature of every
handbook.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 22:46:03 1996<br>
Subject: Arbitration<p>

Having some sort of dispute resolution procedure available to employees
is a good idea; making it "arbitration" is probably inappropriate.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 18:27:07 1996<br>
Subject: Why inappropriate?<p>

Why is having a dispute resolution procedure ending in arbitration
inappropriate? If you want to keep employee disputes out of court, there
has to a procedure ending in a final determination by an independent
neutral body. There is, IMHO, no independent neutral body that is more
suitable than arbitration.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 23:35:28 1996<br>
Subject:  Arbitration<p>

One concern might be that the employer might face a significant increase
in claims being brought and pursued to arbitration, claims that might
not otherwise be significant enough to engender lawsuits. Also,
ADR[Alternative Dispute Resolution] is always an option once in court,
so the employer can wait until then to seek arbitration or mediation.<p>

Perhaps more significantly, as indicated in another thread, there is a
question whether an agreemeent to arbitrate <I>all</i> claims actually
means that. There is not much gained by the employer if, for example,
statutory claims of discrimination, or for wage payments etc. can still
be brought in court.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Sun Jan 28 12:55:23 1996<br>
Subject: Arbitration<p>

The subject of arbitration has been discussed several times in the Labor
and Employment Law discussion group, and a substantial body of case law
has developed on the issue. A growing number of employers believe that
some form of binding ADR is necessary to reduce litigation costs. A
number of courts have deferred to procedurally fair arbitration
agreements, since the <I>Gilmer</i> case. We have included a sample
grievance procedure in our model handbook, but at present, it does not
end in arbitration and most of our clients do not put in such a
requirement. They seem to fear, as noted above, that offering low-cost
arbitration of employment disputes will actually lead to increased
litigation. That could change soon, as more and more employers who do
not have ADR procedures in place are hit with court actions.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Sun Jan 28 14:46:03 1996<br>
Subject: implementation<p>

The insertion of an arbitration clause in a handbook--standing alone--is
not a good idea. Rather, the arbitration agreement should be included in
the handbook as one component of an overarching alternate dispute
resolution procedure. For instance, many employers have an open door
policy in the handbook. This could be intergrated with an arbitration
policy and the employees told that they need to exhaust the open door
policy before resorting to arbitration. Also, the policy must be placed
in context for the employees or they will think that the employer is
trying to do you know what to them. So, some language on why arbitration
is a good idea(litigation only makes lawyers rich, etc.)needs to be put
in the handbook.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Robert Zielinski -- Ross & Hardies - Chicago<br>
Date: Tue Jan 30 02:53:13 1996<br>
Subject: Arbitration<p>

IMO arbitration clauses in handbooks are a bad idea. My guess is that
courts will continue to ratchet back on [the] <I>Gilmer</i> [case] so
that virtually no statutory or common law public policy claims are
arbitrable. So there will be little benefit. On top of that, I think the
existence of an arbitration clause in a handbook would go a long way
toward establishing the handbook as a binding contract of employment. If
the employer did not really intend to be bound in a leglaistic way to
the handbook terms, what is there to arbitrate? The only available
inference is that the Company intended to relinquish its discretion and
that therefore some more objective standards such as just cause are to
be applied.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 09:46:07 1996<br>
Subject: Arbitration<p>

I've actually been surprised by the receptivity of California courts to
mandatory arbitration in employment contracts -- even employee
handbooks. I agree that including an arbitration provision "converts" a
handbook to a contract, and such handbooks should be written with that
in mind. Several of our Silicon Valley clients have opted for
arbitration, with their eyes open -- and those that have done so seem
remarkably satisified with it. It's important to make clear from the
outset that the employer's being in arbitration does
<STRONG>not</strong> mean that the employer will win, or that the
employer can limit its damages or shorten the statute of limitations.
It's a <STRONG>forum</strong>[the place where the dispute is decided]
issue, and nothing else. And it does mean that the employer may have to
"litigate" the case having less knowledge about the employee's claim
than has the employee. It also means faster resolution. And it
substantially reduces the likelihood of a runaway verdict. (Especially
if the process provides for selection of arbitrators knowledgeable in
employment law, such as through the AAA's [American Arbitration
Association's] Employment Dispute arbitration rules.) To paraphrase the
VP of HR of one client, who went through a grueling 2-day arbitration
hearing in a wrongful termination case: However it comes out, it was
still much better than being in court. And in this case, the employer
won.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 23:55:34 1996<br>
Subject: Arbitration<p>

Thank you, Judith. It is comforting to know that your real experiences
validated my theoretical conclusions.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Allan Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 16:13:17 1996<br>
Subject: Separate Agreement<p>

Unless the handbook is a contract of employment, I do not believe that
the mere inclusion of arbitration in the handbook is as enforcable as a
separately signed agreement providing for the final and binding
arbiration of all employment disputes.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Fri Feb  2 09:34:22 1996<br>
Subject: Handbook v. Contract<p>

Absolutely.  I agree completely.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sat Feb  3 20:56:19 1996<br>
Subject:  Handbook v. Contract<p>

Couldn't the employer insert the arbitration language in some other
document which already is an agreement, e.g., the trade secrets
agreement, thereby avoiding making the handbook a contract? What is the
downside to that approach?<p>

Ted Borromeo<p>

<hr><p>

