<H2>Monitoring Compliance</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 10:29:36 1996<br>
Subject: Monitoring Compliance<p>

Last Append: Thu Feb  1 21:51:45 1996<p>

Not being a specialist in employment law, I wonder what dangers there
are to employers who put policies in handbooks and then fail to monitor
compliance. What happens when an employee is terminated for violating a
policy and it turns out that the policy is broadly ignored? Does it
matter whether the particular violation resulted in a loss to the
company? Should companies avoid inserting policies where it is difficult
to monitor or enforce compliance?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 10:01:55 1996<br>
Subject: Failing to comply<p>

There is a practical risk to the employer who says "this is what we do"
(or "don't do), and then who does otherwise. As a general rule, the
employer negates the effectiveness of the handbook at best, and exposes
itself (at least in California) to liability for bad faith and breach of
contract at worst. For example, the employer whose handbook says, "We
evaluate performance annually on the employee's anniversary date), and
then doesn't get around to it, may have independent liability for breach
of contract, and (more likely) will find its hands tied when it tries to
terminate an employee for poor performance. There is also the risk, of
course, of liability for discrimination if the employer enforces a
policy only against some employees. As a general rule: the
<STRONG>best</strong> of all worlds is a well-written handbook that the
employer follows; the <STRONG>worst</strong> is a handbook that the
employer fails to follow. In the middle is no handbook at all -- only a
basic set of benefit descriptions and the legally mandated distributions
and postings.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 21:51:45 1996<br>
Subject: Protecting Clients<p>

The best companies have excellent procedures, rigorously train their
supervisors to follow them, and carefully monitor compliance. The
typical company has some of these features, but nobody's perfect. The
client should be made to realize that nothing should go in the handbook
which they will not fully live up to, but if the handbook's language
preserves sufficient employer discretion and flexibility and does not
overpromise, even the "worst case" client will be protected from itself.
That should be the goal of every handbook provision (and management
lawyer).<p> 

<hr><p>

<hr><p> <P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your
question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the
emailaddress of the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our
online directory ofattorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.</I></P> 

