<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Internet-Online Service Use Policies</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>


From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 10:23:25 1996<br>
Subject: Internet-Online Service Use<p>

Last Append: Wed Jan 24 22:59:44 1996<p>

Does anyone have a model "Internet Use" or "Online Service Use"
policy? Recent surveys suggest that <I>most</i> web browsing is
taking place using company computer systems at the workplace. Of
course, this is not much different from personal use of the
telephone (though it might be less obvious to co-workers -- has
anyone seen the AOL commercial where the worker says "My boss
thinks I'm working on my PC, but actually, I'm goofing off on
AOL"?).<p>

But there are a few differences: One employer I know started to
get complaints from employees that some fellow employees were
displaying offensive graphics on their terminals. As mentioned in
another thread, the LAN can also be used for broad dissemination
of copyrighted works obtained from online services. If an
employee posts to a Usenet Newsgroup, should the company require
a disclaimer that the opinions expressed are those of the poster
and not the company?<p> 

On a related issue, how about policies regarding the installation
and use of personal software on company computers?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br>
Date: Wed Jan 24 22:59:44 1996<br>
Subject: Internet-Online Service Use<p>

Here's one approach that might be considered:<p>

Use of company provided Internet access is intended to be
primarily for business related purposes. Internet access is
monitored, and actual web-site connections are recorded.
Excessive use of company-provided Internet access for
non-business-related purposes will result in loss of access
privileges.<p>

Here's another possibility, in slightly less formal language:<p>

We're allowing you to use the Internet, but we trust that you
won't waste time at work doing stuff that has nothing to do with
our business. Our system automatically tracks the websites you
connect to, so we'll know if you are wasting time. We will warn
you after the first month if we see this stuff going on. If it
continues, we'll advise your boss, who will be pleased to get the
news, since that will mean that he can reduce his department
headcount by one, since you obviously have a lot of time to kill
and not enough work to do.<p>

<hr><p>


<P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit
your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the
