<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Does the ADA Trump Handbook Policy?</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Thu Jan 25 00:09:54 1996<br>
Subject: Does ADA trump Handbook?<p>

Last Append: Mon Feb  5 15:23:13 1996<p>

[The following comment was submitted by a visitor to the workshop "echo"
on the Court TV Small Business Law Center. See the thread "Welcome to
the Workshop" for more information, or visit the site on the Web at:
http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/]<p> 

NAME=Judi Sabo<br>
EMAIL=jls@sierra.net<p>

QUESTION=What are the legal issues regarding the following statement:
"Employees who fail to return to work upon the conclusion of any leave
of absence will be terminated from employment status." Does a policy
such as this exclude an employer from the ADA requirements of
accomodations if an employee qualifies for one?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br>
Date: Thu Jan 25 01:41:42 1996<br>
Subject: New docs in sem library<p>

I just posted into our seminar library two ADA documents that might be
of interest:<p><OL> 

<LI><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/adaprimr.html">A
primer by Mass. atty Richard Berger</a><p>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/basfada.html">A
survey from BASF</a></ol><p>

MB<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 18:40:17 1996<br>
Subject: ADA v. Handbook<p>

No matter what your handbook says, the employer must comply with ADA. If
the employee has a disability (which need not be the case for someone
returning from a leave of absence), the employer has a duty to
accomodate, if it can do without unreasonable hardship. Inability to
comply with the employer's handbook is not an unreasonable hardship.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 09:34:38 1996<br>
Subject: Does ADA trump Handbook? No.<p>

It is clear that an employer cannot avoid ADA obligations by creating a
policy purporting to permit it to do so. The ADA requires that employers
provide "reasonable accommodation" to qualified individuals with
disabilities -- and the regulations provide that "reasonable
accommodation" includes flexible leave policies. So. If an employee is
on leave due to a "disability" (which is likely), and the employee needs
a "reasonable" extention of the leave beyond the employer's established
maximum, the employer must "accommodate" the employee by granting the
request. Again, the limitation is the reasonableness of the duration of
the leave (objectively speaking), not an artificial cut-off.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 23:53:15 1996<br>
Subject: No or Yes<p>

Although Judith Keyes subject line states that ADA does not trump the
employer's handbook, the text of her message recognizes that the answer
is really "yes". In fact, the question is not, as she puts it, the
"reasonableness of the duration of the leave", it is whether the
employer can in fact accomodate the employee's need for a longer leave
without undue hardship. Even if the policy is generally reasonable, it
must give way to ADA unless undue hardship is involved. That's a trump
in my book.<p> 


<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Fri Feb  2 09:38:31 1996<br>
Subject: What's a trump?<p>

Not to quibble, but whether or not a long (unpaid) leave is an undue
hardship doesn't depend on the handbook! If an employer were to say, for
example, that 4 months was the "maximum" leave, and the disabled
employee said "I need 8, and then my therapy will be complete and I can
return to work" -- what difference does the handbook make? I think a
court's analysis as to how hard this 8-month period would be on the
employer would be made without regard to the handbook! But then, I
haven't played bridge in years.<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sat Feb  3 11:40:48 1996<br>
Subject:  Does ADA trump Handbook? No.<p>

The more typical and difficult situation is where the employee
repeatedly gets a doctor's note extending the leave. Is the employer
obligated in this situation to extend leave indefinitely? If the
employee has exhausted any disability leave benefits entitlement and
there are no service-related benefits accruing, so that the termination
is a mere administrative act, and the employer agrees to reconsider the
employee for rehire upon release to work, is there still an ADA issue?
(This assumes the termination policy applies the same way for
non-disability leaves).<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Susan Krell -- Jackson Lewis - Hartford<br>
Date: Sun Feb  4 21:59:11 1996<br>
Subject: ADA-Family and Medical Leave<p>

As to the issue of ADA/extension of leave...no discussion is complete
without considering the impact of the FMLA. Is the employee on an FMLA
leave? If so the leave will be extended for the FMLA period. The more
problematic issue is whether it is a reasonable accomodation for the
employer to allow additional leave time for someone who is claiming an
ADA disability but who has used all of the FMLA leave. The EEOC seems to
think that would be an appropriate accomodation but the courts have not
yet ruled on this issue. It will be a case by case analysis with no easy
answer to cover all situations.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Louis Storrow -- Louis A. Storrow - Carlsbad<br>
Date: Mon Feb  5 15:23:13 1996<br>
Subject: Back to the facts <p>

Doesn't the bottom line (after FMLA and/or state leave such as CFRA)
remain "reasonable accommodation" based on the specific facts? One
employee's extended absence may pose greater hardship than another. And
I think the handbook entry can only hurt (by establishing a minimum),
not help (because there is no max without facts).<p>

With apologies to J. Cochran...<p>

-- Lou Storrow<p>

