<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>[Employee] Evaluations</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Thu Jan 25 09:40:27 1996<br>
Subject: Evaluations<p>

Last Append: Sat Jan 27 00:01:47 1996<p>

Without getting into the subject of whether periodic employee
evaluations are good or bad, or what they should consist of (a
worthy seminar topic in its own right), there is one aspect of
this issue which creates a potential handbook problem, and where
I find an amazingly large number of handbooks to be deficient. It
is also easily correctable. The problem: the evaluation policy
(and this applies to probationary periods as well) states that
evaluations will be made at a specific time (annually, every six
months, whatever). Many employers (or their supervisors) then
lose track of the anniversary dates, or stop doing evaluations
altogether, or figure that a few days here or there wont make a
difference, or want to do a special evaluation sooner than the
anniversary. Subsequent discipline has been jeopardized in some
court decisions on the theory that the employee would have
improved if the promised evaluation had been delivered as
scheduled. The simple solution (after the statement that reviews
will "normally" be conducted every __ months) is to add:
"Performance reviews may be conducted more or less frequently, at
any time, in the Firm's discretion." [or in accordance with the
needs of the business, etc.]. Another answer, of course, is not
to promise specific evaluation dates at all, but most of our
clients have evaluation systems and want them to be regularly
administered, so the first answer allows that to occur while
preserving necessary flexibility for the employer.<p>


<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Borromeo -- Sun Microsystems - Mountain View<br>
Date: Sat Jan 27 00:01:47 1996<br>
Subject:  Another issue<p>

A colleague once remarked, only half-jokingly, that so many
evaluations are of the "walks on water with lead boots on"
variety that they are meaningless for performance feedback, and
only caused headaches to the employer in later litigation. His
solution: do away with mandatory or regular evaluations and
simply tell employees to assume that they are performing at an
"acceptable" level unless they are specifically told otherwise.
Reactions from the panelists?<p>

<hr> 
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your
question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the
email address of the lawyers participating in this discussion, use our
online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.


</BLOCKQUOTE>
