<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>General Provisions</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Michael P. Maslanka -- Clark, West - Dallas<br>
Date: Sun Jan 28 14:54:54 1996<br>
Subject: general provisions<p>

Last Append: Tue Jan 30 00:13:57 1996<p>

A couple of general ideas.<p>

First, do any of you use a general policy requiring co-operation of the
employee. We see this from time to time in a policy on investigation
into misconduct where the employee is told that he or she must
co-operate in any investigation and failure to do so may lead to
termination. I've seen one handbook where there was a separate section
on this issue and the employee told of the requirement that they
co-operate in all areas including helping the company in determining how
or even whether they should get benefits. Second, in a harassment
policy, some handbooks tell the employee that if they believe thay have
been harassed that they must report the conduct withing 48 hours. Of
course, the employe[r] still looks into any complaints made outside that
period, but the 48 hour deal is helpful in convincing a jury that the
employer is serious about harassment. Third, I think that polices
dealing with drugs, guns etc. need to have some provision in them on how
the contrband will be disposed of. (i.e. given to cops, returned (a gun)
to the employee etc. Any sample policies out there on this?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Tue Jan 30 00:13:57 1996<br>
Subject: general provisions<p>

I don't have any sample policies -- at least I don't think so; I'll shop
around. But I think the idea of a "duty to cooperate" policy is an
excellent one. The law (in California, at least) specifies a duty of
loyalty -- but a duty to cooperate makes all the sense in the world to
me. It could be very helpful in a sexual harassment investigation, for
example, where an employee may be under the mis-impression that he or
she has "the right to remain silent." Of course, in the public sector,
they may! But not in the private sector -- at least as far as I know. So
this sort of explicit mandate could be very effective. Thanks for the
idea.<p>

