<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Software Policy</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Anonymous Counsel Connect Member<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 14:10:44 1996<br>
Subject: Software Policy<p>

Last Append: Mon Feb  5 14:29:00 1996<p>

Does anybody have a policy on the use of unauthorized &/or unlicensed
software? Care to share?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - Newark<br>
Date: Fri Jan 26 15:43:25 1996<br>
Subject: Draft Policy<p>

As a baseline, how about:<p>

"Thou shalt not install or permit to be installed:<p>

(i) any software whatsoever on any device connected to the Company's
LAN, without the express prior written permission of the [insert title]
of the IS [information systems] Department;<p>

(ii) any unlicensed software on the Company's LAN or on Company-owned
standalone laptop or desktop workstations."<p>

[To be modified appropriately to conform to company policy and the tone
and vocabulary of the general e-mail policy]<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Anonymous Counsel Connect Member<br>
Date: Mon Jan 29 13:45:31 1996<br>
Subject: Hey Chas,<p>

I knew I could count on you. But what's the deal with this plain English
stuff? Are you sure we're allowed to do that?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Tue Jan 30 00:06:24 1996<br>
Subject: Plain English<p>

I am certain of it.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Charles Merrill -- McCarter & English - Newark<br>
Date: Tue Jan 30 07:48:42 1996<br>
Subject: Depends on Company Culture<p>

It doesn't have to be plain language. Obfuscation in accordance with
company or lawfirm culture is expressly permitted in the template.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Barry D. Weiss -- Gordon & Glickson - Chicago<br>
Date: Mon Feb  5 14:29:00 1996<br>
Subject: Software Policy<p>

Beyond a simple policy, you might be interested in the audit kits
available from Software Publishers Association (SPA) and Business
Software Alliance (BSA). And you might consider weaving the unlicensed
software topic into a broader information technology policy that
includes everything from internet tools, intellectual property policy,
electronic records retention and e-mail, to laptops and cell phones.<p>


