<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Discipline [Policy Language]</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Tue Jan 30 16:33:46 1996<br>
Subject: Discipline<p>

Last Append: Thu Feb  1 21:41:56 1996<p>

A number of the comments in the workshop to date have mentioned
that handbook language dealing with a company's discipline
policies -- what the company will do when an employee engages in
what the company considers misconduct -- is particularly
troublesome.<p> 

In addition to the appropriate dislclaimers about 
<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/workplace/660.html">
at-will employment</a>, <I>what policy language should be in the Ultimate
Employee Handbook regarding misconduct?</i><p>

Neil Bernstein has suggested that the policy should be very
general (Neil?). In the "Pitfalls" thread, Sharon Grodin writes:<p><OL> 

<LI>If it's personal, it should rarely be done in the
workplace;<p>

<LI>Anything done in the workplace presents a greater risk that
it will not be treated as private by the employer;<p> 

<LI>If personal use costs money (as with long-distance calls, use
of copiers, etc.), you should pay for it;<p> 

<LI>If it's potentially offensive to others in the workplace,
keep it out of the workplace;<p> 


<LI>If your use of the employer's communications media is potentially
embarassing or harmful to the employer, don't be surprised if your
employer wants to find out about it and wants you to stop. But then she
suggests that few clients would accept such plain language.</ol><p> 

So, what's the answer? Should an employer just say "Don't Lie, Cheat or
Steal because it may get you fired?"<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 09:53:39 1996<br>
Subject: Discipline-Why say anything?<p>

Sharon's my partner, so I'm biased: I hadn't seen her language until I
read it on-line, and I like it! But I guess the question I'd pose in
response to the main question is: other than what is required by statute
(that is, the no-harassment policy) -- why say anything? If an employer
intends to be at-will, really intends it, why not say only that? For
infractions like tardiness, the employer isn't going to fire the
employee the first time, so the one-on-one warning suffices to put the
employee on notice (or should), regardless of the handbook, that
<STRONG>that</strong> must be corrected. For more serious infractions,
who needs a handbook? It's a question, really -- and I'd be interested
in the thoughts of others. Why say anything at all?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 00:09:21 1996<br>
Subject: Discipline<p>

A handbook can serve one of two relatively inconsistent functions:<p><OL>

<LI>It can be a public relations document to convince employees that
this is a great place to work; or,<p>

<LI>it can be a litigation-support document to provide everyone with
consistent and unquestioned notice of their duties and the consequences
of not living up to them.</ol><p> 

If the handbook is to serve the first purpose, it can provide the
employees with great job security (and get them out of the "at will"
category) by spelling out the only conditions under which they will lose
their jobs. Most of us lawyers, however, think the handbook should be in
the second category. If that is your intention, the handbook should only
list a few of the more important and less self-evident violations and
their consequences (for example, that a thief will be terminated for a
first offense, regardless of the amount involved or whether she stole
from the company or anyone else) and should be careful to state that
these examples are only representative and that anything else the
employer deems to be inappropriate behavior will be punished
accordingly. That kind of a handbook however, often makes the head of
personnel nauseous.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Allan Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 16:06:10 1996<br>
Subject: Termination Policy<p>

In addition to setting forth grounds for dismissal, I think that the
"termination" policy portion of the handbook is an excellent place to
reconfirm the "at-will" nature of the employment relationship. In
addition, I prefer calling the grounds for termination "examples" and
stating specifically: "This list is not exhaustive."<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maurice Baskin -- Venable, Baetjer - Washington<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 21:41:56 1996<br>
Subject: Discipline<p>

Indeed, it is a must that any list of dischargeable offenses be
supplemented by the statement that the list is not exhaustive. We favor
a somewhat longer list than just two or three basic offenses, because
being able to identify a specific written policy which the discharged
employee has violated definitely makes it easier to defend the
termination. Although I have already stated elsewhere which category I
am in regarding the "litigation support" vs. "feel good communications"
debate (the first goal, though not the only goal, of the handbook should
be litigation support), the longer list of work rules actually serves
important communications needs as well, since it lets employees know
where they stand.<p>

The other big issue about discipline policies mentioned above is whether
to spell out a progressive discipline system. A lot of employers have
gotten into trouble by detailing such a system of
warnings/suspension/discharge. Even though progressive discipline is
usually best from both a human relations and legal point of view,
supervisors seem to be incapable of getting it consistently right, and
courts have found that minor procedural mistakes somehow override the at
will disclaimers. See, e.g., 13 Emp. At-will Rep. 33 (Dec. 1995),
listing cases from Colorado, New Jersey, New Mexico, Michigan, W. Va., S.
Car. and Pa. in which progessive discipline policies were held to
support plaintiffs' breach of handbook claims. We at Venable have
developed a policy which seems to take care of this problem while
keeping the good things about progressive discipline. The policy spells
out a variety of progressive steps which "may" be used; it does not
establish any rigid step-by-step approach; it makes clear that some
offenses are more serious than others; and most importantly, the policy
reserves to employers the right to skip steps, in their discretion. No
matter what your policies say, however, supervisory training is crucial,
and too little realized, in reducing litigation costs.<p> 

<hr><p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your question or
comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email address of the lawyers
participating in this discussion, use our online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.

</BLOCKQUOTE>

