<html><head><title> The Ultimate Employee Handbook - A Workshop</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Family Leave Policy and Personal Illness</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

NAME: Donna Denmark<br>
TITLE: Human Resources Coordinator<br>
<a href="mailto:ddenmark@eznet.net">EMAIL: ddenmark@eznet.net</a><br>
COMPANY: Catholic Family Center<p>

Last Append: Thu Feb  1 16:44:10 1996<p>

QUESTION=In our handbook we have a section on [the] FMLA [Family and
Medical Leave Act]. After the new reg[ulation]s went into effect, we
decided we needed to revise that portion, along with the corresponding
policy. I spoke with the U.S. Dept. of Labor regarding this and was
given the following information, which only creates a problem in the
event of an employee's own serious illness. If an employee is receiving
<STRONG>either NYS disability, workers comp[ensation] or accrued sick
time</strong>, that absence can be counted against the FMLA entitlement.
If an employee is receiving disability or workers compensation
<STRONG>and is supplementing</strong> them with accrued sick time, that
time <STRONG>cannot</strong> count against FMLA entitlement. I spoke
with our labor attorney today regarding this because in speaking with
other organizations, I have not found any that are dealing with this in
their policy. He said they have been advising employers that if
employees are receiving DBL [disability] or WC [worker's compensation]
and supplementing with sick time, they <STRONG>can</strong> count that
as FMLA leave. He is going to talk to the person I have talked with at
the Labor Dept. But I am wondering what the understanding is here, and
<STRONG>how</strong> you would address this in a handbook. We allow
employees to accumulate up to 120 hours of sick time. How could we turn
around and tell them you can't use this for your own long term illness?
I'm lost...<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 17:04:58 1996<br>
Subject: Same Subject<p>

[The following comment was submitted by a visitor to the workshop "echo"
on the Court TV Small Business Law Center. See the thread "Welcome to
the Workshop" for more information, or visit the site on the Web at:
http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/]<p>

NAME=Nancy A. Fredian<br>
TITLE=Director, Benefits & HRIS<br>
EMAIL=fredian@gemini.cboe.com<br>
COMPANY=Chicago Board Options Exchange<p>

QUESTION=Coordinating short term disability policies with the Family &
Medical Leave Act, ADA, and Worker's Compensation is incredibly
difficult. You want to accomodate the employee, but close as many
loopholes for abuse as you can. I would be interested in any suggestions
for coordinating these, and in seeing any sample policies that other
companies or firms have used.<p>

Thank you.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Allan Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 16:44:10 1996<br>
Subject: Counting FMLA Leave<p>

I must respectfully disagree with the attorney who advised that an
employer "can" count this as FMLA leave. Given the DOL's position on
this, there are only two options: (i) deny employees the right to
supplement WC [Worker's Compensation] or Disability with accrued sick
leave, in which case the leave "can" be counted as FMLA or (ii) allow
employees to use accrued sick leave as a supplement and do not not count
the leave as FMLA until the sick leave is exhausted. The third
"option" -- ignoring the DOL position until the dust settles on this
issue -- is at your own risk.<p>

