<H2>Romance with Competitor</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 13:19:43 1996<br>
Subject: Romance with Competitor<p>

Last Append: Thu Feb  1 21:54:50 1996<p>

[The following comment was submitted by a visitor to the workshop "echo"
on the Court TV Small Business Law Center. See the thread "Welcome to
the Workshop" for more information, or visit the site on the Web at:
http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/]<p>

NAME=Lucien Campbell<br>
TITLE=Federal Public Defender<br>
EMAIL=lbc@texas.net<br>
COMPANY=Federal Public Defender<p>

QUESTION=A problem is presented if an employee enters into a close
personal relationship with a person connected with an entity adverse to
the firm. It is difficult, however, to address this situation in an
office manual in a way that both protects the firm's interest and
respects the employees' privacy. Suggestions?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>
Date: Wed Jan 31 13:25:58 1996<br>
Subject: Weitzman Policy<p>

Perhaps Allan Weitzman's policy on
<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/seminars/handbook/romance.html">
Romance in the Workplace</a> (see the
workshop library section) can be adapted to meet this concern. Does
anyone think such a policy would be wise?<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Allan Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 16:23:03 1996<br>
Subject: Romance Policy<p>

The "romance in the workplace" policy that I added to the library was
designed to: (i) discourage intra-office relationships that could
potentially lead to sexual harassment and (ii) cope with the reality
that some consensual relationships are inevitable.<p> 

A policy to deal with the problem of "sleeping with the enemy" would
have to be designed with other purposes in mind.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 21:54:50 1996<br>
Subject: Romance with Competitor<p>

A general business conduct policy should cover any improper behavior
that might arise based on this situation, as well as any other
situation. The policy should not try to penalize the fact of the
relationship, but, rather, whether the relationship leads to anything
improper. And the first step of the policy would be disclosure and
review, rather than blanket prohibition.<p>

A policy in this area might cover the following points: No disclosure of
confidential information. No acceptance of payments, loans,
entertainment, gifts, over nominal amount, from anyone seeking to do
business with company. Disclosure if employee or family member has any
interest or employment relationship in competitor. No self-dealing
(i.e., doing business with the company).<p>


