<H2>Privacy</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>

From: Neil Bernstein -- WA Univ. School/Law - St. Louis<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 00:14:14 1996<br>
Subject: Privacy<p>

Last Append: Thu Feb  1 22:12:53 1996<p>

The cases that find employers liable for invasions of privacy
emphasize that the employer interfered with something on which
the employee had an expectation of privacy. That expectation can
be removed by statement in a handbook that the employer has the
right to inspect lockers, desks, restrooms, cars and other areas
on the premises and to monitor all conversations where deemed
necessary or appropriate. Granted, such language does not add to
the attractiveness of the workplace, but it does provide legal
protection. Does anyone include such statements in the handbooks
they draft?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Laura Hoguet -- Hoguet Newman Regal - New York<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 09:09:20 1996<br>
Subject: Privacy<p>

Privacy in the locker room and in the parking lot is the same
basic issue as privacy on the telephone and on email. I guess the
manual could have a paragraph under the heading "Company
Furnished Facilities" that states that employees when using
facilities provided by the Company should be aware that the
Company reserves the right to inspect the facilities and review
their use by employees. An added benefit of such a policy is that
it supports the employer in keeping an eye on the place to
prevent workplace harassment -- a bit like patrolling the halls
in the high school.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br>
Date: Thu Feb  1 22:12:53 1996<br>
Subject: Privacy<p>

The policy should also note that email, phonemail, or other
computer files created on the job are the property of the
employer, and the employee should have no expectation of privacy
for such files.<p>


