<H2>No-Smoking Policies [Even Outside the Workplace]</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Discussion Thread</h3>


From: Judith Keyes -- Corbett & Kane - Emeryville<br>
Date: Fri Feb  2 09:41:52 1996<br>
Subject: No-Smoking Policies<p>

Last Append: Fri Feb  2 13:57:00 1996<p>

A small question for the last day: does anyone have no-smoking
policies in their handbooks? I don't mean smoking in the
workplace (which is illegal in California unless it's a bar --
and that will be illegal in a year or so), but requiring that
employees be non-smokers? Presumably the rationale would be
better attendance and lower health insurance premiums, but I'm
curious to know whether these are being used anywhere in the
country.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Allan Weitzman -- Proskauer Rose - Boca Raton<br>
Date: Fri Feb  2 12:32:19 1996<br>
Subject: Policy for Applicants<p>

On the one hand, the City of North Miami, Florida, has a policy
that all job applicants must sign an affidavit stating that they
have not used tobacco products for one year before seeking a job
with the City. The U.S. Supreme Court recently refused to hear
the appeal of the rejected applicant. Thus, the decision of the
highest court in Florida was left intact.<p> 

On the other hand, such a policy would be illegal in New York
because of its "legal activities" law.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Richard U. Stubbs, Jr. -- Skoler Abbott - Springfield<br>
Date: Fri Feb  2 13:57:00 1996<br>
Subject: No-Smoking Policies<p>

There have been several threads in the ADA forum on this issue.
Some argue an employer cannot have such a policy because it is
facially discriminatory against nicotine addicts. Moreover, the
stated purpose in your hypo[thetical question], to bring health
insurance premiums down, might strike some as similar to policies
that discriminatorily bar individuals with AIDS from health
coverage. Some counter-considerations: is nicotine addiction
really a mental or physical impairment? If so, how does it
substantially limit a major life activity? We all know plenty of
people hooked on the stink weed whose only limitation in life
activities is on where they eat in the restaurant. Also, even if
nicotine addiction is a disability, couldn't the employer allow
the employee reasonable accommodation in the form of time to
"rehabilitate," as if it were alcoholism? Lots of questions, and
I'm sorry that there appear to be few answers.<p>

<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A
HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your question or
comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p><P><I>To look up the email address of the lawyers
participating in this discussion, use our online directory of attorneys, <a
href="http://www.counsel.com/lawyersearch/">Lawyer Search</a>.

