<html><head><title>Seminars - A Cryptography Primer</title></head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0><BLOCKQUOTE><H2>A Cryptography Primer</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Library File</h3>

Contributor: Charles R. Merrill<br>
Firm: McCarter & English<br>
<A HREF="mailto:cmerri01@counsel.com">E-mail:cmerri01@counsel.com</a></h4><p>

<H2>A Cryptography Primer (c)1995 Charles R. Merrill{n.1}</h2>  

[Draft of October 3, 1995. An edited version of this article was
published in January 1996 by The Computer Law Association, Joseph
F. Ruh, Jr., Editor, <I>The Internet and Business: A Lawyer's Guide
to the Emerging Legal Issues</i> , IBSN 1-885169-05-1] <p>

Cryptography is the "art and science of keeping messages
secure."{n.2} Until recently this term has been familiar only to
intelligence professionals, readers of spy novels, and crossword
puzzle buffs. The objectives of this section are to explain why
non-technical business lawyers should make the effort to learn
something about cryptography{n.3}, and to introduce some
terminology and simple concepts as a groundwork for understanding
how cryptography works.<p>

Business lawyers must first realize that the message security
which is of concern to them is a far broader concept than mere
privacy, and demands the reliable delivery of a number of
different security services{n.4}:<p><UL> 

<LI>Confidentiality. When Alice (nickname for the sender) sends a
message to Bob (nickname for the recipient), both Alice and Bob
may want the contents of the message to be kept secret from Eve
(nickname for a hypothetical eavesdropper of unknown identity).
The security service known as confidentiality strives to ensure
that Alice and Bob have the EXCLUSIVE KNOWLEDGE of the contents
of the message.<p>

<LI>Authentication. When Bob receives a message which purports to
be sent by Alice, Bob wants to ensure that the message is
actually coming from Alice, and not from Imp (nickname for a
hypothetical imposter of unknown identity). If Alice is in fact
the sender of the message Bob is receiving, she wants to convince
Bob that she rather than Imp is the sender. The security service
known as authentication answers the question, "WHO sent the
message?"<p>

<LI>Message Integrity. When Alice sends a message to Bob, both
Alice and Bob want to ensure that the message has not been
modified between the time of sending by Alice and the time of
receipt by Bob, neither by innocent computer glitch nor by Imp's
malicious tampering. The security service known as message
integrity answers the question, "WHAT message was sent?"<p>

<LI>Non-Repudiation. When Alice sends a message to Bob and Bob
acknowledges receipt of that message, they are potentially
adverse to the other. Each will have the incentive to block the
other party from a future denial of that party's own actions. Bob
wants to ensure non-repudiation of origin, so that Alice cannot
later deny the message was sent. Alice wants to ensure
non-repudiation of delivery, so that Bob cannot later deny the
message was received. The security service known as
non-repudiation answers the question, "Who is ESTOPPED from
denying origin or receipt of a message?"<p>

<LI>Time-Date Stamping. In the future, Alice and Bob also need to
prove to third parties or to each other, "WHEN was Alice's
message was created by Alice, sent by Alice, or received by
Bob?"<p></ul>

Notice that these security services have been defined without any
reference to computers, electronics, or communications on the
Internet. Although the vocabulary may seem new, the concepts
express principles which are intuitively familiar to business
lawyers who have thus far operated in a commercial world based on
paper. The difference is that the familiar system of tangible
messages on paper with pen-and-ink signatures reviewed by humans,
is replaced by intangible streams of electronic bits (binary
digits, either zero or one) seen only by machines.<p>

<H4>Paperless Commerce is a Double-Edged Sword</h4>

The transition from paper-based to paperless commerce on the
Internet and elsewhere on the infobahn is a double-edged sword.
The good news is the efficiency, speed, flexibility, cost savings
and accessibility of electronic communication and commerce. The
dark side is that online communication and commerce on the
Internet are seriously and notoriously insecure.<p>

When using privately-owned communication service providers known
as VANs (value-added networks), attorneys have come to expect
about the same level of security for e-mail as currently offered
for voice and fax services travelling over land lines. In
contrast, the Internet (which is owned by nobody) is based on
TCP/IP (transfer control protocol/internet protocol) routing of
information packets through unpredictable paths through
interconnected networks linking millions of computers. The
Internet, originally intended as a failsafe communication net in
time of nuclear disaster, was designed more with ease of
networked communication in mind than messaging security.<p>

Even with sophisticated network security precautions such as
firewalls (specialized gateway computers to insulate the inside
network from the outside world), wily hackers outside the
firewall continue to demonstrate their ability to sniff for
network weaknesses, insert password grabbers and trojan horses,
spoof (impersonate) both identity and e-mail addresses, and
subvert system routers to select less-secure paths for
interesting message traffic. Although reports of security
break-ins have increased in frequency during the past year, this
is thought to be but the tip of the iceberg, because of the
reluctance of industry and government to publicize incidents
where they have been careless victims of a "crime of shame."<p>

<H4>Raising Security Expectations</h4>

For an attorney entrusted with ethical responsibilities to
preserve client confidences, what use is the speed and
flexibility of electronic mail, if there is no reasonable
assurance of confidentiality? Who would risk more than trivial
amounts of value to electronic commerce, if an unknown hacker two
continents and six time zones away can, with impenetrable
stealth, impersonate a contracting party or a payee?<p>

Even with the consumer's liability limited to $50 for
unauthorized use of her credit card, how long will consumers
entrust credit card, debit card and PIN numbers to an environment
where theft of this information is probable? How long will
merchants (and their prices) tolerate accelerating credit/debit
card fraud, which already costs society billions?<p>

No matter how sexy the siren of paperless electronic appears at
first glance, it will not succeed unless the security of online
open systems is engineered to at least equal the level of
security offered by traditional paper-based systems. In fact,
upon exposure to knowledge of some recent technological advances,
it becomes apparent that the transition to paperless commerce
actually offers an opportunity to raise our level of security
expectations far beyond what we have come to expect in the paper-
based world. How is this possible?<p> 

<H4>Public Key Cryptography As a Solution</h4>

The solution is a system of public key cryptography (sometimes
called asymmetric cryptography), or a public key cryptosystem. We
can understand the public key cryptosystem system best by first
understanding the more familiar system of single key cryptography
(sometimes called symmetric or conventional cryptography.<p>

<H4>Conventional, Single Key Crypto is Not Enough</h4>

An example of a single key cryptosystem is a password on a word
processing document, or a PIN number on an ATM account. With
single key cryptography, the same key (a stream of bits of a
specified key length randomly created by a computer) is used to
encrypt a message from plaintext (which can be read by anyone)
into ciphertext (which can be read only by those possessing the
key), and to decrypt the ciphertext back into plaintext again.<p>

No matter how secure an encryption algorithm (a process of
programmed steps and conversions) it uses, the single key
cryptosystem has two inherent security weaknesses. First, the
sender and the recipient of the message need to share knowledge
of the same secret key, which means that each is required to
trust the other not to compromise knowledge which is exclusively
known by the two of them. Second, the sender and recipient have a
key distribution problem. It is not possible to securely
communicate the knowledge of a secret key to both parties who
need it, without going offband (using a different channel). This
is not a difficult problem for frequent correspondents or
bilateral trading partners who have ample opportunity to exchange
secret keys, often over a single closed system secure from the
outside world. On the other hand, single key cryptography is
awkward at best on the Internet, where the very first
communication between strangers needs to be secure, the
communication is on an open and hostile system, and the system
has a many-to-many topology (structure of the network).<p>

<H4>The Shared Key Risk and The Key Distribution Problem</h4>

A public-key cryptosystem allows robust security on the Internet
because it offers a solution to both the shared key risk and the
key distribution problem. Rather than a single key, a public-key
cryptosystem uses a pair of keys which are mathematically linked
to each other, so that one key is used for encryption and the
other linked key is used for decryption. Each user possesses a
key pair, one of which (the private key) is kept secret and is
never transmitted, and the other (the public key) is widely
publicized. It is computationally unfeasible (see discussion
below regarding the export of encryption software) to derive the
secret key merely from knowledge of the public key.<p>

<H4>Confidentiality, Digital Signatures, and Hash</H4>

If Alice the sender wants to encrypt a message for
confidentiality, Alice's encryption software will apply the
recipient's public key (of Bob). When Bob the recipient wants to
decrypt the message, Bob will use the same encryption software to
apply the recipient's private key (i.e., Bob's own private key).
The security service of confidentiality (exclusive knowledge) is
achieved.<p>

By reversing the process{n.5}, it is possible to affix a digital
signature to a message. If Alice the sender wants to digitally
sign a message, Alice applies her sender's private key. When Bob
the recipient wants to authenticate the origin of the message
(i.e., from Alice), Bob applies the sender's public key (Alice's
public key). This accomplishes the two security services of
authentication (WHO sent the message) and non-repudiation (who is
ESTOPPED from denying the message).<p>

In addition, when in digital signature mode, the security service
of message integrity is simultaneously accomplished, so that it
is certain that Alice's message has not been altered since it was
digitally signed by Alice. Every character in Alice's message is
run through a one-way hash algorithm (the algorithm maps a
message of any length to a shorter hash result which is virtually
unique to the message, and it is computationally infeasible to
derive the original message from the hash result). The hash
result is then encrypted by applying the public key of Bob the
recipient. When Bob the recipient authenticates the origin of the
message as coming from Alice, Bob also verifies the integrity of
the message by (i) applying his own (Bob the recipient's) private
key to decrypt the transmitted hash result; and (ii) comparing
the decrypted hash result with a second hash result which Bob the
recipient himself prepares from the transmitted message.<p>

With reversible public key cryptosystems such as RSA and PGP, it
is optionally possible to add the security service of
confidentiality to digital signature and message integrity.
Alice's software first digitally signs her message with Alice's
private key, and then super-encrypts the signed message for
privacy with Bob's public key. Bob decrypts the signed message
with Bob's private key, and then verifies that the message was
signed by Alice (and not since altered) with Alice's public
key.<p>

<H4>Certification Authorities to Block Spoofing of Public
Key</h4>

The potential weak spot in the public key cryptosystem is the
possibility that Imp, the imposter, will manage to secretly
substitute Imp's own public key (Imp has the matching private
key) for the public key of another person, which would nullify or
weaken all of the security services offered by the public key
cryptosystem{n.6}. To plug this potential compromise of security,
trusted third parties called Certification Authorities (CAs) are
being developed to bind a key-pair to the identity of its
owner.<p>

How does the CA work? The user will (i) generate her own
public/private key pair; (ii) produce proof of user identity
(including a visit in person) to the satisfaction of the CA;
(iii) furnish her public key to the CA; and (iv) and use software
to demonstrate possession of the complementary private key
without disclosing the private key itself. When satisfied, the CA
will bundle a digital copy of the user's public key together with
a digital certificate of the CA to the effect that the named user
owns this public key, and the CA will digitally sign the entire
package with the CA's private key. CAs will have other duties,
such as maintaining certificate revocation lists (CRLs) of public
keys which are no longer valid because the private key has been
lost or otherwise compromised. CAs are generally organized with
some degree (either flat or steep) of hierarchical structure, so
that each CA will have its own certificates validated by
certificates issued by higher-level CAs, and so on up the chain
until it ends in the top level, known as the root.<p> 

<H4>ABA's [American Bar Association's] InfoSec Committee's
Digital Signature Guidelines</h4>

Shortly before press time, the ABA's Information Security
Committee{n.7} published Digital Signature Guidelines{n.8}, setting
forth general legal principles and commentary for a public key
infrastructure to support a robust system of electronic commerce
based on digital signatures for use in open systems such as the
Internet. Reflecting many years of interdisciplinary study, the
Guidelines set forth a consistent system for apportioning
responsibility with certainty among the principal actors in
paperless commerce: the digital signer, the CA, and the party who
relies upon the digital signature as verified by the CA's
certificate binding the identity of the digital signer to the
key-pair owned by the signer. The Information Security Committee
is currently continuing its study by considering models for
legislative implementation of the Guidelines principles,
including the pioneering Utah Digital Signature Law enacted March
9, 1995{n.9}.<p> 

<H4>Promiscuous, Monogamous and Polygamous Models</h4>

The Guidelines have chosen to address the demanding security
needs of the most challenging model of electronic commerce (I
have nicknamed it the promiscuous model{n.10} of electronic
commerce) on the hostile and open system consisting of the
Internet and its World Wide Web, namely isolated transactions
among strangers in a many-to-many topology. At the opposite end
of the pole, representing traditional EDI (electronic data
interchange) as conducted between frequent bilateral trading
partners in a one-on-one topology, often within a closed and
protected system such as a VAN, is the monogamous model of
electronic commerce. The monogamous model has in the past
operated with single-key or no encryption, and may perhaps
continue to do so with acceptable security risk, at least until
such time as the seemingly irresistible lure of the Internet
increases the exposure to hackers.<p>

What I call the polygamous{n.11} model of electronic commerce is a
cryptographic halfway house on the Internet which combines
features of both the promiscuous and the monogamous models. The
polygamous model has a topology of one-to-many, based upon a
single central figure (e.g., a merchant, a bank, a credit card
company, an online service provider) which interacts directly
with many subscribers, none of whom interact commercially with
each other. This structure, which is common today, may offer the
opportunity for using public-key encryption securely without the
need for independent CAs. Instead, the central figure will
certify the key-pairs of its subscribers for purposes of its own
reliance only, without risk of CA liability to third parties who
may rely on a mistaken public key certificate. Such a system
could tolerate pseudonymous and possibly even anonymous
subscribers, by providing a security service whose objective is
to authenticate origin not absolutely, but merely relatively, by
answering the question "Is this message signed by the same person
who is my subscriber and promptly pays my invoices?" Moreover,
because there is privity of contract between the only commercial
actors in the polygamous model, it may be possible, through
bilateral trading partner agreements between the central figure
and each of its subscribers, to adopt rules which take the place
of the legislation needed under the promiscuous model of
electronic commerce.<p>

<H4>Public Key Crypto for Attorney/Client Confidentiality</h4>

Business attorneys dealing with their clients and other business
attorneys have an obvious major need for the security service of
confidentiality. The security services provided by digital
signatures (authentication, message integrity and non-
repudiation) can also be useful, but are of lesser importance to
the attorney than confidentiality. Business lawyers typically
have only dozens or hundreds (not thousands) of confidential
correspondents, with a topology that can be described as
few-to-few, and increasingly lawyers are being attracted to the
hostile and open environment of the Internet's World Wide Web.
Public-key cryptography is ideal for the needs of lawyers in this
circumstance. Although the topology is the same shape as the
topology in the promiscuous model, the limited size of the
universe of correspondents allows all public key certification to
be performed first-hand, with contract privity, for reliance by
the certifying attorney only, analogous to the situation under
the polygamous model.<p>

<H4>Encryption Software Export Restrictions</h4>

A major obstacle to the national and global development of a
secure public key infrastructure continues to be the strong
hostility of the U.S. security and law enforcement establishment
toward strong public key encryption, namely any cryptosystem
which cannot be readily, quickly and cheaply broken with the
brute force of the massively parallel processing systems and
supercomputers of the NSA (National Security Association), or
which has decryption keys deposited in escrow in a manner so as
to cause them to be available to law enforcement agencies upon
wiretap order. This hostility has been expressed in a variety of
strategies and tactics which have had the effect of delaying and
hindering the development and spread of public key encryption,
including (i) the Clipper Chip initiative announced April 16,
1993, and subsequently embodied in the Escrowed Encryption
Standard, mandatory for the federal government but voluntary for
the private sector; (ii) occasional speeches by federal
officials, suggesting that the use of unescrowed strong
encryption might be made illegal, as in France; (iii) continued
restrictions upon export of strong encryption products considered
"munitions" or "defense items" under ITAR (International Traffic
in Arms Regulations){n.12}. 


<H4>Only "Crypto-Lite" Software Is Exportable</h4>

At the current time, encryption software with a key-length of
40-bits{n.13} is exportable outside the U.S. and Canada under ITAR.
NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology) proposed in
August of 1995 to allow export of 64-bit software upon condition
that it be escrowed so as to be amenable to wiretap order. That
same week, a French college student succeeded in breaking 40-bit
encryption software with brute force over a few days, using an
assortment of two supercomputers and a hundred or so powerful
workstations. The difference of cracking difficulty between
40-bits and 64-bits is a factor of 10 to the 7th power or 10
million. Both become cheaper and faster as computing power
increases over time. Bruce Schneier estimates that $1 million of
specialized hardware in the year 1995 can crack a 40-bit key in
.2 seconds or crack a 64-bit key in 38 days. In the year 2000,
however, the time to crack the 40-bit key will reduce to .02
seconds, and the 64-bit key to 4 days. In the past, such
projections of increased computer power and speed have tended to
be overly conservative. Both RSA and PGP ViaCrypt support a
key-length of 128-bits in their domestic products, which is 10 to
the 19th power harder to crack than the 64-bit key!{n.14} 

Has it become "computationally feasible" to crack the exportable
encryption software? Most likely by the NSA, but probably still
not by the foreseeable private hacker in 1995. The fact remains,
that U.S. export policies are clearly hindering the global
deployment by U.S. corporations, of standard industrial-strength
software of 128 bits which is safely out of reach of hackers for
the foreseeable future, and forcing the use of clearly inferior,
"crypto-lite" configurations. Because public key cryptosystems
used for digital signature are also based upon such encryption
algorithms, the U.S. policies hamper the development of
commercially important digital signature software as well as the
privacy encryption software which is intended target of the
export restrictions. And finally, another casualty of these
policies is the damage done to the U.S. balance of payments, as
those who need robust encryption are forced to import rather than
export software{n.15}. Almost 30 months after the Clipper Chip
initiative was announced{n.16}, there is little sign of any
softening in these policies, and they need a hard re-examination,
so that the law-enforcement objective can be weighed against the
competing goal of secure electronic commerce and e-mail.<p>

<hr><br>
