13 This is the key length of the conventional, single key algorithm which is
part of a typical public key cryptosystem, being RC4 in the RSA cryptosystem,
and IDEA in the PGP cryptosystem. Both RSA and PGP use the RSA algorithm for
key-distribution algorithm, which is based on the factoring of the product of
two huge primes. The size of the product to be factored is typically either 300
decimal digits (1024 binary bits) or 600 decimal digits (2048 binary bits). In
1993 a Bellcore team broke a product 129 decimal digits long (about 400 binary
bits) in about a year, using approximately 1000 workstations cooperating via the
Internet.<p>

14 Bruce Schneir, E-Mail Security (John Wiley & Sons 1995), at pp 24-25, 48-
