<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Model Employee Handbook - Information and Introduction</h2>



<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>



<H3>Workshop Library File</h3>



Contributor: Maurice Baskin<br>

Source: Model Employee Handbook. Cost: $250.<br>

Firm: Venable, Baetjer, Howard & Civiletti, LLP<br>

Address: 1201 New York Ave., N.W. Suite 1000 Washington, D.C. 20005-3917<br>

Telephone: (202) 962-4800<br>

Fax: (202) 962-8300<p>



E-mail:<A HREF="mailto:mbaskin0@counsel.com">mbaskin0@counsel.com</a><p>



<H4>Author's caveat: These documents do not constitute legal advice

or an opinion, which can only be provided after review of

specific facts. </h4>



MODEL EMPLOYEE HANDBOOK<p>



PROVISIONS AND INFORMATION<p>



Prepared by<p> 



THE LABOR & EMPLOYMENT LAW DEPARTMENT<br>

VENABLE, BAETJER AND HOWARD<p>



Office Locations<p>



1800 Mercantile Bank & Trust Building<br>

Two Hopkins Plaza<br>

Baltimore, Maryland 21201<br>

Phone:  (301) 244-7400<p>



Suite 400<br>

2010 Corporate Ridge<br>

McLean, Virginia  22102<br>

Phone:  (703) 749-3500<p>



2101 Allegheny Avenue<br>

Towson, MD  21204<br>

Phone:  (301) 823-4111<p>



Suite 1000<br>

1201 New York Avenue, N.W.<br>

Washington, D.C.  20004<br>

Phone:  (202) 962-4800<p>



1 Church Street, Fifth Floor<br>

Rockville, MD  20850<br>

Phone:  (301) 217-5600<p>



NOTE: This Model Employee Handbook is not intended to apply to

any particular employer or to provide legal advice or opinion.

Such advice may only be given when related to specific handbooks

and specific fact situations. The discussion and employee

handbook provisions herein are only intended to provide

suggestions and guidelines to individual employers for their use

in developing their own handbooks. In no circumstances should any

employee handbook be adopted and issued to employees before the

final draft has been approved by your labor counsel.<p> 



THIS BOOKLET IS THE PROPERTY OF OUR FIRM<p>  



DO NOT REPRINT ANY PROVISION HEREIN WITHOUT OUR PERMISSION<p>



Copyright 1994 Venable, Baetjer and Howard. All rights

reserved.<p>



FOREWORD<p>



Today's workers are more litigious than ever before. Every

employment-related lawsuit involves some aspect of the policies

and practices applied by management to solving people-problems in

the workplace. These operating rules frequently are set forth in

an employee handbook or personnel policies manual. In the course

of the trial of these cases, some executives will be

cross-examined on what the handbook rules mean, and how they are

applied. The case may be tried before a jury, with both actual

and punitive damages awardable. Verdicts against employers are

running into millions of dollars.<p>



This new type of litigation may charge that breach of an "implied

contract" has occurred because an employer failed to follow some

work rule in an employee handbook, or that an employee was

damaged by reliance on management's promise of benefits set forth

in the handbook.<p>



Courts have also interpreted the provisions of some handbooks as

a contractual limitation on the common law managerial right to

discharge employees. For example, the highest court in Texas had

declared that:<p>



"--absolute employment-at-will is a relic of early industrial

times, conjuring up visions of the sweatshops described by

Charles Dickens and his contemporaries. The doctrine belongs in a

museum, not in our law."<p>



As a result, some workers are beginning to claim that their jobs

are like a vested property right, and it is no wonder that

employers have suffered "handbook horrors." A few firms have

reacted by eliminating their handbooks altogether. The question

thus arises whether it is advisable to maintain an employee

handbook and, if so, how can an employer best draft the handbook

to maximize its human relations benefits while at the same time

minimizing the legal risks?<p> 



Our answer is that, as a practical matter, the greater risk is

posed by abandoning your handbook and relying on unwritten work

rules because the same courts have also held that ORAL

representations to employees and established but unwritten

practices can be just as contractually binding. These cases are

difficult to defend because of the credibility gap in proving

what management's policy or practice really was. The factual

determination may be sent to a jury where (psychologically) it's

the "poor, helpless, downtrodden worker" versus the "big, bad,

rich, powerful employer".<p> 



On the other hand, if workplace policies and benefits are clearly

stated IN WRITING, there can be no question about what they mean.

A well-drafted and consistently applied personnel policy manual

or handbook thus can serve a number of useful purposes. It

provides an effective tool for training supervisors and orienting

new employees. Without such a manual, inadequate

employee/management communications can result in workers not

having any concept of corporate policies, not knowing how to

communicate, and not understanding the company's work rules.

Supervisors will be unable to answer employee questions quickly

and accurately. This could lead to erroneous interpretations of

company policies as well as inconsistent application of work

rules, complaints and grievances, discipline, benefits -- and

eventually to costly lawsuits.<p> 



One of an employer's best defenses in a union organizing

campaign, moreover, is the ability to counter the so-called

"security" of a labor contract (as advertised by the union) with

an employee handbook that similarly sets forth equal or better

benefits, real job security, and favorable work rules for

employees. Furthermore, an excellent defense in equal employment

opportunity litigation raising claims of disparate treatment is

management's ability to show its good faith attempt to comply

with civil rights laws protecting minority groups and prove that

non-discriminatory employment policies were established, were

communicated to employees through a handbook, and applied

consistently by supervisors. Finally, the properly drafted

disciplinary rules in a handbook can assist management in

defending itself against employee lawsuits for "implied

agreements" and "wrongful or abusive discharge." <p>



While the law concerning the interpretation and enforceability of

employee handbooks is in a developing mode, three major drafting

precautions can be gleaned from the cases to date:<p>



First, as noted above, employer must recognize that some

provisions of the handbook may be interpreted as contractually

binding on management. It therefore is essential to remove or

amend all policies and benefits that you do not intend to follow

consistently.<p>



Second, because the potential contractual liability of the

handbook may be negated by legally protective language, employers

should include such disclaimers where consistent with their

employee relations objectives. For example, the handbook should

include a statement that it is not intended to be an express or

implied contract of employment. The handbook should also state

that employees can be discharged at will at any time, without

prior notice or warning, in management's discretion. Employers

should be aware that some courts require these disclaimers to be

prominently placed in order to have any effect.<p> 



Third, because an employer's obligations under a contract cannot

exceed what was promised, every handbook drafter should consider

including broad reservations of managerial prerogatives. At the

least, the handbook should reserve management's right to amend or

delete any handbook provision. Many more disclaimers and caveats

developed by our law firm to protect legitimate management

functions are included in this handbook manual.<p> 



A final word of caution: depending on how strongly the handbook's

legal disclaimers and caveats are worded, they may tend to

undermine the human relations value that the handbook is intended

to promote. Management therefore must balance the legal

protective value of such statements against their possible

detrimental impact on employee morale and job security. Certain

compromises are noted herein.<p> 



In summary, those handbook horrors can be avoided. But it takes a

friendly, people-oriented approach as well as careful drafting,

an attractive and readable format, plus thorough legal review.

Under these conditions, an employee handbook should be one of

management's best friends.<p> 



HOW TO USE THIS MODEL HANDBOOK<p>



The Model Employee Handbook manual is a compendium of policies

and procedures on various workplace subjects from recruitment to

retirement that might appear in your Employee Handbook. The

authors have drafted and reviewed literally hundreds of handbooks

and policy statements for use in a wide variety of employment

settings, bringing that experience to bear in composing the

statements and provisions you will find here.<p>



This Model Employee Handbook manual should assist you in drafting

your own handbook, tailored to the specific needs of the

NON-UNION employees in your Firm. Our manual is divided into

EIGHT MAJOR TOPICS, with sub-sections titled and numbered as

indicated in the TABLE OF CONTENTS that follows. Some sub-

sections contain more than one policy draft sample. They are

designated as SAMPLE A, SAMPLE B, etc., for your consideration.<p> 



Throughout this manual we have also inserted FOOTNOTES at the end

of each section in order to remind you of the need for special

review of certain provisions, or to mention relevant state or

federal laws and court decisions, or provide you with additional

information about the reasons underlying specific handbook

clauses. These footnotes are NOT to be republished as part of

your actual employee handbook.<p> 



Our manual thus is a general guide to the types of provisions

that are frequently included in handbooks. It also contains NOVEL

provisions that we have developed in our law firm to help protect

your managerial prerogatives in an increasingly legalistic age.

These legal disclaimers and caveats have been approved and

enforced by federal and state courts in actual cases involving

defense of our clients.<p> 



No firm should adopt this Model Employee Handbook draft verbatim,

however. Every handbook should be tailored to the employer's

specific situation. Some of the provisions contained herein are

NOT appropriate for every firm. You should only use this manual

as a STARTING POINT, and mold the suggested language to fit your

own situation and convey the message you want to express.<p> 



A basic goal of every employee handbook should be to engender a

positive response from employees. They need to identify with your

Firm; to realize that what is good for your business is good for

them too. The handbook, as one of a new employee's first

experiences with your Firm, can initiate that response. Its style

and format should be upbeat and friendly. It should contain

provisions that foster a sense of well-being and security on the

part of employees.<p> 



Since one of the aims of an employee handbook is to communicate,

it must be organized and written in a style that is

understandable. The basic rule is: KEEP IT SIMPLE, CLEAR, AND

BRIEF. The language used should not be complex or burdensome. The

only EXCEPTION to this general rule of style is -- regrettable

but necessarily -- the legal disclaimers and caveats that appear

in some of the following pages of our manual. These provisions

must be written in "legalese" for your protection and

independence of operation, with managerial prerogatives intact.<p> 



Decide what it is you want to say and provide for your workers,

and consider fully the commitments of each policy and benefit.

Try to keep the tone of the handbook personal. Avoid cold third

person references such as "the employee" and "the management."

Instead, use "you," "we," and other terms of familiarity and

informality whenever possible.<p> 



Charts often convey and supplement information in a clearer, more

concise manner than long narratives. Photographs and graphics

also help make the ideas you wish to communicate easier to

understand and more interesting to read.<p> 



Be careful about highlighting distinctions among various classes

of workers. If the salaried employees in your office have a more

generous vacation schedule than the mechanics on your job sites,

or if one group of employees has more lenient sign-in and relief

procedures than another, the differences could create legal or

people-problems if highlighted in the handbook. The fairest

solution is to treat everyone alike -- at least as to published

work rules and benefits, and keep executive "perks" unlisted.<p> 



Be sure to include specific reservations of management's

discretionary authority to operate its business and direct its

work force. Choose your terminology carefully, thinking through

the nature of the prerogative you want to protect and how to

protect it. Obviously, this is an element of the handbook where

labor counsel is essential. You can avoid many of the pitfalls

that have resulted in protracted litigation for other companies.<p> 



Be wary of allowing employees to have access to supervisors'

personnel policy manuals. Some firms publish a separate,

comprehensive management brochure that explains in more detail

the policies contained in the employee handbook, or even adds

additional work rules. Remember the same legal principles that

apply to your handbook apply to a lengthy supervisors' policy

booklet. We believe the safer practice is to avoid such

supplementary guidebooks, and advise your Supervisors either to

handle employee questions personally or refer them to your

Director of Human Resources for consistency in administration

under your handbook.<p> 



In addition, we strongly recommend that you review the latest

legal requirements in your state (statutes, court and

administrative rulings) with regard to employee benefits,

workplace rules, employee handbooks and policy manuals. Many laws

concerning employees are governed on the local level, and they

vary from state to state.<p> 



You should also make the outside cover of your handbook pleasing

to the eye. Bold type communicates clearly. Remember that the

cover is an opportunity to present both your company logo in a

positive yet personal way to your employees.<p> 



Avoid making your handbook unwieldy to read and handle. The more

compact and convenient to use the handbook is, the more likely

employees will keep it close at hand and refer to it. Loose leaf

booklets are expensive and the amended pages sent out

periodically to employees are seldom filed.<p> 



An employee handbook must, of course, be used in conjunction with

effective supervisory training on how to administer it firmly,

consistently and fairly. All policies and work rules that appear

in the handbook must be uniformly enforced by your supervisors

and other managerial personnel. The positive-but- friendly

attitude that you hope to generate through the handbook must be

supported and implemented by your entire management team.<p> 



Finally, we repeat that this Model Employee Handbook manual is

not intended to apply to any particular employer or to provide

legal advice or opinion. Such advice may only be given when

related to specific handbooks and specific fact situations.<p>



1.0  INTRODUCTION<p>



1.1  About This Handbook*<p>



Our Firm has always believed in promoting an atmosphere of open

communication and cooperation among all of our personnel. This

Employee Handbook reflects that thinking. It supersedes in all

respects any prior handbook, policy manual, benefits or practices

of the Firm and has been prepared for our [OPTIONAL:

non-managerial or non-executive, non-officer, non-supervisory,

non-exempt, non-represented, or other definition of those covered

by the Handbook if not all employees are covered] employees** to

provide you with general information about some of your benefits

and the highlights of rules and policies under which we operate.

Obviously, we could not begin to explain every Firm policy or

rule or benefit in this Handbook, and its provisions can be

considered as no more than general summaries of the benefits,

work rules and policies they address.<p> 



While we hope our personnel actions will continue to be positive,

from time to time our Firm may unilaterally, in its discretion,

amend, supplement, modify, or eliminate one or more of the

benefits, work rules or policies described in this Handbook, or

any other employment benefits, work rules or policies, without

prior notice.***<p> 



This Handbook does not constitute a guarantee that your

employment will continue for any specified period of time or end

only under certain conditions. NOTHING IN THE HANDBOOK

CONSTITUTES AN EXPRESS OR IMPLIED CONTRACT OF EMPLOYMENT OR

WARRANTY OF ANY BENEFITS. Employment at our Firm is a voluntary

employment-at-will relationship for no definite period of time.

While we hope to have a long and mutually beneficial working

relationship together, regardless of anything which may appear in

this Handbook or any other Firm publication, policy, statement or

practice, you have the right to terminate your employment

relationship for any reason with or without cause or notice at

any time, and the Firm reserves the right to do the same to amend

or delete handbook provisions. Although the disclaimer contained

here should provide substantial protection, employers may want to

consider providing some new benefit to employees when the

handbook is significantly changed, so that binding consideration

for the change can be shown to exist.<p>



</BLOCKQUOTE>
