<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Seven Basic Rules on Solicitation</h2>



<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>



<H3>Workshop Library File</h3>



Contributor: Gerard Morales<br>

Firm: Snell & Wilmer<br>

Address: One Arizona Center, Phoenix, Arizona 85004-0001<br>

Telephone: (602) 382-6362<br>

Fax: (602) 382-6070<p>



E-mail:<A HREF="mailto:jmorales@counsel.com">jmorales@counsel.com</a><p>



<H3>SEVEN BASIC RULES ON SOLICITATION BY EMPLOYEES AND ACCESS TO THE

EMPLOYER'S PRIVATE PROPERTY</h3>



<h4>Copyright 1995 by Gerard Morales</h4><OL>



<LI>During non-working times, the employees' right to engage in

solicitation and to distribute literature in non-working areas is

protected by the National Labor Relations Act. e.g., <I>Anderson

Company</i>, 305 NLRB 878 (1991).<p>



<LI>Because of the disruption which solicitation and/or

distribution may create in the workplace, however, an employer

may adopt and enforce rules prohibiting solicitation during

working time and distribution in working areas. <I>Our Way</i>, 268 NLRB

394 (1983). Nevertheless, as a general proposition, if the

employer permits solicitations by employees for outside entities,

"even for admirable, charitable and benevolent purposes," it

cannot argue that union solicitations create an intolerable

disruption because their purpose is less admirable. e.g.,

<I>Sunnyland Packing Company</i>, 227 NLRB 590.<p>



<LI>An employer may prohibit non-employees seeking to communicate

with its employees from coming into the employer's private

property, except in the rare case where "the inaccessibility of

employees makes ineffective the reasonable attempts of

nonemployees to communicate with them through the usual

channels." e.g., <I>Lechmere, Inc.</i>, v. NLRB, 502 U.S. 527

(1992).<p>



<LI>An employer may not prohibit off-duty employees from gaining

access to its premises except if it: a) limits access solely with

respect to the interior of the plant and other working areas; b)

clearly disseminates the prohibition to all employees; and c)

applies the prohibition to off-duty employees seeking access for

any reason. A rule that denies off-duty employees entry to

non-working areas, such as parking lots, would be invalid, unless

justified by business reasons. e.g., <I>Tri-County Medical Center</i>,

222 NLRB 1089 (1976).<p>



<LI>The employer's electronic and telephonic communication

systems may be limited to business-related purposes only.<p>



<LI>Employees have the protected right to wear union insignia

while at work, unless special circumstances apply. Exposure to

customers or general public, standing alone, is not a sufficient

"special circumstance" to justify prohibiting the display of such

insignia by employees. e.g., <I>United Parcel Service</i>, 312

NLRB No. 103 (1993). (Some courts of appeal disagree with the

NLRB in this area. See e.g., <I>United Parcel Service v.

NLRB</i>, 41 F.3d 1068 (6th Cir. 1994).)<p>



<LI>When an employer permits its employees to utilize its

bulletin boards for the posting of notices relating to personal

items, it may not validly discriminate against notices of union

meetings, etc., an employer's motivation, no matter how well

meant, is irrelevant. e.g., <I>Guardian Industries Corp.</i>, 313

NLRB 1275 (1994). (Here, also, some courts of appeal have

disagreed with the Board. <I>Guardian Industries Corp. v.

NLRB</i>, 148 LRRM 2665 (7th Cir. 1995).)</ol><p>



<hr><p>



<hr><P ALIGN=CENTER><I><A

HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form2.html">Submit your

question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></p>




</BLOCKQUOTE>
