<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>A Few Words About Unions</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Library File</h3>

Contributor: Maurice Baskin<br>
Source: Model Employee Handbook. Cost: $250.<br>
Firm: Venable, Baetjer, Howard & Civiletti, LLP<br>
Address: 1201 New York Ave., N.W. Suite 1000 Washington, D.C. 20005-3917<br>
Telephone: (202) 962-4800<br>
Fax: (202) 962-8300<p>

E-mail:<A HREF="mailto:mbaskin0@counsel.com">mbaskin0@counsel.com</a><p>

<H4>Author's caveat: These documents do not constitute legal
advice or an opinion, which can only be provided after review of
specific facts.</h4>


<H3>A FEW WORDS ABOUT UNIONS*</h3>

(Sample A)<p>

Our Firm, like more than eight-percent of the businesses and
institutions throughout the United States, is
<STRONG>Union-Free</strong>. There is always a chance, however,
that in the future a labor union organizer will try to persuade
some of our employees to sign union authorization cards. For this
reason, it is important that you understand our position
concerning unions.<p>

To say it simply and clearly, although you have the legal right
to join a labor union, you also have the legal right
<STRONG>NOT</strong> to join a union. We believe that remaining
union-free has definite advantages for you, our employees. For
instance, along with labor unions come the possibility of many
changes such as (a) restrictions of individual freedom to discuss
and solve your problems directly with us without any union
involvement; (b) your compulsory union membership and dues; (c)
union discipline, fines, suspension and expulsion from
membership; (d) union control over you through the union's
constitution and bylaws; (e) union politics; (f) union coercion
and violence; (g) union hypocrisy; (h) union strikes and strike
assessments; (i) resulting job replacements, sometimes temporary,
sometimes forever. In other words -- over the years, some unions
have fostered turmoil, job insecurity, dollars out of workers'
pockets, and loss of independence.<p>

So if a labor union organizer ever asks you to sign a union
authorization card, remember that it can be a legally binding
document in which you may sign away your right of individual
freedom in our workplace for exclusive representation by that
union. We hope you would hesitate -- and think carefully --
before signing any such union pledge card. It could be your first
step into the workplace turmoil described above. It might be like
signing a blank check and giving it to a stranger!<p>

<hr><p>

*NOTE: Many executives are not aware that, in exercising freedom
of speech, they have a legal right to advise their employees of
the Firm's opinion that representation by a labor union is not in
the employees' best interest. So long as you do not
<STRONG>THREATEN</strong> employees with reprisals if they
unionize, or <STRONG>PROMISE</strong> improved benefits if they
refrain from unionizing, it is perfectly legal to tell your
employees that you do not believe they need a union, and explain
why. However, it is important that your handbook not
<STRONG>REQUIRE</strong> employees to adhere to your non-union
policy as a condition of employment, as the National Labor
Relations Board has held that such a requirement can be found to
be an unfair labor practice.<p>


<H3>A FEW WORDS ABOUT UNIONS</h3>

(Sample B)<p>

There is always a chance that in the future a labor organizer will try
to persuade some of our employees to sign union authorization cards. For
this reason, it is important that you understand our position concerning
unions.<p> 

To say it simply and clearly, although you have the legal right to join
a labor union, you also have the legal right <STRONG>NOT</strong> to
join a labor union. We prefer to work with our employees informally,
personally, and directly, rather than through third party outsiders
intervening between us. We think you agree. So we will make every effort
that is legally permissible to retain our status as a NON-union
employer.<p> 


<H3>WORKING TOGETHER</h3>

(Sample C)<p>

The growth and personal achievement we have experienced at the Firm is
the result of working together in a spirit of cooperation and teamwork
that has enabled us to meet many difficult challenges. The progress that
has been achieved reflects this strong mutual commitment between the
Firm and our employees. All of this was done without third party
influence or interference. It is not necessary for any employee to join
or pay dues to any outside organization in order to work here.<p> 


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><br>
