LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Guidelines for Editorial Employees - American Lawyer
Media, L.P. </h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Library File</h3>

<H4>Contributor: Cloyd Laporte III<br>

Source: Counsel Connect<br>
Address: 600 Third Ave., 2nd Floor, New York, NY  10016<br>
Telephone: (800) 455-4354<br>
Fax: (212) 692-7855<br>

<A
HREF="mailto:claporte@counsel.com">E-mail:claporte@counsel.com</a></h4><p>

<H3>Guidelines for Editorial Employees</h3>

1. CORRECTIONS<p>

a) Do it prominently: It is our policy to publish
corrections as
soon as possible in a way that is at least as prominent as
the
original mistake. Thus, if we make a mistake on page one,
the
correction should run on page one, in type as large or
larger
than the mistake. Remember, the goal is to make the
correction at
least as prominent as the error.<p>

b) Come clean: A correction should never be coated in
euphemisms
such as "clarification." When we make a mistake, we should
say so
candidly.<p>

2. HANDLING COMPLAINTS<p>

When a reader or the subject of an article complains that
something is inaccurate or unfair, the highest editorial
person
on the scene should be made aware of it immediately.<p>

Although complaints are handled by the editors of each
publication, tear sheets of all corrections, no matter how
trivial, are sent to Steve Brill.<p>

3. SOURCING<p>

a) Know the ground rules: All reporters are obligated to be
thoroughly familiar with the vocabulary of reporting ground
rules. To avoid confusion and because usage varies, we'll
repeat
the basics here.<p>

"Off the record" means your source never told you the
information
and you can't use it in your story. Of course, a good
reporter
can usually get the story from other sources once he or she
knows
it's there to get.<p>

"On background" means that you can act on the information
without
attributing it to your source personally or to sources at
his or
her firm. You can use the information, you just can't
attribute
it.<p>

"Not for attribution" means that the source will be
identified in
a general way. Be careful here: You want to give the reader
as
much information as possible about your source's credibility
(or
lack of credibility). But you don't want to give away so
much
that a careful reader can identify the source.<p>

"A partner at Smith, James who worked on the case" is better
than
"a Smith, James lawyer" but if only one partner is working
on the
matter, you've screwed your source.<p>

Always push people to be on the record. Remind them that
readers
put more stock in an attributed quote. If you must, allow
them to
go "not for attribution," then, if that fails, "on
background,"
and if all else fails, "off the record." But remember that
"off
the record" pretty much means you can't use it in your story
at
all unless confirmed independently.<p>

b) Be Explicit: All reporters should try to use the most
explicit
sourcing possible. NEVER USE "SOURCES SAID." The words
"sources
say" or "a source said" mean nothing to a reader and should
never
appear in our journalism. Always tell the reader how many
sources, precisely. And, to the extent possible, tell what
kinds
of sources: Your doorman? Or a top lawyer working on the
case?<p>

Some reporters think "sources say" is a figure of speech,
meaning
one source told them something. To us, it means more than
one,
and readers want to know how many more. So say five
litigators,
or two dozen associates, or whatever. Similarly, don't use
"more
than" if you can be more specific. Precision adds more to
your
credibility than a vague allusion to larger numbers.<p>

If a source insists that he not be described in any way at
all,
then you really can't cite the source. You can't say "a
source
said" or anything equivalent to that.<p>

c) Tell About a Source's Weakness: If your anonymous (or
named)
source clearly has an ax to grind, tell your readers.<p>

An example: "says a lawyer involved in the Texaco/Pennzoil
case"
is not as good as "says a lawyer on the Texaco side."<p>

Another example: "says someone who knows Smith well" is not
as
good as "says someone who claims to know Smith well, but who
left
his employ after a falling out." Our goal is to tell our
readers
what we know and convey our impression of the information,
not to
sell our readers something we don't buy or of which we're
wary.<p>


4. GETTING FAIR COMMENT<p>

In this company, the single worst thing a reporter can do is
to
attribute an act or thought to someone without getting that
person's specific comment about whether that act or thought
happened.<p>

To take a seemingly simple example, suppose you're writing a
profile of Smith and you interview his college roommate,
Jones.
If Jones says the two of them used to wake up at 4:30 to
study,
ask Smith. Similarly, if Smith says that he and Jones were
arrested at college for indecent exposure, ask Jones.<p>

If Smith (the subject of the profile) says, "Business is
full of
tough decisions, but you have to make them. A year ago I
even had
to fire my college roommate, Jim Jones," you'd better ask
Jones
about that.<p>

This is necessary both for fairness and for accuracy.<p>

What if Jones is unavailable for comment? Make sure you
leave an
explicit message about what you want to ask and that you
make a
note of who took the message and the time of the call. This
is
not so much for legal protection as to ensure that you work
in a
way that produces careful, accurate reporting and which will
enable you to write a snappy reply when Jones writes a
letter
complaining about how stupid and unfair you are.<P>

If all efforts to obtain fair comment have been exhausted,
remember that you may and should incorporate any statement
the
person has previously made on the point. You should also
seek to
obtain his side by calling his lawyer or a friend, associate
or
anyone else who can knowledgeably describe the person's
point of
view on the subject.<p>

No one we write about should ever be surprised about what we
say
because we will have either asked him about it or left an
explicit message that we want to ask him about it.<p>

For those with daily deadlines, if you can't leave an
explicit
message that someone can be reasonably expected to receive
in
time to respond to you, and if the information you are about
to
write is negative, then hold the story for a day. In other
words,
either we sacrifice a scoop or you do a better job at
leaving
effective messages. We don't sacrifice fairness or
accuracy.<p>

When in doubt about any of this, call Steve Brill.<p>

5. QUOTES<p>

a) No Embellishment: Quotes are never to be embellished.
They
should never be taken out of context. A good test of whether
they're taken in context is for you to assume the person
you're
quoting has secretly recorded the interview, and he can
produce
that recording for your editor and your readers to judge how
fair
you've been.<p>

If a spokesman for Jones says he is speaking for Jones, you
still
must attribute it to "Smith, a spokesman for Jones," not
Jones.<p>

b) Label All Quotes: Don't say: Smith's firm is "the most
congenial place" he's ever been associated with. Say: Smith
says
his firm is "the most congenial place" he's ever been
associated
with. Or: To Smith, Jones, Day is "the most congenial place"
he's
ever been associated with.<p>
 
c) Be Careful of Blind Quotes: It's unfair to have your most
negative quote about someone be anonymous. Don't do it.<p>

d) Be Careful of Deals: You should try never to make a deal
with
someone to read his quotes back to him before you publish
them.
People will always want to change their quotes. But
remember, no
one has to talk to you, and this is sometimes the only way
to get
someone on the record. What you sometimes can do is tell
someone
who insists on not being quoted at all that what he's saying
is
for background only unless you decide he's said something so
important that you want to come back to him for approval, at
which point it can go on the record if he agrees to it.
That's a
deal to read back quotes, but it's one that's been made only
with
someone who really wasn't going to be quoted at all.<p>

Generally, you are free to make deals with a source but with
two
caveats: (1) you must keep to them, and (2) you can never
make a
deal to let anyone see a draft or part of a draft in
advance.<p>

Don't make deals that restrict your ability to do other
reporting. It's one thing to promise you won't use what a
source
tells you, but don't promise that you won't make calls or
won't
use the information under any circumstances. What if someone
else
tells all?<p>

e) Give Credit for Old Quotes: If you are quoting someone
from
what he said to another reporter in another article, be sure
to
say where the quote is coming from. And be explicit. Don't
just
say: "'I own the world', he was quoted as saying." Say: "'I
own
the world,' he told The New York Times last year."<p>

6. GIVING CREDIT<p>

All of us hate it when larger publications steal from us.
The
answer isn't to do the same, but to show the way. Bend over
backwards to give credit for things reported first
elsewhere,
especially if the credit belongs to a competitor. Not only
is
this the right thing to do; it also demonstrates to readers
how
much class we have and how secure we are about how good we
are.
When in doubt, give credit.<p>

7. HONESTY IN REPORTING<p>

Some narrowly defined deceptions in reporting are perfectly
acceptable. For example, it's perfectly appropriate for a
consumer reporter to take his car to eight repair shops when
he
knows it's in perfect shape, just to see what each mechanic
will
say. Similarly, it's fine for a restaurant reviewer to make
reservations under a phony name in order to pose as a
typical
customer. But most other deceptions are unacceptable and all
proposals for deceptions should be cleared with the editor
in
advance.<p>

Most areas are not at all gray. For example, in the normal
course
of things, a reporter should always identify himself as
such.
(Don't just walk up to a juror after the verdict and ask
what the
deliberations were like without identifying yourself.)<p>

Other things that are not allowed at all:<p>

a) Tape recording any conversation, by telephone or in
person,
unless all parties to the conversation are aware of the
taping
and have given their consent.<p>

b) Taking without authorization documents or anything else
in the
course of reporting, no matter how important the documents
may
be. This is known as stealing.<p>

c) Reading documents (upside down or otherwise) on someone's
desk
during an interview without being invited to do so. This is
dishonest.<p>

d) Calling jurors while they are deliberating or sequestered
or
during the course of a trial.<p>

8. COURTESY<p>

You're a professional, and you need to act like one. The
First
Amendment doesn't give you a right to be angry when people
won't
cooperate with you. They don't have to, and we all know that
in
many instances they have to be crazy or stupid to cooperate,
which, happily, they often are.<p>

While we're on the subject, don't be offended if the person
you're interviewing wants to record the interview or have
someone
else with him. He's being smart, and/or he's been burned by
a bad
reporter before. (It happens, you know.)<p>

9. LAWSUITS<p>

Lawsuits will sometimes come with good reporting. We will
fight
them vigorously when we think we're right; in fact, we'll
usually
sue for our costs. But for us to be effective we need to
know
immediately when someone has threatened you. Tell your
editor
when someone starts talking lawsuit. Other than for acts of
dishonesty or plagiarism, we indemnify all of our reporters
and
editors for all costs and damages in any lawsuit.<p>

10. NOTES<p>

Keep accurate, complete notes. That means keeping the time
and
date of all interviews, as well as the time and date of all
messages left and with whom they were left. In order to
avoid
clutter, you might want to discard your notes, but please
wait
four weeks after publication before you do so. That way,
we'll
have your notes if anyone questions the accuracy of your
work.<p>

In instances where you think someone may later deny being
interviewed, it's usually a good idea to write something
detailed
in your notes about the location of the interview, e.g.
something
about what the office looks like or what pictures were on
the
wall.<p>

11.  STYLE POINTS<p>

Good reporters must be good writers as well. This means
following
rules of grammar, usage and style. It also means writing a
story
as strongly as your reporting allows but no stronger and
constructing it clearly and logically for your reader.<p>

A good editor can be a good writer's best friend in
accomplishing
these goals. A good writer will listen attentively to an
editor's
suggestions and cooperate in making revisions to meet sound
criticisms. At the same time, a good editor will remember to
respect a reporter's knowledge of the story and to defer to
individual matters of style where appropriate.<p>

Your editor will provide you with our style manual and with
the
other authorities we rely on. Here are some style points
that
should be stressed:<p>

a) Use full names: Always use full, formal first names,
never
"Billy Bob" or "Tom." Don't let readers think that some
source is
your best friend. For lawyers, use Martindale-Hubbell as the
standard.<p>

b) Avoid redundancy: Never say "still pending," "general
consensus," "lawsuit," or "future plans."<p>
 
c) Be precise: Never use "sources say" or "a source said" as
an
attribution. Don't say "several" if you mean three. Don't
say
"more than two dozen" if you know it's 28. And if you don't
know
if it's somewhere between 28 and 32, say that, or say
"approximately 30," but don't just say "more than 28."<p>

12. CAPTIONS<p>

Our rule is that there should always be a caption, even if
it's
just a name burnt into a photo over a long pull quote. Think
to
yourself: Is there any chance that a reader will doubt, even
for
a second, who this person is? Too much identification is
never a
problem; too little is. Your job is to make reading (and
being
informed) easier for our customers.<p>


13. IDENTIFYING PEOPLE<p>

Don't hesitate to re-identify people. If you mentioned
someone
1,000 words ago (or before the jump), tell us again
(parenthetically, if necessary) who he is. The Wall Street
Journal is great about this; just about every other paper is
terrible. Your job isn't to prove that readers are fools, or
aren't paying enough attention. It's to make it easy for
them to
read what you write. Bear in mind that people often jump
into a
piece in the middle to see if they want to read it. You
can't
compensate for that fully, but this helps.<p>

14. CATCHING REDUNDANCY AND RHYTHM<p>

Read out loud, in order to check for annoying redundancy and
bad
rhythm. You'll often know it only when you hear it. The best
way
to read a piece the way a reader will is to read it aloud to
yourself.<p>

15. GUIDELINES FOR PHOTOGRAPHY<p>

Quality journalism is not limited to words. We respect and
want
good photography.<p>

Like any good journalist, a photographer working for this
company
should always be thinking how best to tell the story.
Obviously,
environmental props are helpful: for instance, if a lawyer
defends farmers, take him out to the fields. If he has
bizarre
(and relevant) knick-knacks in his office, include them in
the
shot. But most frequently, our photographers will be
confronted
with a special challenge. What lawyers do, at first glance,
looks
quite dull. It's not like shooting sports events or riots.
The
challenge is to look for subtlety. If there is no
interesting
environment, we can do the most classic photograph - the
portrait. Not a ho-hum, who cares, five-frame snap, but an
insightful portrait that strongly brings out the personality
of
the subject. There is a big difference between a powerful
portrait and the wooden publicity head shot that a trade
paper
would normally run. We want the powerful portrait.<p>

We encourage our photographers to be involved with their
pictures
even after they are taken. Photographers shouldn't hesitate
to
protest and come up with solutions if their pictures aren't
getting good play, good captions, or good reproduction. We
want
the best possible photographs for each story, and we want
them to
look right.<p>

The photos we take should reflect the truth. We don't try to
make
people look better or worse than they are. If the subject is
a
slob, we take a picture that shows it. If he is neat, we
take a
picture that shows that. If he has blemishes, we don't
retouch
them. To be fair, if he unintentionally looks like an idiot,
you
could help by pointing out his unzipped fly. But if his desk
is
messy and it's relevant to the story, shoot him there
without
trying to make it nice.<p>

Photographers should never set up shots in which a situation
is
faked, even if that picture is identified as a set-up in the
cutline. News is news and should never be faked. You can get
the
bankruptcy lawyer to stand in front of the company that just
went
bankrupt. This is legitimate combining of relevant facts.
But
posing him reenacting the time when he boarded up the
company's
door with hammer and nails is wrong. However, it's okay to
pose
him in front of the door holding the hammer. It's not fake,
and
the caption can make reference to the real timing of
events.<p>

Retouching should be done only to alter minor points about
the
photo. It should never be done to alter the facts or to
change
anyone's appearance. Flopping photos when they're used is
also a
bad idea. Photos can be altered to emphasize the facts, such
as
fading the background slightly to better portray people in
the
foreground.<p>

Staff photographers' prints and negatives (that is, photos
shot
for the publication) are owned by the company. Free-lance
photographers own their own copyrights and are paid by the
assignment or by the piece.<p>

All photographers guarantee that the work they submit is
their
own. You also guarantee that your work has not been altered,
by
setting up a false situation, by substantive retouching, or
by
any other means.<p>

All photographers are indemnified by this company against
lawsuits from people they are assigned to shoot. So, don't
be
cowed by a hostile lawyer who threatens to sue you if you
press
the shutter. It is legal to photograph people against their
will
if you both are on public property. This does not come up
very
often, but when it does, you are protected.<p>

All photo departments must have organized files. Pictures
must be
credited carefully, free-lancers' and photo agencies' bills
should be paid right away, and any prints or negatives we
don't
own have to be returned quickly. Unlike most newspapers, we
do
keep free-lancers' prints, with their permission, but the
burden
is on us to make sure the photographer is paid for any
re-use.<p>

Details on photo use, contracts, and our chain wide photo
library
are available through the photo department at The American
Lawyer.<p>

16. CONFLICTS OF INTEREST<p>

The key to our conflicts policy is disclosure. Tell your
editor
about any potential conflict or anything that could create
the
appearance of conflict in your reporting or editing. You
should
also, in most cases, tell your readers.<p>

Conflicts arise when you write about close friends or
relatives,
about entities or people on whom close friends or relatives
are
dependent, or about subjects or entities in which you might
have
some financial interest. It is easy to say that if you are
writing or editing or even know about a story in any of our
publications that might affect the value of a stock, you
should
not trade in that stock for a six-month period surrounding
the
article (and not own significant amounts of it in the first
place
without informing your editor and your readers). But with
our
publications, as with most others, conflicts are rarely that
clear. The key s advance disclosure.<p>

17. GIFTS<p>

Gifts of any significant value (more than $50) from any
person
you might be writing about now or in the future should not
be
accepted. Gifts of less than $50 must be disclosed to your
editor. You should refuse even minor gifts whenever you can
do so
gracefully.<p>

You may, however, accept a lunch or a dinner from a source,
including the subject of a story, if that person has invited
you
and picks the place and asks to pay, and your insistence
that he
not would be awkward, insulting or just plain much ado about
nothing. But in any other situation, including any ambiguous
situation, you should pay and charge it to the company.
Under no
circumstances should you accept anything else of value from
a
subject or potential subject, including but not limited to
free
trips.<p>

18. AD-EDIT SEPARATION<p>

As you know, we do not in any way let factors related to
advertisers and potential advertisers influence our
editorial
decisions. However, because ours are commonly seen as
"trade"
publications, and because such ad-edit distinctions are
often
blurred in trade publications, some advertisers and
potential
advertisers may not understand or appreciate our policy.
Thus,
those involved in reporting and editing articles may get
inquiries and even threats about advertising.<p>

You should explain our policy in a friendly way. But no one
on
the editorial side should ever discuss, even casually, with
a
subject or potential subject of a story the benefits of
advertising in our publications. If someone makes an
inquiry, you
should refer them to an advertising salesperson.<p>

Our own advertising salespeople know that they should not
talk to
reporters or other editorial people about advertisers'
requests
or questions concerning our editorial product. If they have
specific ideas for our publications, we ask that they talk
to the
editor. This doesn't mean you should never talk to our ad
people.
You can learn from their knowledge of the legal marketplace,
and
they can learn about our editorial approach from your
experience.
But be careful: don't talk about specific advertisers or the
details of our editorial content. If you ever feel that an
advertising salesperson is pressuring you or inquiring
improperly, please tell that person. If it persists, tell
your
editor.<p>



</BLOCKQUOTE>
