<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>Understanding the ADA: A Primer</h2>

<H2>The Ultimate Employee Handbook -- A Workshop</h2>

<H3>Workshop Library File</h3>

Contributor: Richard K. Berger<br>
Address: 258 Main Street, Suite 203, Milford, MA 01757<br>
Telephone: (508) 478-9647<br>
Fax: (508) 478-9648<p>

<A HREF="mailto:rkberger@rkb.com">E-mail:
rkberger@rkb.com</a><p>

<A HREF="http://www.rkb.com">website: http://www.rkb.com</a><p>

<H3>Understanding the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA): A Primer</h3>  

c.1995 Richard K. Berger.<p>

<H4>Editor's note: This primer on ADA is an example of a document
that could be prepared for clients or for other educational
purposes.<p>

Author's caveat: The contents of this article: (a) should not be
considered or relied upon as legal, financial or other
professional advice in any manner whatsoever, and; (b) may be
considered advertising under the Rules of the Supreme Judicial
Court of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts of the United States
of America. Unless otherwise stated, this article, is, has not
been updated or revised for accuracy as statutory or case law
changes following the date of first publication in June, 1995.
Always consult with your lawyer and/or your other professionals
before acting.</h4>

<hr><p>

You have complied with the laws relating to discrimination based
on sex, origin, religion, nationality and race. The next
generation of legal obligations from Congress involves
disabilities. As a primer, here's what you need to know. The
Americans with Disabilities Act (the ADA) was passed by the
United States Congress in 1990. Title I of the Act deals with
issues of employment, while the other titles deal with issues
including public service, public accommodation, and
telecommunications. From July 26, 1992 to July 26, 1994, Title I
of the ADA applied only to those employers having 25 or more
employees. As of July 27, 1994, the employee number is reduced to
15. Covering virtually all aspects of employment (including job
application procedures, the hiring, advancement, or discharge of
employees, employee compensation, job training, and other terms,
conditions, and privileges of employment), the Act prohibits
employers from intentionally or unintentionally discriminating
against persons with disabilities, and it obligates them to make
reasonable accommodations in the workplace to allow disabled
persons to perform the essential functions of their job. The Act
is a very powerful social tool.<p>

Is every disability covered under the Act? No. Under the Act, a
disability is: "(A) a physical or mental impairment that
substantially limits one or more of the major life activities of
such individual; (B) a record of such an impairment; or (C) being
regarded as having such an impairment." (42 U.S.C.  12102 (2))
Examples of disabilities covered under the Act are: cerebral
palsy; muscular dystrophy; emotional illness; epilepsy; heart
disease; specific learning disabilities; cancer; diabetes; HIV
positive; multiple sclerosis; mental retardation, and; hearing
and speech disorders. Not all disabilities are covered under the
Act. For instance, employees currently using illegal drugs (i.e.
because they are addicted) will receive no protection under the
Act. However, a recovered addict can not be denied employment or
any of its other privileges simply on the basis that he or she
was an addict in the past. An exhaustive discussion of exactly
which potential disabilities may or may not be targeted under the
Act for protection is beyond the scope of this article, and in
every event should be decided in the workplace on a case-by- case
basis with the advice of counsel.<p>

What is a "reasonable accommodation"? Congress provided that: The
term 'reasonable accommodation' may include: (A) making existing
facilities used by employees readily accessible to and usable by
individuals with disabilities; and (B) job restructuring, part
time or modified work schedules, reassignment to a vacant
position, acquisition or modification of equipment or devices,
appropriate adjustment or modifications of examinations, training
materials or policies, the provision of qualified readers or
interpreters, and other similar accommodations for individuals
with disabilities. (42 U.S.C. Section 12111 (9)) The employer has
the burden to acknowledge the disability and work to find a
reasonable accommodation -- and this entire process should be
well and thoroughly documented especially if the employer in its
final analysis determines that a "reasonable accommodation"
cannot be found. This can be a significant burden (administrative
and otherwise) on the employer, but if handled carefully and
properly the desired result may be accomplished usually for
little or no cost and in complete compliance with the Act. For
example, a hearing-impaired person (who as an essential function
of his or her job needs to answer the phone and take messages)
may be accommodated through providing him or her with a cordless
phone equipped for the hearing-impaired. A person confined to a
wheelchair (who works in an office) may be accommodated by having
a raised desk under which the chair will fit, or by simply
raising the desk with blocks. There are many governmental and
private organizations which can be used to assist the employer in
working to find a reasonable accommodation for a disabled
prospective or already-hired employee -- and this will make the
employer's job much easier as well as adding credibility to the
employer's efforts. <p>

Does the employer always have to accommodate the disabled person?
No. As broad as it is, the Act does not require any employer to
accommodate a disability which, even with the accommodation,
would pose a direct threat (meaning a significant risk) to the
health or safety of the disabled person or others. The Act also
provides that employers do not have to make accommodations which
would amount to an "undue burden" on their business. The factors
to be considered in determining whether an accommodation would
constitute an "undue hardship" have been set out by Congress as
follows: In determining whether an accommodation would impose an
undue hardship on a covered entity, factors to be considered
include (i) the nature and cost of the accommodation needed under
this chapter; (ii) the overall financial resources of the
facility or facilities involved in the provision of the
reasonable accommodation; the number of persons employed at such
facility; the effect on expenses and resources, or the impact
otherwise of such accommodation upon the operation of the
facility; (iii) the overall financial resources of the covered
entity; the overall size of the business of a covered entity with
respect to the number of its employees; the number, type, and
location of its facilities; and (iv) the type of operation or
operations of the covered entity, including the composition,
structure, and functions of the workforce of such entity; the
geographic separateness, administrative, or fiscal relationship
of the facility or facilities in question to the covered entity.<p>

These amorphous factors have begun and will continually gain specific
form and shape through federal regulations, litigation (lawsuits), and
state and federal government investigations. Among other things, I would
suggest that to avoid litigation the input of the prospective or
already-hired employee be sought on this issue to empower him or her and
thereby increase a sense of team spirit and decrease the animolying with
the Act. Whether large or small, if your company falls under the
jurisdiction of the ADA, you should work closely with your counsel to
proactively handle ADA compliance at all stages of employment from
hiring to discharge. If you are large enough to have your own HR
department, have them work with your counsel. If your HR department
tells you that they don't need counsel to help them because they know
exactly what to do, ask them to sign a personal guarantee to that
effect. If they won't, ask them why and then pick up the phone and call
your lawyer.<p> 



</BLOCKQUOTE>
