<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Menendez</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/top-casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/top-casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>The Menendez Retrial: February 1996</H2>

<P>NOTE: These files are in a compressed format (zipped). You will need to <A HREF="/download/utility/">download an unzipping utility</A> to open them.</P>

<P>If you prefer, you may <A HREF="february.zip">download the entire month's transcripts</A> at once.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<H3>The Transcripts</H3>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 29</B> [<I><A HREF="feb29.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Closing arguments ended with prosecutor David Conn telling jurors that the defense was a big hoax. Conn said Lyle and Erik Menendez blamed the victims, put their parents on trial, crafted an abuse excuse and told a lot of lies to justify the shootings.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 28</B> [<I><A HREF="feb28.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Defense attorney Leslie Abramson issued an emotional plea in her closing argument for Erik Menendez, saying it would be the "ultimate tragedy" in her life is she lost the case because it  would be so unjust.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 27</B> [<I><A HREF="feb27.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Defense attorney Leslie Abramson urged the jury to acquit Erik Menendez in the slaying of his mother and find him guilty only of manslaughter in the death of his father. She told jurors that Erik was in a state of terror on the night of the shootings and that terror made it impossible to form the mental state for murder.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 26</B> [<I><A HREF="feb26.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Defense Attorney Leslie Abramson opens her closing arguments which include a personal attack of prosecutor David Conn.  She says Conn put on fraudulent witnesses in a desperate effort to win the case.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 23</B> [<I><A HREF="feb23.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Prosecutor David Conn ended his closing argument by asking jurors to convict the brothers of first degree murder.  He argues that the defense did nothing to refute the prosecution's evidence of premeditated and deliberated slayings.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 22</B> [<I><A HREF="feb22.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Prosecutor David Conn took jurors on a meticulous tour through the testimony.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 21</B> [<I><A HREF="feb21.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Prosecutor David Conn continued his assualt on Lyle and Erik Menendez, telling jurors that the tension in the Menendez home did not come from molestations. Instead, it came from the family's realization that the brothers would never be able to walk in their father's footsteps.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 20</B> [<I><A HREF="feb20.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Prosecutor David Conn began his closing argument.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 16</B> [<I><A HREF="feb16.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Judge Stanley Weisberg ruled that the Menendez brothers were not in imminent danger when they shot their 47-year-old mother and therefore could not be considered for manslaughter for her death. But in the shooting of their father, they could be considered for manslaughter.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 15</B> [<I><A HREF="feb15.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Judge Stanley Weisbeerg's decision to limit the testimony of a defense psychiatrist prompted an angry response from a defense attorney who said the brothers were not getting a fair trial.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 14</B> [<I><A HREF="feb14.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
A 27-year-old black female juror was excused for being inattentive during portions of the trial. Later, the defense presented witnesses to contradict the testimony of Craig Cignarelli, Erik Menendez's former best friend.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 13</B> [<I><A HREF="feb13.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The defense called Teresita Baralto, the Menendez brothers' aunt, who testified that just days after the killings, the family replaced the furniture in the den where Kitty and Jose Menendez were killed. This defense is using this testimony to rebut prosecution witness Craig Cignarelli, who claims that Erik gave him a tour of the room, providing details of the shooting.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 9</B> [<I><A HREF="feb09.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The prosecution completed its rebuttal case after defense attorneys concluded a surprisingly short cross-examination of psychiatrist Dr. Park Dietz.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 8</B> [<I><A HREF="feb08.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
A prominent psychiatrist testified that Erik Menendez did not suffer from any disorder that would have impaired his ability to make decisions on the night he shot his parents.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 7</B> [<I><A HREF="feb07.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The jury didn't hear testimony because Erik Menendez was sick. In the morning, lawyers argued over the scope of Dr. Park Dietz' testimony. Dr. Dietz, a prosecution witness, has refused to diagnose Menendez with Post Traumatic Stress Disorder or any other condition that would have impaired his ability to make a decision the night he opened fire on his parents.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 6</B> [<I><A HREF="feb06.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Jamie Pisarcik, Lyle Menendez's former fiancee, completed her testimony.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 5</B> [<I><A HREF="feb05.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Lyle Menendez's former fiancee contradicted Erik's earlier testimony that he did not know his brother wore a wig. This testimony could call into question a major part of the defense case: that a week-long family confrontation between Jose and Kitty Menendez and their sons led to the fatal shootings on August 20, 1989.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 2</B> [<I><A HREF="feb02.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Attorneys questioned Craig Cignarelli, about the $25,000 he received in 1994 for telling the tabloid television show "Hard Copy," all he knew about the killings.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: February 1</B> [<I><A HREF="feb01.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Lawyers argued over the possible testimony of a representative from the California Department of Motor Vehicles. Prosecutors said the representative will testify that Erik Menendez never applied for a duplicate license. Menendez said that he lost his license and that is why he used Donovan Goodreau's to buy the shotguns he and his brother used to kill their parents.</P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
