<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Menendez</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/top-casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/top-casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>The Menendez Retrial: January 1996</H2>

<P>NOTE: These files are in a compressed format (zipped). You will need to <A HREF="/download/utility/">download an unzipping utility</A> to open them.</P>

<P>If you prefer, you may <A HREF="january.zip">download the entire month's transcripts</A> at once.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<H3>The Transcripts</H3>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 31</B> [<I><A HREF="jan31.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The defense was dealt two painful blows before resting its cas-in-chief. Judge Stanley Weisberg ruled defense attorneys could not introduce the testimony of Dr. William Vicary, a psychiatrist who has been treating Erik Menendez since 1990. The judge ruled the testimony only would be relevant as sur-rebuttal testimony, to rebut the testimony of the state's psychiatrist. The judge then ruled the defense could not introduce the videotaped testimony of Lyle Menendez's testimony from the first trial.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 30</B> [<I><A HREF="jan30.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
After presenting 25 witnesses and more than 400 exhibits, the defense indicated that it is about to rest its case. Noticeably absent from the defense case-in-chief was Lyle Menendez.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 29</B> [<I><A HREF="jan29.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The defense presented testimony to try and refute prosecution claims that Lyle and Erik Menendez killed their parents in order to get the family fortune. Marta Cano, Jose Menendez's older sister, testified that shortly after the August 1989 killings, the brothers told her that they believed they had been written out of their father's will a year earlier.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 26</B> [<I><A HREF="jan26.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Judge Stanley Weisberg cut six witnesses from the defense list, ruling that they are irrelevant in the current trial, although they did testify at the first trial. The witnesses include Lyle and Erik's teachers, friends and a coach, and all would have testified about the parents' alleged psychological mistreatment of the brothers. The judge ruled that the issue of psychological mistreatment is irrelevant in the current trial.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 25</B> [<I><A HREF="jan25.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
A key expert defense witness completed his testimony after seven days on the witness stand. Dr. Wilson, director of the Center for Stress & Trauma in Cleveland, testified that Erik suffers from the Post Traumatic Stress Disorder as a result of prolonged sexual and physical abuse. He also said Erik was suffering from the disorder when he and his brother Lyle shot their parents on August 20, 1989.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 24</B> [<I><A HREF="jan24.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Prosecutor David Conn questioned defense witness Dr. John Wilson about the results of psychological diagnostic tests given to Erik Menendez. When Conn pointed out that it would be easy to lie in answering the test questions, Dr. Wilson responded that he had to rely on Erik's word as the basis of most of the test results.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcirpt: January 23</B> [<I><A HREF="jan23.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Defense attorneys demanded a mistrial after the prosecution began its cross-examination of a key defense expert witness. The defense request came after prosecutor David Conn asked Dr. John Wilson whether he knew that one of Erik Menendez's lawyers had written a book about Post Traumatic Stress Disorder.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 22</B> [<I><A HREF="jan22.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The defense presented further expert testimony to explain why Erik Menendez never tried to escape the alleged abuse at the hands of his father.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 19</B> [<I><A HREF="jan19.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The defense presented expert testimony to explain why Erik Menendez never tried to escape the alleged abuse at the hands of his father. Dr. John Wilson testified about what he called the common misconceptions about victims of child abuse. Two of the misconceptions, he said, are that abuse victims can just pack up and leave their abusers and that abuse victims reveal their situations.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 18</B> [<I><A HREF="jan18.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The defense offered additional testimony about possible abuse in the Menendez home. The witnesses included Kathy Simonton, a cousin of the brothers, who testified how Jose Menendez treated his sons when he taught them how to swim. She said he dunked their heads under water until they kicked, flailed, choked and cried. Additional testimony came from Dr. Kerry English who reviewed Erik's childhood medical records. He said Erik suffered an injury to the back of his throat that could be consistent with forced oral sex.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 17</B> [<I><A HREF="jan17.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
A cousin of the Menendez brothers testified that Jose Menendez spent hours with Erik behind the closed door of his bedroom -- a claim the defense says is evidence of sexual molestation. The witness, Diane Vander Molen, testified that Jose Menendez terrified his son by "roaring at him," and that he was "fierce in his anger." Vander Molen broke down in tears as she told jurors how Kitty Menendez would scream at Erik for making mistakes on his homework.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 16</B> [<I><A HREF="jan16.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Brian Alan Anderson, the Menendez brothers' cousin, testified about summer visits he made to the Menendez home, offering evidence of possible sexual and physical abuse to corroborate Erik Menendez's story. He said Jose Menendez would snap a belt on the coffee table as Kitty Menendez rattled off reasons to discipline the children. From a nearby room, Anderson said he heard Jose whip Erik and Lyle. He said he later saw scars on the boys' legs and buttocks. Anderson also recalled Jose showering with Erik and Lyle when the brothers were teenagers. The defense claims this is evidence of sexual molestation. On cross-examination, Anderson to admitted that shortly before Lyle's arrest,  Lyle gave him a $8,500 loan. Prosecutor David Conn suggested that it was a payoff. Anderson said he told Lyle that he couldn't pay the loan back because his daughter is in the hospital, dying from E. Coli, an infectious disease.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 12</B> [<I><A HREF="jan12.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The lawyer defending Lyle Menendez indicated a significant change in legal strategy. Attorney Charles Gessler told the court that he plans to argue Lyle killed in the heat of passion -- that fear and anger overwhelmed him on August 20, 1989, when he and his brother shot their parents. During the first trial, Lyle said he killed out of the honest but mistaken belief that his parents were going to kill him.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 11</B> [<I><A HREF="jan11.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
The defense case entered a new phase as a psychologist testified that Erik Menendez suffered from Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder at the time he killed his parents. Dr. John P. Wilson told jurors that the cause of Erik's disorder was the repeated acts of sexual molestation and physical and psychological abuse. He said Erik exhibited classic disorder symptoms such as recurring nightmares and amnesia.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 9</B> [<I><A HREF="jan09.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Erik Menendez stepped down from the witness stand after 15 days of testimony. The defense tried to introduce a letter found in Menendez's cell about three months after the brothers' arrest. In the letter, Lyle Menendez writes about not wanting to reveal the family secret of sexual abuse as a defense to the crimes. He says he would rather die or escape. The letter is proof the brothers did not concoct the story, defense lawyers said. But Judge Stanley Weisberg did not allow it to be entered into evidence, ruling it hearsay.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 8</B> [<I><A HREF="jan08.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
After eight days, Prosecutor David Conn concluded his cross-examination of Erik Menendez, spending most of the session hammering away at Erik's tape recorded therapy sessions with Dr. Jerome Oziel. In those sessions, Erik admits that he and his brother killed their parents. But if he trusted the doctor so much, why did he fail to mention the lifetime of abuse? Conn asked. Erik said he did not trust Dr. Oziel. Rather, Oziel was blackmailing the Menendez brothers to get his hands on the family fortune. </P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 5</B> [<I><A HREF="jan05.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
With one of the jurors called out of court because of a family emergency, no witnesses testified. Lawyers argued before Judge Stanley Weisberg about whether the defense can introduce videotapes of Lyle Menendez's testimony from the first trial.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 4</B> [<I><A HREF="jan04.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Did Erik Menendez confide in his former friend Craig Cignarelli about the night of the killings? According to Cignarelli's testimony from the first trial, the brothers entered the family den while their parents sat on the couch. Lyle Menendez shot his father and told his brother to "shoot Mom," who stood and started to yell when the fatal shots were fired. Prosecutor David Conn quizzed Erik Menendez about Cignarelli's testimony. Menendez repeatedly denied ever making those statements. The defense contended that Conn followed this line of questioning as a way to put Cignarelli's testimony before the jury without calling Cignarelli as a witness. In the first trial, Cignarelli's credibility was shaken under cross-examination.</P>

<P><B>Trial Transcript: January 3</B> [<I><A HREF="jan03.zip">Download Compressed File</A></I>]<BR>
Prosecutor David Conn grilled Erik Menendez on the minute details of the shooting spree. Menendez said he couldn't remember much more than the boom and red flare coming from his shotgun as he fired at his parents. Under Conn's pressure, Menendez said he did not actually see his father coming at him, but the fear that his life was in danger made him believe it.</P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
