<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Menendez</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>On March 27, the first day of the Menendez trial penalty phase, Mary Jane Stevenson appeared on America Online's Globe, a virtual auditorium that allows as many as 5,000 people to participate in a live chat. Though the judge placed a "gag order" on lawyers involved in the case until the end of the penalty phase, Stevenson was in the courtroom and answered the following questions posed by the audience.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P><B>CourtTV9:</B> Our guest in the Center Stage tonight is Court TV reporter Mary Jane Stevenson, who has been covering the Menendez trial from the courtroom in Van Nuys. Well, Mary Jane, for those of us who missed your report tonight on Prime Time Justice, what happened in today?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> The lawyers gave short opening statements in the morning. The prosecution said it would not call any witnesses. The defense called Aunt Teresita Baralt, who cried on the witness stand and begged for mercy for Lyle and Erik.</P>

<P><B>CourtTV9:</B> What can you tell us about the prosecution's strategy? Isn't it unusual?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Yes. Normally, the prosecution begins a penalty phase with its most powerful evidence -- the victims' family and friends describing their loss. But in this case, almost all of the family members have thrown their support behind Lyle and Erik. This is a problem for the prosecution.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> How are Lyle and Erik looking/acting?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> They definitely seem more downtrodden. Erik seems angry. Today in court, their grandmother showed Lyle a picture of him when he was younger and free. Lyle smiled.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Mary Jane, If Lyle testifies in penalty phase could the Tracy Baker letter be used against him?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I'm not sure because all hearings regarding penalty phase witnesses have been held in secret but Lyle's attorney told me earlier that Lyle most likely will not testify.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Does California require all 12 jurors to vote yes for death penalty?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Yes, The verdict must be unanimous. If the jury deadlocks, the state will have to decide whether to try the penalty phase again.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> MJ, What was the demeanor of the jury this morning?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> They did not smile, even when Leslie Abramson got personal with them during opening statements. They seemed very solemn.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Mary Jane, How did you get chosen to cover the Menendez trial?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I think part of it was because I covered the first trial for a legal newspaper in Los Angeles.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Mary Jane, I am curious to know what you think of the verdict?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I think the interesting point is that this result is so very different than the result in the first trial, and that's because the two trials were so very different.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Did Garcetti win the nomination for DA and did anyone find his partying on the news video upsetting?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Garcetti has been forced into a runoff in November against one of his deputy district attorneys. Many people, including lawyers, have told me they were offended by the cheering on verdict today.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Is there interaction between Erik and Lyle?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Yes, often they talk or pass notes. When the lawyers go to a sidebar conference, they sit and chat with each other.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> During your PTJ broadcast last week, it looked like someone in the DA's office said "Let 'em die" or something. True?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> That's what it sounded like on the tape, but it's impossible to tell who said it. I think the quote was "We'll kill them."</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> How do you handle (or feel) about seeing the penalty phase for two people you have known for over four years?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Good question. It is difficult to watch the family members, especially, plead for the brothers' lives. They have already been through so much.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> MJ, if the jury deadlocks, and the state declines to retry, can the judge give a sentence other than life without parole?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> No.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> What is the minimum that the brothers can receive?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Life without parole. And that means no parole. They will never get out of prison alive.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> MJ, You probably can't wait until this trial is over! Do you have any idea how long the penalty phase is expected to last? Also, what will your next assignment be?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> The penalty phase should last between three to five weeks. I have no idea what I will do next.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Is it true that Lyle and Erik will be sent to different prisons and never allowed to see each other again?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I don't know. I have asked the attorneys, but they say they don't know. One thing is for sure. Their attorneys will do everything they can to keep the brothers out of the general population.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Does the brother's grandmother still visit both Lyle and Erik regularly?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Yes. She visits them in jail, and she comes to court everyday without fail.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Is an appeal realistic?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Many legal experts think a successful appeal is a long shot. Mainly because a higher court would hesitate to overturn these convictions. And send the case back to a third trial. However, some lawyers say Judge Weisberg overstepped his bounds and is likely to be overturned.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> What happened to the families properties?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I believe everything was sold.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> How do the brothers feel about each other? Is there one that blames the other for the responsibility of the killings?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> They have never turned against each other, nor have they ever said, in court, that either one is more responsible than the other. However, Lyle took responsibility for shooting Jose in the back of the head and for reloading and shooting Kitty Menendez at close range in the face.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Do you think that the apparent backlash from the O.J. trial that kept the cameras out of the Menendez trial and others will ever fade, or have we seen the last of high profile cases on TV?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I hope not. Court TV just got into a trial in Los Angeles which is a race-discrimination case which is against the LAPD. Hopefully, that's the beginning of a trend of the camera being allowed in more courtrooms.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> As for Leslie Abramson, is this the end of her legal career?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> So she says. According to her, Erik is her last client.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Did it seem obvious to you that Judge Weisberg was against the brothers? Isn't he supposed to remain impartial?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> The defense argued that he wanted the brothers convicted. The prosecution says he was completely fair.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Were the brothers able to use their inheritance and life- insurance moneys for legal fees?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Yes. They used most of it for legal fees.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Why did Domminick Dunne make such a big deal on CNN about no reaction in the Courtroom when he knows very well the judge and bailiffs forbid any reaction?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I don't know.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Why do you think the jury was as hard on Erik as they were on Lyle?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I have no idea. I can't wait to talk to the jury about their reasoning on all of this.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Is there going to be an interview show made of all the interviews you've done with the people involved, since we couldn't see them all?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I will do my best to interview as many people as I can.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Have you ever talked to either Lyle or Erik? Bob Rand?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Yes, all three. I talk to Bob Rand every day.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Do you think the jury might have second thoughts or doubts when they hear all of the abuse evidence during the penalty phase?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I don't know. The jury may have rejected all of the abuse evidence already which may be devastating for the defense, if that is true.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Well, if they are sentenced to death, how long will they be on death row?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> For years and years. They will have automatic appeals to the State Supreme Court, and that will take years.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> How is the health of the two dismissed jurors?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I don't know. I have tried to find out, but I haven't heard anything since I reported that one of them had a heart attack and the other went into premature labor. The court will not release any information about them.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Why do you think the country was so mesmerized by this trial?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Because it was a family story. It had all the elements of wealth, greed, allegations of sexual molestation, secrecy, murder which makes a very compelling story.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> What happened to Dr. Oziel?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> He moved to Arizona, and he did not testify in this trial because the prosecution did not want him to undergo the same blistering cross-examination as he did in the first trial.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> What are conditions like in general in the California prisons and on death row?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I don't know the details. But I can say that Leslie Abramson is extremely worried about Erik joining the prison population.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> What do you think of gag orders in these type of cases?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I think it is too extreme. This is the ultimate action of a state to seek the death penalty, and the attorneys should be able to discuss it publicly. It is a political act, and the people have the right to know how it is being carried out. It should not be carried out in secrecy.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> How did Abramson get along with the lawyers for Lyle?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Very well. They are all friends and longtime colleagues.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> If they are sentenced to death how long does it take for the deaths to be carried out and are they carried out by lethal injection?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Yes, they are carried out by lethal injection. It will take years for the brothers to be executed, if they are sentenced to death.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> What does "special circumstance" mean?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> There are certain circumstances to murder which the State deems especially heinous. And the special circumstances, in this case, were multiple murder and lying in wait --which means waiting to take the victim by surprise. Those special circumstances are what made the brothers eligible for the death penalty.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> What is an average day like for the brothers in prison? Do they have to work? Do they get to watch TV (like Court TV) or have any kind of recreational activity?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> They get to watch TV. They can talk on the phone. Erik has a job. I don't know if Lyle has a job. They read a lot and write a lot of letters.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Is it true that Lyle and Erik are having lots of health problems?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I have not heard that.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Can there be an appeal if the brothers have no money and what lawyers will handle it?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> Different lawyers will handle the appeals, and they will be paid for by the tax payers' money, because the Menendez brothers are broke.</P>

<P><B>Question:</B> Why do you think the Menendez Brothers are hated so much?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> I think a lot of it has to do with that they're rich and from Beverly Hills. And they lied about their involvement in these crimes and they spent hundreds of thousands of dollars of their parents' money after killing them.</P>

<P><B>CourtTV9:</B> We're about out of time. Mary Jane, what will we see the rest of this week?</P>

<P><B>StevensnMJ:</B> More family members and friends of the Menendez family pleading for mercy for Lyle and Erik. After that, a parade of coaches and teachers will discuss Jose and Kitty Menendez' parenting techniques.</P>

<P><B>CourtTV9:</B> Thanks a lot for joining us in The Globe. Good night, everybody.</P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
