<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Menendez</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<h2>Penalty Phase: How It Works</h2>

<P>The jurors who convicted Lyle and Erik Menendez of first-degree murder then had to decide whether the brothers should be sentenced to life in prison or death by lethal injection.</P>

<P>The penalty phase of the trial was different from that in most trials. The prosecution usually presents evidence first, often testimonials from the victim's family, known as "victim impact statements."  But most of Jose and Kitty Menendez's relatives supported the brothers. Brian Andersen, the brother of Kitty Menendez, was the only family member to publicly express support for the state's case.</P>

<P>So the prosecution had to wait while the defense presented its case to the jury of eight men and four women.</P>

<P>The rules of evidence in the penalty phase differ greatly from those during the guilt phase of the trial. Since jurors are asked to make a life or death decision, the defense is allowed to appeal to their sympathy. </P>

<P>The rules allowed the defense to offer evidence of mitigating factors, such as the brothers' ages, whether they were "under the influence of extreme mental or emotional disturbance," whether  "the victims were participants in their own deaths" and any other evidence that diminished the gravity of the crime.</P>

<P>So the jury heard testimony about the brothers' lives and the allegations of parental abuse that was declared inadmissible during the murder trial. Defense attorneys started with the brothers' early childhood and worked their way up to the present. The defense witness list included relatives, friends, coaches, teachers,  the brothers' therapists,  Kitty Menendez's psychiatrist,  Jose Menendez's business associate and a priest.</P>

<P>During the closing argument part of the penalty phase, the prosecution goes first and then the defense. There is no prosecution rebuttal closing argument. The rules also are much more lax. The attorneys are allowed to say almost anything. They may not evoke religion but they can quote from the Bible. The only thing they are not allowed to do is describe how an execution takes place.</P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
