<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Menendez</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>The state wants to present Craig Cignarelli's testimony before a single jury in the retrial of Lyle and Erik Menendez. The testimony involves statements that Erik Menendez made to him. This is the text of the state's motion, filed December 8, 1994.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
GIL GARCETTI 
District Attorney 
DAVID P. CONN 
Head Deputy District Attorney 
CAROL JANE NAJERA 
Deputy District Attorney 
210 West Temple Street 
Los Angeles, California 90012 
Telephone: (213) 974-3739 
 
Attorneys for Plaintiff 
 
SUPERIOR COURT OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA 
IN AND FOR THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES 
 
PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA 
Plaintiff 
 
v. 
 
JOSEPH LYLE MENENDEZ and 
ERIK GALEN MENENDEZ 
 
Defendants 
 
CASE NO. BA068880 
 
PEOPLE'S SUPPLEMENTAL 
PROFFER OF EVIDENCE TO BE
PRESENTED BEFORE A SINGLE JURY 
 
DATE: DECEMBER 19, 1994 
TIME: 9:00 A.M. 
PLACE: DEPARTMENT NW  "N" 
 
TO THE HONORABLE STANLEY WEISBERG, JUDGE 
OF THE VAN NUYS SUPERIOR COURT, AND TO THE 
DEFENDANTS AND THEIR ATTORNEYS 
 
PLEASE TAKE NOTICE that on December 19, 1994, the 
People of the State of California will move this court to rule 
that the following proposed testimony presented herein may 
be presented before a single jury in the retrial of the 
defendants. This motion will be based upon this notice, the 
previously filed points and authorities, and such argument as 
will be made at the time of the hearing of this motion. 
 
I 
 
INTRODUCTION 
 
On May 16, 1994, the People filed a motion with this court 
entitled, "PEOPLE'S PROFFER OF EVIDENCE TO BE 
PRESENTED BEFORE A SINGLE JURY." This motion 
was filed in an effort to identify and litigate prior to the trial 
key areas of evidence that raise issues of admissibility 
before a single jury. Included in this proffer was the 
proposed testimony of Craig Cignarelli concerning 
admissions made to him by Erik Menendez. (see page 15 of 
that motion). This statement, offered as an admission of the 
defendant under Evidence Code section 1220 was redacted 
to deleted references to the defendant's brother Lyle 
Menendez. 
 
This proposed statement was based upon the testimony of 
Craig Cignarelli from the first trial. Upon reviewing the 
police reports of statements made by Craig Cignarelli, 
however, it is apparent that the testimony of Craig Cignarelli 
at the first trial only included a portion of the statements that 
Mr. Cignarelli originally related to the police. At this time 
the People seek to supplement our proffer of evidence 
concerning the proposed testimony of Craig Cignarelli. 
Specifically, the People seek to call Craig Cignarelli to have 
him testify to the contents of the reports dated November 
17, 1989 and March 7, 1990. 
 
II 
 
THE PROPOSED STATEMENTS  
 
The People propose to offer, through the testimony of Craig 
Cignarelli, the following statement contained in the report 
dated November 17, 1989: 
 
Erik Menendez said that he drove up to the house, opened 
the front gate, pulled into the driveway, unlocked the front 
door and walked in.  His parents were in the family room 
watching television. He walked outside to the front of the 
house and got a gun. He walked back inside and went into 
the room. He was unable to shoot his mother and she tried to 
get away. After it looked like his mother was dead, he shot 
her twice with his gun. He ran out the back door and jumped 
the fence to the front. 
 
He said that his father taught him everything, the only thing 
that he didn't teach him was how to live on his own. 
 
The People also propose to offer, through the testimony of 
Craig Cignarelli, the following statement contained in the 
report dated March 7, 1990. 
 
Erik Menendez said that he walked inside through the front 
door, into the foyer and up to the library. The left door 
leading into the library was slightly open. The right door 
was shut. He looked in and saw his dad sitting in the chair. 
His mom screamed and stood up, and he shot his mom after 
she had stood up. She was standing when he shot her. He 
continued shooting until the gun was empty. There was skin 
and blood on the wall. He opened the back door from the 
living room and left the house. He came back a couple of 
hours later and found them. The floor was cleared of all 
shotgun shells. 
 
Craig asked Erik why he shot his parents. Erik told him that 
all great leaders had no parents. He then gave examples of 
Alexander the Great and Hitler. He said that their parents 
had died or they had left their parents or something to that 
extent. Erik then said that he needed money to succeed in 
what he wanted to do in life. Dying was his father's final 
lesson to him, to be able to do things on his own and to 
teach him to live with responsibility. 
 
Erik was in a very descriptive mood and he was very quiet 
and very deliberate in what he had to say. Erik was walking 
through the library pointing out the areas where particular 
things happened. He stated that his father was seated in a 
chair or at the end of the couch. His dad and mom were 
watching a movie on television. His mom was at the end of 
the couch. After Erik shot her, she fell to the floor. 
 
Erik told Craig that he would get 45 million dollars and that 
his father had a Swiss bank account with approximately 80 
million in it. 
 
III 
 
ADMISSIBILITY OF THE PROPOSED STATEMENTS 
IN A JOINT TRIAL 
 
As more fully elaborated upon in our original motion, 
because the statements have been redacted to exclude 
references to the codefendant, they do not violate the 
principles of Aranda-Bruton. In Richardson v. Marsh, the 
Supreme Court provided for the mechanism of redacting a 
statement and offering it in a joint trial, provided that a 
limiting instruction is given which states in clear and 
unambiguous terms that the statement is limited to the 
declarant and cannot be considered against any other  
defendant. The People ask this court to follow the reasoning 
of Richardson and allow this relevant evidence to be 
admitted in a joint trial accompanied by an appropriate 
limiting instruction. 
 
Admission of this evidence would not violate Evidence 
Code Section 352 either. Once again, as discussed in our 
original motion, the California Supreme Court has 
interpreted the term "prejudice" in People v. Wright (1985) 
39 Cal.3d. 576, 585, as referring to statements which would 
"uniquely tend to evoke an emotional bias against ...(one 
party) as an individual" and which would have "very little 
effect on the  issues." The statements in issue are not so 
inflammatory that they would evoke an emotional bias 
against the declarant or the codefendant, who is not even 
mentioned in the statement. Hence, Evidence Code Section 
352 would not warrant the exclusion of this evidence, 
particularly where a limiting instruction is employed. 
 
In the first trial,  this court ruled that portions of the 
defendant Erik Menendez's confession to Mr. Cignarelli 
would be admitted before Erik Menendez's jury. Because 
both sides had agreed to proceed with two juries, the 
Aranda-Bruton issue and the 352 issue was not litigated in 
the prior proceeding. In this proceeding, where the People 
have indicated our intention to proceed with a single jury, 
we ask that the proposed statements be ruled admissible 
before a single jury. 
 
There was a discussion on the record concerning portions of 
the above-described reports in volume 53 of the transcript, 
starting on page 7644, line 9, and continuing to page 7680. 
The People indicated that they would not be offering the 
statement about "great leaders" on page 7658, lines 14-24. 
The People also stated on page 7674, lines 1-14, that they 
would not offer the statement concerning Erik Menendez's 
expectation concerning the 80 million dollar Swiss back 
account because they felt that Mr. Cignarelli did not have 
first-hand information concerning this. It is now our position 
that whether Mr. Cignarelli had personal knowledge of this 
account is irrelevant. What is relevant is that the defendant 
had this expectation. 
 
IV 
 
CONCLUSION 
 
Based upon the argument appearing in our previously-filed 
motion, as well as our argument advanced in this motion, the 
People respectfully request that this court admit the 
statements in issue in a joint trial conducted before a single 
jury, accompanied by an appropriate limiting instruction. 
 
Respectfully submitted this 8th day of December, 1995. 
 
/s/ David P. Conn 
/s/ Carol Najera 
</PRE>
