<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<P> In this three-day hearing, lawyers argued over what evidence the prosecution must turn over to the defense. Prosecutors are obliged to provide the defendants any evidence they consider using in a trial as well as any information that might help the defense side. Defendant Timothy McVeigh's attorney, Stephen Jones, asked for details on negotiations between authorities and Michael Fortier, a former associate of McVeigh's who is expected to testify for the government in exchange for a plea agreement. Jones contended that Fortier changed his story as part of deal to avoid trial.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
                 IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
                                FOR THE DISTRICT OF COLORADO

               Criminal Action No. 96-CR-68

               UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,

                   Plaintiff,

               vs.

               TIMOTHY JAMES McVEIGH and TERRY LYNN NICHOLS,

                   Defendants.

               

                                    REPORTER'S TRANSCRIPT
                   (HEARING ON MOTIONS - VOLUME I)

   

            Proceedings before the HONORABLE RICHARD P. MATSCH,

   Judge, United States District Court for the District of

   Colorado, commencing at 9:00 a.m., on the 13th day of November,

   1996, in Courtroom C-203, United States Courthouse, Denver,

   Colorado.















    Proceeding Recorded by Mechanical Stenography, Transcription
                 Produced via Computer by Paul Zuckerman, 1929 Stout Street,
       P.O. Box 3563, Denver, Colorado, 80294, (303) 629-9285



                                                                           2



                             APPEARANCES

            PATRICK M. RYAN, United States Attorney for the

   District of Oklahoma, 210 West Park Avenue, Suite 400, Oklahoma

   City, Oklahoma, 73102, appearing for the plaintiff.

            JOSEPH H. HARTZLER, SEAN CONNELLY, LARRY A. MACKEY,

   BETH WILKINSON, SCOTT MENDELOFF, and VICKI BEHENNA, Special

   Attorneys to the U.S. Attorney General, 1961 Stout Street,

   Suite 1200, Denver, Colorado, 80294, appearing for the

   plaintiff.

            STEPHEN JONES, ROBERT NIGH, JR., ROBERT WYATT,

   Attorneys at Law, Jones, Wyatt & Roberts, 114 East Broadway,

   Suite 100, Post Office Box 472, Enid, Oklahoma, 73702-0472, and

   JERALYN MERRITT, 303 East 17th Avenue, Suite 400, Denver,

   Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant McVeigh.

            RONALD G. WOODS, ADAM THURSCHWELL, and REID NEUREITER,

   Attorneys at Law, 1120 Lincoln Street, Suite 1308, Denver,

   Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant Nichols.

                            *  *  *  *  *

                             PROCEEDINGS

       (In open court at 9 a.m.)

            THE COURT:  Please be seated.

            Good morning.  We're here in 96-CR-68, United States

   vs. Timothy James McVeigh and Terry Lynn Nichols for a hearing

   on several defense motions; and as usual, I'll ask for the

   appearances.



                                                                           3



            MR. HARTZLER:  Good morning, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  Good morning, Mr. Hartzler.

            MR. HARTZLER:  Joseph Hartzler along with Larry

   Mackey, Sean Connelly, Vicki Behenna, Scott Mendeloff, and Beth

   Wilkinson.

            THE COURT:  And for Mr. McVeigh?

            MR. JONES:  Your Honor, Stephen Jones for McVeigh.  To

   my right, Ms. Merritt, Ms. Wyatt, Mr. Nigh; and Mr. McVeigh is

   present in person.

            THE COURT:  Good morning.

            For Mr. Nichols?

            MR. WOODS:  Good morning, your Honor.  Ron Woods for

   Mr. Nichols.  To my left is Reid Neureiter and Adam

   Thurschwell.  We have the defendant Terry Nichols present.

   Lead counsel, Mike Tigar, had a prior commitment to teach in

   France this week.

            THE COURT:  Yes.  And, Mr. Nichols, as I understand

   it, you've agreed that we can continue without him for purposes

   of these hearings.

            THE DEFENDANT NICHOLS:  Yes, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  All right.  Thank you.

            Now, there are -- a lot of paper has been filed in

   connection with these matters; and my suggestion with respect

   to our sequence of hearing these matters is that we start out

   with the Rule 16, what's been described as "the narrowed Rule



                                                                           4



   16 motion"; and I think that's going to take some time item by

   item.  I reviewed the Government's response as well as the

   motion; and unless something has happened since the last papers

   filed, I assume we're going to discuss those item by item.

            Then there is a discovery motion filed on behalf of

   Mr. Nichols that raises four matters that we'll consider next.

            Then there is a request, again called "the narrowed

   request for expert witness discovery."

            Then there is a hearing on a motion to compel

   production of exculpatory evidence, Brady material, part of

   which may have to be taken in chambers.

            I have directed that notice be given that we would at

   9:00 tomorrow morning hear the Government's proposed criteria

   for admission to closed circuit televised proceedings and this

   related collateral matter, 96-X-134, petition for admission of

   media to closed circuit television proceedings.  We'll do --

   wherever we are in this sequence, we'll interrupt it to do that

   so that the lawyers for the media will have an opportunity to

   appear on the 96-X-134.

            Then at some point, I also need to meet with counsel

   for the Government and for Mr. McVeigh with respect to the

   technical aspects of closed circuit television -- televised

   proceedings and matters that relate to the first trial.

            So that's what I suggest.  Now, I don't know whether

   you've met and made your own suggestions, but if there is no



                                                                           5



   disagreement, that's how I'd propose to proceed.

            MR. JONES:  I don't have a disagreement with it.  That

   would be fine.

            I would like to ask -- I wasn't quite sure where you

   were going to hear the matters with respect to our motion on

   national security.

            THE COURT:  Well, I consider that to be under the

   general heading of the exculpatory evidence, and that's the

   portion of it that I think requires an in-chambers meeting with

   counsel.

            So given that, I'm ready to start on the narrowed Rule

   16.

            Ms. Wilkinson?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, the Government has one

   request.

            THE COURT:  Okay.

            MS. WILKINSON:  When we came to court this morning,

   Mr. Jones brought in a variety of charts and gave us copies of

   those charts.  We would object to those being introduced during

   this discovery hearing and ask that the Court review copies of

   those charts prior to Mr. Jones being permitted to use them

   during this hearing, either during the Rule 16, the

   exculpatory, or any other portion of the hearing.

            THE COURT:  Well, are there small ones that I can look

   at before we --



                                                                           6



            MR. JONES:  Well, there is a court's copy, yes, sir.

            THE COURT:  Yeah.  Well, I suggest we take those up at

   the time that Mr. Jones thinks they're relevant.

            MR. JONES:  A few of them, your Honor, relate in

   general to the Rule 16 matter, some preliminary remarks I have

   with respect to discovery.

            I can, if the Court will give me just a second here --

            Your Honor, I believe the ones that I'm handing to the

   Court now would come up during the discussion of Rule 16 and

   the presentation with respect to the methodology.

            THE COURT:  Well, D is something I've already seen,

   isn't it?  Or is this something different from Mr.Lloyd?

            MR. JONES:  It's been filed, your Honor.  It's dated

   November 10.

            THE COURT:  I've already seen it.

            MR. JONES:  It's to be used or intended to be used

   during the oral argument to highlight certain -- I'm sorry.

   Mr. Wyatt says the November 10 letter hasn't been filed yet.

   It's attached to --

            THE COURT:  Well, why do these have to be blowups?

            MR. JONES:  For ease of discussion, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  I can read them right here.

            MR. JONES:  Sure.  Ease of discussion of the Court and

   to the Government and to Mr. Tigar and ourselves.

            THE COURT:  Well, we'll deal with them as they come up



                                                                           7



   one at a time, but I don't see the need for the blowups.

            I do have a question, actually, before we start.

            Ms. Wilkinson, you, I think -- the glossary that you

   submitted which is very helpful except with respect to one item

   and that is 1C "(potential exhibit)."  This is a "large 1A."  I

   think I understand what 1A is, but is a large 1A a larger

   category?  What does the adjective describe?

            MS. WILKINSON:  In this case, your Honor, there isn't

   much of a difference between what's listed on the 1A and the 1C

   list other than the volume.  1A has many more items.  1A and

   1C's are the FBI designators for evidence or information or

   documents collected that don't normally need a chain of

   custody, so they're paper documents.

            In this case, the 1C's, I believe there is 685 -- I

   can't remember -- and Mr. McVeigh's counsel has seen all of

   those.

            THE COURT:  So "large" means a greater number of the

   same type of thing?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Correct.

            THE COURT:  Which may or may not become exhibits,

   then.  Is that correct?

            MS. WILKINSON:  That's right, your Honor.  Those that

   we believe will be exhibits at that time, we have already

   provided copies to counsel months ago, but they've also

   reviewed all of the 1C's the Government has.



                                                                           8



            THE COURT:  Okay.  So 1A are the things that are

   likely to be exhibits and that are also not 1B in the sense

   that they're not big --

            MS. WILKINSON:  1B stands normally for "bulky."  1C is

   other things we've collected.  Polygraph information in the

   1A's:  Obviously, that information, evidence is not admissible;

   but we keep track of it through the 1A system, other things

   like that.

            THE COURT:  I see.  Thank you.  That helps.

            All right.  Mr. Jones?

            MR. JONES:  Thank you, your Honor.

            May it please the Court, before going directly into

   the Rule 16, I would like to make just a few very preliminary

   remarks about the scope of the discovery issue and the -- what

   has transpired since the last time we were in court with

   respect to hearing it and then some information that we have

   put together which will also be included in the status report

   we will file with the Court, but I take just a moment now in

   the full representation of my client to put it on the record

   with respect to the types of problems that the counsel on all

   three sides have faced in this case.

            At the last time, I mentioned to the Court on the

   public record -- and I do so again today -- two points that I

   think can never be overstated.  There is no question but that

   this is a massive, unprecedented case.  Certainly, there have



                                                                           9



   been large criminal investigations in the history of the United

   States commanding the full resources of the FBI and other

   agencies.

            But this case perhaps is unique in itself because it

   combines not only a large number of deaths -- 168 -- the

   substantial destruction of several blocks in a downtown major

   metropolitan city, an unprecedented number of injuries, a truly

   significant amount of just physical debris, not to mention

   perhaps 100,000, if not more, individual items of -- if not

   evidence, at least tangible objects that had to be reviewed by

   someone.  That information had to be collated, assembled first

   by the prosecution and given to the defense.

            And the Government has repeatedly said to the Court

   that while it's ready for trial, it is also continuing the

   investigation.  So who knows when the investigation may end and

   at what stage?

            So we recognize that when it may be that it seems that

   we are being unduly harsh or critical to the Government in some

   of these problems, I have to first recognize, as I do candidly,

   that this is an unusual case with unusual problems in

   collecting and assembling and making the information available

   to us.

            The second thing that I want to say again is that

   Linda Vernon of the FBI, who has sort of been in charge of the

   physical assembling and distribution of this evidence, has been



                                                                           10



   very helpful, very professional in all of the things that she

   has done in this case.  And, frankly, although there are

   differences between ourselves and Mr. Hartzler and

   Ms. Wilkinson and the others on the Government side, there has

   been in some areas extraordinary cooperation and response to

   letters and inquiries that we have had.  And Mr. Mackey

   continues to work on the phone problems -- or record of phone

   call problems.

            So when I speak, as I hope to do later today, about

   some of the unresolved issues, I do it without rancor and I do

   it with full recognition of what I just said.

            I think also that it sometimes is forgotten that in

   addition to the case of United States vs. Timothy McVeigh in

   which the parties are the Government, ourselves, and Mr. Tigar

   on behalf of Mr. Nichols, we have counted up 61 other

   proceedings that have interfered -- if I may use that term in a

   neutral setting -- with the preparation and investigation of

   this case.  Those 61 issues include 14 other miscellaneous

   cases, 7 appeals, 5 interventions by the victims, and I believe

   it's 56 separate -- I'm sorry -- 36 separate media motions, for

   a grand total of 61 separate proceedings that I count.  And

   then it's possible that I may have overlooked some, because I

   know Mr. Tigar's office was involved in 1 or 2.

            Those 61 proceedings have involved an inordinate

   amount of time of the Court and all of us; and to the extent



                                                                           11



   they impact upon discovery, they are a diversion from the

   principal function here, which is to get this case ready for

   trial.

            I also made it clear, I think, in our pleadings and

   what I have said before that the defense in this case is "not

   guilty"; that we will seek to challenge the Government's

   evidence and the allegations of the grand jury; that we

   certainly will contend that there is a John Doe 2 and maybe 3,

   4 and 5, there are multiple Ryder trucks, and that our client

   is not guilty.

            And with one or two exceptions, each and every thing

   in the Government's case will be challenged.

            I have also indicated to the Court that I see the case

   from the standpoint of the trial and the discovery issues as

   breaking down essentially into five large areas, which for the

   sake of organization and clarity to follow are what I think are

   the five major thrusts of the indictment and the case that we

   will be called upon to defend against.  Those include the

   eyewitness identifications alleged at Junction City and the

   writing -- renting of the Ryder truck in which the Government

   alleges that our client was Robert Kling.  The forensic

   evidence from the lab would be the second one.  The third would

   be the proffered testimony of Michael and Laurie Fortier which

   presumably will come at the trial.  The fourth will be the

   issue of the arrest of Mr. McVeigh by Trooper Hanger, what I've



                                                                           12



   called the proximity issue.  And the fifth will be the issue

   raised by Government's pleadings of Mr. McVeigh's motives

   insofar as it relates to Waco and perhaps other incidents.

            So when we look at the discovery issues and we prepare

   for trial, we look generally to those five areas.

            The Government has produced to us 25,000 witness

   statements and still counting.  The index alone to those

   statements is 580 pages by the most recent count.  We are told

   that the 1A list consists of 15,000 items.  The index to that,

   which covers only 6,000 items -- those being the 6,000 the

   Government thinks that we are entitled to know the existence

   of -- I believe covers 680 pages.

            There is a 1B index which exceeds 440 pages and covers

   over 5,000 items.  There are 350 audio cassette tapes, 500

   video cassette tapes, and approximately 160,000 sheets of paper

   on top of the 25,000 witness statements.

            In organizing the material, I think the Court is

   probably less interested in what our dispute is than what our

   proposed resolution of it is.  And the Court has suggested that

   we go through each of these items individually, and I propose

   to do that; but there are certain items that cut across each of

   these five areas and each of the four motions or five motions;

   and rather than address each of them in turn, I would just

   briefly, if I may, address them now and simply say that they

   follow throughout these matters.



                                                                           13



            Part of the problem has been with the delayed

   production of the 302's.  There is an exhibit which I believe

   is Exhibit F, which is one of the documents that I handed to

   the Court and another exhibit -- it's Exhibit F.

            If I might ask Mr. Wyatt, is this the complete

   exhibit, or only the ones that are on the blowup?

       (Discussion off the record between Mr. Jones and Mr. Wyatt)

            MR. JONES:  The Government has been giving us 302's;

   and part of the problem that we have had, quite seriously, your

   Honor, is significant delayed production from the date of

   transcription to the date it's given to us.  So we simply took

   the most recent three or four productions and took what we

   considered to be the significant 302's, leaving aside those

   that aren't significant; and we made a chart of seven columns,

   the first column being the 302 number, the second being a very

   cryptic description of what the item is and who it may relate

   to.  The third is the investigation date, which is the date

   shown on the 302 that the incident described in the 302

   occurred.

            For example, at the very first -- let's take the

   second one.  That particular witness was interviewed on July 1,

   1995, in 302 No. 16217.  The dictation date is the date from

   the 302 that it shows that the FBI agent -- and usually, it's

   an FBI agent -- dictated the result of the interview.  The

   transcription date is the date it was transcribed by the FBI



                                                                           14



   typist and the production date is the date we got it.

            And the final column is the number of days from the

   transcription to the production, not the number of days from

   the interview and not the number of days from the

   transcription -- I'm sorry -- from the dictation but the actual

   number of days from the date it was transcribed and presumably

   in hard copy to the date we got it.

            And as this chart shows, the average time is almost

   500 days.

            Now, the Government's answer to that is, well, we give

   it to the defense when we, the prosecution, gets it.  And then

   that may be so; but the FBI is part of the prosecution and it's

   a little difficult for me to understand how these obvious

   important 302's involving, as the Court can see -- some of

   these are extremely critical witnesses to the defense.  Some of

   them involve material very helpful to the defense.  Others are

   perhaps incriminating of the defense case; and we have

   production delays not of 50 days, not of 6 months or even a

   year, but over a year.

            That is something that we ask the Court to address;

   and the specific remedy that we ask for as it applies to

   whether it's Brady or Rule 16 or methodology is for the Court

   to set a date -- and I don't care when that date is; but let's

   just take as an example December 1 -- that all 302's which are

   the subject of an investigation before November 15 have to be



                                                                           15



   given to the defense on December 1; all 302's from November 1

   to December 1 have to be given to us by December 15; all from

   December 15 to January 1 have to be given to us by January 15,

   and so on, down to, including those last few days before trial,

   because these delays are unconscionable and they are delaying

   the case going to trial, because it is difficult for us to go

   out and interview witnesses, to plan exhibits, to plan

   cross-examination and trial when we are still getting a year

   and a half later 302's from say, Trooper Hanger, who arrested

   Mr. McVeigh, or James Rosencrans or Marife's father or any of

   these people.

            That, we believe, has to be addressed, and that is one

   of the most serious problems.  It's not a question of whether

   we get them, which is a different issue.  It's a question of

   when we get them.

            The second issue has to do with the description of

   what we get.

            We submitted to the Court a sealed appendix.  And I'll

   ask Mr. Wyatt if he would find it so I can at least visually

   show it to the Court and the Court will know which one I'm

   referring to, which had a large number of colored tabs.  And

   behind Tabs, I believe, B, C, D and X, are graphic examples:

   Docket entry 1966, which looks like this.

            If the Court will look at -- we have copies here just

   of the pages that I'm going to refer to.  Exhibit D and Exhibit



                                                                           16



   X, we have described.  And I know the Court has read this

   before, but there is so much material the Court may not have

   understood fully its significance to us of how an item is

   described on the master Q and K list, which is the list of

   questioned documents -- I shouldn't say documents -- questioned

   items and known items, which the FBI laboratory or some other

   laboratory works -- how those same items are described on the

   1A, 1B list, and then the notes.

            It's a mishmash.  It's simply not possible for us to

   take the documents the Government gives us and consistently on

   material items match up and follow those items from the lab --

   or rather from where they came from to the lab to the material

   we receive.  And we have taken again representative samples,

   not the worst samples, not the best samples, but just

   representative samples across the board.

            The relief we ask is this: that the Court enter an

   order requiring the Government and in cooperation with the

   defense -- we'll be glad to sit down with them -- to make a

   list that accurately and fully describes as to the originating

   source whether it comes from Trooper Hanger or Charlie Brown or

   the Daylight Motel in Enid, Oklahoma, and not the name of the

   FBI agent that has it.  That doesn't mean anything to us.  If

   you say, "Special Agent John Smith," that means absolutely

   nothing.  Where did Mr. Smith get it from?

            That's just one example.  The inconsistency in the way



                                                                           17



   items are described as they go through the laboratory.

            Now, that's not something that we can solve ourselves,

   unless the Government lays everything out on a table -- and

   it's going to take a very large table and a large room -- and

   we will make our list.  And we'll go through it one by one and

   make the list.

            But I suspect that in a week's time, if the Court

   orders it, that the Government and the defense working

   together, because after all, this is material in their

   possession which they got and we didn't get it.  We don't have

   it in our possession.  Some of it we have copies of.  But when

   you're talking about 50- or 60,000 items -- and that's a

   conservative number -- and you don't have a master list to

   follow, it is impossible.

            So the relief that we ask of the Court is to order the

   parties, with the Government taking the lead, to prepare a 1A

   list of those items that they think we're entitled to receive

   or view.

            Now, I want to advise the Court that on the 1A items,

   the Government says, Well, a lot of those items are things that

   you're not entitled to see.  And I think that's true, certainly

   at this point.  I mean a substantial number of them are FBI

   agent field notes where they handwrite the note.  And I'm not

   arguing that now.

            But what I am arguing is there are some items in the



                                                                           18



   1A, and in this case, the Government has admitted to us --

   admit perhaps is a poor choice of words -- they have advised us

   that the traditional distinction that the FBI makes between

   items that are 1A and 1B is largely lost in this case,

   considering how the items came in, the quickness with which

   they came in, and the mere size of them.

            But if we just start with those 6,000 items that the

   Government thinks that we are entitled to view under 1A, we

   want a list of them, what they are precisely.  And just let me

   take the most recent, dramatic example of how misleading this

   is and the fact that I believe that the Government has such a

   list but we don't.

            Here is a letter dated November 12 -- we're not using

   these exhibits so much as just aids to the Court, your Honor.

   This letter is in response to a letter that I wrote on

   October 8, and so five weeks later I get the response.  And I

   don't really have a complaint about the five weeks.  I can

   understand there might be a problem.  This letter was written

   because of an article that appeared in a newspaper which

   purported to report the discovery of a very important piece of

   evidence, a piece of evidence that as far as I could tell was

   in no way mentioned in the 302's.

            So I wrote the Government and I made reference to and

   Ms. Wilkinson accurately summarized this in my letter:  I asked

   her for the identification of the item that was recovered in



                                                                           19



   downtown Oklahoma City.  She responds they did recover it; and

   then she says -- and I think I can read this part with a minor

   exception:  "The description for the item is contained on your

   1B inventory list as 1B78, Item 16-26, described as 'numerous

   fragments.'"

            Well, considering what this item is, your Honor -- and

   I think the Court can see what it is and understand its

   significance -- and I can tell you that its significance is

   very great -- there is no way in God's world that I would know

   that that item is to be found in numerous fragments as 16-26 on

   1B78.

            Now, they obviously knew what that item was; so why

   they didn't just simply say Item 16-26 is blank to blank and I

   would have known instantly what it was.

            But then she goes on to say, "The item is also listed

   on your master Q inventory list as Q2323 described as

   miscellaneous debris."

            It isn't miscellaneous debris.  Miscellaneous debris

   is something that is miscellaneous debris.  This is a specific

   item that relates to a specific vehicle that is specifically

   important in this case.

            There are hundreds of examples like that.  We cannot

   prepare for trial under that state of the discovery.  Had this

   article not appeared in the newspaper, I would have never known

   about it; that it had been recovered, much less where it was



                                                                           20



   recovered from.  And as I say, that's just one example.

            If I might have just a moment to refer to my notes,

   your Honor.

            THE COURT:  Yes.

            MR. JONES:  Our position, then, is that, first, there

   is an unreasonable and unconscionable delay in the production

   of 302's, in which the Court must intervene and set some

   deadline for in order to get this case ready for trial.  We

   have the duty to investigate the facts.  Hopefully, we'd like

   to investigate them only once.

            Secondly, there are numerous errors in the 1B and the

   Q and A which are inaccurate and misleading and that must be

   addressed.

            Another thing that the Government does -- and this one

   may not be done deliberately in the sense of misleading -- the

   Government each month has furnished us lists; and as they

   discover errors in the previous lists, they have made changes

   in the lists.  But the changes that they make are not

   noticeable to us; so when we get a new index each month, if an

   item on page 40 has been changed, we don't have any way of

   knowing that.

            So there has to be some mechanism beginning at some

   point.  I mean we can't go back and put the toothpaste back in

   the tube on that portion that's been squeezed out.  When the

   Government finds an error or -- and it's not always an error;



                                                                           21



   sometimes it's simply an omission or an admission and in some

   cases a deletion -- that needs to be addressed and indicated in

   such a way that we fully understand and are made aware of it.

            The new indexes that are presented to us, as we

   understand it, is only to add additional items.

            Last night, the Government delivered to us after 4:00

   a substantial amount of new material, material that we have

   asked for since last October; and based upon the letter that

   accompanied it, it would appear that many of these items again

   go back to April, May, and June of 1995 --

            MS. WILKINSON:  Mr. Jones, can you tell me what letter

   are you referring to?

            MR. JONES:  Sure.  I'm sorry.  It's the one dated

   November 12.

            Last time when I spoke with the Court on this issue, I

   brought in the eight boxes we had received then and represented

   to the Court that the pattern of Government production in these

   matters is that on the eve of the day of decision when the

   Court will hear our argument to suddenly change the landscape

   by a massive compliance with something that's been asked for

   for a year, which then confuses the issue because the

   Government can then say, Well, we've given it to them.  Well,

   of course they have, a year and a half after the incident and

   in some cases a year after it's been requested.

            I think the Court needs to address that issue.



                                                                           22



            That contains the summary of the items that I

   represent to the Court go through and cut through all of these

   various motions.  And as the Court knows, because we previously

   submitted Mr. McVeigh's reply to response of the United States

   Government to McVeigh's discovery motions beginning on 10,

   we -- under the heading "The Government Cannot Bury Evidence,"

   we cited to the Court the case law from those cases which have

   discussed the case in massive paper cases, what is the

   Government's duty and obligation to organize it in a fashion

   that it can be used and understood.  And I simply refer the

   Court to the Ollison case and the Turkish case and the other

   cases cited there.

            With respect to the narrowed 16 motion, if I may with

   the Court's permission, I wonder if I could ask leave of the

   Court to have Mr. Wyatt join me at the podium, because he is

   the person on the defense team most -- or charged with the

   responsibility to organize, collect, and analyze the evidence;

   and I want to be sure that as I make representations to the

   Court; that I'm not in error.

            I'll be speaking, but he'll be --

            THE COURT:  Yeah, we'll do that.  But before we do it,

   I think the Government should have an opportunity to respond to

   your general observations; and I have this to ask of you,

   Mr. Jones, and that is you began this statement with your

   intention to challenge everything and of course provide a



                                                                           23



   vigorous defense in the case; but I would anticipate and expect

   that with the kind of discovery involved here and recognizing

   the reciprocity that is also due to the Government by you under

   Rule 16 that there will be a time when we -- if it takes me,

   I'll be there -- should have some type of conference with

   regard to what -- and of course, Mr. McVeigh -- what is -- what

   are the possibilities of stipulations with respect to at least

   foundation and some of these admissibility, authentication

   issues, and so forth, to provide some trial efficiency.

            MR. JONES:  I will -- do you wish for me to respond?

            THE COURT:  Yes.  I mean, I have been assuming that

   you're going to be prepared to do that at some time before

   trial.

            MR. JONES:  Well, I will address that issue frankly

   and candid, as I know the Court will want me to do.

            I would like to do that; but I'm increasingly

   skeptical that it's in the best interest of Mr. McVeigh to do

   it, and I will tell the Court why.  I think it's possible it's

   not too late to change the history of discovery problems in

   this case; but unless I am satisfied, your Honor -- and I think

   it's the duty of the Government to present to us in a form that

   we can use it, study it, analyze it, verify it, and check it

   ourselves -- I don't see how in good faith I can stipulate to

   something.

            THE COURT:  Well, I wouldn't be asking you to



                                                                           24



   stipulate to anything that you're not absolutely confident can

   be proved at trial through the ordinary method, certainly.  I'm

   not asking you to cut any corners with respect to it.

            MR. JONES:  That's fine.  And I have advised both

   Mr. Hartzler and Mr. Mackey when we have discussed this matter

   both in correspondence and face to face when we have met, and I

   told them quite frankly -- and I don't think they will dispute

   it -- that I said there will come a time when you will want me

   to stipulate -- and I said this early -- and I tell you

   gentlemen, looking you in the eye, that if you hold back, you

   confuse, you withhold, you give us stuff that we cannot use,

   I'm not going to sign the stipulation.  And I repeated that as

   recently as two months ago in a letter.

            I would like to stipulate.  Otherwise, it's a trial

   without ending, so to speak, which is certainly not my desire.

   But I've been burned twice before on stipulations with the

   Government, and I don't think it's appropriate -- not in this

   case -- to discuss those publicly; and so I'm once burned,

   twice shy.

            I know that one of the matters we're working on are

   these telephone records that the Government has indicated

   they'd like a stipulation.  But as of today, a year and a half

   later, we don't have a complete set, even of the summary, so we

   can then check the summary against the raw data.

            Now, Mr. Mackey has diligently been working on that,



                                                                           25



   and I recognize the mammoth task that's involved; but here's

   what troubles me -- I mean, the Court has invited me to speak:

   I get a little tired of reading in the newspaper that the

   Government is ready to go to trial.  The Government isn't ready

   to go to trial.  That's a myth.  If they're ready to go to

   trial, where are the rest of these exhibits, where are the rest

   of the 302's, where are the rest of the lab reports?  They're

   not ready.  If they're ready and they've got them, why don't we

   have them.  And if they don't have them, then they're not

   ready.  And they're sure not ready to ask me for stipulations,

   because I haven't even seen the raw data of what they're asking

   me to stipulate.  The first meeting we had on the phone records

   was yesterday or Monday.

            So this kind of posturing that we're ready for

   trial -- this case isn't ready for trial; and certainly,

   they're not ready.  If they are, then they've just been sitting

   on the material that the Court expects them to have given us

   months ago.

            And I'm not saying that critically.  I understand the

   need to make public statements, given the nature of this case.

   And I do compliment Mr. Mackey on it.  But I -- and the Court

   may overrule me and the Court may tell me I'm wrong and the

   Court may tell me to shut up and sit down; and I will do

   everything that the Court tells me to; but before I stipulate,

   I want accurate indexes, I want this 302 delayed production



                                                                           26



   ended, I want to know where the raw data is, and I want to see

   that material and have time to study it, not a weekend.  I

   don't want to get a letter on Thursday and say we expect you to

   stipulate in seven days.

            THE COURT:  Well, let me make it clear.  What I have

   in mind is that there be a stipulations conference at some

   point when we're ready for it and with Mr. McVeigh present, of

   course, who can participate in it.

            But I didn't mean to suggest anything beyond that,

   certainly not that stipulation become some sort of bargaining

   element.  I'm just talking about it as a procedural efficiency

   in the presentation of evidence.

            Well, Ms. Wilkinson, do you or someone on behalf of

   the Government wish to respond to these general comments from

   Mr. Jones?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, we appreciate Mr. Jones'

   acknowledgement at the beginning of his presentation about the

   volume of material produced in this case; but as I was

   listening to his list of problems or disputes, I could not help

   but think that no good deed goes unpunished.

            When Mr. Jones tells you that he has just received,

   last night information that the Government had since the case

   began, what he fails to tell you is that that information is



                                                                           27



   polygraph information and post-April 19 surveillance

   information, information that clearly under the law the defense

   is not entitled to but nevertheless, we've listed on the 1A

   inventory and we have provided to Mr. Jones.  And as he shows

   you in his own pleading in Exhibit B, there is a letter to me

   from one of his co-counsels that states we have been providing

   them regular lists of the 1A inventory and advising them in

   writing each month that if they wanted any of these items, all

   they had to do was request those items and we would make

   copies.  So they have had notice of this information; and it

   was only, I believe, in September or August that they wrote and

   specifically said that they saw it listed on the 1A inventory

   and the information was provided.

            As to -- so as to Mr. Jones' request that we furnish

   an index of these items, we have been doing that and we have

   been doing that since January.

            As to his complaint that the index is not complete, I

   understand his frustration with that; but what I can tell you

   is the index that we are providing -- the indices that we are

   providing to him are the only indices that we possess.  Those

   indices were made, as you might imagine, when agents went out

   right after the bombing and seized evidence.  They collected a

   lot of evidence at the scene and they described it, as

   Mr. Jones described for you, as miscellaneous fragments or

   metal fragments; and that is why we set up the procedure.  And



                                                                           28



   Rule 16 provides a procedure for the defense themselves to

   review all of that evidence.

            I understand that he's frustrated that a bag of

   different metal fragments was not identified by each piece.

            THE COURT:  Well, but with respect to the item in

   question as revealed in this letter, surely somebody on your

   side noted that and noted that it in and of itself had perhaps

   significance.

            MS. WILKINSON:  We did, your Honor; and that was

   months later.  After reviewing photographs of the scene, we

   noticed that metal piece.  We went back and looked through all

   those fragments just like the defense does when they come to

   look through the evidence and found it.

            But Mr. Jones is incorrect when he said he was not

   notified of that, because on August 2 the Government provided

   expert witness summaries.  And in those expert witness

   summaries we had an expert named Charles Hurd, who talks about

   that piece of evidence and talks about how that evidence fits

   the vehicle that we're discussing.

            So since August, Mr. Jones has had no notice about

   that particular item.

            But I use that to point out that when you talk about

   these indices, I believe it's impractical to suggest that the

   Government go back and review all these items and provide

   enhanced descriptions.  That, I believe, is the purpose of Rule



                                                                           29



   16, to allow the defense to do their own review of the physical

   evidence; and if Mr. Jones and his team would like to come and

   look at evidence one more time, we'd be happy to provide a room

   for them to inspect the evidence once again.

            THE COURT:  You know, it seems to me we have to

   divide:  Rule 16 covers basically two things.  One is the

   Government's evidence.  And of course, that is important for

   you to have ready to go and for the defense to know, as is

   consistent with the criteria in Rule 16, what it is.

            Then there is that part of Rule 16 that requires

   matters which may be material to the defense, a different

   category.  And I am concerned in reviewing your responses to

   the narrowed Rule 16 when it will be that all of the 302's to a

   given time have been collected and produced.  So it's been

   ongoing month by month, but we've got to set some dates and

   some time limits.

            MS. WILKINSON:  May I address that, your Honor?

            THE COURT:  Please.

            MS. WILKINSON:  As of October 31, which is the last

   time we made production, we produced 16,442 302's and 8,833

   inserts.  That is 98 percent of the 302's that the Government

   has to date.  So we are prepared to provide those remaining

   302's that are in our possession by December 15 or whatever

   date the Court and the defense and the Government agree to; but

   we must remember that the Government's investigation is



                                                                           30



   ongoing, and that is due to several factors.

            THE COURT:  That's a different issue, though.  And I

   think Mr. Jones addressed it; that is, that there be a time set

   for the production of that which has been accomplished to a

   given date, so that December 15 for what's been done by

   November 15 or whatever.  Then, of course, as new activity

   results in new reportage, that can be done as it comes in; but

   I think it is imperative that, you know, when you've got

   2 percent roughly out there now, that relates, I take it, to

   something before today.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Well, it depends, your Honor.  There

   is a wide variety of categories of 302's that we turn over.

   Many of them, for example, are the review of the prison tapes

   of Mr. Nichols.  So that is going to be ongoing.

            Some of them are leads that are sent out to other

   offices.  And as I have explained, since those do come back

   within the month that the lead is sent out, the investigation

   is conducted and the 302 is generated and then sent back into

   our system.  But I believe that the Government can abide by, I

   think, what the Court is requesting, is that we provide all of

   the historical 302's by December 15, and that is anything that

   we started before November 1, the interview was conducted

   before November 1, we can provide those by December 15.  That

   is not a problem.

            However, anything else that's ongoing, we just want to



                                                                           31



   advise the Court we're going to continue to follow up.  For

   example, Mr. Jones has provided reciprocal discovery to us to a

   certain limited extent; and when we read his interviews of

   certain witnesses, that sometimes generates additional

   investigation on our part.

            THE COURT:  Yes.  I understand that.  But you know,

   what we have to do is to say, all right, this is the evidence

   that the Government is relying on to prove these charges at

   trial and get on with it.

            MS. WILKINSON:  We're prepared to do that, your Honor.

   I would point out that I believe we'll be ready to do that by

   December 15, other than the newly generated 302's or

   investigation, if that would satisfy the Court as to the

   production of those reports.

            THE COURT:  Okay.

            MS. WILKINSON:  I believe that addresses Mr. Jones'

   delay in production, which was his first item that he raised.

            The second was the description.  I would like to use

   another example, your Honor.  There was an inquiry by the

   defense for an item that the media mentioned, a piece of paper

   that was recovered in Mr. Nichols' trash.  We had found that

   piece of paper.  It had been identified generally as documents

   coming from Mr. Nichols' trash on the 1B list.  Mr. Jones wrote

   to us and asked about that.  We identified it.  We have

   characterized it as something more than a piece of paper from



                                                                           32



   the trash; however, I'm not sure that the defense would agree

   with that characterization.

            So in terms of going back and further identifying the

   evidence that we have collected, the problem with having us

   come up with these descriptions is the defense does not always

   agree with our description, or we don't, as they say, have a

   complete enough description of those items.  It seems to me if

   we go back and try and re-create a new list and add a

   description, there are going to be further disputes with the

   defense over whether we properly characterized a certain item

   of evidence.

            As to identifying where that evidence came, again,

   they have all the information that we have.  When it says it

   came from Agent Smith at the bombing crime scene, that's all

   the documentation that we have about where it came from.  Now,

   we can interview Agent Smith and find out where he found it.

   That's usually contained on the 302 that he writes up about

   seizing that piece of evidence.  I think we pointed this out

   last time, that when you have a piece of evidence that's listed

   on the 1B list, let's say the rear axle that was found, the

   agent who seized that, there is also a 302 that says where that

   item of evidence was seized and it's identified through the 1B

   number.

            So that information is already within the defense's

   custody.  We've already turned over those type of documents.



                                                                           33



            If, your Honor, there are specific questions about

   certain items of evidence that the defense has, obviously we

   have always been available and we will continue to be available

   to answer questions and to research certain items; but to order

