   believe Mr. Jones suggested that we do have the list, and we

   don't -- would be incredibly burdensome for us for those items

   that we don't intend to introduce at trial.  And as you know,

   we have turned over everything in this investigation.  A very

   small percentage of that will actually be introduced at trial.

            So it seems to me a better avenue would be to talk

   about exchanging an exhibit list, because that -- those are the

   items the defense really cares about in terms of preparing for

   trial.  And instead of us creating an entire list redescribing

   everything for them, perhaps we could discuss exchanging draft

   exhibit lists with the clear understanding that this is subject

   to change, we're going to be constantly updating it; and then

   the defense would at least have an idea of what items we intend

   to introduce.

            THE COURT:  Well, I -- that's exactly the approach

   that I think is appropriate; that we be looking at a time when

   exhibit lists will be prepared; and the exhibit lists will have

   descriptions of the items that are numbered in the list, so

   that gets us down, as I said, to, you know, what is going to be

   relied on at trial.  That doesn't mean that these other things



                                                                           34



   might not be significant in some fashion, but they're

   secondary, I think, to the time schedule that we must address

   here.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Perhaps to assist the defense further,

   your Honor, and for our own purposes on the exhibit list, we

   could put our potential Government's exhibit number, the 1B

   number and the lab number, which is the Q number or the K

   number, and that way the defense will know that item, have it

   identified three different ways.

            THE COURT:  Cross-referenced.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, sir.  They can go back to their,

   you know, work product that they've generated and be able to

   reference each item.

            Your Honor, if we do that, we would like to do that

   with defense.  We would also ask that we complete our

   reciprocal discovery obligations or the defense complete their

   reciprocal discovery obligations by turning over to us all of

   their witness statements including tapes and transcripts.

            Mr. Jones has advised us that he would not turn over

