   over the grand jury statements in this case; but we're willing

   to do that if we could have full disclosure by the defense of

   all of their witness statements and tape-recordings and

   transcripts.

            THE COURT:  Well, sometimes it's not possible to do



                                                                           35



   these things simultaneously because there is in the trial

   process a sort of punch/counterpunch, so that, you know, you

   can't hold in any trial, civil or criminal, the defense part of

   the case to having an exclusive list until they know what the

   prosecution's list is.

            So there has to be, I think, a two-step involvement;

   and we will be addressing that before we leave in the next

   several days.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Just so the Court --

            THE COURT:  But I think we'll be doing that in

   chambers.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, sir.

            Just so the Court is aware, we have received, as I

   said, those limited statements.

            We have not severed any tangible items or documents,

   and I don't know if the defense has any to share with us; but

   obviously we would request those when it's appropriate.

            Your Honor, I think it would be best for us to move on

   to the specific --

            THE COURT:  Well, I have just this one additional

   matter, and that is mentioned by Mr. Jones; that it would be

   appreciated when you see an error or omission or some change in

   the previous list that it be specifically noted and

   communicated.

            MS. WILKINSON:  We can do that, your Honor.  Again, I



                                                                           36



   guess that's what brings me back to the "no good deed goes

   unpunished."  We were trying to complete these descriptions

   when we realized they were incomplete.  And when we send an

   updated copy -- I believe we say in our letter that this is an

   updated copy, but we will try and highlight specifically the

   descriptions that have been changed to aid the defense.

            THE COURT:  Well, the goodness of a deed is

   qualitative judgment made depending upon one's perspective, I

   suppose.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, just for the record, I

   would like to make clear what the Government has done in terms

   of disclosing information, because I think that will affect

   your rulings on the Rule 16 materials.

            As I said, as of today, we've turned over 25,000

   witness statements.  We have disclosed all the laboratory

   reports that have been generated to date.  That is 477

   laboratory reports.  We have provided all the telephone records

   and set up a private viewing room for the defense to continue

   viewing all of the telephone records.  We have turned over or

   provided an inventory for 8,335 1As, which is 99 percent of the

   1As.

            We've turned over or had the defense view and made

   copies of 3893 1B items, which is 99 percent of what the

   Government has to date.  They have seen 695 1Cs, which is all

   of the 1Cs we have to date.  They've received 440 videos or



                                                                           37



   approximately 95 percent of those; and over 30,000 photographs

   in this case, your Honor, have been provided or made available

   to the defense.

            We've turned over all the defendants' statements.

   We've turned over the summaries, the indices, the CD-ROM disks

