            Now, I sort of suspicioned when I saw it that that's

   what it was.  But it's not clear from reading it.  So to say,

   Well, we knew about it because we got an expert summary, if

   it's not described accurately, I don't know about it at all.

            In this item right here, this docket number that I

   gave the Court earlier, there is an example.  Every so often in

   a description something gives us a clue.  And Exhibit G is a

   list of 1B items.  And in the very middle of the page, 1B,

   1225, says "scout handbook for" subject.  And that gave me the

   hint that probably all of this items -- all of these items came

   from this individual.  But the source is identified as FBI

   Agent Charlie Brown.

            So occasionally, there will be a hint, but I don't see

   how the Government can represent to the Court that, Well, gosh,

   we don't know where it came from other than Charlie Brown.  How

   are they going to put it on the stand and introduce it as an

   exhibit if they don't know what the original source of it is?

            Now, they say, well, there is a 302, and there is a

   302 from Charlie Brown that says that he got Items 921 through

   1225 from subject -- and I don't want to say John Doe, so let's



                                                                           39



   say Sam Doe.

            Well, that's true.  But that assumes that we've got

   Charlie Brown's 302.  If Charlie Brown's one of the delayed

   302's, we have no way to match it up.

            Now, if we can work out some system where there is a

   cross-reference between the 302 and the 1B list and we have the

   302, fine; but it's strains credulity to believe that the

   Government or FBI doesn't have a master list of where they got

   these items from in the field.

            With respect to the reciprocal discovery, we didn't

   have an agreement that they would get transcripts.  In fact, we

   barely had an agreement.  What we had was a unilateral

   statement by Mr. Hartzler what he was going to do.  And it

   wasn't even a written agreement.  And then problems arise.

            But this is a place where I disagree with my brother,

   Ron Woods.  Mr. Hartzler made it very clear to us that we

   weren't getting grand jury transcripts, not even exculpatory

   ones, until later.

            Well, a grand jury transcript is a transcript.  And

   that's fine with me; but you're not going to get my

   transcripts, either.  You'll get my equivalent of the 302 if we

   go out and interview Trooper Hanger, which, of course, we

   couldn't, along with a number of other witnesses; but if we

   could, we'd do an investigative report on him.  I'll give you

   the investigative report, just as you give me your 302.  When



                                                                           40



   you give me the transcript of what he told the grand jury, I'll

   give you the transcript of the interview.  That's reciprocity.

            I learned later that the Government is not giving us

   any of their interviews with witnesses that may testify in the

   second stage yet.  But I've been routinely giving them my

   witness statements for people in the second stage until

   Mr. Mackey told me that I wasn't getting his.  I didn't

   understand we weren't getting his.

            So this reciprocal discovery agreement, as Oliver

   Wendell Holmes said, "a good catch word can escape analysis for

   50 years"; and that's certainly one of them.

            But I would agree with Ms. Wilkinson:  If the Court

   sets a time and if Mr. Hartzler -- and this is the first time

   I've heard it this morning -- if they're willing to give us the

   grand jury transcripts and they get in return our transcripts,

   great.  I accept that.  All we need to do is set the date, and

   we can exchange them; and that will eliminate that problem.

            With respect to the exhibit list, I understand the

   Court's desire in that respect, but let me be frank and tell

   the Court where the danger is for the defense.  The Government

   would very much like the Court, in my opinion -- the

   prosecution -- to buy that argument.  Here's the fallacy in it:

   They've got the evidence.  They've got the tangible objects.  I

   can't talk to Trooper Hanger, I can't talk to Lea McGown, I

   can't to Vickie Beemer, I can't talk to Eldon Elliott.  They've



                                                                           41



   got guards out there.  The Court won't let me take their

   depositions in the civil suit, so my hands are tied.

            The one place they're not tied is the Government has

   got all this evidence.  I can't make my exhibit list until I

   know what they've got, because 99 percent of my exhibits come

   from theirs.

            THE COURT:  That's why I said there is a two-step

   process involved in this, as there is in every case.

            MR. JONES:  The Court understands it, and that's all I

