            MR. JONES:  Your Honor, item -- items on page 12

   beginning with 2, they are labeled at the top, Telephone

   Records of Defendant, Modified Request.  Here is what we

   propose to the Government as a way to resolve this dispute and

   to save their time and sort of shift the burden over to us.

   What we ask was that the Government's phone record database,

   which is a kind of a computerized brain of the phone numbers of

   many different individuals, be furnished to us so that if we

   had their database, then we would simply put it into our

   computer equipment and it would print off all the phone records

   that we need.

            The Government's first response to that -- and we

   dealt with Mr. Mackey in that respect -- was that we could

   prepare our own database from the computer disks of the phone

   summaries they provided for us.  We've already done that, but

   the problem is that our database is limited to the following

   individuals:  Tim McVeigh, Terry Nichols, Michael Fortier,

   James Nichols, Kevin Nichols, Bill McVeigh, and various motels.

   Now, in addition to those individuals, there are dozens of

   other people and institutions or businesses whose phone records

   the Government has, and they have a database for them.

            For example, from the material that we have received,

   it appears that the Government has, for example, the phone



                                                                           53



   records of David Millar's phone number which are not produced

   for us.  But from the material that we saw, we could identify

   that they had those records.  So on their database, they

   entered David Millar's phone records, but we don't have David

   Millar's phone records so we can't enter it.

            The second reason that was given to us was that, well,

   there could be a lot of inaccuracies and we would have the same

   problem that we had with the original records on the -- what I

   call the spotlight credit card, also known as the Darrell

   Bridges debit card and the Government did not want to be caught

   in what we call an Oklahoma Wewoka switch, where they gave us

   something and then we came back and said it was inaccurate.

   Well, we view that as an issue.

            We're prepared to accept any inaccuracies in that

   database for the purpose of doing our own analysis of the phone

   records.  And if they are inaccurate, they are inaccurate to

   both sides and what this is is really more an investigation

   item than it is the preparation of a specific exhibit.

            We need the database to study the patterns and themes

   and geographical locations of the calls being made.  For

   example, there is a suggestion in some of the materials we

   received that there is a strong pattern of calls between an

   individual that lives in the state of Arkansas and an

   individual who lives in the state of Oklahoma.  So what if

   there are one or two mistakes in that database?  It's not going



                                                                           54



   to prevent us from discovering the pattern.

            Then we were told that the Government would create

   phone summaries for anyone that we gave them the name for and

   that we could add those to the database.  That would be great

   if it worked that way, but it doesn't work that way.  We still

   do not have as of this morning accurate phone summaries of all

   people, Tim McVeigh and Terry Nichols, nor do we have the

   actual phone records for Tim and Terry, not to mention everyone

   else's, to prepare our own summary, even though we have been

   asking for them for 11 months.  When we brought this up to the

   Government, their response was, well, okay, tell us the 1A and

   1B numbers and we will copy them and produce them to you.

            Well, we did that just as they asked us to do.  We

   wrote -- actually, Ms. McLaughlin wrote a two- or three-page

   letter specifically listing each phone record by 1A or B number

   in response to their suggestion of how to proceed.  The

   Government's response was -- and it's recorded in their

   correspondence -- that we requested too many phone numbers and

   90 percent of what you requested is irrelevant.  Well, 75 to

   80 percent of what we requested were the phone records of

   Mr. McVeigh, Mr. Nichols, Mr. Fortier and other principal

   persons identified in this case.  25 percent of the requested

   items were phone records which the Government did not identify

   on their index.

            So after we wrote that letter, they said they would



                                                                           55



   review all the phone records or have them available for us to

   review on November 11.  Well, on November 11, we appeared and

   only the 1B numbers were produced that day.  We still haven't

   seen those that are in the 1A category, which is about a third

   of the total.

            On November 12, Ms. McLaughlin returned and waited an

   hour and a half for the Government to open the doors of the

   room where the records were located, and records were

   eventually opened.  But we still don't have all of those phone

   records, and I think it's fair to say that in this case, phone

   records are incredibly important to the Government and they are

   certainly -- if somewhat less important to the defendant, they

   are still crucial in preparing our answer to the Government's

   arguments and to analyzing the phone records of individuals

   that we think are relevant to this case.

            All of that is my way of bringing it down to saying

   that in -- that we simply ask them if you'll give us your

   database, we'll put it in our computer and we won't have to

   mess with all of this paper because you've got the database.

   Otherwise, you have to give us all the raw records and then we

   have to construct our own database from them.

            THE COURT:  Well, let me -- as I understand this

