   Mr. McVeigh's presence at Waco, which is, I don't think,

   disputed at various dates.  And the Government has given us

   material, and they do say that we are not aware of any

   documents responsive to this request and in the possession of

   the Government that have not been made available.  And we do

   have some, but I was again struck by the omission of the word

   "tangible items," which of course might imbue video film or

   photograph or something else.  And I just wondered if the

   omission of the words "or tangible items" from the last

   sentence at the bottom of page 31 was by design or inadvertent.

            THE COURT:  Well, I don't see "tangible items" in the

   request.

            MR. JONES:  That's my point.  It's not in there.  But

   a photograph would be a tangible item.

            THE COURT:  But your request is for reports,

   documents, notes, photographs.

            MR. JONES:  Or films.

            THE COURT:  Or films.  Okay.

            MR. JONES:  And I think of that as a tangible object

   as opposed to a document.  Maybe it's just my own glossary.

            THE COURT:  You've given a list of the things.  The



                                                                           99



   Government's response, as I interpret it from the language that

   I'm reading, is that they are not aware of anything else --

            MR. JONES:  Okay.

            THE COURT:  -- that has not been already provided.

   That's your answer.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes.  To be clear, your Honor, we have

   disclosed a videotape of Mr. McVeigh at Waco.

            THE COURT:  Okay.

            MS. WILKINSON:  And a newspaper article where he was

   interviewed, so there is some information responsive --

            THE COURT:  Yes, and you don't have anything that you

   haven't already given, is what you said.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Right.

            THE COURT:  Okay.

            MR. JONES:  Number 19, your Honor:  We received of

   course, this material yesterday.  And I had a question, though,

   about it, if I might just address it to the Government.

   Ms. Wilkinson, in reviewing the letter that accompanied it, I

   didn't see that included were the results, a report of the

   results.  Is there no written report of the results, or is that

   somewhere else, or is it just not listed on --

            THE COURT:  Are you asking an interpretation?

            MR. JONES:  Yes.

            THE COURT:  Okay.

            MS. WILKINSON:  It's my understanding, your Honor,



                                                                           100



   that everything we received as to this type of evidence that's

   in our files, we disclosed; so if we had a report, it's

   disclosed.  If we didn't have it, obviously, we can't disclose

   it.

            MR. JONES:  My question is, the FBI's very cautious

   and conservative with those reports.  And she said what we

   received.  I want to be sure the FBI, if they had a report,

   gave it to her.  I'm sure she gave me everything she got.  The

   question is did she get everything.

            THE COURT:  Well, I -- I'm operating on the assumption

   that you've asked the pertinent -- the relevant agency for the

   information.

            MR. JONES:  It just seems strange to me there's no

   report on these multiple polygraph examinations.  That they

   took it, and after looking at it, they decided A, B, C, was

   deceptive or not deceptive.

            MR. WOODS:  Your Honor, may I address that?  I looked

   at those items last night.  We received 57 polygraphs.  Only 11

   of them had the questions attached.  The rest were just the

   polygraph charts, which are worthless without the questions.

   And none of them have the report or the result.  Talked with

   Ms. Wilkinson, and she said well, That's all the FBI gave us.

   The FBI has the list of questions, and they have the report and

   the result.  They just haven't given them to the prosecutors,

   which merely copied them and forwarded them to us.  And that's



                                                                           101



   been common throughout this, I would point out.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, why don't I over the break

   research this and get back to the Court?

            THE COURT:  Good.  Thank you.

            MR. JONES:  Mr. Wyatt would like to address 20, your

   Honor.

            MR. WYATT:  Your Honor, I believe that we can withdraw

   all of the requests except as to paragraph (d), based on the

   Government's responses; but paragraph (d) is a unique animal.

   The Government says they don't intend on using any results from

   the Dipole Might project; and I assume that's based on the

   Court's order at the previous hearing that certain recent tests

   could not be used.  However, the Government expressly reserved

   the right to use certain evidence from pre-1995 or 1996

   tests --

            THE COURT:  Right.

            MR. WYATT:  -- as I understood it.  And we would like

   to have access to that information, and that is the purpose of

   that request, your Honor.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, I believe Mr. Wyatt is

   confused.  Dipole Might is a study conducted by the ATF.  It

   has nothing to do with the Socorro testing, which was the

   subject of the suppression hearing.

            THE COURT:  Which was the British --

            MS. WILKINSON:  Correct.  That was the British.



                                                                           102



   Dipole Might has been conducted by the ATF for several years.

   And we do not intend to rely --

            THE COURT:  Separate and totally independent.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Totally independent from the Socorro

   British testing.

            MR. WYATT:  Your Honor, I accept her word on that; but

   the references in that hearing were to Dipole Might, as I

   understood it; and I believe that they were part of the same

   test.  They were just done in conjunction as it related to

   these samples with other governments.  That's my understanding

   of the entire project.  And I may be totally mistaken, your

   Honor.

            MS. WILKINSON:  He is totally mistaken, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  What can I say?  All right.  We'll accept

   your representation.

            MR. JONES:  With respect to what Mr. Wyatt's looking

   at on E, I assume that we have all documents relating to the

   matters requested from the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo

   Park, California.  Is that -- if I may ask through the Court,

   is that what was intended by your response?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, we've turned over everything

   we've received from Mr. Holt, who is the expert, although we

   have been informed by him that he is publishing an article

   showing that the seismic data showed there was one explosion.

   And when we receive a copy of that document, even though it's



                                                                           103



   public, we'll provide it to the defense.

            MR. JONES:  Their seismic data shows there were two

   explosions, and that's what we are interested in.  My question

   is -- this is my concern -- is whether we are getting

   everything these agencies have.  I'll -- and I just again state

   that that is our overriding concern: that the Government relies

   on what somebody gives them their expert without knowing

   whether that's everything that's there.  We then relied that we

   got everything, only to find out later there was something

   else.  Ms. Wilkinson says they have got everything.  I don't

   have any choice but to accept it.

            THE COURT:  That's right.  Neither do I.  And I made

   it clear -- and I'm sure it's well understood -- that, you

   know, all of these Government agencies and so forth speak

   through Counsel, who are representing the United States in this

   case.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, could I just clarify one

   thing as to the seismic data?  I believe Mr. Jones referred to

   him as our expert.  We have informed the defense, we do not

   intend to present Mr. Holt or anyone about seismic data.  We do

   not believe it's in question.  Obviously, the defense can raise

   that as an issue at trial if they want to.  This is not a

   person who is going to be an expert on behalf of the

   Government.

            THE COURT:  Is this somebody that works for the



                                                                           104



   Government and they are going to publish something?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Because there's been what I would call

   uninformed speculation about the seismic data and what it

   shows, he and his colleagues are publishing an article

   interpreting the data Mr. Jones is referring to to say that it

   shows --

            THE COURT:  When?

            MS. WILKINSON:  -- there was one explosion.

            He informed us several months ago he submitted it for

   publication; and the first time, they would not accept it

   because they didn't think it was an issue in dispute.  And he

   resubmitted it, and he said it was accepted for publication;

   but we -- I have not been informed as to when it will be

   published.

            THE COURT:  Well, I think you better find out what's

   in it first to make sure that it's not in violation of the

   order with respect to extra-judicial statements concerning this

   case.

            MR. JONES:  We -- we do have a concern about that.

   And this is perhaps just the place to -- to raise it.  And I

   don't want to delay discussion on this, but the Government

   filed its response on Monday or Friday.  And they made two

   statements.  That's a response filed in court.  One of them

   says as the Government has no prior knowledge of bombing

   warning.



                                                                           105



            Well, they surely know that's in dispute.  I mean,

   we've asked to interview three Government employees two months

   ago, and we haven't even received a response.  That goes to

   that very issue at the Department of Justice, where a phone

   call was received before the bomb went off according to a 302.

   I don't know whether it's accurate.  That's what the 302 says.

   Secondly -- I just that as a press release for the

   prosecution's theory.

            Secondly, there is a dramatic story about an elevator

   falling eight floors.  It didn't fall eight floors.  We have

   the report.  And -- and to put something into the press record

   which is then carried in dramatic fashion to the newspapers

   about this ATF agent to paint this story when the report we

   have disputes it -- and if there is a report that disputes

   that, we don't have it.  And now we find that -- these

   statements that well, it's not seriously in dispute.  There's

   one explosion.  It is.  There's respectable scientific opinion

   at the University of Oklahoma exactly to the contrary.  The

   seismic reading is like a polygraph.  It depends on the

   examiner.  They are entitled to their position; but to argue

   that well, it's not seriously in dispute, of course it's

   seriously in dispute.

            THE COURT:  Well, I'm only at this point cautioning

   that publication, if it's in the form of some opinion with

   respect to it and that opinion is relevant to the issues in



                                                                           106



   this case, I would not expect to see such a publication by any

   Government official or employee.

            MR. JONES:  Your Honor, No. 21, we first requested the

   names, current addresses, and current telephone numbers of the

   known survivors of each deceased victims, which I assume is in

   the 22 list -- 2200 list.  The Government has advised us that

   approximately 45 of those people may be called to testify if

   and when the stage -- we go to the second stage.

            Mr. Nichols' lawyers raised a motion, which we will

   join in concerning, these meetings that were held in Oklahoma

   City on Sunday and Monday night.  And those people are

   witnesses.  Some of them are fact witnesses, certainly on the

   second stage.

            And I just don't believe that it is right that the

   Government have the exclusive list of the phone numbers and

   addresses of victims, many of whom make public statements to

   the television camera who seek to join these proceedings in

   amicus curiae, who seek to intervene and who then go out and

   talk to the press about what happens in Government meetings.

   Some of these people, we would like to interview.  We don't

   have a way to reach them, and I don't think we're required to

   write the Government and say -- because we sure don't have any

   luck with Government employees, and I don't think we're going

   to have any less luck here.  But we don't know who these people

   are, and they are very key.



                                                                           107



            They have invoked jurisdiction of the Court to aid

   them.  And we're certainly going to treat them with respect and

   dignity.  And I suspect that our first approach to them would

   simply be to write them and ask them if we could talk with

   them.  We are not going to show up on their doorstep.  And we

   need that.  It's material to the preparation of the second

   stage and might conceivably be material to the preparation of

   the first stage.

            THE COURT:  Well, we've got several things mixed

   together here; but, certainly, with respect to witnesses,

   you're going to have to provide the information as to all

   witnesses expected to be called.  When it comes to all of the

   others, I'm -- and this matter of meetings and so forth, we'll

   address later, since it's the subject of a motion.

            MR. JONES:  It is, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  Although I'm not sure whether Mr. Tigar

   wants to argue that.

            MR. WOODS:  We're prepared to argue it today, your

   Honor, if the Court wants to hear it.

            THE COURT:  All right.  Well, at least during this

   session, whichever day.

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  Well, your Honor, if I could just, as your

   Honor said, that's what you're here for.  And I ask the Court



                                                                           108



   to sustain A1, 2, 3, 4, 5; that is, specifically that we be

   given the names, addresses and telephone numbers of the known

   survivors of the deceased victims to the extent the Government

   has them; that we be given the names, addresses and telephone

   numbers of all persons within the group of persons referred to

   in the death penalty notice which is on file suffering, quote,

   "serious physical and emotional injury," close quote, and so

   forth, down through it.  I submit that that material -- I can't

   imagine anything more material to the preparation of the second

   stage and certainly, may be preparation for the first stage.

            THE COURT:  Well, you've got it -- all this in a

   database -- right -- under the Victims Assistance Unit, or

   whatever it's called?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, we do.  Your Honor, we have

   agreed in our response that we would provide once we get the

   authorization from the victims and make the final determination

   the names of the victim witnesses as the Court has --

            THE COURT:  What's wrong with access to the database?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Because there's an incredible amount

   of personal information --

            THE COURT:  Well, yeah.

            MS. WILKINSON:  -- on the victims, your Honor; and I

   don't --

            THE COURT:  What about the names and address?

            MS. WILKINSON:  I think they would feel very strongly



                                                                           109



   about that information being turned over to them.  I would

   believe it's protected by the Privacy Act, unless there's some

   reason why it would be material.

            THE COURT:  You'll brief that, then.  I don't see

   this -- you know -- only the Government gets access to those

   people?  I don't understand that, particularly since some of

   them have been so vocal.

            MR. JONES:  May I -- do I understand that the Court --

   the Government will brief --

            THE COURT:  Privacy Act objection to that is the

   specific objection.

            MR. JONES:  All right.  And I presume we'll respond.

            THE COURT:  Right.

            MR. JONES:  Then may I then delay further discussion

   of 21 to the brief?

            THE COURT:  Yes.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, we have permission to

   brief any legal basis for withholding that information, not

   just the Privacy Act?

            THE COURT:  Yes.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Thank you.

            MR. JONES:  All right, your Honor.  That -- it's

   12:00.  Do you want to --

            THE COURT:  Well, I have it as two minutes -- two and

   a half minutes to twelve.  If you'd like to break early, I



                                                                           110



   guess we could.

            MR. JONES:  No, your Honor --

            THE COURT:  Well, if it saves time, that's all right.

   You have been on your feet a while.  We'll recess until 1:30.

       (Recess at 11:55 p.m.)

                            *  *  *  *  *

                       REPORTERS' CERTIFICATE

            We certify that the foregoing is a correct transcript

   from the record of proceedings in the above-entitled matter.

            Dated at Denver, Colorado, this 13th day of November,

   1996.



                                    ______________________________
