<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<P> In this three-day hearing, lawyers argued over what evidence the prosecution must turn over to the defense. Prosecutors are obliged to provide the defendants any evidence they consider using in a trial as well as any information that might help the defense side. Defendant Timothy McVeigh's attorney, Stephen Jones, asked for details on negotiations between authorities and Michael Fortier, a former associate of McVeigh's who is expected to testify for the government in exchange for a plea agreement. Jones contended that Fortier changed his story as part of deal to avoid trial.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
                 IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
                                FOR THE DISTRICT OF COLORADO

               Criminal Action No. 96-CR-68

               UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,

                   Plaintiff,

               vs.

               TIMOTHY JAMES McVEIGH and TERRY LYNN NICHOLS,

                   Defendants.

               
                                    REPORTER'S TRANSCRIPT
                  (HEARING ON MOTIONS - VOLUME II)

   

            Proceedings before the HONORABLE RICHARD P. MATSCH,

   Judge, United States District Court for the District of

   Colorado, commencing at 1:30 p.m., on the 13th day of November,

   1996, in Courtroom C-203, United States Courthouse, Denver,

   Colorado.















    Proceeding Recorded by Mechanical Stenography, Transcription
                 Produced via Computer by Paul Zuckerman, 1929 Stout Street,
       P.O. Box 3563, Denver, Colorado, 80294, (303) 629-9285



                                                                           112



                             APPEARANCES

            PATRICK M. RYAN, United States Attorney for the

   District of Oklahoma, 210 West Park Avenue, Suite 400, Oklahoma

   City, Oklahoma, 73102, appearing for the plaintiff.

            JOSEPH H. HARTZLER, SEAN CONNELLY, LARRY A. MACKEY,

   BETH WILKINSON, SCOTT MENDELOFF, and VICKI BEHENNA, Special

   Attorneys to the U.S. Attorney General, 1961 Stout Street,

   Suite 1200, Denver, Colorado, 80294, appearing for the

   plaintiff.

            STEPHEN JONES, ROBERT NIGH, JR., ROBERT WYATT,

   Attorneys at Law, Jones, Wyatt & Roberts, 114 East Broadway,

   Suite 100, Post Office Box 472, Enid, Oklahoma, 73702-0472, and

   JERALYN MERRITT, 303 East 17th Avenue, Suite 400, Denver,

   Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant McVeigh.

            RONALD G. WOODS, ADAM THURSCHWELL, and REID NEUREITER,

   Attorneys at Law, 1120 Lincoln Street, Suite 1308, Denver,

   Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant Nichols.

                            *  *  *  *  *

                             PROCEEDINGS

       (In open court at 1:30 p.m.)

            THE COURT:  Mr. Jones.

            MR. JONES:  Thank you, Your Honor.

            THE COURT:  Ready for the next item.

            MR. JONES:  The next round, Your Honor.

            THE COURT:  Item I think I said, yes.  Wasn't looking



                                                                           113



   at it as rounds.  Yet.

            MR. JONES:  It felt like it sometimes this morning,

   Your Honor.  We're back.

            Apologize to the Court.  I had it in my hand and set

   it down.  I've got it.  I see it.  It was in my hand.

            I believe, Your Honor, that we had been on No. 21 --

            THE COURT:  Yes.

            MR. JONES:  -- and that had, we had gone down through

   the 21, we had gone down through No. F.

            THE COURT:  Right.

            MR. JONES:  Your Honor, I'm sure the Court will

   recognize F as a request that we must file, but I believe under

   the existing case law that the Government's position would find

   sympathy with the Court.

            THE COURT:  Yes.

            MR. JONES:  With respect to Item B, which was to ask

   the Government to identify persons who are subject to a, quote,

   grave risk of death, close quote, for the statutory aggravating

   factor set forth in No. 2 in the death penalty notice, the

   Government's objection was that was tantamount to a bill of

   particulars, as was Item No. 1, but I place a distinction

   between F1 and No. 5C, 5B, which appears to be addressed to a

   specific class of people.  The Government says that's

   tantamount to a bill of particulars, and I suppose that it is

   in one sense; but in the other sense, the identity of those



                                                                           114



   people to the extent that there's a specific individual or

   individuals involved, I think we're entitled to know.  If they

   mean, on the other hand, to a group, then just the identity of

   the group is sufficient.

            THE COURT:  I presume that it was a group that we're

   talking about rather than particular individuals, but I may

   presume too much.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, can I have a moment,

   please?

            THE COURT:  Yes, this is on the grave risk of death.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, he's referring to a group

   in the most general sense; that is, people who were in the

   building and the surrounding area, because due to the nature of

   the device itself, it would cause that grave risk to anyone in

   the area.

            THE COURT:  I think there ought to be some definition

   of the relevant zone, though.

            MS. WILKINSON:  I believe we could do that by the

   damage, your Honor.  Perhaps that would be the best way to do

   that.  But we'd have to consider that, I think, and get back to

   the Court.

            THE COURT:  Okay.  Well, I think the defense is

   entitled to know what zone geographically constitutes persons

   within grave risk of death.

            MR. JONES:  Item C, your Honor, they said there were



                                                                           115



   no others, and we'll accept that as a statement of the

   Government's position.

            Item E1 and 2 were withdrawn, your Honor.

            Item F, persons having knowledge, that again is, as

   the Court I'm sure recognizes, inquiry of the defense which the

   courts has traditionally disallowed.

            THE COURT:  Yes.

            MR. JONES:  The Government in any event has said they

   would provide a tentative list.  Another good deed, but it

   won't go unpunished.

            Item 2, I agree that it is overbroad, and I'll

   withdraw it.

            No. 3 is withdrawn.

            No. 4, I assume that anyone that falls into this

   category we have the 302 for or similar witness statement,

   except for Mr. David Irving which is an issue, but that can be

   addressed in another setting.

            MS. WILKINSON:  I'm sorry --

            THE COURT:  I'm lost as to where you are.

            MR. JONES:  I'm sorry.  Excuse me.

            THE COURT:  What page?

            MR. JONES:  Let me ask my lawyers.

            Yes, 38, your Honor, No. 4.

            THE COURT:  Yes, I think we'll have to discuss that in

   connection with another, your other request.



                                                                           116



            MR. JONES:  That's fine, your Honor.  5, 6, 7, 8 are

   withdrawn.

            9 I believe that they may have furnished us, your

   Honor.  And if I still have concerns about it, I'll raise it,

   but I believe we have that material.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  Now, No. 10, the issue arises in this way:

   There are witness statements furnished to us from individuals

   identified here in this request who claim that the Oklahoma

   City Fire Department received certain information concerning a

   certain group of people.  That's the report that the 302 says.

   And this information came to them on April the 14th, I believe,

   or 15th.  However, the information that we have received in the

   form of these statements, it isn't clear whether in fact the

   person who allegedly called the Oklahoma City Fire Department

   was in fact a government employee acting in some official

   capacity.  And that's really all we're trying to seek there is

   does the Government have information that the person who called

   the Oklahoma City Fire Department with this information,

   allegedly, is a government employee and if so, who is it and

   what is the agency.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, I'm sorry, but I'm having

   a hard time following the cryptic description.  If he's talking

   about that individual in this request, which is a public

   document -- are you talking about Harvey Weathers?



                                                                           117



            MR. JONES:  Yes.  But there's others.  Maybe I can

   clear it up this way.  But you're on the right one.  Let me put

   this this way.  There are press reports that members of the

   Oklahoma City Fire Department staff received a phone call on

   the Friday before the bombing, on Wednesday from an individual

   who they inferred was a government employee, and I think

   specifically the FBI, warning them as to or alerting them or

   advising them that there may be a certain group of people or

   incident the following week.  And the Court will appreciate I'm

   trying to be somewhat general here.  The material that the

   Government has given us says that Harvey Weathers and these

   other people say, yes, that's true, we did receive such a call

   and it did say such and such concerning an event that could

   happen next week.  My question --

            THE COURT:  This in the form of 302?

            MR. JONES:  Yes, sir.  First we learned about it in

   the press; and then when we got the 302, the 302's were

   consistent with the press accounts.

            The material the Government gave us does not identify

   whether in fact some employee of a government agency made the

   call to the Oklahoma City Fire Department or is this somebody

   else totally unrelated to government.  If there is a call from

   a government employee, from a government agency, particularly

   FBI or the ATF or whoever, alerting the Oklahoma City Fire

   Department, it goes to the issue perhaps of prior warning or



                                                                           118



   prior knowledge.

            THE COURT:  So your question is who called?

            MR. JONES:  Well, I don't know if the Government knows

   that.  My question is narrower than that:  Did a government

   employee call?

            THE COURT:  If you know.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Judge, we don't know.  We have put all

   the investigative material into the 302's and disclosed that to

   the defense, whatever we have on this issue.  I'm not sure that

   the facts as Mr. Jones is saying them are accurate; I'm not

   saying they're inaccurate, I'm not familiar with all those

   302's.  I know any information we did investigating these

