            MR. WOODS:  So that's two items out of the four.

            THE COURT:  Speaking for the Government today, we have

   Miss Wilkinson.

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, but Mr. Hartzler was the one who

   advised me this morning that he would provide me with the list.

   That's two of the four items.  The third item is notes of the

   attorneys when they interview witnesses.  And we had an example



                                                                           140



   of that last week in a deposition of a witness who came up with

   some additional information that was not in the eight FBI 302's

   that had been provided to us.  We were surprised with new

   information at the time of the deposition, and the witness

   advised, well, that he had told the prosecutor of that a couple

   months ago.

            So where a prosecutor's interviewing a witness and

   gets new information that's not in a 302, it appears to me that

   that would -- it's not work product, that's -- he's gathering

   facts, it's just like a 302, and we would request the

   prosecutor's notes of interviews with witnesses where there's

   additional information from the 302 that we have.

            And I think probably that can be cleared up by

   receiving the grand jury testimony because the grand jury

   testimony will probably omit all of the -- or cover all of

   those problems where it won't be necessary.  But there are

   going to be instances where they learned new information in

   their interviews and it's not work product.  It's just plain

   old fact gathering --

            THE COURT:  Well, there's a difference, though,

   between information in the notes and, you know, you cited the

   Goldberg case --

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, sir.

            THE COURT:  -- and the Goldberg case deals with Jencks

   Act statements and is restricted really to the attorneys' notes



                                                                           141



   where the witness or person being interviewed has in some

   fashion adopted those notes as his or her statement.  But it is

   not unusual, I would think, for a lawyer doing the interviewing

   to make notes which mix together what the witness or person

   being interviewed says and what the lawyer thinks.

            MR. WOODS:  Right, and we would not want their work

   product --

            THE COURT:  We're not talking about --

            MR. WOODS:  We just want the new information that's

   received, and that can be given to us in a 2-page, 2-sentence

   summary.

            THE COURT:  I think that's sort of under the category

   of continuing discovery where there is some information that

   explains, extends, changes the 302's or whatever the previous

   information was.  It's hard to --

            MS. WILKINSON:  It's very hard --

            THE COURT:  -- it's hard to define exactly what we're

   talking about here.  But if you, through a lawyer's interview,

   gain something that changes what this same person said when he

   or she was interviewed by the FBI or some other agent and

   there's a report of that, then I think there's an obligation to

   make that available to the defense, and that's what I

   understand your request to be.

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, it is.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, to the extent it's a



                                                                           142



   change and there's an inconsistency, fine.

            THE COURT:  Or an extension.

            MS. WILKINSON:  The problem with that, your Honor, is

   that as we are interviewing these witnesses to prepare them for

   trial -- not as an investigative interview, but to prepare

   them -- obviously as the attorney, you're asking them more

   detailed questions to prepare them for cross-examination and to

   determine the extent of their knowledge.  So there's always

   going to be more information than was contained in the 302.  I

   believe that's our responsibility as attorneys, to prepare

   these witnesses thoroughly for trial testimony.  So --

            THE COURT:  Well, I don't know what thoroughly means.

   I hope you're not video-taping them and all those things.

            MS. WILKINSON:  No, we're not video-taping them, but

   the point is to make sure we know what knowledge they have and

   what questions that they can answer.

            So if the general rule by the Court is any extension

   of the information provided in the 302, that seems impractical.

   It would be -- I mean we're always going to find out more

   detailed information from them about certain incidences.  It

   seems to me if there's a material change in their statement, a

   material addition, we can provide the defense with some --

            THE COURT:  But also if they, if you, if a lawyer were

   to go through this and hand write a bunch of notes and then say

   check this and see if it's what you just said, now you're



                                                                           143



   talking Jencks.

            MS. WILKINSON:  You can be assured, your Honor, that

   that is not occurring.

            THE COURT:  I didn't expect it to be.

