            I told the Court this morning when we started that one

   of the five key elements that I thought the Government would

   present in structuring its case is the forensic evidence.  And

   the fact that the Government has acknowledged that there are

   468 reports that they furnished to us is an indication of just

   how extremely important to them and to us this forensic

   evidence is.



                                                                           150



            We have with the Court's permission and order employed

   world-renowned scientists who spent their entire career either

   in law enforcement or in academic work on the subjects, and in

   this particular report, bomb residue analysis, trace analysis,

   and the bomb engineering.  And I don't think there's any

   question based upon their resumes that they are extremely

   qualified and, in fact, many of them have far superior academic

   and professional qualification than the resumes furnished by

   the Government.

            Each of them, with the exception of one, has testified

   in major world-famous -- if I could use that term, in the sense

   of notoriety -- cases involving bombing.  We submitted to them

   and sent to them the entire laboratory notes that Ms. Wilkinson

   said we got.  And they have analyzed them.  And furnished us

   letters and affidavits which we will submit to the Court.

            Now, either one of two things has happened here.

   Either the FBI laboratory does not have protocols, except on

   some oral tradition, or else we're not getting them.  Because

   they have, with painstaking analysis as scientists, gone

   through this material and pointed out the wide gaps of what is

   missing in order for them to advise us and to testify, if need

   be, at trial.

            And for the reasons set forth in their affidavit, what

   we believe has happened here is that the Government has once

   again at the 12th hour or 11th hour given us 15,000 sheets of



                                                                           151



   paper which we've gone through with our experts and said that

   the quantity of the paper means that we have received the

   quality.  And we haven't.

            In other words, that material which is absolutely

   necessary to determine whether the analysis is accurate is

   missing.  Now, it's either missing because it doesn't exist,

   which is a damning indictment, or we simply haven't been

   furnished it.

            This is critical for us, this forensic evidence.  And

   it is all the more critical for us because the Court has under

   seal and is familiar and we've addressed it in court here, that

   there are serious allegations concerning contamination,

   methodology, adherence to protocols, and qualification of the

   people performing this, serious enough that the Inspector

   General is conducting an investigation and there are press

   reports this week concerning some very damning statements that

   will be made about an individual that's going to testify in

   this case.

            Now, whether those press reports are correct or not, I

   don't know.  But that's what we've been told.  And hopefully,

   they're not correct, but, nevertheless, that's what the report

   is, the press speculation.

            But in addition to that, the Attorney General herself

   has appointed a five-member panel consisting of three

   foreigners to investigate these allegations.  So when we say to



                                                                           152



   the Court, we want the protocol to know what Mr. Burmeister and

