   the FBI uses, and it may depend on what was available at the

   crime scene.  I don't know, particularly in this case where

   there was so much debris, but that's an issue that will be an

   issue for the Court at some point.  Or for the jury.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, we can resolve that right

   now.  As to the crime scene, there's only one piece of evidence

   referred to as Q 507 in the lab and in the master Q and K list

   that has explosive residue and it's not really a explosive

   residue, it's ammonium nitrate crystals on it.  One piece.

   It's contained in a plastic bag, and when the defense saw it,

   it was still in that same plastic bag with the original

   packaging.  When they come to observe it and view it again,

   they can look at that plastic bag.  But out of all the crime

   scene evidence at the actual bombing of the building, there's

   only one piece of evidence.

            THE COURT:  Do you know what kind of plastic the bag

   is?



                                                                           182



            MS. WILKINSON:  Looks to me like a heavy Zip Lock bag,

   your Honor; I'm not a plastic experts.

            MR. WYATT:  That would be my response as well.  We're

   not plastics experts when we come in to look at this.  But the

   laboratory should have a protocol -- the experts obviously are

   aware that that's an issue and they should be able to identify

   it, either ours or theirs.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, there's not high-explosive

