            If the Court will give me just a moment here.

            Your Honor, from the materials that the Government has

   furnished to us plus published accounts in the press, it



                                                                           188



   appears that the General Accounting Office, which is as the

   Court knows a branch of the legislative branch of government --

   division of the legislative branch and that they perform

   certain surveys and investigations at the request of Congress,

   conducted an investigation of the FBI laboratory within the

   past, recent past, a report which is completed and may have in

   fact been completed before the bombing in this case.

            In addition to that, the Office of the Inspector

   General has been conducting an investigation, and it's my

   understanding the reports will shortly be available on that to

   the Government.

            And then there are also certain audits and reviews and

   compliance studies both of the Office of Inspector General and

   the General Accounting Office with respect to the FBI lab.

            We have raised the issue before.  And to some extent

   this also comes under the nature of exculpatory evidence, but

   we put it in this because it directly impacts upon the

   methodology.

            We believe that the Court should order that the

   Government furnish us the Inspector General's report, the full

   report when it's released with an appropriate protective order,

   any GAO studies of the lab, the last three years before

   April 19, 1995, and the period since then and any other audits

   or reviews of the lab that discuss the issues as it relates to

   the personnel involved in this case concerning qualifications,



                                                                           189



   disciplinary matters, which presumably would be under Henthorn,

   contamination, methodology and review.

            Now, what the Government has done is furnish us thus

   far copies of certain material only as it relates to the

   Oklahoma City bombing case; but the other material, which up to

   this point we've not pressed for because the Court had other

   things on the front burner, but now we're getting down to the

   point where we must analyze very important forensic evidence.

   And to us, it is exculpatory in the first place and secondly

   necessary to evaluate the thoroughness of these examinations

   and the reports that will given from the witness stand and

   where there are allegations and findings or allegations or

   findings concerning inadequacies in the laboratory in the areas

   that are relevant to this case.  And I mean, I'm sure there is

   an element that are not.  For example, there is a photography

   unit.  And I don't know that there is any photography in this

   case that's in dispute; but handwriting, hairs and fibers,

   fingerprints, bomb residue -- all of that directly relates to

   this case and is critical for it.

            It doesn't make any difference whether it's just one

   report for one hair or one fiber.  That could be the crucial

   matter in this case either for the Government or the defense.

            And I'll give the Court an example:  If's my

   understanding that a major national periodical will report that

   one of the FBI laboratory personnel who will testify in this



                                                                           190



   case, according to what we have been given, will be criticized

   in the report for work he did in another major bombing case, to

   wit:  The World Trade Center case.  To me, it is relevant even

   though under their standards we wouldn't get that because that

   doesn't relate to Oklahoma City; but if this same scientist/

   examiner, whatever his qualifications may be, was criticized

   for similar work involving a similar bomb within two years of

   this case, I think we are entitled to review that to determine

   whether we can use it on cross-examination.

            And I ask the Court with whatever appropriate

   protective order that the Government submit those studies of

   the General Accounting Office, the audits and reviews of the

   lab, and the full Inspector General's report as well as the

   rest of the material that was redacted to us.

            Alternatively -- and I know the Court is loath to do

   this and for good reason -- I think at a minimum, it should be

   submitted to the Court for in camera inspection, because there

   has been a close holding of this material to the bosom; and

   while Ms. Wilkinson has said to the Court that we received this

   material, the history of this has not been reassuring.  No one

   ever mentioned a word to us during all of these meetings and

   exculpatory evidence about Frederic Whitehurst and that there

   would be these problems until ABC reported when a transcript

   became released or was released to the public in the World

   Trade Center case.



                                                                           191



            And even after we wrote them and pointed out to them

   that we had received over the transom internal documents from

   the Department of Justice that a special section had been set

   up to review the impact of these allegations on various cases,

   we still didn't get it.  And finally, after the Court indicated

   its impatience that we hadn't received it, we began to get it.

            So we went almost seven and a half months while they

   knew there was this ticking time bomb in the laboratory of

   these very serious allegations in the very units that are

   crucial to this case involving the very people who worked in

   this case.  And my concern is we want to know what else they

   were criticized for when they did similar work in other cases,

   because if we don't have that, we cannot evaluate completely

   their work in this case.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, we disagree that

   information about agents' conduct in other cases, where there

   are just allegations that aren't relevant to this case, should

   be disclosed; and we have disclosed all of the relevant

   allegations about examiners in this case, whether or not

   they're going to eventually testify.  But the ones that we

   currently believe will testify, we have turned over all those

   allegations made by Dr. Whitehurst and the memoranda of

   interview by the Inspector General of other people involved

   with the investigation.

            In a case in Delaware called United States vs. 



                                                                           192



   Gonzales, this information was turned over post-trial relating

   to their case and an agent who had testified in that case.  And

   the judge in his opinion ruled that it was not a Brady

   violation or that the information would not have changed the

   verdict in this case and went through a long discussion about

   whether this information would be admissible or not and ruled

   that most of it would not have been admissible because it was

   this person's reputation and his actions in other cases or

   general reputation evidence.

            So relying in part on that and on our understanding of

   our Brady obligations, we have disclosed only those allegations

   relevant to this case.  We do that for that reason but also

   because these allegations in other cases are being decided by

   prosecutors in those cases and judges in those case, and we

   feel like we have a responsibility to just give this defense

   counsel those allegations that are relevant.

            On the other hand, the IG's report will discuss all of

   the allegations, is our understanding.  And unless there is

   some reason that the IG does not want us to disclose it under a

   protective order, which I can't imagine there would be, we will

   give the entire report to defense counsel, which will contain a

   discussion of all the allegations.

