<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<P> In this three-day hearing, lawyers argued over what evidence the prosecution must turn over to the defense. Prosecutors are obliged to provide the defendants any evidence they consider using in a trial as well as any information that might help the defense side. Defendant Timothy McVeigh's attorney, Stephen Jones, asked for details on negotiations between authorities and Michael Fortier, a former associate of McVeigh's who is expected to testify for the government in exchange for a plea agreement. Jones contended that Fortier changed his story as part of deal to avoid trial.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>                 IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
                                FOR THE DISTRICT OF COLORADO

               Criminal Action No. 96-CR-68

               UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,

                   Plaintiff,

               vs.

               TIMOTHY JAMES McVEIGH and TERRY LYNN NICHOLS,

                   Defendants.

                                       REPORTER'S TRANSCRIPT
                  (HEARING ON MOTIONS - VOLUME VII)

   
            Proceedings before the HONORABLE RICHARD P. MATSCH,

   Judge, United States District Court for the District of

   Colorado, commencing at 3:35 p.m., on the 14th day of November,

   1996, in Courtroom C-203, United States Courthouse, Denver,

   Colorado.















    Proceeding Recorded by Mechanical Stenography, Transcription
                 Produced via Computer by Paul Zuckerman, 1929 Stout Street,
       P.O. Box 3563, Denver, Colorado, 80294, (303) 629-9285



                                                                           408



                             APPEARANCES

            PATRICK M. RYAN, United States Attorney for the

   District of Oklahoma, 210 West Park Avenue, Suite 400, Oklahoma

   City, Oklahoma, 73102, appearing for the plaintiff.

            JOSEPH H. HARTZLER, SEAN CONNELLY, LARRY A. MACKEY,

   BETH WILKINSON, SCOTT MENDELOFF, and VICKI BEHENNA, Special

   Attorneys to the U.S. Attorney General, 1961 Stout Street,

   Suite 1200, Denver, Colorado, 80294, appearing for the

   plaintiff.

            STEPHEN JONES, ROBERT NIGH, JR., ROBERT WYATT,

   Attorneys at Law, Jones, Wyatt & Roberts, 114 East Broadway,

   Suite 100, Post Office Box 472, Enid, Oklahoma, 73702-0472, and

   JERALYN MERRITT, 303 East 17th Avenue, Suite 400, Denver,

   Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant McVeigh.

            RONALD G. WOODS, ADAM THURSCHWELL, and REID NEUREITER,

   Attorneys at Law, 1120 Lincoln Street, Suite 1308, Denver,

   Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant Nichols.

                            *  *  *  *  *

                             PROCEEDINGS

       (Volumes IV through VI, pages 269 through 406, are ordered

   sealed by the Court and are not part of the public record.)

       (In open court at 3:35 p.m.)

            THE COURT:  Be seated, please.

            I'm sure that there's some interest and curiosity

   about what has been happening in chambers, and I can only tell



                                                                           409



   you that some of that will be reflected in an order to be

   entered, but that there will be some additional time in

   chambers tomorrow and that what we are doing is working out

   some scheduling and that necessarily has to be something that's

   discussed privately and then announced publicly and will be.

            Now, we do have another motion that needs to be heard

   and will be heard here, and that is what's designated as a

   Defendant McVeigh's narrowed motion to compel production of

   exculpatory evidence.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, may I consult with

   Mr. Jones for one moment?

            THE COURT:  You may.  And there's been a response.

            And, Mr. Woods, is Mr. Nichols joined in part with

   this motion or --

            MR. WOODS:  No.  Your Honor, we had our separate

   motion, and the Court has already heard just those four items.

            THE COURT:  Yes.  All right.  So we have the

   Government's response which, as in the same fashion as with the

   Rule 16, repeated the requests and gave the responses to it.

   And perhaps just as we did with the Rule 16 yesterday, we can

   go to those items and see which of them are still in dispute

   and need rulings.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, Mr. Jones has agreed to --

   graciously agreed to let me stand at the podium this afternoon

   while he sits at the table and we discuss the responses if



                                                                           410



   that's --

            THE COURT:  All right.  Do we want to set up a

   microphone there or --

            MR. JONES:  Well, I don't think I'll have trouble

   being heard, but I'll do whatever you want to do.  If you want

   a microphone for the record, that's fine.

            THE COURT:  I just want you to be heard on the tape, I

   guess.  That is the backup or auxiliary record.

            MR. JONES:  I don't think this is quite what she had

   in mind, your Honor.

            MR. HARTZLER:  It's not what I had in mind.

            THE COURT:  Do we need that microphone?

            COURTROOM DEPUTY:  No, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  All right.  You can go back to your -- to

   your own friendly environs.

            MR. JONES:  My own what?

            THE COURT:  Friendly environs.

            MR. JONES:  Your Honor, the first item that --

   proceeding in the order in which they are listed in the

   motion -- and I suppose it would be more accurate to

   characterize what I'm going to do is to simply put on the

   record our acceptance or rejection of where we think the

   Government has made a statement.  Most of them, we'll accept

   the representation they have made.  And by "accept," I mean

   that the Government has given us its good faith



                                                                           411



   representations, and, of course, we don't have any way to

   challenge that in the absence of evidence to the contrary.

            The first items were discovery requests which are

   clearly disputed either because we claim the Government has not

   produced in discovery or the Government has failed to make a

   representation as to the completeness of the production or

   there is some timing, and I will dispute that.  And I'll first

   take up the disputes as to the timing of production.  Some of

   these have already been addressed, but just to complete the

   record.

            1A was the name and addresses of all unindicted

   co-conspirators, and I understand the Government's response to

   be that it will provide material impeaching information for

   trial witnesses and that the Government has no obligation to

   characterize.  I assume they are referring to unindicted

   co-conspirators in that impeachment evidence.  I believe that

   in the scheduling, we should address the time when the Court

   will -- or the Government will give us the names of the

   unindicted co-conspirators, if any, and the time for which any

   further impeachment material will be provided.  Other than

   that, I think 1A is resolved.

            THE COURT:  Yes.  And we were, at least for those

   whose statements may be offered in evidence.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, your Honor.  We provided that

   proffer of the co-conspirator statements.  Obviously, we'd have



                                                                           412



   to identify any statements and who made them.

            THE COURT:  So that's one of those things that will be

   incorporated in the scheduling order to be completed tomorrow.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, your Honor.

            MR. JONES:  1B, your Honor, was all criminal

   prosecutions investigating or potential prosecutions that could

   be brought against such witnesses and other types of

   investigations concerning probation for all legal disputes with

   Government and convictions.  The Government says that it will

   produce all criminal records, which I understand to be

   convictions, and rap sheets where available for all witnesses

   intended to be called at trial.  And again, that's the question

   of timing, which I assume will be addressed in the Court's

   order.

            THE COURT:  Right.

            MR. JONES:  1C was any federal or state arrests.  The

   Government has said it will produce any criminal records for

   all witnesses intended to be called at trial, and that also

   will be covered by the Court's timing order.

            THE COURT:  Correct.

            MR. JONES:  1D was any federal or state prison

   records.  The Government has responded -- and if I

   mischaracterize the response, please let me know.  But the

   Government has responded they will disclose so long as related

   to prison records which contain impeachment or exculpatory



                                                                           413



   information.  Otherwise, not required.  We accept the

   Government's representation and that would be subject to the

   Court's timing order.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  1E was information concerning

   hospitalization for psychiatric or emotional disorders.  The

   Government will produce, if they are aware of, for witnesses

   intended to be called at trial.  That is acceptable to the

   defense and subject to the Court's timing order.

            1F is information for hospitalization for alcoholism

   or drug abuse.  The Government, if aware of it, will produce it

   for the witnesses intended to be called at trial and subject to

   the Court's timing schedule.

            1G was all information concerning psychiatric,

   emotional disorders, alcoholism or drug abuse, regardless of

   hospitalization.  The Government's response is that if they are

   aware of it, they will produce the information for witnesses

   intended to be called at trial, again to be included in the

   Court's timing order.

            1H is all information concerning veracity of any such

   person has been submitted to polygraph, sodium pentothal,

   hypnosis, et cetera.  This appears to be resolved.  And the

   Government represents that it has been delivered to us and is

   contained in 1A and 1B inventories.  And there's a question

   Mr. Woods raised which we adopted concerning the completeness



                                                                           414



   of what had been provided, and I understand Ms. Wilkinson is

   making inquiry to be sure that we have everything the FBI has.

   If that is the case, the Government's response is acceptable to

   the defense.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, we are going to make a

   further disclosure on the polygraph information, as I believe I

   represented --

            THE COURT:  Yes.

            MS. WILKINSON:  -- earlier.

            THE COURT:  Particularly as to whether there are

   interpretations and summaries.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  1I is consistent or contradictory

   statements of witnesses.  The Government's response is it's

   overbroad and burdensome, but the Government has provided 302's

   and the defense can compare to determine if inconsistent or

   contradictory.  The Government also claims it is overbroad for

   nontestifying witnesses.  It is subject to the Court's

   scheduling order.  The Government's response is acceptable to

   the defense.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  1J is all statements, incident reports,

   302's, et cetera, regarding eyewitness accounts reporting

   Mr. McVeigh and other suspects in locations other than downtown



                                                                           415



   Oklahoma City on April 19, 1995.  The Government's response is

   that as to Mr. McVeigh, the Government has provided 302's.  The

   Government does not know what we mean by "other suspects."

            MS. WILKINSON:  I don't believe that's correct,

   Mr. Jones.  Or, your Honor, we -- I think we stated that we

   provided information as to other suspects.  But to the extent

   the request includes information on other individuals the

   defense considers other suspects, but of which we are unaware,

   of course we can't comply.

            THE COURT:  All right.  So you want to provide

   information on those who are suspects in the Government's view?

            MS. WILKINSON:  We've done that.

            THE COURT:  Yeah.

            MR. JONES:  All right.  K, information of prior

   misconduct or bad acts by witnesses.  The Government will

   provide it to the extent that it is aware of it for witnesses

   intended to be called at trial.  Time to be set in the Court's

   discovery -- scheduling order.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, just to be clear, I

   believe Mr. Jones is generally saying we will.  In many cases,

   we have already disclosed this and will continue to disclose.

            MR. JONES:  Thank you for the clarification.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  L, evidence of physical infirmity which

   affect the ability to perceive or recall, to be aware.  To the



                                                                           416



   extent the Government is aware of it, they have and will

   provide for testifying witnesses, again subject to being

   included in the Court's scheduling orders.

            M, admissions of poor memory or of lack of knowledge

   of any grand jury witness.  To the extent the Government is

   aware of it, they have or will provide for testifying witnesses

   subject to the Court's scheduling order.

            MS. WILKINSON:  The only difference there, your Honor,

   is that -- to the extent the request includes witness' lack of

   knowledge.  I believe the Court addressed that back in December

   that that would not be Brady, some who just didn't know a fact.

            THE COURT:  Right.

            MR. JONES:  N, information concerning reputation.  If

   such person --

            THE COURT:  Well, excuse me.  With this modification:

   That if the person professes a lack of knowledge on one

   occasion but knowledge on another occasion, that's like an

   inconsistent statement.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Of course.  That would be impeachment

   material under Giglio.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  Item N, information concerning reputation

   if such person is questionable for telling the truth.  The

   Government's response is to the extent aware, the Government

   has or will provide for testifying witnesses.  Again, to be



                                                                           417



   included in the Court's scheduling order.

            O has been withdrawn.

            P, contradictory statements or conflicting statements

   concerning involvement of Mr. McVeigh or any associate,

   accomplice or co-conspirator or co-defendant.  The Government's

   response is overbroad and burdensome, but the Government has

   provided 302's.  Defense can compare to determine if

   inconsistent or contradictory.  This is overbroad for

   nontestifying witnesses.  Our response is that in view of the

   Government's representation that all witnesses' statements will

   be provided, we accept the Government's representation, and the

   balance of it would be included in the Court's scheduling

   order.

            Q, evidence inculpating the witness or indicating the

   witness' involvement in the alleged offense or refusal to

   inculpate Mr. McVeigh; for example, the Fortier statements on

   CNN.  The Government's response is the Government has

   disclosed.  And as it becomes aware, it will provide materially

   impeaching material for trial witnesses; i.e., testifying

   witnesses.  Our response is that we previously identified our

   definition of what is materially exculpating material, and the

   Government's response is otherwise acceptable, and the material

   cutoff date would be included in the Court's scheduling order.

            No. 127.  All claims filed for the $2 million reward

   for information leading to the arrest of those involved in the



                                                                           418



   Oklahoma City bombing.  I believe that matter was resolved

   yesterday.

            The next items are disputes as to completeness of

   production.  No. 3, impeachment because of an -- inaccurate or

   misleading information has been resolved by the Government's

   response.

            Items 10, 11, 52, have been withdrawn.

            53 was modified.  Identification of objects germane to

   the Oklahoma City bombing investigation and the collection of

   fingerprints of undisclosed or unidentified individuals or

   suspects in this case has been resolved by the Government's

   response.

            No. 82, identity and statements of informants has been

   resolved by the Government's response.

            Third category, disputes as to evasiveness of

   production.  No. 15 -- and that's our characterization when I

   say "evasiveness of production."

            No. 15 modified, request any evidence that a

   Government bomb expert was present at the scene at the time of

   the explosion.  I believe that that has been resolved by the

   Government's pleadings in which they indicated the presence of

   Special Agent Eberhardt -- I believe he is of the ATF -- who

   was in the federal courthouse.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes.  Agent Eberhardt had left the

   Murrah Building shortly before 9:00 to walk over to the federal



                                                                           419



   courthouse to watch an arson trial.

            MR. JONES:  No. 18 which is one that is still, I

   think, disputed.  We asked your Honor in that one for

   Government contacts with civil litigants.  We were particularly

   interested if the Government had contacted the plaintiff in the

   case or her lawyer, Mr. Hayes, in the original civil suit that

   was filed against Mr. McVeigh that -- that was pending in

   Canadian County.

            The Court may recall that late Friday afternoon before

   the depositions were scheduled on Monday, the depositions --

   the civil suit was dismissed.  And we were not notified and we

   had the expense of going to Kansas to take the deposition.  Of

   course, the witnesses did not appear because suit had been

   dismissed.  They were aware of it, we weren't.  And we asked

   the Court to order the Government to disclose to us any

   contacts with the civil litigants that may have led to the

   dismissal of that case.  And the Government says it's beyond

   Brady.

            THE COURT:  Are you pressing that one?

            MR. JONES:  Well, I think it's material, your Honor,

   because it might constitute pressure on the witness to dismiss

   the case or might constitute witness tampering if they had such

   contact.  They may not have had the contact.  Their response

   doesn't say one way or the other, as I recall.

            THE COURT:  Yeah.  The response is in the way of an



                                                                           420



   objection.  Can't you just respond to that no if that's the --

   if that's correct?

            MS. WILKINSON:  We're not aware of any contact, your

   Honor, by Government agents to the civil litigants, but the

   point I think was that under Brady, we didn't see how that was

   exculpatory to Mr. McVeigh.  I'm not sure --

            THE COURT:  If the answer is no, answer it no and we

   can move on without worrying about it.  Arguments as to whether

   it is or is not exculpatory --

            MS. WILKINSON:  Could I have a moment, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  Sure.

            MS. WILKINSON:  I believe that there was a reason I

   gave you a legal response, your Honor; Mr. Ryan did speak with

   the plaintiff's lawyer.

            THE COURT:  I -- I'm trying to remember who the

   plaintiff was.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Mr. Ryan?  Edye Smith.

            MR. JONES:   Brandy Liggons is who I had.

            THE COURT:  I think we're talking about two different

   lawsuits.

            MR. RYAN:  I don't know anything about the Brandy

   Liggons lawsuit.  To my knowledge, I've never spoken to her

   lawyer.  I don't know who her lawyer is.  Didn't know she had a

   lawsuit.

            MR. JONES:  Gaylon Hayes was her lawyer.



                                                                           421



            MR. RYAN:  Excuse me?

            MR. JONES:  Gaylon Hayes was her lawyer.

            MR. RYAN:  That doesn't mean anything to me.  Maybe

   it's faulty because I haven't thought about this.  It's been a

   long time ago.  I was thinking it was Edye Smith that had filed

   a lawsuit over in Canadian County.

            THE COURT:  That's still going, that lawsuit?

            MR. RYAN:  Right.

            THE COURT:  That's the one where there's the motion to

   stay it because of its interference with this prosecution,

   which is one of those things that I've never actually issued an

   order on.  We stayed it, but not with a formal and final order.

   Isn't that the state of the record?

            MR. JONES:  It is.  Well, I wasn't asking about the

   Edye Smith lawsuit.

            THE COURT:  That's not being inquired about.  This is

   an earlier case, isn't it?

            MR. JONES:  It is.  It's the first one.  And --

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, then the prosecution team

   is unaware of any Government contact, but, again, the problem

   with that is to assure the Court and feel comfortable with my

   response, we would need to contact everyone to ask them the

   question.

            THE COURT:  Absent an additional showing, I'm in

   agreement with the response that it's not exculpatory.



                                                                           422



            MR. JONES:  Item 48 was withdrawn.

            Item 95 requested the Government identify terrorism

   experts that it had consulted who had proffered opinions

   concerning the involvement of others.  And by "others," we were

   referring to different -- to use the terminology we adopted

   earlier this morning -- involvement in the bombing and any

   reports related to those opinions.

            The Government's response was it had disclosed all

   statements of individuals interviewed in connection with the

   investigation and then said that an opinion by an expert in

   terrorism or counter-terrorism regarding other's possible

   involvement does not constitute Brady unless there is some

   evidence supporting that opinion, and then the Government said

   that any evidence that could support such an opinion had been

   and would continue to be disclosed to the defense.

            The problem I have with the response -- and again,

   perhaps it's just a semantic one -- is I read the response as

   saying, well, whatever the expert reviewed has been furnished

   to you, but that wasn't what I asked.  What I asked was for the

   identity of experts they had consulted who had given that

   opinion.  I got whatever facts they may have based the opinion

   upon, if, in fact, there were any experts, but I still think I

   am entitled to know who the experts were.  If there's an expert

   who reviewed this evidence and thought there were others

   involved, it seems to me that his identity is clearly



                                                                           423



   exculpatory.

            THE COURT:  Well, the way I read this response,

   though, is they are excluding what amounts to speculation

   without supporting factual information.

            MS. WILKINSON:  That's correct, your Honor.  We have

   not received any written opinion or what I'm aware of or -- the

   prosecution team is aware of, any opinion from expert that

   other individuals were involved.  But what we're trying to make

   sure of is if the director of the FBI consulted with another

   expert and someone gave him an opinion off the cuff on the

   first, second day after the bombing, surely, that would not

   fall under Brady.

            THE COURT:  Well, I'm in agreement to the extent that

   I think the opinion has to be something that amounts to an

   opinion that's supportable and not necessarily admissible in

   evidence, but which constitutes something more than speculation

   or conjecture without identifiers.

            MR. JONES:  I would agree with that, and we weren't

   seeking that.  But --

            THE COURT:  It's not clear that, you know, somebody

   could offer an opinion and say, well, I think that there are

   certain signature qualities to this explosion that suggests an

   identification with a similar explosion in another place and

   country.  I don't -- that, to my mind, is not sufficient

   opinion to be produced under Brady.  I hope that clears it up.



                                                                           424



   That's -- that's the basis for my -- essentially, my agreement

   with the Government's response.

            MR. JONES:  Item No. 112 was a list prepared by

   federal law enforcement authorities of men who fit the John Doe

   description and were known to have been associated with

   Mr. McVeigh.  The Government said basically in its response, We

   have also designated those 302's and inserts that may arguably

   contain exculpatory information regarding John Doe 2 and other

   suspects.  But it was the term "other suspects" -- if I may

   have just a moment, your Honor.  We will withdraw it, your

   Honor.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  136 said identification -- requested --

   I'm sorry.  136 requested identification of all sweeps of the

   Alfred P. Murrah Building for any bombs between April 15 and

   April 22, 1995.  The Government's response was --

