   is that these individuals were not investigated as suspects or

   witnesses.

            And 8 has been withdrawn.

            Number 10, I think we should address today, although

   after addressing it, the Court may want to put it as part of

   the other matter.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, could we go through these

   one at a time?  I'm having a hard time following Mr. Jones just

   on these few.

            No. 6, are we including that in the classified

   information category?

            MR. JONES:  Yes.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Okay.

            MR. JONES:  5, 6, 7 in the classified information

   category.

            MS. WILKINSON:  I'm not sure, your Honor, why No. 5

   would fall under the classified information category.  Just

   because the individuals have Middle Eastern ancestry or

   nationality --

            MR. JONES:  I'll withdraw 5.  I agree with you.

            THE COURT:  Yeah.  6 and 7 do relate, although you

   made a response to 7.

            MS. WILKINSON:  We could not always discern why the



                                                                           447



   defense put certain requests in the classified information

   brief and why in the exculpatory, but we understood the Court

   to have requested us to answer each request, and this one had

   not been put into the classified information request.  As we

   said, we're not aware of any warnings.

            THE COURT:  But again, there's a qualifier in there.

   "Credible."

            MR. JONES:  That's my concern because we have

   submitted to the Court --

            THE COURT:  It really does go into the classified

   information matter, I think.  Should be addressed there.  And

   then 9, also?

            MR. JONES:  Yes.

            THE COURT:  Is that right?  9?

            MR. JONES:  Yes.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, I'm not sure why these two

   individuals again fall under classified information.  Just

   because their names are of foreign descent, I don't think that

   qualifies them.

            THE COURT:  No.  But the source of the information

   with respect to them might be one of the sources that's being

   -- I'm being asked to structure an order related to the

   approach to that source?

            MS. WILKINSON:  It could, but from their request, it's

   impossible to discern that; and it seems to me that for these



                                                                           448



   two individuals, I mean, we have thousands of individuals who

   have been in --

            THE COURT:  Let me ask you this:  Is your answer to

   response No. 69 inclusive of all of the agencies who might know

   this, have this --

            MS. WILKINSON:  You mean if any agency has ever

   investigated this?  Of course not.  We didn't know these names

   beforehand so we've never asked other agencies whether they

   have investigated --

            THE COURT:  That's what I interpreted your response to

   mean.  You don't know who they are.

            MR. JONES:  Your Honor, the first one is the

   co-defendant to Ramzi Yousef.  I mean, he's named in the

   indictment and I believe was convicted and the second one, over

   my index here -- I'll notify Ms. Wilkinson.

            THE COURT:  Who they are.  Further identification is

   requested by you; is that right?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, your Honor.

            MR. JONES:  That's reasonable.  No. 10 is, strictly

   speaking, not a CIPA matter, but -- it could be that the Court

   wants to address it there and not address it today.  That was

   the one for application of --

            THE COURT:  Yeah.  Isn't that -- I don't have ready

   familiarity with that act.  Isn't that act those applications

   are made to a special court?



                                                                           449



            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes.  To FISA court, your Honor,

   but --

            THE COURT:  And I don't know what the -- that court

   does with respect to the secrecy of those records.

            MS. WILKINSON:  The Government maintains copies of

   those applications, just as we would in a Title 3 wiretap.

            THE COURT:  But are you free to disclose them?

            MS. WILKINSON:  It depends on the nature of the

   criminal proceeding and the relation between the FISA wiretap

   and the criminal proceeding here.  Under Alderman, we've

   already reported that no wiretaps, whether they fall under FISA

   or Title 3, were conducted on these defendants; and we

   understand that to be the -- you know, the extent of -- that we

   have to respond in this case.  That's what we're objecting to,

   revealing whether we had --

            THE COURT:  Okay.  So the Department of Justice has

   records of any such applications having been made to that

   court?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Correct.

            THE COURT:  And there aren't any.

            MS. WILKINSON:  As to these defendants, that's

   correct.

            MR. JONES:  Well, that's my point and I agree with her

   that, generally, we would get the information or should get the

   information if applications were made concerning our clients,



                                                                           450



   but if applications were made to FISA for individuals other

   than these defendants for wiretaps, I think that's a -- meets

   the low threshold showing that there could be different

   suspects or perpetrators.

            THE COURT:  Again, I'm not familiar with what that

   statute requires as compared with Title 3 that we use, but if

   it's anywhere similar, then there has to be a justification

   shown; and it seems to me that the appropriate inquiry here is

   whether the application shows as justification the

   investigation of threats against this building.

            MR. JONES:  That was exactly my point.  If -- if

   the -- the Government made an application for a wiretap order

   against someone else other than these defendants and cited as

   support that wiretap order, the probable cause showing to get

   it, I think that clearly is material to the defense here.

            THE COURT:  If the probable cause relates to this

   event.

            MR. JONES:  Yes, sir.

            THE COURT:  As compared to just --

            MR. JONES:  Yes.

            THE COURT:  Yeah.  That isn't the way I read the

   request.

            MR. JONES:  I'm sorry.  That's the way we meant it.

   And the Government has never responded that there were no FISA

   applications with respect to this case.  They simply say there



                                                                           451



   are none with respect to these defendants, but if they made one

   concerning other suspects and mentioned this case, then we want

   to know those.

            THE COURT:  Yes.  What about that?  Have you checked

   that?

            MS. WILKINSON:  I'm unaware of that, your Honor.  But

   we will go back and double-check that.  I don't believe there

   were any --

            THE COURT:  I think they are entitled to know the

   answer to that.

            MS. WILKINSON:  So in other words, if the basis of the

   probable cause was that some -- I know the standard is an agent

   of a foreign power, it's different obviously than a Title 3,

   but the same general probable cause is necessary.  If that

   individual were involved with some kind of plan or threat or

   plot to bomb the Murrah Building, obviously, that would be --

            THE COURT:  -- the subject of requiring this

   technique --

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes.  I --

            THE COURT:  -- related to this event.  Yes.

            MS. WILKINSON:  I'm sure that does not exist because

   we would be aware of the underlying information, but we will

   double-check.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. JONES:  12, 13, 14, 15, withdrawn.



                                                                           452



            16.

            MS. WILKINSON:  I'm sorry.  What happened to No. 11?

            MR. JONES:  Resolved by your response.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Okay.

            MR. JONES:  If I might have just a moment, your Honor.

   This is matters relating to Mr. Strassmeir and I assume should

   be addressed as part of CIPA, although his Immigration Service

   file, I believe, is a 1A item -- I assume any items listed on

   the 1A index concerning him, we can get copies of.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Of course.  Those have always been

   available to the defense.

            MR. JONES:  The rest of it, I suggest be held in

   abeyance pending the Court's order on CIPA.

            THE COURT:  No. 16?

            MR. JONES:  Yes, sir.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, just to be clear, we have

   already disclosed materials regarding Mr. Strassmeir,

   interviews.

            THE COURT:  Quite a few of them.

            MS. WILKINSON:  And Mr. Jones has disclosed an

   interview to us that he had.

            MR. JONES:  No. 17, the Court -- or the Government's

   response, it is overbroad, speculative, and beyond the scope of

   Brady.  They say, however, they have and will continue to give

   us all information pertaining to Richard Snell; and if I may



                                                                           453



   inquire, would that include information concerning plans,

   plots, conspiracies or whatever with respect to his execution

   and protest or efforts to avoid it?

            MS. WILKINSON:  No.  Only -- the documents we've

   disclosed on Richard Snell are only to the extent we've

   collected them in connection with this investigation.

            THE COURT:  I've seen them.  You supplied them in the

   appendix.

            MS. WILKINSON:  People who make allegations, we go out

   and check them out, write a 302 and then disclose it to the

   defense.  But in terms of his general involvement or alleged

   involvement in solicitation or encouragement or attempts to

   mark his execution or others in that by violent acts, we have

   not gone out and done an investigation of that general nature,

   and we think that's beyond the scope of Brady.

            THE COURT:  I agree.

            MR. JONES:  18 is withdrawn.

            19 concerning Department of Justice phone call 24

   minutes before the bombing.  Government claims to have

   disclosed the Tolson logbook, which I -- was in the most recent

   discovery.  I don't think we have it yet.

            THE COURT:  Where does this quotation come from?  From

   302's?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Yes, your Honor.

            MR. JONES:  Yes, sir.



                                                                           454



            THE COURT:  And you've disclosed what you have?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Relative to that.  That's where

   Mr. Jones got it from, is us, from our investigation.

            THE COURT:  Your response is those 302's.  And what is

   that D?  Is that an insert?  D13814?

            MR. WYATT:  Those are 302's, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  I'm sorry.

            MS. WILKINSON:  That's the way the defense writes it.

   We usually just write the 302 with the serial number.  They

   have the D in front of it.

            THE COURT:  That's what you have.

            MS. WILKINSON:  That's what we have.  And any further

   investigation we do, we'll disclose.

            THE COURT:  Okay.

            MR. JONES:  Well, the reason I put it on here is that

   I wrote Mr. Hartzler a couple months ago and asked if we could

   interview these agents and he said yes, that he wanted to check

   into it first, and we haven't heard back from him.  So although

   they now have produced the Tolson logbook -- so I don't mean to

   pressure him, press him about it today, but it is still a

   matter outstanding.

            THE COURT:  Well, I don't think, though, that the

   question of interviewing them is the subject of ruling on this

   present motion.

            MR. JONES:  I agree.



                                                                           455



            THE COURT:  All right.  No. 20.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, so as to 19, are we

   resolved, Mr. Jones?  Is it resolved?

            MR. JONES:  I still want to interview them --

            THE COURT:  The motion is resolved.

            MR. JONES:  Right.  The motion is resolved.  Yes.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MS. WILKINSON:  As to exculpatory evidence that we're

   disclosing.

            THE COURT:  This motion is resolved with respect to

   Item 19.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Thank you.

            MR. JONES:  No. 20, any information that federal or

   state law enforcement authorities had suspicion or knowledge of

   a violent terrorist attack to occur in Oklahoma City around

   April 19.  The Government has responded that they have given us

   the two letters and they provided the Star Ledger memo or will

   provide it for in camera review by the Court.  Our problem is

   that we have information that the FTS operators in the Murrah

   Building were specifically warned to be on the lookout for a

   possible threat.  And there's no reference here as to whether

   they have contacted the FTS operators with respect to that

   matter.  And that's our information.  It may be wrong, but we

   have it from a credible source.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, this is the first time



                                                                           456



   we're hearing this that I recall.  Perhaps Mr. Jones has

   written us a letter about it.  I don't recall it.  However --

            THE COURT:  Well, is that what the request --

            MS. WILKINSON:  No.

            MR. JONES:  No.  I think in the specifications or

   elsewhere, we have specifically mentioned the FTS, but I'll

   write them a letter to be sure about it.

            MS. WILKINSON:  But, your Honor, we've disclosed

   anything we have checked in our investigation about threats.

   We are unaware of any threats that -- to Oklahoma City or to

   the Federal Building during that time period, any specific

   threats.  As I said, I believe this is probably related to the

   March warning that went out across the country for everyone to

   heighten their security, and that makes sense that everyone

   would be alerted.

            THE COURT:  Well, I think the question, though, is in

   answering that, does that include a check of these FTS

   operators?

            MR. JONES:  It was --

            MS. WILKINSON:  I don't know what the FTS operators

   are, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  They are the people who handle the long

   distance, among other things, the telephone lines for the

   building.

            MS. WILKINSON:  You're talking about the federal



                                                                           457



   Government operators for FTS?  I thought FTS was a federal line

   that we used to make calls among the agencies.

            THE COURT:  Yeah.  But you can contact operators to

   assist in calling.  At least you used to be able to.  I don't

   use the phone that much anymore.

            MR. WYATT:  I believe the FTS is a division of GSA,

   and we're specifically referencing e-mail that went over the

   wires in the days immediately preceding the bombing.

            THE COURT:  I don't know that e-mail goes FTS.  I

   don't think it does.  I think FTS is strictly telephone.

            MR. JONES:  This was a distribution to them and

   specifically the --

            THE COURT:  Well, you better make your request more

   specific.

            MR. JONES:  All right.  No. 21 has been resolved by

   the Government's response that they don't know who Mr. Robinson

   is.

            1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, and 8 are general Brady requests,

   your Honor, and the Government has responded accordingly.

            And that completes this review and leaves --

            MS. WILKINSON:  On page 19, No. 80 was the first one

   we left, I believe, unresolved; is that right?

            THE COURT:  No. 80.  I -- I don't know that we'll get

   these resolved in the next 10 or 15 minutes.  We still have

   these items that will warrant some discussion, I take it, and



                                                                           458



   we have the identification motion that we agreed we could hear

   tomorrow.  And we have the additional conference to do.  So

   maybe the best thing -- I was discussing it in the nonpublic

   meeting, timing with that.  Maybe the thing to do is come back

   to this at 9:00 and also the identification issue and get those

   things done and then retire to the conference.  How's that?

            Mr. Woods.

            MR. WOODS:  Your Honor, may it please the Court.  We

   had that one pending motion asking for a list of attendees at

   the Oklahoma City meeting.

            THE COURT:  Yes.  We'll address that, too.

            MR. WOODS:  Thank you.

            THE COURT:  You'll be prepared to address that or

   whoever.

            MS. WILKINSON:  We will, your Honor, yes.

            THE COURT:  Okay.  We'll do those things at the 9:00

   incoming.  And then whenever those things are done, we'll -- I

   don't want to say retreat.  We will discuss scheduling and see

   where we are.

            MR. JONES:  Your Honor, we advised the Court yesterday

   that we had a status report which addressed some of the matters

   we discussed in chambers.  Attached to the status report were

   some charts that I believe Ms. Wilkinson had an objection to,

   and so I would like to ask to file this, but ask that it be

   filed under seal until the Court can decide if the charge



                                                                           459



   should be removed.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, I believe since it's a

   discovery request -- I mean, it's -- it deals with discovery

   matters, we've been putting those other things under seal.  But

   if the Court wants to take it under advisement and then have us

   address it, we can do that.

            THE COURT:  Well, does the status report include

   editorializing in addition to factual information?

            MR. JONES:  No.  It arose this way:  Yesterday, we had

   the charts and the Court -- the Court got before it at -- at

   the Court's request, I handed the Court the charts, but the

   Court had them, but they are not in the record anyplace.  And

   so I was just trying to put a place -- to put them in the

   record to complete the record, but I'm not necessarily

   suggesting they are public.  I mean, some of this material, I

   think, is public, but I understand the concern about --

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, it has correspondence,

   discovery correspondence between the parties.

            THE COURT:  That comes under the nonpublic criteria.

            MS. WILKINSON:  And the brief, itself, the status

   report does have -- as you might imagine, we disagree on the

   characterization -- does have some editorializing, so we would

   request that it be placed under seal.

            MR. JONES:  I request it be placed under seal.



                                                                           460



            THE COURT:  You said part of it.

            MR. JONES:  I'm sorry.  Well, the status report is no

   different than three or four others that have been filed that

   analyze the delay.

            THE COURT:  File it sealed and we'll decide what needs

   to be opened.

            MR. JONES:  All right.

            THE COURT:  We don't need blowups, though, anyway,

   because demonstrative exhibits are not necessary for these

   proceedings.  So I'll see you at 9:00 in the morning.

            Court's in recess.

       (Court recessed at 4:50 p.m.)

                          *   *   *   *   *

                       REPORTER'S CERTIFICATE

       I certify that the foregoing is a correct transcript from

   the record of proceedings in the above-entitled matter.  Dated

   at Denver, Colorado, this 14th day of November, 1996.



                                    _______________________________
                                                       Bonnie Carpenter
