<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<P> In this three-day hearing, lawyers argued over what evidence the prosecution must turn over to the defense. Prosecutors are obliged to provide the defendants any evidence they consider using in a trial as well as any information that might help the defense side. Defendant Timothy McVeigh's attorney, Stephen Jones, asked for details on negotiations between authorities and Michael Fortier, a former associate of McVeigh's who is expected to testify for the government in exchange for a plea agreement. Jones contended that Fortier changed his story as part of deal to avoid trial.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
   FOR THE DISTRICT OF COLORADO

               Criminal Action No. 96-CR-68

               UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,

                   Plaintiff,

               vs.

               TIMOTHY JAMES McVEIGH and TERRY LYNN NICHOLS,

                   Defendants.

                                    REPORTER'S TRANSCRIPT
                 (HEARING ON MOTIONS - VOLUME VIII)


            Proceedings before the HONORABLE RICHARD P. MATSCH,

   Judge, United States District Court for the District of

   Colorado, commencing at 9:58 a.m., on the 15th day of November,

   1996, in Courtroom C-203, United States Courthouse, Denver,

   Colorado.















    Proceeding Recorded by Mechanical Stenography, Transcription
                 Produced via Computer by Paul Zuckerman, 1929 Stout Street,
       P.O. Box 3563, Denver, Colorado, 80294, (303) 629-9285



                                                                           462



                             APPEARANCES

            PATRICK M. RYAN, United States Attorney for the

   District of Oklahoma, 210 West Park Avenue, Suite 400, Oklahoma

   City, Oklahoma, 73102, appearing for the plaintiff.

            JOSEPH H. HARTZLER, SEAN CONNELLY, LARRY A. MACKEY,

   BETH WILKINSON, SCOTT MENDELOFF, and VICKI BEHENNA, Special

   Attorneys to the U.S. Attorney General, 1961 Stout Street,

   Suite 1200, Denver, Colorado, 80294, appearing for the

   plaintiff.

            STEPHEN JONES, ROBERT NIGH, JR., ROBERT WYATT and

   RICHARD BURR, Attorneys at Law, Jones, Wyatt & Roberts, 114

   East Broadway, Suite 100, Post Office Box 472, Enid, Oklahoma,

   73702-0472, and JERALYN MERRITT, 303 East 17th Avenue, Suite

   400, Denver, Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant McVeigh.

            RONALD G. WOODS, ADAM THURSCHWELL, and REID NEUREITER,

   Attorneys at Law, 1120 Lincoln Street, Suite 1308, Denver,

   Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant Nichols.

                            *  *  *  *  *

                             PROCEEDINGS

       (In open court at 9:58 a.m.)

            THE COURT:  We are again resumed in 96-CR-68.  It

   would appear that the appearances are the same.

            MR. HARTZLER:  Right, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  And the start of our hearing was delayed

   past the 9 o'clock established time because counsel asked for



                                                                           463



   and I granted the opportunity for them to meet together and

   without me to have free discussion with respect to attempting

   to resolve any of the issues that could be resolved in that

   fashion.  So we're now ready to proceed.

            As we recessed yesterday afternoon, we had gone

   through item by item the matters requested in the motion for

   production filed August 30 as docket entry 1939.  In the course

   of that, several items were reserved for hearing and

   disposition.  So I suggest we take those items up now.

            Mr. Jones.

            MR. JONES:  Thank you, your Honor.

            May it please the Court, I believe that I have

   previously described or characterized the issue of the FBI

   laboratory in terms of our modern culture as being the

   potential Detective Mark Furman issue of this case.  But with

   respect to the Brady motion and particularly the five items

   that are remaining, I think that those can be characterized

   slightly different, and that this relates primarily and most

   importantly, Request No. 80 and 84, to one of those legs that I

   talked about on the first day, and that specifically is the

   testimony to be offered at sometime in the trial of Michael and

   Lori Fortier.

            The requests that are still pending is Request No. 80

   and 84.  And if I may, I'll just read it into the record.  We

   requested any and all notes, reports, minutes, and/or



                                                                           464



   transcripts of the negotiating sessions by and between Michael

   Fortier and his lawyers and Lori Fortier and her lawyers and

   representatives of the United States Government which contain

   language or details of the proffer either by Michael or Lori

   Fortier or the alleged details of factual representations

   together where a copy of immunity agreement or immunity

   extensions or agreements to prosecute or plea bargains extended

   to either Michael or Lori Fortier.

            Request No. 84 requested all prior inconsistent

   statements of Michael Fortier and Lori Fortier together with

   all statements of Michael Fortier and Lori Fortier given to the

   grand jury, the United States Attorney's Office or its

   representative, the Federal Bureau of Investigation, the ATF,

   or any other law enforcement, additionally we requested 302s,

   reports, summaries, notes, memoranda, and all statements that

   intend to inculpate Michael and Lori Fortier.

            Now, the Government has given to us pursuant to a

   Court's order the grand jury testimony of both Michael and Lori

   Fortier.  I believe the Government's representation in the

   materials submitted to us is that both of them appeared before

   the grand jury only once, and I believe those dates were

   immediately prior to the return of the indictment, perhaps

   August 9, August 10 of last year.

            In addition, we received in January of this year

   copies of 302's of Michael and Lori Fortier, and we may have



                                                                           465



   received one or two since then.  So it appears, your Honor,

   that we have received the 302's and we have received the grand

   jury testimony.  But there is a gap beginning at sometime

   unknown to us but presumably in May or June, because our

   information comes basically from a very informative article

   that appeared in USA Today written by Kevin Johnson, a copy of

   which was attached to the motion to begin with.

            This article took up approximately a third of a page

   and purports to detail discussions of the negotiating sessions.

   We don't know what happened in those sessions, but we can

   certainly surmise because the last of the 302's and the

   beginning of the grand jury testimony show that during that

   period of time, the story changed considerably.  And we end

   with the last information given on the 302, and then we get the

   grand jury material.

            Well, what happened between the last of the 302's and

   the grand jury material is they reached an agreement.  And

   under the rules, undoubtedly that proceeded with a proffer.

   And what we believe happened is that because this took so long,

   it took a period of many weeks in which joint sessions were

   held with attorney for both of these individuals, that proffers

   were made of what the testimony could do and what we had was a

   give and take.  So in other words, the original proffer of what

   Michael Fortier knew and would testify to increased and got,

   quote, better, close quote, for the Government as the



                                                                           466



   Government's negotiations and his perception of what was his

   best interest also got better.  And the reason we know that is

   because, first of all, human experience teaches us that, but

   secondly because of the long period of time over which these

   negotiations and meetings took place.

            So Mr. Hartzler and his staff met with Mr. McGuire on

   behalf of Mr. Fortier and Mr. Martin on behalf of Mrs. Fortier,

   and they engaged in some horse trading.  And all we have is the

   final product.  And what we want are the statements that were

   made because we don't believe that either Mr. Fortier or

   Mr. McGuire, his agent, came in and on the first day told the

   Government what's in that grand jury testimony.  What we think

   happened is the story changed and got better for the

   Government's standpoint.

            Now, we are dealing with people, at least in Fortier's

   case, who made at least a dozen statements to national

   television networks and to national newspapers concerning his

   lack of involvement, the lack of involvement of Mr. McVeigh,

   and some of those statements are preceded with the word

   honestly, meaning an honest representation of what he was

   telling his interlocutors was true.  He's come 180 degrees now,

   implicating not only himself, but his wife and making

   incriminating statements concerning our client which the

   Government will represent to the jury are truthful.

            In addition to that, the Government has disclosed



                                                                           467



   exculpatory information concerning him that would detract from

   his credibility in front of a jury aside from the statements

   that were already in the public domain.  So we asked the

   Government for that, and we were told that any exculpatory

   information contained in the attorney notes would be provided

   to us.  And we got back a letter related to an alleged drug use

   by the Fortiers.

            But that's not really central to the issue here of

   during these negotiating sessions, how much did Michael

   Fortier's statement evolve and did he change or withdraw those

   statements.  There are no 302's of any of those meetings.  It's

   my understanding there were always FBI agents present, but they

   had writer's cramp and they didn't make any notes of those

   meetings, and we don't have Mr. Hartzler's notes.

            Now, there may be some exception to the production of

   attorney notes in the interview and preparation of a witness

   for trial.  We understand that, that's attorney work product.

   But this is a different type of meeting.  This was a meeting to

   elicit information from a potential defendant in order to

   determine how the Government would respond to a suggested plea

   bargain.  And we simply want to know what he said during those

   sessions because we believe it highly material and highly

   exculpatory.

            THE COURT:  What he said, meaning Mr. Fortier.

            MR. JONES:  Or his agent on his behalf.



                                                                           468



            THE COURT:  Well, there's a big difference, big

   difference.

            MR. JONES:  Well, I understand and appreciate that the

   Court recognizes that difference.  But in terms of this case, I

   wonder if it isn't a distinction without a difference.  If

   Mr. McGuire goes in and makes a proffer and says this is what

   my client would say, there's no attorney/client privilege

   because he's repeating it to others.  There's no attorney work

   product privilege because he's repeating it to others.  And if

   for example he said to them, All my client can tell you is that

   Tim McVeigh once told him X, but if two weeks later he comes in

   and says, My client can tell you that Tim McVeigh said X and Y

   and did A and B, that is a material difference, and

   inconsistency, if you will, from the earlier statement.  And

   that is what we are asking to be produced.

            And I think the dispute we have with the Government

   has been narrowed to the issue, 'cause I think they produced

   everything else, to what transpired in those negotiating

   sessions.  And I'm not asking for what the Government said.

   I'm only asking for what Mr. Fortier and his wife said or was

   said on their behalf with their authorization.

            THE COURT:  All right.  Ms. Wilkinson, do you have any

   response?

            MS. WILKINSON:  Your Honor, to get right to the point,

