            THE COURT:  All right, Mr. Hartzler, if you wish to.

            MR. HARTZLER:  What happened was the attorneys came in

   and made a proffer to Government attorneys, the attorneys for

   the Fortiers.

            THE COURT:  An oral proffer.

            MR. HARTZLER:  An oral proffer that I did not witness



                                                                           470



   but was advised that they identified highlights, which of

   course I won't go into here today, highlights of what the

   witnesses could testify to.  Those highlights are revealed in

   the grand jury testimony.  After that initial proffer was made,

   I then took over and met separately with the Fortiers and their

   attorneys with agents and other Government attorneys present,

   and we asked for additional details about those highlights.

   For the most part, those additional details are disclosed in

   the grand jury testimony.

            Horse trading is an unfair characterization of what

   went on.  We listened to what the Fortiers could testify to

   under a proffer agreement which has been disclosed.  They

   provided us with information consistent with what they said in

   the grand jury.

            At the conclusion of our receiving the details from

   them, we told them what information, we told them what plea

   agreement we would except from Michael Fortier, presented that.

   It was accepted.  There was no dickering back and forth.  There

   was certainly no negotiating for additional information or

   additional facts.  And I think that the information that's in

   the grand jury provides not only the highlights that were in

   the proffer but provides much of the detail that was presented

   to us in the additional sessions.

