   mentioned.  He may want to refresh his memory.  I've read 302's

   where individual witnesses were shown one photograph at a time,

   so I'm sure he did not intentionally overlook that.

            THE COURT:  Well, it's not surprising that in taking

   these interviews, they say have you ever seen this person, or

   something like that.

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  That's what you're referring to, I take

   it.

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  As opposed to the interview for the

   purpose of in and of itself making a display of photographs or

   drawings?

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            MR. WOODS:  Your Honor, we are asking for a list of

   the attendees and any written report or record of two meetings

   that occurred in Oklahoma City approximately three weeks ago on

   October 27 and 28.  They came to light because of press

   coverage here in Denver and in Oklahoma City.  I understand



                                                                           497



   that there was a meeting with the victim/witnesses on Sunday

   night, October 27, approximately 200 present.  On Monday night

   approximately 100 present.

            The comments that are reported in the press after this

   meeting cause us some concern of possible violation of Rule

   615, the exclusion of witnesses, and also possible violation of

   the Court's order of June 13 regarding extracurricular

   statements of counsel and the support staff in this case.

            THE COURT:  Extrajudicial I think it says, not

   extracurricular.  Maybe I'm mistaken.

            MR. WOODS:  You're exactly right, your Honor,

   extrajudicial statements.

            MR. JONES:  We'd like to stop the others, too, your

   Honor.

            MR. WOODS:  Your Honor, I would like to quote two or

   three of the statements that were reported in quotation marks

   after the meeting.  A Ms. Kathleen Treanor reported that I can

   certainly see how we would have an open-and-shut case, it's

   nice to hear our side of the story.

            And Mr. Daniel DeMoss said that I think the evidence

   they have is really clear-cut, I think they just can't wait to

   get this thing to trial.  Further he said that he heard how

   little it would cost to construct a fertilizer bomb that blew

   up the building, less than $500, in this conference.

            And Mr. Hartzler was then quoted as he came out of the



                                                                           498



   meeting that he said that prosecutors have evidence that has

   not been made public yet.  There's been some information that

   has gotten out, no question about that, but there is evidence

   that the Government will present at trial that has not yet been

   presented publicly.  I think that's definitely the case.

            He then characterized the meeting as stating to that

   extent I think we were able to, I hope, lay to rest some of the

   claims of what I characterize as the wacky theories; that is,

   the defense theories.  These are statements made to the press

   after the meeting there in Oklahoma City.

            We feel that this is a possible violation of the

   Court's extrajudicial statement ruling issued on June 13, '95,

   on page 10, specifically where the Court admonishes all counsel

   not to make any statement as to any opinion as to the guilt or

   innocence of the defendants or as to the merits of the case or

   the quality or quantity of evidence, as to any charge in the

   case.

            Also, on page 9 of the Court's orders, none of the

   lawyers appearing in this case or any persons associated with

   them, including any persons with a supervisory authority over

   them, will release or authorize the release of information or

   opinion about this criminal proceeding which a reasonable

   person would expect to be disseminated by any means of public

   communication if there is a reasonable likelihood that such

   disclosure will interfere with a fair trial of the pending



                                                                           499



   charges or otherwise prejudice the due administration of

   justice.

            The Court issued this order after a number of comments

   and in the press over a period of a year.  And when the parties

   brought it to the attention of the Court, the Court issued this

   order and gave us a stern warning as to trying to minimize the

   publicity in this case so we can pick a jury here in Colorado.

            And we feel that the comments made here and also the

   comment made in this morning's press by one of the prosecutors,

   in The Denver Post, second page, We want to get the evidence

   before a jury and the American public, we want justice to

   prevail and see the defendants sentenced to death, those are

   comments that are not going to help us reach -- find a jury

   that's not been prejudiced or biased in this case.

            And we ask, number one -- back to our motion, we ask

   for the list of attendees so that if some of them testify at

   trial, we can inquire as to whether or not there were group

   meetings of witnesses wherein the evidence was discussed with

   them, because that will affect their testimony.

            And then secondly, we would like a report.  The

   Government rarely has meetings where reports are not compiled,

   and we would like to get the report of that to see if that did

   occur.  The Government has represented to us that we don't

   really understand the Victims Rights and Restitution Act of

   1990 and they have a right to meet with victims.  I understand



                                                                           500



   that fully.  The Act was passed in 1990 when I was a U.S.

   Attorney, and I hired the first victim/witness coordinator and

   implemented the act in the fifth largest office in the country.

   They have probably the best victim/witness coordinator I have

   ever seen and any of the 93 United States Attorney's offices

   would be proud to have.  Ms. Lynn Anderson is doing a super job

   in this case and is helping in the healing and counseling of

   the victims in this case and keeping them advised of the status

   of the case.

            But the Victims Right and Restitution Act does not

   authorize the Government meeting with victims in groups and

   discussing the evidence with them in preparation for their

   testimony.  And so we would respond to their allegation that

   this was merely a meeting pursuant to the Victims Right Act.

   It cannot be used as a cover to go out and hold these group

   meetings, discuss the testimony.  They know from past

   experience that these victims, who the press has great sympathy

   for, will make numerous comments to the press and the press

   will repeat those comments.  The Government knows --

            THE COURT:  What is the language?  I don't have that

   opinion in front of me that I authored.  But something about a

   substantial probability that it will become public.

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  Is that essentially --

            MR. WOODS:  Yes, if there's reasonable likelihood that



                                                                           501



   such disclosure will interfere with the trial of the pending

   charges or otherwise prejudice the administration of justice.

            THE COURT:  Well, there's something about the

   probability --

            MR. WOODS:  Which a reasonable person would expect to

   be disseminated by any means of public communication.

            THE COURT:  Right.

            MR. WOODS:  And we think that based on the history of

   this case, the Government fully knows and understands and may

   be using it -- although I don't want to attribute that to

   them -- but the Government understand that the victims are

   going to be speaking out publicly and that the press will

   invariably repeat what they state.  So we think that to make

   sure that we can have a fair trial in this case, we ask that

   the comments stop and we ask that we be given a list of the

   attendees for proper cross-examination when they testify at the

   trial, be it the guilt or innocence or the punishment hearing.

            THE COURT:  All right.

            Mr. Hartzler, are you going to respond.

            MR. HARTZLER:  Yes.

            MR. JONES:  Before Mr. Hartzler responds, Mr. Burr

   has, I don't know whether the Court wants to know whether we

   join in or distinguish ourselves.

            THE COURT:  Go ahead, Mr. Burr, and we'll get a

   response from both of you.



                                                                           502



            MR. BURR:  Your Honor, we filed a pleading early this

   morning which you may not have seen.

            THE COURT:  Joining.

            MR. BURR:  We joined in part.  Our concern was also on

   the statements by the victims that were quoted in the newspaper

   and the statements by Mr. Hartzler, Mr. Ryan, and we are

   certainly -- part of what happened here was shortly after this

   reporting.

            Mr. Hartzler had a conversation with Mr. Jones and

   apologized for his comments.  And we accepted that, and we

   acknowledged that in the heat of the moment, at times each of

   us makes things that sometimes we -- make comments that we

   later wish we had not made or made differently.  And our

   concern is not so much with attorney comments, although it

   continues to be a bit of a concern in light of the report this

   morning.

            What is of more concern, I think, is what was passed

   on by the victims, characterizing the evidence in the case and

   characterizing defense strategy or defense questions.  Had the

   attorneys themselves made that, those comments, they would have

   clearly been in violation of the order.  And making them in a

   meeting which was private was probably not inappropriate, but

   making them in a meeting and then knowing that there was press

   outside and not taking any steps to be sure that those comments

   were not passed on to the press is a problem.



                                                                           503



            It raises in our view a need for the Court to consider

   extending the order concerning extrajudicial statements to

   victims, not in a broad way, but in a way that when counsel for

   the Government meets with victims and discusses the evidence in

   the case in a way that could lead to comments that might be

   prejudicial and would be violative of the order, victims should

   be bound by that order as well.  So we would ask that the Court

   consider that small extension of the order regarding

   extrajudicial statements to victims in these very narrow kinds

   of circumstances.

            THE COURT:  How would victims be defined in such an

   order?

            MR. BURR:  Well, I would think, your Honor, they would

   be people who met with counsel for the Government because of

   their duty to meet with victims who then -- who then are privy

   to information the Government passes on about their views of

   the case.

            THE COURT:  Okay.

            Now Mr. Hartzler.

            MR. HARTZLER:  I'm having some difficulty with this

   microphone.  It won't stay up.  So if you don't mind, I'll just

   hold it.

            THE COURT:  All right.  I don't mind if you don't.

            MR. HARTZLER:  We may ask for the court mechanic to

   come and give me some help.



                                                                           504



            THE COURT:  You're assuming such a person exists.  Go

   ahead.

            MR. HARTZLER:  First of all, I accept full

   responsibility for these meetings with the victims and for

   comments that I made after the meeting.  I have one regret

   which was that the meetings were held privately and they were

   informal meetings.  The press was not invited.  And I think

   that had the press been there or frankly a defense

   representative, we might not be having this hearing and we

   might not have had the motions.

            We have routinely exercised caution in our comments to

   the press as well as in our comments to the victims, and we

   certainly did so at this meeting.  Part of the problem that we

   have faced is that the victims, as I'm sure you understand,

   want to know more than we can tell.  And in our meeting with

   them, we explained why it is that we cannot tell more than we

   have.

            Our primary purpose in meeting with them was to advise

   them of your rulings, the suppression ruling in particular, and

   the severance ruling as well and to give them some assurance

   that those rulings did not affect our presentation of evidence,

   that we didn't lose any evidence as a result of the suppression

   ruling, we didn't lose any evidence as a result of the

   severance ruling.

            In addition, we introduced each of ourselves and



                                                                           505



   talked about our background.  And I think that what resulted

   from the meeting was a feeling among the attendees that this

   was a group of well-qualified, confident prosecutors, who were

   anxious, ready to go to trial.  And my impression is that

   people left the meeting feeling good about that and therefore

   feeling good about the Government's case and therefore made

   comments about the strength of the Government's case that were

   not made inside the room.  We did not discuss the evidence with

   the victims.

            We certainly talked about the comments that Ms.

   Wilkinson has made in response so some of the discovery

   motions, and there is no doubt that we pointed out that.  For

   example, the allegation that the Government itself knew before

   the bombing that the building was going to be bombed was

   addressed, but that's been a matter of public record for many,

   many months.  You may have heard the allegation that ATF agents

   were not present in the building, and of course the ATF issued

   a press release soon after the building to detail that there

   were ATF employees in the building, and that's been reiterated

   in one of our recent responses.

            So to the extent that some people left the meeting and

   made comments indicating that we were laying out the evidence,

   it is simply incorrect; and it's for that reason that I regret

   that there wasn't someone there that could have recorded the

   meeting and I think thereby satisfied you that we're not



                                                                           506



   violating the Court's protective order.  We're being cautious

   in our conversations with the victims.  In fact, we explained

   the protective order to the victims and explained for that

   reason we wanted them not to talk about matters to the press,

   that we wouldn't talk about matters to the press.

            We obviously can't control everyone.  And I don't

   think it would be appropriate for your Honor to enter an order

   that would -- might poorly define who is covered by it.  But in

   our meetings with the victims, which I trust you're not going

   to prevent, we will continue to advise them not to make

   comments that might in any way prejudice these defendants.

            There have been exceptions, no doubt, but I think for

   the most part, the victims of this crime have demonstrated

   remarkable strength and maturity, and I'm confident they'll

   continue to do so.

            THE COURT:  Well, did you say wacky theories of the

   defense?

            MR. HARTZLER:  Your Honor, I said -- no, no.  I said

   we had laid to rest some of the wacky theories.  I wasn't

   referring -- I think the context -- I don't recall exactly.

   That's why I called Mr. Jones to apologize to him to say that

   if it in any way demeaned theories of the defenses, that was

   not the point.  The point is there has been a theory -- I don't

   believe it's the defense theory -- that the Government bombed

   its own building.  But it was really the theory based on fact



                                                                           507



   that ATF had some forewarning and the agents weren't there,

   which has been addressed in open court.

            THE COURT:  Was there some kind of record kept of who

   attended?

            MR. HARTZLER:  I believe there was certainly an RSVP

   card that came in and we had name tags made for the victims, so

   I'm confident that we could probably come up with a list

   probably from those cards or otherwise.

            THE COURT:  Now, I don't want to necessarily get

   through this motion, get some disclosing the names and

   addresses of all of the victims, the data base issue, which is

   going to be briefed.  But you have in some papers here put on a

   number of the possible victim/witnesses who may testify to

   victim impact if that becomes relevant.  And the list --

   instead of producing the list in its entirety, as Mr. Woods has

   moved, you can check the list to see if any of those people

   were in attendance.

            MR. HARTZLER:  Certainly.

            MR. WOODS:  It can be produced under seal.  We're not

   concerned with any --

            THE COURT:  I'm just going to require that the

   Government keep the record it has of who attended and be

   prepared to identify whether any persons who are then

   identified as victim/witnesses were at this or these meetings.

            MR. HARTZLER:  Certainly.



                                                                           508



            MR. WOODS:  Thank you.

            THE COURT:  Then with respect to the motion made on

   behalf of Mr. McVeigh to put some kind of restriction on

   comments by the victims, I'm not going to do that.  I think

   they have First Amendment interests here that are somewhat

   different from what a lawyer must do as an officer of the

   court, of course.  And I have some sympathy for the problem

   that the Department of Justice lawyers have in attempting to

   comply with the mandate of the 1990 statute requiring them to

   do certain things for victims and their obligations as

   prosecutors in the courtroom.

            My suggestion to you is -- and, you know, these

   private meetings as such, that's a matter of discretion as to

   whether the people who are actually trying the case do that or

   the victims assistance people do that or whatever -- but I

   must, I think, say that when you make observations to these

   people, you can't consider them to be private.

            I'm not going to require them to withhold, you know,

   comment on it.  And I think you have to therefore -- within the

   language of my memorandum opinion and order which I asked

   Mr. Woods to remind us of, you must consider that those

   conversations in groups like that will have a substantial

   probability of being publicly disseminated, and therefore the

   order applies to what you tell them.

            MR. HARTZLER:  Of course.



                                                                           509



            THE COURT:  And therefore you shouldn't be discussing

   the evidence or except in the most general of terms as you

   would if you walk out here and talk to the press.  So please

   follow that admonition.

            MR. HARTZLER:  We will.

            THE COURT:  All right.  And with respect to Ms.

   Wilkinson's, I don't know this comment, but I suppose that's

   not inconsistent with the notice of intention to seek the death

   penalty.

            MS. WILKINSON:  But I will we careful with my remarks,

   nevertheless, your Honor.

            THE COURT:  All right.  Do we have any other matters?

            MR. JONES:  I don't believe we have any other matters

   publicly, but I think we are prepared now to meet with the

   Court.  And the Court may at the conclusion decide if we may or

   may not need to come in for five or ten minutes.

            THE COURT:  All right.  Well, do you want to do that

   immediately, do you want to break first, what do you want to

   do?  You see how amenable I am when I have sensed a certain

   spirit of cooperation.

            MR. JONES:  Well, you might jeopardize it, though,

   with the breaks.

            THE COURT:  I'm at your pleasure.  If you want to

   retire to chambers immediately, we should do so.

            MR. JONES:  We should probably perhaps take a short



                                                                           510



   break.

            THE COURT:  All right, 20 minutes.

            MR. JONES:  How long did you say?

            THE COURT:  20.  We'll be in recess in open court.  I

   don't know whether we'll return to open court.  I guess it

   depends upon this.  And I'm sure those who are here understand

   the need for us to try to continue this spirit of cooperation

   in private.

            Court's in recess.

       (Recess at 11:11 a.m.)

                          *   *   *   *   *

                       REPORTER'S CERTIFICATE

       I certify that the foregoing is a correct transcript from

   the record of proceedings in the above-entitled matter.  Dated

   at Denver, Colorado, this 15th day of November, 1996.



                                    _______________________________
                                                         Kara Spitler

</PRE>
