20   At counsel table are Reid Neureiter, Adam Thurschwell and



21   Ronald Woods.



22            THE COURT:  Thank you.



23            MR. TIGAR:  If your Honor please, pursuant to a



24   stipulation with the Government, the witnesses we intend to



25   tender to the Court are present in the court.  I wanted to make







                                                                 4





1   sure that your Honor had no objection to that practice.  They



2   are expert witnesses, and we thought it would move things along



3   more quickly if they were here in court.



4            THE COURT:  I'm in agreement with that.  So that's



5   acceptable.



6            And we will, because there are witnesses involved,



7   proceed first with the defendants' motions for severance for



8   prejudicial joinder under -- or prejudice under Rule 14.  And



9   Mr. Tigar, are you going to proceed first on that?



10            MR. TIGAR:  Yes, your Honor.  We call Bryan Stevenson.



11            THE COURT:  Mr. Kelley, why are you standing up?



12            MR. TIGAR:  I'm sorry.



13            MR. KELLEY:  I apologize to Mr. Tigar.



14            Your Honor, I'm standing up to ask to be excused until



15   the Court gets to the matter on which the Court has indicated



16   it would hear the media.



17            THE COURT:  Yes.  I -- you're speaking now to which



18   motion by the media?  The unsealing of parts of the record



19   involving the motions for severance?



20            MR. KELLEY:  Yes, sir.  To my understanding, that's



21   the only matter on which the Court is now hearing from the



22   media.



23            THE COURT:  Yes.  On the other matter which will be



24   heard later, you've got my order, I assume, with respect to the



25   submission of amici brief?







                                            5







1            MR. KELLEY:  I do.



2            THE COURT:  Yes.  Well, stay in touch.  We may reach



3   that later today.



4            MR. KELLEY:  I'll be available.



5            THE COURT:  All right.  You're excused then.



6            Go ahead, Mr. Tigar.  I missed your statement about



7   who the witness is.



8            MR. TIGAR:  I'm sorry.  We call Bryan Stevenson.



9            THE COURT:  All right.  If you'll come forward and be



10   sworn, sir.



11            THE COURTROOM DEPUTY:  Raise your right hand.



12       (Bryan Stevenson was sworn by affirmation.)



13            THE COURTROOM DEPUTY:  Please have a seat.



14            Please state your full name for the record and spell



15   your last name.



16            THE WITNESS:  It's Bryan, B-R-Y-A-N, Stevenson,



17   S-T-E-V-E-N-S-O-N.



18                         DIRECT EXAMINATION



19   BY MR. TIGAR:



20   Q.  What do you do for work, Mr. Stevenson?



21   A.  I'm an attorney.



22   Q.  Where did you go to law school, sir?



23   A.  I graduated from Harvard Law School.



24   Q.  In what year?



25   A.  1985.







                                            6



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   Q.  After graduating from Harvard Law School, what kind of work



2   did you do and where?



3   A.  I joined a nonprofit organization in Atlanta, Georgia, now



4   called the Southern Center for Human Rights, and represented



5   death row prisoners and capital defendants in the Deep South.



6   Q.  After you left the Southern Center for Human Rights in



7   Atlanta, what job did you have?



8   A.  I was at the Southern Center in Atlanta for four years, and



9   then I went to Montgomery, Alabama, where I became the director



10   of the Alabama Capital Representation Resource Center.



11   Q.  After the Resource Center closed -- was that 1995 --



12   A.  Yes.



13   Q.  -- what have you been doing?



14   A.  We created a new project called the Equal Justice



15   Initiative of Alabama; and I'm currently the director of that



16   organization, also an organization providing representation to



17   death row prisoners and capital defendants.



18   Q.  How many capital cases have you tried to verdict, sir?



19   A.  At the trial level, I've been involved in nine cases to



20   termination.



21   Q.  And in appellate and post-conviction review, how many cases



22   have you been involved in as counsel?



23   A.  I don't have an exact number, but it's four or five dozen.



24   Q.  And in connection with your work in appellate cases, do you



25   have a practice of interviewing jurors?







                                            7



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   A.  Certainly, in our practice, in post-conviction work -- that



2   is, in state and federal collateral challenges -- we make it a



3   practice to interview jurors in every case.  I have four other



4   lawyers working with me.  We've handled 30 or 40 of those cases



5   in the last five years, so we've interviewed jurors in each of



6   those cases.



7            MR. TIGAR:  Your Honor, we're tendering Mr. Stevenson



8   as an expert on the problems of case management in capital



9   cases.



10            THE COURT:  Any questions or objection?



11            MR. RYAN:  We have no objection to his qualification



12   in that area.  I didn't realize that was what the subject of



13   this hearing was about.  It's a question of whether there



14   should be a severance or not.  I haven't heard anything from



15   this witness that would indicate to me that he's an expert in



16   matters of joinder or severance, either one.



17            THE COURT:  Well, I don't know who is, except for me.



18            MR. TIGAR:  I think I'm looking at the expert that I'm



19   trying to speak to most persuasively, your Honor.



20            THE COURT:  Well, you may proceed.



21            MR. TIGAR:  I want --



22   BY MR. TIGAR:



23   Q.  Well, let me get to it, then.  Mr. Stevenson, do you think



24   that it is possible in a highly publicized case involving



25   allegations of an extremely aggravated crime in which the claim







                                            8



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   is made that the defendants have differing kinds of involvement



2   that the defendants can receive a fair trial when the



3   Government is seeking the death penalty as to both?



4   A.  No.  I think it's problematic in any capital case; and for



5   me, the issue is driven by the unique nature of a capital



6   trial.  I think it's problematic in any case.



7            I think in a highly aggravated case where there is a



8   great deal of pretrial publicity, it becomes impossible; and



9   that deals primarily with the challenge that defense lawyers



10   have in a capital trial to get the jury focused on the



11   defendant, the character of the defendant.  The penalty phase



12   of a capital trial is not just about the circumstances of the



13   crime, where there is some common evidence; but it's also about



14   the character of this defendant, getting the jury focused on



15   whether this particular defendant's life has purpose, has



16   value, even accepting that they were involved in a highly



17   aggravated crime.



18            This challenge, which I think all defense lawyers face



19   in a penalty phase, of trying to get the jury to understand



20   that even though this person may be guilty of a capital crime,



21   there is still some redemptive potential here, there is still



22   some hope here -- it's very difficult.  And when that gets



23   intertwined with somebody else's story and you have to tell the



24   story to get the jury to appreciate that -- when it gets



25   intertwined with somebody else's story, I think it's very







                                            9



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   difficult to provide that defendant with a fair consideration



2   of his or her unique circumstances toward making a judgment



3   about life or death.



4   Q.  Well, I want to start, then, sir -- if we start with the



5   penalty phase or the capital nature of the trial as a given --



6   and let us take as a given that we have jury sentencing under a



7   weighing statute, which -- you've had experience with those



8   kind of situations?



9   A.  That's correct.



10   Q.  Let's look at the phases of the case and talk about some of



11   those practical difficulties.  What are the difficulties that



12   would arise in voir dire?



13   A.  Well, trying a capital case is like trying two cases



14   simultaneously.  And until you've been in the situation of



15   having to think about your mitigation and penalty phase defense



16   at the same time of your guilt phase defense, it's kind of hard



17   to kind of see this stuff.



18            But it starts in voir dire.  In a capital case, there



19   will be death qualification; that is, you'll be engaged in voir 



20   dire where you're asking prospective jurors about their



21   opinions related to the death penalty.  Under federal law, if



22   the juror has a moral or religious opposition to the death



23   penalty and can't consider that, that juror is subject to



24   excusal for cause.



25            The defense lawyer's obligation in this area is not







                                            10



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   only to simply inquire about death qualification but also life



2   qualification; that is Morgan vs. Illinois and the Supreme



3   Court cases hold that a juror cannot serve on a capital trial



4   unless that juror is prepared to also consider a sentence of



5   life imprisonment.  There are a lot of people who believe in an



6   eye for an eye; and their view is if you kill somebody, you



7   must die.  Well, that kind of person under Morgan is not



8   qualified to serve.



9            Talking to the jurors about their ability to even



10   accept that somebody might be guilty of the crime charged but



11   still be able to consider a sentence of life is difficult; and



12   you want to sensitize them to the potential mitigation



13   evidence.  You want to sensitize them to the anticipated story



14   that you're going to tell about your client; and that's very



15   difficult in any case.  It's particularly difficult when your



16   story is again being undermined or intertwined with somebody



17   else's story, and your ability to decide whether a prospective



18   juror can actually respond to the mitigation you expect to



19   present is again very much threatened by a joint trial.



20   Q.  Now, let's move into the presentation of evidence in the



21   guilt phase.  In the guilt phase, is a capital trial different



22   from a trial in which the Government is not seeking the death



23   penalty?  And if so, can you tell us based on your experience



24   how?



25   A.  It is different in that your guilt phase presentation has







                                            11



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   to be aware of the possibility that there could be a penalty



2   phase.  And therefore, what we've learned in our juror



3   interviews in post-conviction work is that jurors are very



4   sensitive about consistent theories.  They resent defendants



5   coming in on an alibi defense and then saying well, we lied to



6   you at the guilt phase, but now let us tell you what really



7   happened at the penalty phase.  And a defense has to work



8   through these very difficult strategic questions about how to



9   present the case in a way where there is still some credibility



10   left at the penalty phase.



11            And so the presentation of the case at the guilt phase



12   has to keep in mind that there is a chance that your verdict --



13   that your judgment is not going to be what you want and that



14   you're still going to have to get these jurors to accept you



15   and believe you when you say my client's life still has some



16   purpose, my client is more than the worst thing he has done;



17   and getting them to understand and go with you when you start



18   talking about how you need them to accept this idea that each



19   of us is more than the worst thing you've ever done:  If you



20   tell a lie, you're not just a liar; if you steal something



21   you're not just a thief; if you kill somebody, you're not just



22   a killer, and we want to talk to you about how my client is



23   more than just a killer.  We want to focus on that before you



24   decide whether their life is worth taking or worth saving.



25            That whole credibility process, that whole strategic







                                            12



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   approach to capital litigation, has to start in the guilt



2   phase.



3   Q.  Is there a difference between a capital trial and a non-



4   capital trial with respect to proposed lesser included



5   offenses -- and I'm looking now and asking you hypothetically,



6   because we're not to get into the facts that are under seal --



7   a case in which the alleged involvement of the defendants is



8   very different?



9   A.  Yes.  Absolutely.  The most strangely appealing defense for



10   many capital defendants involves getting the jury focused on a



11   lesser included theory.  I mean, the whole case law,



12   particularly in my jurisdiction of Alabama, has really emerged



13   to protect this critical function.  Beck vs. Alabama, the case



14   that came out of our state when jurors were precluded from



15   considering lesser included offenses, was such a setback for



16   defense lawyers because they did not have the option of getting



17   jurors focused on some degree of culpability but not the degree



18   that would warrant moving the case into a phase where the



19   defendant -- where the jury would be asked to take the



20   defendant's life.



21            So absolutely, it's a very common defense, it's a very



22   important option for jurors to have in a capital case,



23   particularly where there are co-defendants and disputes about



24   the degree of culpability.



25   Q.  In the Deep South where you have spent your working life,







                                            13



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   is there a working hypothesis about whether capital cases



2   should be tried separately or jointly?



3   A.  Oh, absolutely.



4   Q.  What is that working hypothesis?



5   A.  That hypothesis is that capital cases are tried separately.



6   We have 150 people on death row in my state of Alabama, only



7   two of whom were tried in a joint trial.  They were



8   co-defendants in the same trial.  They did not object to the



9   state's effort to consolidate the trial.



10            I consult on cases all across the Deep South:



11   Mississippi, Georgia, Florida.



12   Q.  How many people on death row in Mississippi?



13   A.  50.  110 in Georgia.  It is absolutely the exception and



14   not the norm that cases would be tried jointly.  In fact, I've



15   never worked -- consulted with lawyers who were forced to take



16   a case in a consolidated way because of precisely these kinds



17   of issues.



18   Q.  Now, moving on to the problems that would arise in the



19   penalty phase of a joint trial, again, in our hypothetically



20   highly publicized, alleged-aggravated-crime, alleged-different-



21   involvement case, what barriers do you see in your experience



22   to a fair jury consideration in a jury sentencing weighing



23   statute jurisdiction such as the federal courts?



24   A.  Well, again, the penalty phase will be about reinforcing



25   for the jury their obligation to consider the character of the







                                            14



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   offender, the life of the offender.



2            We accept that the circumstances of the offense are



3   aggravated, or we wouldn't be at the penalty phase in the first



4   place.  Now the law requires the jurors to do something very



5   difficult, which is to nonetheless consider that despite that



6   aggravated crime, this person could be properly sentenced to



7   life.



8            Well, to get jurors to do that, you really do have to



9   talk to the jurors about this person's life.  It's a life



10   story.  It's a history.



11            You have to be willing to talk in very personal and



12   specific terms about the unique circumstances of this



13   particular defendant so that the jury can consider the fact



14   that despite this aggravated crime, death is not the



15   appropriate punishment.



16            When you're telling that story, it's difficult enough



17   because again, I think the presumption is that we think about



18   punishment in relation to crime, in relation to conduct, not in



19   relation to the individuals at question.  The law gives us the



20   opportunity to force jurors to consider the individual in



21   question, but it's a difficult challenge.



22            When that challenge is confused and compromised and



23   undermined by somebody else's story, I think it becomes very



24   difficult for a jury to do the kind of weighing of mitigating



25   circumstances and aggravating circumstances that the law







                                            15



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   compels.



2   Q.  Would the problem be more difficult when the mitigators



3   that are presented and the aggravators that are presented are



4   different as to the two or more defendants in a joint



5   proceeding?



6   A.  Absolutely.  Absolutely.  The -- I think there is a -- what



7   we've experienced in talking to jurors in post-conviction work



8   is a very strong sentiment that there should be consistency



9   among punishment for the same kind of crime; that is, jurors



10   will say we felt like if one did it, the -- both did it, then



11   both should be sentenced similarly.



12            It reflects, in my view, a misunderstanding about the



13   importance of giving individualized sentencing attention to



14   each offender, but it's a very powerful instinct on the part of



15   jurors.  It seems somehow inequitable or unfair to have



16   different sentences for the same conduct.  But that's what the



17   law compels.



18            So yes, it becomes very difficult when the aggravators



19   and the mitigators are different as to particular defendants.



20   It's also very, very difficult in cases involving a great deal



21   of pretrial publicity.  There tends to be sort of a presumption



22   that whoever committed this crime deserves the death penalty.



23   And the more publicized the crime and the more common that



24   presumption, the more widespread that presumption, I think the



25   more difficult it is for jurors to kind of really focus on the







                                            16



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   fact that they alone, the 12 people in that box, are going to



2   be the only people to hear this unique life story, this unique



3   life history about this person, and be forced to consider the



4   character of this offender and the circumstances of this



5   individual before coming to sentencing judgment.



6            It's a very difficult and I think not widely



7   understood challenge that it's hard to get jurors focused and I



8   think doubly hard when two stories are going at once.



9   Q.  In your interviews with jurors in the dozens of cases in



10   which you have talked to them, is there a difference, a broad



11   gauge difference between the focus of jurors who voted for life



12   and the focus of jurors who voted for death?



13   A.  Oh, yes.  I mean, invariably, those jurors who vote for



14   life are jurors who can tell you about the defendant in



15   personal terms, who can talk about circumstances of that



16   defendant's life, who can tell you -- who remember the issues



17   around mental health evidence or emotional evidence, who could



18   talk about the defendant's history of abuse, if that's a part



19   of the case, who could talk about the pressures that defendant



20   was dealing with at the time of the crime.



21            It's interesting because they've remembered those



22   things quite well, and those are the things they talk to you



23   about when you go and interview them.



24            Jurors who come back with death sentences invariably



25   talk about the crime.  They talk about how aggravated the crime







                                            17



    Bryan Stevenson - Direct



1   was, the circumstances of the crime, and usually are very



2   reluctant to say much about the defendant, usually because they



3   don't remember very much.  They haven't been allowed to focus



4   very much on those defendants.  And those are the differences



5   you see between jurors who voted for life and voted for death.



6            MR. TIGAR:  Thank you, very much, Mr. Stevenson.



7            THE COURT:  Mr. Ryan?



