16   A.  That's correct.



17   Q.  Those kinds of problems.



18   A.  It's a range of problems; but inadequate preparation in



19   capital cases in the Deep South is a very big problem that we



20   speak to a great deal.



21   Q.  Now, none of these problems which you have testified to in



22   the past exist in this case, do they?



23   A.  No.  I would presume that these defendants will get very



24   good representation; but I would not frankly suggest that the



25   fairness problems that we encounter in our cases in the Deep







                                            20



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   South are any different here.  Any time you have basically a



2   very publicized crime where there is a great deal of public



3   hostility toward the defendants, there is the risk that an



4   effort will be made to minimize the risk of acquittal or a



5   sentence less than death.  And that's the circumstance that



6   gives rise to unfairness creeping into these proceedings.



7   Q.  But that wasn't my question.  My question was:  Do any of



8   the problems that you have testified to about and in which you



9   have been so vocal about and which you are knowledgeable about



10   that we've just gone over -- none of those exist in this case,



11   do they?  We don't have elected judges here.  We don't have



12   black defendants and white victims.  We don't have drunk -- or



13   don't anticipate that either Mr. Jones or Mr. Tigar or their



14   colleagues will be drunk in court.  They've certainly shown



15   every indication of preparedness at every step of these



16   proceedings, as much as it pains me to compliment them.  Those



17   kinds of problems which you have testified about -- they don't



18   exist here.



19   A.  That's right, Mr. Ryan.  And it's certainly true that many



20   of the problems that I testify about that I confront in my



21   cases are not existing here:  Quality of counsel, perhaps some



22   of the race issues, some of those other issues.  But we also



23   talk about in our cases fairness, making sure that the



24   procedures are not pushed by public desires for a particular



25   judgment, making sure the procedures do not undermine the







                                            21



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   defendant's right to present his or her story free from



2   presumption or bias.



3            I think the risk of unfairness is no different,



4   frankly -- it's a different kind of problem, but it's the same



5   issue, which is making sure that we recognize that defendants



6   are presumed innocent and that they have a fair chance to tell



7   their story in the face of these kinds of aggravated charges.



8   Q.  Do you have any doubt that this court will not try in every



9   way to protect these rights that you're concerned about?



10   A.  Oh, no.  I have great confidence in the Court.  The very



11   nature of this proceeding speaks I think well of the Court's



12   willingness to consider carefully the importance of protecting



13   individual rights in these trials.



14   Q.  And you realize that we are here on the defense motions to



15   sever --



16   A.  I'm sorry.



