25   these cases involve joint trial where there were joined







                                            23



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   defendants?



2   A.  No.  As I said, that's extremely rare in the Deep South.



3   Q.  Have you ever tried any kind of a case, whether it be



4   capital or otherwise, in which there were joined defendants?



5   A.  At the trial level, no.



6   Q.  Is it fair to say, then, that you really have limited or no



7   trial experience with the types of issues that frequently arise



8   in joint criminal trials, such as Bruton issues and



9   antagonistic defenses?



10   A.  Well, I guess it really depends on what you think are the



11   relevant issues.  We obviously deal with claims of co-defendant



12   testimony in separate trials in the same way that you deal with



13   them in a joint trial; but I have not tried at the trial level



14   a consolidated case with multiple defendants.



15   Q.  I am curious about your testimony -- maybe I didn't



16   understand it correctly -- that you indicated that you felt a



17   jury in a joint trial based on your conversations with jurors,



18   I thought, presumed that the joined defendants would receive



19   the same punishment.  Did I understand your testimony



20   correctly?



21   A.  I guess what I was trying to say is that there is a general



22   presumption which defense lawyer must combat and overcome that



23   many people have -- and jurors are people -- that punishment



24   should be consistent, should be the same, without reference to



25   the fact that Eighth Amendment law, at least in death penalty







                                            24



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   cases, allows a defendant to talk about his or her situation,



2   accepting involvement in a crime that oftentimes is difficult



3   for jurors to get to.



4   Q.  So did I misunderstand that you based that statement of



5   yours on conversations with jurors?



6   A.  Yes.  I mean that's -- that -- I base that on conversations



7   with jurors we've interviewed in post-conviction proceedings



8   but with prospective jurors in voir dire, people who deal with



9   these issues in a variety of contexts.  It's not a difficult



10   sentiment to get out of folks when you talk to them.



11   Q.  But none of these people have ever been faced with the task



12   of assessing capital punishment or sentencing in a joint trial?



13   A.  No.  None of the jurors that we have interviewed were



14   actually jurors in a consolidated trial.  That's correct.



15   Again, it's a very rare event in our jurisdiction.



16   Q.  And as I understand, your primary focus of your testimony



17   is your concern about the jurors giving the Supreme Court's



18   required individualized consideration to joined defendants.



19   A.  Well, I guess it's more than that.  I think it's the



20   jurors' ability to hear the story and then give adequate



21   consideration to that story as it relates to one particular



22   defendant; but it's also the defendant's opportunity to tell



23   that story fairly, to tell that story effectively.  I think



24   it's difficult to tell the story in the best of circumstances



25   when the whole 12 jurors are focused on you.  I think it







                                            25



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   becomes even more difficult when you don't even get that kind



2   of undivided attention and focus and your story is mixed in



3   with somebody else's, the presumption being that a lot of



4   people think you can just rotely apply aggravating



5   circumstances and mitigating circumstances and come to a



6   judgment by going down some kind of queue.



7            I think effective defense lawyers in this area reject



8   that approach and get jurors to try to appreciate that this is



9   about their client, their client's life, their client's



10   history, their client's background, their client's



11   circumstances, the value of that life, the purpose of that



12   life; and that's a very difficult thing to do in any proceeding



13   but I think doubly difficult in a proceeding where it's not



14   about your client's life.



15   Q.  And the better the defense counsel is, the better



16   opportunity for that individualized consideration?



17   A.  No question.



18   Q.  And I take it you know Michael Tigar?



19   A.  Yes.



20   Q.  Did you know him prior to today or yesterday?



21   A.  Not really.  We met -- I know of him.  We've been on the



22   circuit together from time to time.



23   Q.  What does it mean to be on the circuit?



24   A.  I've lectured at training programs where he's also



25   lectured.







