                                            27



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   Q.  And I think -- I take it you would say it speaks very well



2   for the federal system that federal courts have appointed



3   counsel of this quality to represent these two co-defendants?



4   A.  Yes.



5   Q.  Let me back up a second, a moment, to something you said



6   earlier about this feeling that jurors were going to give the



7   same punishment in every case.



8            Have you looked at any actual cases where joint



9   defendants were tried to see what the outcome was?



10   A.  Again, the only joint case we've had in the jurisdiction



11   where I've worked, the defendants were convicted and sentenced



12   to death.



13   Q.  Are you familiar with Gibson vs. State, 555 S.2d 784, 1984,



14   an Alabama case?



15   A.  Not a death case.



16   Q.  One defendant got life and one got less?



17   A.  That's correct.



18   Q.  Joint capital case?



19   A.  Pardon me?



20   Q.  Joint capital case?



21   A.  It did not advance to the penalty phase of a capital



22   proceeding, though.  Neither defendant advanced to the penalty



23   phase of a capital case.



24   Q.  Have you looked at any of the federal cases that have gone



25   to trial to see whether or not there was a difference in







                                            28



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   whether joined defendants were more likely to get the death



2   penalty than life?



3   A.  Not carefully, no.  I'm aware that there have been people



4   who have been sentenced to life in joint proceedings and people



5   who have been sentenced to death in joint proceedings.  That



6   doesn't surprise me.



7   Q.  It does run contra to what you said, though, about a jury



8   wanting to impose identical punishments?



9   A.  No.  I think frankly it depends on the case.  I think in



10   less aggravated cases, you can overcome the problems inherent



11   in a joint trial.  In cases where the defenses are not



12   dissimilar, where both defendants are together and are using



13   the same alibi defense and the same alibi witnesses and whole



14   focus of the trial is about their noninvolvement or some degree



15   of involvement that is equally nonculpable as a capital crime,



16   I think these barriers and burdens can be overcome.  I don't



17   think it's impossible in every case.



18            I think in aggravated cases, though, like this and in



19   cases where the need to make the story at the penalty phase is



20   going to be even more personal because of the highly aggravated



21   nature, it becomes extremely difficult.



22   Q.  Are you aware that the prosecution contends that



23   Mr. McVeigh was the person who delivered the bomb to the Murrah



