25   time.  That shouldn't be a fact that is confusing to a jury,







                                            30



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   should it?



2   A.  I think it really depends on how -- what the Government's



3   theory is as to why both defendants are equally guilty of the



4   same crime.  I mean I think those facts certainly speak to



5   different approaches; but I don't know that they help the jury



6   necessarily come to different conclusions or to -- about the



7   verdict.



8   Q.  We don't think they do.  My question is:  Do you think that



9   the jury will have any difficulty understanding the differences



10   in the roles between these two defendants on April 19, 1995?



11   A.  In a joint trial?



12   Q.  Yes.



13   A.  I think that in a case where there are different defenses,



14   different theories of defense, disputes among the defendants



15   about the evidence and about their culpability, the burden on



16   the jury grows greater; that is, if both defendants were



17   alleging precisely the same defense, alibi or whatever, then I



18   think it would be less of an issue for the jury.



19            But again, driving -- I mean just so you're clear



20   about my perspective on this, my perspective on this is really



21   driven from the harder question of the penalty phase and the



22   need to develop that in the guilt phase.



23   Q.  All right.  Well, let's talk about that penalty phase for



24   just a brief second.



25   A.  Sure.







                                            31



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   Q.  Do you feel that Mr. Tigar is incapable of demonstrating to



2   the jury the differences between his client and Mr. Jones'



3   client, Mr. McVeigh?



4   A.  I think in a case like this, it would be unfair for



5   Mr. Tigar or the best lawyer in the world to try to get the



6   jury to consider a sentence less than death without an



7   opportunity to talk exclusively about your defendant and the



8   unique circumstances of that defendant as it relates to an



9   appropriate punishment; in this case, arguably less than death.



10   Q.  That was not my question.  The question was:  Do you think



11   Mr. Tigar is incapable of distinguishing his client in the



12   penalty phase from Mr. McVeigh in terms of what mitigating



13   factors apply to Mr. Nichols?



14   A.  I think frankly yes, it would be unfair for any lawyer to



15   have to make that presentation in a joint trial with the



16   charges as aggravated as they are in this case, with the



17   pretrial publicity as it is in this case.  I don't think it's



18   about Mr. Tigar.  I think it's about the nature of the



19   proceeding.  I wouldn't want to be in that situation.  I



20   wouldn't presume to put him or anyone else in that situation.



21   Q.  You don't think that he can, through charts and through



22   testimony of witnesses, talk exclusively about Mr. Nichols?



23   A.  Oh, I have no doubt that he will do those things.



24   Q.  Yes?



25   A.  He will make as good a presentation as he possibly can on







                                            32



    Bryan Stevenson - Cross



1   behalf of Mr. Nichols about his life, his circumstances, etc.



2            The problem won't be, in my opinion, his ability to



3   make the presentation.  It will be the nature of the process.



4   It will be getting the jury focused, if you will, on the unique



5   circumstances of his client and coming to a judgment about his



6   client's life, not anybody else's life, his client.



7   Q.  And based on your practical experiences since you have none



8   in joint trials, you have no reason to think that that will not



9   be successful?



10   A.  Well, I guess my experience is really in generally trying



11   to get jurors to appreciate the need for an individualized



12   sentencing.  It's a problem in any case.  I think it's a double



13   problem in a case that's highly aggravated.  I think if you



14   create this kind of procedural obstacle to making that



15   presentation fairly, you're courting the kind of unfairness



16   that I guess, as you talked about my record in the past, I



17   would be subject to criticize.



18            MR. RYAN:  No further questions.



19            THE COURT:  Any redirect?



20                        REDIRECT EXAMINATION



21   BY MR. TIGAR:



22   Q.  Mr. Stevenson, one last question to clarify it:  Are the



23   problems made more difficult, the problems of individualized



24   consideration, when not only the Government but the



25   co-defendant is attempting to undercut the position that one







                                            33



   Bryan Stevenson - Redirect



1   defense counsel is presenting?



2   A.  Oh, absolutely.  It's almost, in some ways, having to deal



3   with three theories, which I think does add to the burden of



4   the defendant, does make it even more difficult to sensitize



5   the jury to the particular story you're trying to tell with



6   relation to mitigation; and I think given that the crime has



7   some commonality as to both defendants, it adds to the burden



8   of getting the jury to accept, look, we understand that there



9   are common facts about this crime that are related to both



10   defendants, but we now need you to understand that the judgment



11   as to penalty is unique to this individual.  It's about this



12   individual's life and history and circumstances.



13            Yes, I think it's complicated when you have a



14   co-defendant also introducing a theory.  That adds to, frankly,



15   the problems of getting the jury focused.



16            MR. TIGAR:  Thank you very much.



