11   Q.  Judge, where do you live now?



12   A.  In Austin, Texas.



13   Q.  Where did you grow up and go to school?



14   A.  Basically, in Dallas.



15   Q.  Give the Court a brief summary of your educational



16   background.



17   A.  I went to undergraduate school at Southern Methodist



18   University in Dallas and also at the University of Texas at



19   Arlington.  I received a B.A. degree in political science in



20   1966 from the University of Texas at Arlington.  I went to law



21   school at Southern Methodist University, where I received a



22   J.D. degree in 1969.



23            In 1988, I enrolled in an LLM program at the



24   University of Virginia and received an LLM of judicial process



25   from the University of Virginia in 1990.







                                            35



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   Q.  Would you give the Court the background of your



2   professional experience after law school at SMU?



3   A.  After law school, I started as a young prosecutor in



4   Houston in the grand jury section of the office and progressed



5   from there into the trial sections, the misdemeanor trial



6   section, the felony trial section and --



7   Q.  How many years did you work there in Harris County?



8   A.  Just about three years.



9   Q.  During those three years, which were pre-Furman, there were



10   a lot of murder cases that were capital murder cases.  Did you



11   sit as second chair on any capital murder cases during those



12   years?



13   A.  I sat as second chair on two or three capital murders, yes,



14   sir.



15   Q.  What did you next do after your three years at Harris



16   County district attorney's office?



17   A.  I then went and ran for county attorney of Hill County,



18   which is in Hillsboro, Texas, about, oh, 60 miles south of



19   Dallas, I suppose, and was elected to that post and served four



20   years in that post.



21   Q.  Would you relate to the Court what the jurisdiction of the



22   county attorney is under Texas law?



23   A.  It varies from county to county; but in that particular



24   county, it was to prosecute misdemeanors and also to handle



25   eminent domain and also to represent commissioners in court in







                                            36



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   all civil matters involving the county.



2   Q.  Did you have an occasion as the county attorney to try



3   capital cases?



4   A.  I did.  The district attorney had not ever tried one, and I



5   had been involved in several in Houston; and so when they came



6   up in Hill County, he asked me if I would take the lead.  And I



7   took the lead for that four years at a salary of $14,000 a year



8   as county attorney.  I took the lead in at least three or four



9   capital cases.



10   Q.  What years were those, sir?



11   A.  That would have been from 1973 -- January 1 of '73 to



12   December 31 of 1976.



13   Q.  During that period, Furman was decided, Texas revised its



14   capital murder statute.  Would you briefly just relate to the



15   Court how Texas narrowed its murder cases to conform with



16   Furman so that not every murder case was a capital murder case?



17   A.  Basically, Texas did two things.  One was to try to create



18   a substantive crime of capital murder; that is, a murder



19   committed in the course of committing some other offense, such



20   as robbery, burglary, kidnapping, something that would, in



21   essence, take a murder case, an ordinary murder case and



22   aggravate it to a capital murder.



23            The second thing that the legislature did was to



24   propose at the punishment phase of a capital murder trial that



25   certain special issues be submitted to the jury to answer and







                                            37



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   then depending upon the jury's answer to those questions would



2   depend on what the trial judge -- whether the trial judge would



3   sentence the defendant to life or to death.



4   Q.  After the four years as a county attorney occasionally



5   trying capital murder cases, what did you next do, sir?



6   A.  I then ran against the incumbent district attorney, whose



7   capital docket I was handling anyway, and defeated him and



8   began that particular job January 1 of 1977.



9   Q.  And while you were district attorney, did you have an



10   occasion to try any capital cases?



11   A.  I tried three or four, yes, sir.



12   Q.  Did you serve the full four-year term as district attorney?



13   A.  No, I did not.



14   Q.  Would you relate to the Court what you did before your



15   four-year term was up?



16   A.  I was offered a position by Mark White when he was elected



17   Attorney General in 1978 -- in the fall of 1978, to head up his



18   prosecutor's assistance division in Austin when he took office



19   January 1 of '79.  That would have been in the middle of my



20   term.



21            I accepted that position and resigned my position as



22   district attorney of Hill County.



23   Q.  Would you relate briefly to the Court what the nature of



24   your duties were heading up that prosecutor's assistance office



25   for the Attorney General as it relates to capital murder cases.







                                            38



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   A.  The prosecutor's assistance division was basically



2   comprised of lawyers who had a fair amount of trial experience;



3   and our mission essentially was to go out and help the smaller



4   offices in the state of Texas that didn't have the resources,



5   the manpower, the money from their county commissioners,



6   whatever, to try complicated cases, not just capital cases but



7   official misconduct cases, white collar crime, complex



8   narcotics trafficking cases, things of that nature.



9            But capital cases is one of the things that we focused



10   on because that's where the biggest need was, especially in



11   rural areas where there just weren't the resources.



12   Q.  How many capital cases did you personally try while you



13   were in that position?



14   A.  I believe I personally tried three.



15   Q.  Did you supervise other lawyers in your office who were



16   trying the capital cases?



17   A.  Right.  We had, I think, about eight lawyers total.



18   Q.  Approximately how many cases were you supervising -- murder



19   cases -- during your time in the prosecutor assistance --



20   A.  I would say probably a half a dozen at any given time.



21   Q.  Was there one person in your office that did the majority



22   of the capital murder cases?



23   A.  A lady named Linda Walden, yes.



24   Q.  And did you sit second with her on some of the cases?



25   A.  I sat second with her.  She was fairly experienced, at







                                            39



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   least insofar as the technical aspects of presenting evidence.



2   She was not as experienced in jury selection as I was; and so I



3   would sit with her to -- more to aid her with jury selection



4   than anything else.



5   Q.  Did she have any particular nickname within the office?



6   A.  "Homicide Hilda."



7   Q.  After serving in that office as prosecutor assistance for



8   the Attorney General, what did you next do, sir?



9   A.  I ran for the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals in 1982 and



10   was successful in defeating an incumbent in the Democratic



11   primary and took office January 1 of 1983 in that capacity.



12   Q.  Is that a statewide office?



13   A.  Yes.



14   Q.  Would you relate briefly to the Court what the jurisdiction



15   of the Court of Criminal Appeals is in Texas?



16   A.  The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals is kind of an unusual



17   animal.  I think only Texas and Oklahoma have, among the 50



18   states, courts of last resort that are set apart for criminal



19   cases.



20            The court as its jurisdiction now stands has



21   jurisdiction over all death penalty cases, has original



22   jurisdiction over all death penalty cases in which the death



23   penalty has been assessed.  If the death penalty has not been



24   assessed, the case is going to go to an intermediate court.



25            All non-death penalty cases go through first the 14







                                            40



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   intermediate courts of appeals in Texas in a direct appeal, and



2   then there is a discretionary review process similar to a writ



3   process in Federal Court to the Texas Court of Criminal



4   Appeals.



5            The Court of Criminal Appeals also has post-conviction



6   writ jurisdiction as well as mandamus prohibition, procedendo



7   jurisdiction.



8   Q.  It is the highest court of jurisdiction in Texas for



9   criminal cases?



10   A.  It is.



11   Q.  It is equal with the Texas Supreme Court?



12   A.  Well, there is debate about that.  It is an equal



13   institution, yes.



14   Q.  Yes, sir.  How many judges sit on that court?



15   A.  Nine.



16   Q.  How many years did you sit on that court, Judge?



17   A.  12 years.



18   Q.  During that 12-year period, how many death penalty cases



19   with a death penalty verdict did you personally review?



20   A.  Several hundred.  I couldn't tell you exactly.



21   Q.  In 1994 when the Republican sweep of Texas took place in a



22   general election, did you lose your position as a result of



23   that sweep?



24   A.  I did indeed.



25   Q.  What have you done since that period of January 1, '95?







                                            41



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   A.  I have sat as a visiting judge both on the trial bench and



2   the intermediate appellate bench and I also am adjunct



3   professor of law at Baylor Law School.



4   Q.  And during that period of time from January 1, '95, to



5   present, have you sat as the trial judge on capital murder



6   cases?



7   A.  I sat on two; one last year and one that commenced last



8   year and actually finished up January, February of this year.



9   Q.  Before I get to those two cases, let me go back to your



10   term on the Court of Criminal Appeals.



11            Did you have any official or unofficial position there



12   regarding death penalty issues?



13   A.  I did.  In later years, we were getting backlogged in our



14   death penalty cases, pretty seriously backlogged.  With Harris



15   County, which is Houston, trying scores and scores of them, our



16   death row population reached somewhere in excess of 380 and so



17   we had to do something.



18            We went to the legislature, we got an appropriation of



19   money to actually go out and hire four lawyers and train them



20   and have them work on nothing but capital cases until we could



21   get ourselves in a position that we could have some control



22   over our capital docket.  And basically, my responsibility was



23   to hire those people and to train them in the handling of



24   capital cases.



25   Q.  All right.  Judge, as a prosecutor, approximately how many







                                            42



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   cases did you try -- capital murder cases?



2   A.  Counting first and second chair, probably a dozen.



3   Q.  And then --



4   A.  A few more, maybe.



5   Q.  Then you sat for 12 years reviewing capital cases.



6   A.  Yes, sir.



7   Q.  And now as a trial judge, you have recently sat as the



8   trial judge on two capital murder cases; is that correct?



9   A.  Yes, sir.



10            MR. WOODS:  Your Honor, may it please the Court, we



11   would tender Judge Campbell as an expert in capital murder



12   cases.



13            MR. MACKEY:  No objection, Judge.



14            THE COURT:  All right.  Thank you, Mr. Mackey.



15   BY MR. WOODS:



16   Q.  Mr. Campbell, let me address these two recent cases; but



17   first, let me ask the question:  Is it the practice in the



18   state of Texas, especially in the larger counties and if not



19   the whole state -- is it the practice where you have multiple



20   defendants in a death penalty case -- is it the practice that



21   the prosecutors bring those separately, rather than jointly?



22   A.  Yes.



23   Q.  Is that a pretty much widespread practice, or just barely



24   51 percent of the cases?



25   A.  As far as I know, it's a widespread practice and has been







                                            43



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   for some time.



2   Q.  In the case starting in -- the one that you tried in Tyler



3   as a trial judge, were there multiple defendants accused of



4   committing the murder?



5   A.  Yes, there were three.



6   Q.  And were they tried jointly?



7   A.  No.



8   Q.  Did the district attorney attempt to try them jointly?



9   A.  I don't believe so.



10   Q.  Was it a crime where all participants participated equally?



11   A.  Pretty much, yes, it was.  It was -- it was unusual in that



12   situation that the participants -- the three defendants pretty



13   much all played the same role, not only in the aggravating



14   factor, which was kidnapping and robbery -- actually, two, but



15   also in the actual killing of the victim.  They each had a



16   weapon, they each were participating in the kidnapping, they



17   each participated in the robbery essentially equally and they



18   each attempted to -- two of them successfully -- to shoot the



19   victim at the same location at the same time; so essentially,



20   their participation in the guilt phase was almost identical.



21   Q.  Had the district attorney attempted to try those three



22   jointly and had a motion for severance been offered by the



23   defense, would you have granted the motion for severance?



24   A.  Yes, I would, but not on the basis of guilt/innocence



25   problems; more on the basis of punishment problems.







                                            44



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   Q.  Would you explain to the Court why you would have granted a



2   severance on that?



3   A.  There was a fairly vast difference --



4            MR. MACKEY:  I object to the hypothetical question.



5            THE COURT:  Overruled.  You may proceed.



6            THE WITNESS:  Thank you.



7            There was a fairly vast difference in the backgrounds



8   of the three individuals and also in their ages.  And when I



9   say "backgrounds," I'm really talking about family backgrounds



10   and work backgrounds and criminal history backgrounds and that



11   sort of thing.  There was a substantial difference in their



12   backgrounds, and that would have been the reason why I would



13   have -- would have granted a severance regardless of the



14   guilt/innocence phase of the trial.



15   BY MR. WOODS:



16   Q.  Following up on that being the reason why you would have



17   granted severance, why is it more fair, if that's the reason



18   that you're doing that, for an individual -- one individual at



19   a time to go before a punishing jury, a jury that's hearing the



20   punishment stage?



21   A.  Well, I'm afraid I'm going to sound like an echo to -- I



22   don't know if his name is Professor Johnson or Mr. Johnson



23   (sic).  In any event, the witness that testified before I did.



24            The individualized assessment concept that the Supreme



25   Court has written about in a number of cases, going back to







                                            45



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   Lockett vs. Ohio and Eddings vs. Oklahoma and continuing



2   through California vs. Brown and even Penry vs. Lynaugh -- the



3   individualized assessment, the need to address the personal



4   moral culpability of the defendant in order for a jury to give



5   a reasoned moral response not only to the crime but to the



6   situation of the defendant is what led me to this particular



7   belief.



8   Q.  Would the problem be compounded if you had two or more



9   people in a punishment stage who were each trying to convince



10   the jury that they were less culpable?



11   A.  I think so.  I think it is a problem because I think it's



12   kind of a situation where they're playing against each other,



13   more or less.  They're fighting against one another to put



14   themselves in the best light.



15            And it all depends really on how any of us, including



16   this judge here, interpret the concept of individualized



17   assessment for a defendant's personal moral culpability.



18            I wish I could tell you what the Supreme Court meant



19   by the term "personal moral culpability."  I really don't know;



20   but because they have treated death differently in their case



21   law, it seems like that is a major factor.  And that's



22   especially so when you've got a situation, as I had in Tyler,



23   where although the guilt/innocence evidence is virtually



24   identical on co-defendants, the punishment evidence is going to



25   be substantially different.







                                            46



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   Q.  You have seen examples where a defendant will put forth



2   mitigation or mitigating evidence concerning age or concerning



3   family background.  Have you seen incidents where that can work



4   both ways:  Age can be considered not only a mitigator but also



5   an aggravator?



6   A.  I've seen it work both ways with my colleagues on the Court



7   of Criminal Appeals as far as trying to decide what's



8   mitigating and what's not, what's mitigating, what's



9   aggravating.



10            Some people, for instance, feel that a 17-year-old



11   should be -- that the age of 17 should be considered a



12   mitigating factor simply because the person is young, he made a



13   mistake, they're of tender age and they shouldn't -- they



14   shouldn't have the same personal moral culpability, the words



15   used by the Supreme Court.



16            Other people feel just the opposite:  That a 17-year-



17   old is not capable of learning from his or her mistakes and



18   will probably go out and do something like this again, whereas



19   a person who is 35 or 40 or 45 years old is less likely to be a



20   problem to society in the future; so even though something that



21   is seemingly as simple as age is not so simple because personal



22   moral culpability is in the eyes of beholder, frankly.



23   Q.  What about another mitigator, such as a family background?



24   Have you seen that work both ways?



25   A.  I think that can work both ways.  If you have -- if you







                                            47



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   have a good family background, some people -- some jurors would



2   see that as a mitigating factor.  Others, especially in a state



3   as conservative as Texas, would see that as a reason -- as an



4   aggravating factor; that you had every opportunity, every



5   chance in the world, to make something out of yourself:  You



6   came from a good family and you go out and you do something



7   this heinous, they would consider it an aggravating factor



8   rather than a mitigating factor.



9            So yes, I think that it's a very real problem.



10   Q.  Could you foresee a difficulty if there are two defendants



11   in a punishment stage at one time where one defendant puts



12   forth a mitigator and the other defendant then would attack it



13   as not really a mitigator but an aggravator?



14   A.  Well, that's what I was talking about a while ago; that



15   essentially they end up playing against each other as to what's



16   mitigating and what's aggravating, and the whole thing gets



17   lost.  It's like breaking three eggs to make an omelet:  Once



18   you stir the eggs up with a whisk, it's awfully difficult then



19   to separate the yolk from the white.



20            And I think that's basically what can occur in a



21   situation like you just described.



22   Q.  Are you using that analogy as in the guilt or innocence



23   stage, where they're instructed on law of parties or aiding and



24   abetting and the conspiracy law and then when you get to the



25   punishment stage, they've got to be uninstructed as to that and







                                            48



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   instructed that you've got to be considering these people



2   individually?



3   A.  I think it can really occur at both stages.



4   Q.  Now, as a trial judge and also as a prosecutor, you've



5   observed trial judges issuing limiting instructions to juries



6   as to what to consider and what not to consider.  Do you feel



7   that limiting instructions can effectively control that issue



8   in a capital punishment hearing where we've got two or more



9   defendants?



10   A.  To a certain extent, it can.  I think juries -- it's like



11   during the course of a voir dire, a juror will tell you that



12   although he expects a defendant to testify that if he's



13   instructed that he can't consider that that he will not



14   consider that and he will be instructed about that during the



15   course of the trial.  And I think that it's fairly accurate to



16   say that jurors, for the most part, follow instructions that



17   judges give them.  If they didn't, we'd be in a real mess.



18            On the other hand, juries are human beings, like all



19   of us.  So when you tell them not to consider something, they



20   will try very hard.  In fact, they'll tell you during voir dire



21   that they will try very hard.  It's unusual to have a juror who



22   will actually say, I will unhesitatingly follow the law, if you



23   give it to me, because you're the judge and I'm not.



24            Human emotions generally take over in the jury room,



25   where none of us are allowed, nor should we be; and I think --







                                            49



   Charles Campbell - Direct



1   you know, the limiting instruction, I'm sure, has some effect.



2   How much effect, I really don't know.  I couldn't measure it



3   quantitatively.



4   Q.  Is there a strong presumption of jurors to believe that



5   birds of a feather flock together and that's very difficult to



6   dislodge?



7   A.  I think that's a problem that you fight any time that you



8   have multiple defendants, whether it be a capital case or a



9   non-capital case.



10   Q.  Is it more exacerbated in a capital case?



11   A.  I think it is, especially the more heinous the crime,



12   because I think that the jury tends to want to find at least



13   one person who is going to be assessed a death penalty simply



14   because the crime is so heinous that someone out of this group



15   must be punished by having their life taken.  And that --



16   therein can create a problem.



17   Q.  And if there are two or more jurors (sic) there in the



18   penalty stage, they're trying to convince the jury to take the



19   other person and not them?  Is that correct?



20   A.  Yes.  That's right.



21   Q.  Have you ever tried a capital murder case as a defense



22   lawyer, Judge?



23   A.  No.



24            MR. WOODS:  Thank you.  We pass the witness.



25            THE COURT:  All right.  Mr. Mackey?







