                                            54



    Charles Campbell - Cross



1   Q.  The issue addressed to the trial court, Judge Campbell, is



2   one that requires a balancing of various factors?



3   A.  Oh, yes.  Yes.



4   Q.  What have you done, Judge Campbell, to become familiar with



5   the facts or factors in this particular prosecution?



6   A.  Very little.  Read hurriedly through a portion of the



7   motions for severance.



8   Q.  Did you read the Defendant Nichols' motion for severance?



9   A.  Yes.



10   Q.  Did you --



11   A.  Not the entire motion.  I read pretty much the part that



12   pertains to the punishment phase.



13   Q.  Did you read any portion of the motion and exhibits of



14   Defendant McVeigh?



15   A.  Not any of the exhibits, no.



16   Q.  Did you read any portion of the motion?



17   A.  Yes.



18   Q.  Did you read any portion of the Government's response?



19   A.  I believe I read the Government's entire response, yes,



20   sir.  I think I read that on the plane yesterday afternoon, as



21   a matter of fact.



22   Q.  In the course of that review, Judge Campbell, did you



23   identify certain factors that might be addressed if you had the



24   same decision facing you in this case?



25   A.  I identified some factors in the federal death penalty







                                            55



    Charles Campbell - Cross



1   statute that I looked at that seemed to take care of some of



2   the problems that Texas had in its previous statute.



3   Q.  You would agree that a legitimate factor in the decision



4   whether to sever is the cost of two trials; correct?



5   A.  I think it's a legitimate factor.  I would not weigh it in



6   as a very heavy factor in a death penalty case.



7   Q.  But it ought to be in the equation?



8   A.  Probably should, yes, sir.  I mean I don't believe that you



9   can ever treat taxpayers' money like it's play money, is what



10   I'm trying to say; but on the other hand, the Supreme Court



11   itself has said that death is different, and that means that



12   perhaps it's not as important in the equation in a death



13   penalty case as it would be in a non-death penalty case.



14   Q.  You would agree, Judge Campbell, that the risk of tainting



15   the jury pool by attempting to select a second jury after a



16   first highly publicized trial is a factor to weigh?



17   A.  It would be a factor, yes, sir.



18   Q.  In your experience, Judge Campbell, have you had any case



19   as highly publicized as this one?



20   A.  Not nationwide publicity, no.  Statewide publicity, yes.



21   Q.  Judge Campbell, would you also agree that it's a legitimate



22   factor to concern yourself with the risks of inconsistent



23   verdicts?



24   A.  Inconsistent verdicts in what sense?



25   Q.  Two juries presented with the same set of facts reaching







                                            56



    Charles Campbell - Cross



1   starkly different results.



2   A.  I would find it unusual at least as to the punishment phase



3   of a capital trial that you would have the same set of facts as



4   to any two defendants.  I would not think that would be a great



5   consideration because I just don't think that you've got any



6   two people in this world that are similarly situated for the



7   punishment phase, at least of a capital trial.



8   Q.  You agree there is a risk of inconsistent verdicts when the



9   same case is presented to two different juries?



10   A.  There could be insofar as the guilt phase is concerned.



11   Much less so as far as the punishment phase is concerned.



12   Q.  As you weigh the various factors in that decision, would



13   you take into account the number of defendants in that



14   potential joint trial?



15   A.  You mean two as opposed to twelve?



16   Q.  Is the number itself relevant in your analysis?



17   A.  Logistically, I would think so, yes, sir.



18   Q.  When you test it against the risk of juror confusion, would



19   you agree there is less risk if there is two defendants as



20   opposed to a greater number?



21   A.  Juror confusion about what?



22   Q.  About the individual characteristics of each defendant,



23   about their role in the crime.



24   A.  No, I wouldn't think that that would be a particularly



25   important thing to -- for a judge to consider.







