12                         DIRECT EXAMINATION



13   BY MR. THURSCHWELL:



14   Q.  Mr. Wymore, how are you currently employed?



15   A.  I'm the chief deputy public defender for the state of



16   Colorado.



17   Q.  And how long have you been chief deputy public defender?



18   A.  14 years.



19   Q.  What -- briefly, what are your responsibilities in that



20   position?



21   A.  I'm the lead counsel on death penalty cases.  I supervise,



22   I instruct on death penalty litigation.  Primarily, I'm the



23   chief trial deputy, one of them.  There's two of us in death



24   penalty.  I assist in administrative matters.  I teach on a lot



25   of other things, instructing in trial tactics, litigation.







                                            67



     David Wymore - Direct



1   Q.  Is that a state-wide position?



2   A.  Yeah.



3   Q.  How many capital cases have you handled?  Let me revise



4   that.  How many capital defendants have you represented during



5   your career?



6   A.  A rough estimate, 30 to 35, 40.  Capital defendants.



7   People who have had the threat of the death penalty attached to



8   them one way or the other, either by formal filing or some sort



9   of the threat of the death penalty.



10   Q.  And of those, how many did you try to verdict?



11   A.  Five.  One of them was hung.  One of them was a hung trial.



12   One of them actually hung himself so --



13   Q.  That's unfortunate for him.  How many capital cases have



14   been tried to verdict in the state of Colorado to your



15   knowledge since -- during the past fourteen years?



16   A.  Well, in the past 14 years, I would use 1979 as a line of



17   demarcation because it -- certain things happened in terms of



18   structuring the penalty, but my -- my number is 35 trials.  38



19   defendants.



20   Q.  All right.  And are you generally familiar with the facts



21   and proceedings in those trials?



22   A.  Yes.  In a sliding scale.  Obviously, the cases I've tried



23   myself, I'm more familiar with.  The ones by my office, less



24   familiar with.  And then as it goes down to private counsel.



25   Generally, yes.







                                            68



     David Wymore - Direct



1   Q.  Have you tried any joint capital trials?



2   A.  Yes, I have.



3   Q.  How many?



4   A.  Joint capital trials?  One.



5   Q.  How many have been tried in the state of Colorado, to your



6   knowledge?



7   A.  Two since '79.



8   Q.  How many jurors in your estimate have you voir dired in



9   capital cases?



10   A.  As death litigation, publicity, those issues?



11   Q.  Yes.  All of the issues that one would voir dire in a



