14   Q.  Are there -- in your knowledge -- to your knowledge, are



15   there any attorneys either for the prosecution or the defense



16   who have tried more death penalty cases in the state of



17   Colorado than you?



18   A.  More?  No.  Not since '79.



19   Q.  Have you taught or lectured in the area of capital



20   litigation?



21   A.  Yes, I have.



22   Q.  And when would that been?



23   A.  Over the course of the last 14 years, I sometimes go and do



24   presentations at bar associations for various criminal defense



25   bars in other states.  I'm also on the faculty of the NAACP,







                                            69



     David Wymore - Direct



1   LDF Airlie conference which I consider to be the most



2   prestigious organization dealing with capital litigation.  I've



3   given presentations at Life in the Balance, which is another



4   national organization that gets a group of attorneys, capital



5   defendants -- capital defense attorneys and give them



6   presentations there.



7   Q.  Have you ever tried a case in federal court?



8   A.  No.



9   Q.  Are you familiar with the federal capital sentences?



10   A.  To the extent that I've reviewed it, yes.  Not to the



11   extent that I've actually had to work through it, but I've read



12   it.



13   Q.  And could you describe the similarities between the



14   Colorado sentencing -- death penalty sentencing scheme and the



15   federal scheme?



16   A.  Yes.  Generally, it's a -- they are the same thing.  It's a



17   jury decision as opposed to a judge decision.  It's a



18   bifurcated trial where you have the guilt phase -- what we call



19   the guilt phase first.  You have the penalty phase second.



20   It's a weighing statute where the jurors are going to weigh



21   mitigation versus aggravation, certain guidelines that are



22   built into the statute.  There's some burdens of proof that are



23   attached.  There are some statutory aggravating factors.



24   There's some statutory mitigating factors, some open-ended



25   mitigation, and it appears to be a one vote for life or







                                            70



     David Wymore - Direct



1   unanimous for death statute, also, Federal, same as state.



2   Q.  Are there any particularly relevant differences?



3   A.  There is one from the point of view of the defense that I



4   think is interesting and somewhat makes it different is that



5   there's a burden of proof attached to mitigating factors in the



6   federal statute.  Preponderance of the evidence as to



7   mitigation.  In the Colorado statute, what we have is the fact



8   of mitigation where mitigation carries no burden.  It just



9   simply -- if there's a suggestion of mitigation, a juror can



10   find it to exist and then attach whatever weight it wants in



11   the determination; whereas, here, you have mitigation by



12   statute with an attached burden of proof which gives it a



13   burden of persuasion.  You've got to carry the burden to



14   establish the mitigating factor.  You don't in Colorado.



15            MR. THURSCHWELL:  Your Honor, we would tender



16   Mr. Wymore as an expert in the conduct of bifurcated capital



17   trials.



18            MR. MACKEY:  No objection.



19            THE COURT:  All right.  You may proceed.



20   BY MR. THURSCHWELL:



21   Q.  Mr. Wymore, in your opinion, given the same two defendants



22   and all other things being equal, is a joint trial of two



23   capitally charged defendants likely to be as fair as a joint



24   trial of two noncapital defendants?



25   A.  No.







                                            71



     David Wymore - Direct



1   Q.  Okay.  Now, I -- without re-covering ground already



2   covered, I want to take you through the trial process and have



3   you explain to me on the basis of examples and hypotheticals



4   why you hold that opinion.



5   A.  Okay.



6   Q.  And I'd like to start with jury selection.



7   A.  All right.



8   Q.  You heard Mr. Stevenson testify about life qualification of



9   jurors.



10   A.  Yes.



11   Q.  Could you -- life qualification is the process by which the



12   Court is assured that a particular juror is capable of



13   rendering a life verdict in an appropriate case; is that



14   accurate?



15   A.  Yes.  Yes, essentially.



16   Q.  Could you briefly give us an example of how a life



17   qualification voir dire would work.



18   A.  Well, okay.  It comes primarily after death qualification.



19   I mean, the series of questions begin as to what they feel



20   about the death penalty, and the juror may come up with an



21   answer of whether or not he believes in it or doesn't believe



22   in it or for or against, things like that.  Primarily what the



23   defense -- what you're interested in under Morgan vs. Illinois



24   and Wainwright vs. Witt, taking those two principles together,



25   is not only is the juror death-qualified, could he render a







                                            72



     David Wymore - Direct



1   death verdict in an appropriate case, but could he also render



2   a life verdict if the burden of proof or the situation calls



3   for a life verdict.



4            As you go through and start to have to deal with



5   qualifying or understanding if a juror is a life juror -- he



6   may be mitigation-impaired for your case but otherwise a good



7   juror in another case -- it's important to try and understand



8   whether or not that particular juror can listen to mitigation



9   in your case.



10   Q.  Let me stop you there and ask you:  What do you mean by



11   mitigation-impaired?



12   A.  Mitigation is -- is a rough concept for jurors.  It's a



13   rough concept for them to get a grip on, and half -- half the



14   time in voir dire you spend trying to explain to them what it



15   is.  It's one of the first questions they ask.  Mitigation-



16   impaired is that although -- mitigation could be a number of



17   things.  It comes from -- the definition from Black's Law 



18   Dictionary, I think, is about fairness and mercy factors given



19   for life as opposed to for death is a simple way of putting it.



20            If your mitigation -- let's take age, and that's an



21   example the judge was using.  If your mitigation is that you're



22   old or -- older -- I'm starting to call myself that now.  If



23   you're 45, 46 years old, you've led a good life and you have a



24   good background, is that a mitigating factor if it's put forth?



25   It is mitigation under the -- under all the concepts of the







                                            73



     David Wymore - Direct



1   Eighth Amendment and the way it's been determined.  However, 17



2   is also a mitigating factor, too.



3            However, if the juror is impaired from believing or



4   cannot consider your theme of mitigation, whatever it may be --



5   it could be drugs.  I didn't take them, I did take them.  If



6   it's drugs and they think that it's an aggravating factor,



7   they're mitigation-impaired from considering a mitigating



8   factor in terms of giving you a life verdict.



9   Q.  So would it be accurate to say that if a juror who -- who



10   cannot consider age, older age as a mitigating factor for your



11   client who is -- has that age, that that has -- as to your



12   client, that juror is mitigation-impaired?



13   A.  I'd challenge him under Wainwright vs. Witt.



14   Q.  And that -- and if you could show successfully under



15   Wainwright vs. Witt, he was essentially impaired from



16   considering that as mitigation, that person would not sit as a



17   life qualified juror?



18   A.  I'd challenge them for cause.  It would up to the judge to



19   determine whether or not it was a sustainable challenge or not,



20   but I'd challenge them for cause and leave it for the appeal



21   court if I'm -- if he's on.



22   Q.  Mr. Wymore, how does this concept of mitigation impairment



23   complicate the joint capital voir dire proceeding?



24   A.  The way it -- the way it complicates a joint capital trial



25   is this:  If you have -- it's pretty simple.  If you have two







                                            74



     David Wymore - Direct



1   competing mitigation theories, say one is age and say one is --



2   one guy is older, one guy is younger; one guy has a history of



3   drugs and alcohol, one guy does not; one defense attorney -- or



4   one party, party A, is going to be saying that the juror is



5   saying, well, I find drugs to be -- lack of drugs is -- would



6   be or the use of drugs is an aggravating factor essentially for



7   me.  I can't consider it as mitigation.



8            That may be consistent with A's theory of mitigation.



9   However, B cannot live with that because he may have drugs and



10   alcohol in his background that is going to be put forward as



11   mitigation and under the law have the right to have it



12   considered as mitigation, but that juror would be not a juror



13   that could listen to that mitigation package or that mitigating



14   factor.  You would have a challenge from one and an objection



15   from the other.  A would object to the challenge of B.



16   Q.  Mr. Wymore, why isn't that a problem that can be solved by



17   judicial instructions; for example, a judicial instruction to



18   each juror that they must seriously and carefully consider all



19   mitigating factors put forth as to each defendant individually?



20   A.  I think you can always instruct as to anything.  The



21   problem is is it a realistic aspect that the juror is going to



22   respond to it.  I think that's unrealistic on a juror to try



23   and understand two things that are connected both emotionally



24   and from their own inherent moralistic assessment of whether a



25   person should live or die.







                                            75



     David Wymore - Direct



1            Take the example of the person who does not believe in



2   drugs or alcohol.  He's not going to connect, just simply



3   doesn't believe that alcohol and drugs can be a mitigating



4   factor.  You're basically going to be telling that juror, reset



5   your emotional and -- reset your emotional situation back to



6   zero and reset your -- your inherent moralistic compass back to



7   zero and do this again, whether you've already emotionally



8   attached to a mitigation such as drugs or alcohol and child



9   abuse and everything else.  It's just simply unrealistic.  I



10   don't believe they can do it.



11   Q.  Let me pose another situation for you.  Take the -- as a



12   hypothetical, the example of two joined capital defendants



13   against one whom there is evidence of racial prejudice on his



14   part and against the other, there is no such evidence.  One



15   racially prejudiced -- there's evidence of racial prejudice,



16   one there is not.  Does that pose any special problems in a



17   capital proceeding?



18   A.  That would explode the problems.



19   Q.  And how so?



20   A.  Well, the situation is this:  What you know inherently and



21   intuitively as a criminal defense lawyer and I think as a



22   person in the judicial system as well as from the studies, is



23   that jurors -- that, basically, there's a skewing of the jury



24   that begins to go on immediately upon death qualification.  If



25   you don't believe in the death penalty, you're out of the case.







                                            76



     David Wymore - Direct



1   So it begins to skew as it goes on.  And so the pile seems to



2   get a little smaller and a little more twisted off to one part.



3   Q.  When you're talking about skewing, you're talking about



4   skewing towards a willingness to impose the death penalty?



5   A.  Well, you're skewing it basically out of a fair cross-



6   section of the jury.  I mean, people who are not against -- who



7   are not for the death penalty are left out of the pile



8   immediately, and then you start taking them off the other back



9   end.



10            What happens is in -- intuitively in what I've seen



11   from my practice is that people who are -- who succeed in



12   making it into the eligible death pool, been qualified as a



13   death juror, that are of racial minority, black, Hispanic,



14   women, or other minority aspect where they have a minority



15   sense about them, that not that many -- you start losing a good



16   deal of them as you go on into death qualification.



17            Now you have them in the pool, the ones that have



18   survived that can consider a life or death sentence at the



19   time.  Well, they can consider a death sentence.  Let's take it



20   there.  Then those jurors inherently are more sympathetic, in



21   my opinion, to hearing mitigation after they have convicted



22   somebody of first-degree murder beyond a reasonable doubt of a



23   heinous crime.  Those are jurors you want to protect and to



24   save and to have as part of the pool that's eligible to go in



25   and hear the case.







                                            77



     David Wymore - Direct



1            If you have two defendants -- and the example you gave



2   me, you have A and you have B.  If there's going to be evidence



3   of racial motive, bias, something else directed against A, A



4   cannot live with those jurors that are traditionally and just



5   inherently more able to hear the mitigation package of B.  A



6   may begin to challenge the jurors on legitimate cause



7   challenges, your Honor -- such as I could envision the



8   challenge such as this:  Your Honor, I'm challenging Juror A --



9   or Juror No. 12, who happens to be a black person, on the basis



10   that my mitigation package is that I was a racist and that I



11   was raised to be a racist.  I was raised in a situation that



12   might cause me to be a racist and I behaved that way, so,



13   therefore, I'm challenging because he will not listen to my



14   mitigation package, as a racist.



15            That, to -- the dilemma then becomes if the court



16   entertains that and allows that to be a sustained challenge for



17   cause.  Because if the person says, if you bring forward to me



18   a person who's a racist, I will not listen to whatever else may



19   be in their life.  Co-defendant B, they say wait a minute,



20   where is my juror going?  Where is my part of my jury going?



21   Because one co-defendant's jury in mitigation is not



22   necessarily another co-defendant's jury in mitigation.  The



23   choices become three- or four-fold.



24   Q.  Let me stop you there.  If you're Defendant B, the one



25   against who there is no racial prejudice evidenced -- if you're







                                            78



     David Wymore - Direct



1   his attorney, what do you do at the point where Defendant A's



2   attorney moves to strike the minority juror?



3   A.  Well, you know -- I mean, just in this hypothetical, you



4   can challenge, you could object to the entire pool.  You could



5   move to have the entire pool stricken.  You could move for



6   severance.  You could definitely start beginning raising the



7   Batson challenge because the basis of the challenge is race



8   based even though it may be a legitimate cause base challenge.



9            Depending on whether the prosecutor is choosing to



10   join in on the challenge or not, you begin and it begins to



11   unfold.  I mean, that's the issue of Batson.  That's the issue



12   of race in jury selections and complications as it goes into



13   death qualification.  You challenge.



14   Q.  So the judge will be confronted with a Batson challenge as



15   to each of the minority jurors is at least likely in a case



16   involving two co-defendants?



17   A.  In the hypothetical, B would have to make those challenges.



18   As to Co-defendant A and -- and whether or not the prosecution



19   joins in it or not, it just complicates it.



20   Q.  Okay.  Now, let me move on to the guilt phase.



21   A.  All right.



22   Q.  You heard, I think, Mr. Stevenson testify that one of the



23   concerns in the guilt phase in a capital trial is the need for



24   consistent theories between the guilt phase and penalty phase



25   of that trial in order to convince ultimately the jury that







                                            79



     David Wymore - Direct



1   your client should live.  Do you agree with that?



2   A.  Yes.  Inherently -- you're talking about your own case?



3   Q.  That's correct.



4   A.  One defendant.



5   Q.  One defendant?



6   A.  Yes.  Absolutely.



7   Q.  Okay.  Is -- is part of that problem the -- the fact that



8   evidence entered in the guilt phase can and will be used by the



9   jury in considering whether the defendant should live or die in



10   the penalty phase?



11   A.  Absolutely.  From the very minute you begin picking a jury



12   in a capital case, you're picking the jury with the assumption



13   that you may or will end up in the penalty phase.  If you're a



14   competent, effective defense attorney, you have to believe



15   you're going to be there.  So it affects the entire way you



16   select jurors, the questions you ask during voir dire, your --



17   your evidence that you present and how you -- how you present



18   your evidence within the guilt phase.



19   Q.  Staying with the guilt phase for the moment, isn't it



20   possible -- is it possible for a judge, by sufficiently



21   specific instructions, to cure any of that spillover prejudice



22   if I can call it that, or spillover evidence or prejudice



23   between the guilt phase evidence and the penalty phase evidence



24   by sufficiently adequate instructions?



25   A.  I don't believe so.







                                            80



     David Wymore - Direct



1   Q.  Okay.



2   A.  Not in all aspects, no.



3   Q.  Could you give us an example to illustrate the problem.



4   A.  All right.  Back to A and B.  Say, the prosecution calls a



5   witness for the limited purpose of introducing evidence against



6   Co-defendant B.  And it's going to be similar transaction



7   evidence, or we call it a 404(b) or some other bad act that may



8   be connected to motive or something else.  The prosecution will



9   get up and begin to tell the -- in a limiting instruction to



10   the jury, please only consider this against the Co-defendant B



11   and do not consider it in terms of credibility, do not consider



12   it in terms of character.  It can be concerned with the



13   credibility of W, but not in terms of character.  You can't



14   show propensity to violence.



15            B -- or A at this point in time may take advantage of



16   Witness W for the purposes of, number one, solidifying their



17   position within the trial as less culpable or their state of



18   mind.  They may attack the witness totally unrelated to the



19   B -- to the limited purposes evidence but to begin develop



20   state of mind evidence such as you knew this man, too, you've



21   indicated to the prosecution you knew him.  Isn't he bad?



22   Doesn't he take drugs?  Were you afraid?  Weren't you fearful?



23   And by connecting that way, you're saying, I was, too.



24            For your purpose of state of mind right at that point,



25   there's cross-instruction.  You're telling the jury don't







                                            81



     David Wymore - Direct



1   consider his propensity or his character on this crime.



2   However, as it goes to A, his character is relevant to A's



3   state of mind.  Then as it transposes over -- the jury is going



4   to resolve the issue in the guilt phase.  They are going to



5   come to a conclusion, he's bad or he's not bad or he's a liar



6   or he's not a liar or somebody is bad or not, just given that



7   one instance of character versus limited instruction.



8            It goes into the guilt phase -- it goes into the



9   penalty phase.  Right.  Then the instruction at that point in



10   time is you can't essentially say disregard everything you've



11   already resolved.  And now bad character can be mitigation for



12   A, but it can't be used to kill or give the death penalty to B.



13   It's a complicated package of instructions.



14   Q.  Let me stop you there.  Let me back up.



15   A.  It's a little complicated.



16   Q.  That's why I want to -- why couldn't that evidence be used



17   as -- explain your last statement.



18   A.  It's your mitigation.  It's A's mitigation.  It's A's



19   mitigation within posturing of relative culpability.  I mean,



20   as you look at the mitigators in the federal statute, you have



21   equal culpability, which means if you're less culpable, it's



22   even a better mitigator.  You have minor participant.  In the



23   reality of death litigation, you want to be less culpable.



24   Q.  So now A -- A will -- in the penalty phase will ask the



25   jury to consider that witness provided by W of -- of B's bad







                                            82



     David Wymore - Direct



1   character as demonstration that A is less -- was less culpable?



2   A.  Correct.  Minor participant.



3   Q.  Under a form of duress, on the one hand?



4   A.  Yes.



5   Q.  And on the other hand, the jury is not allowed to consider



6   that evidence of bad character for purposes of aggravating --



7   well, give me the other half.



8   A.  Since it's mitigation for A, it can't be aggravation for B



9   within the same trial with the same two jurors.  It's just



10   constitutionally infirm.  It's -- it's not a designated



11   aggravating factor by the prosecution that A was fearful of B



12   and that B was a person who had a mental illness, deranged



13   mind, drugs, everything else caused him to be fearful.  That's



14   not an aggravating factor that's to be presented either in its



15   nonstatutory or aggravated package to the jury as a reason to



16   give B the death penalty.  However, do I believe the jury is



17   going to use that one way or the other, yes.  Probably use it



18   adverse to B.



19   Q.  Let me give you another example that faces every defendant



20   in a capital or noncapital case -- it raises this problem --



