                                            83



     David Wymore - Direct



1   A.  Absolutely.



2   Q.  And what are the factors there?



3   A.  Just in a single trial, the presentation your client gives



4   in front of the jury in the guilt phase can either essentially



5   give him life or give him death in the penalty phase.  How he



6   comes off, whether he's telling the full truth, if that person



7   delivers on the factual basis wrong, hesitant, doesn't answer



8   the questions well, and -- and in terms of cross-examination,



9   you know, just the entire thing.  It affects the penalty phase



10   because the jury judges you as a human being.  They are making



11   a judgment of you.  Am I going to convict you, am I going to



12   give you the death penalty.  They are constantly aware that the



13   second phase exists, so it affects you.



14   Q.  Okay.  In a -- specifically in a joint capital trial, how



15   will that --



16   A.  Specifically, in a joint capital trial, it's -- it's very



17   complex.  First of all, advising your client as to the basis or



18   expansion of cross-examination because you have an opposing



19   defendant who wants to posture themselves always as better than



20   you and less culpable than you, perhaps more helpful than you,



21   more cooperative than you, and it becomes this entire playout.



22   You have a hard time --



23   Q.  Let me stop you there.



24   A.  Okay.



25   Q.  All those issues you've just raised, more helpful than you,







                                            84



     David Wymore - Direct



1   more cooperative than you, less culpable than you, are those



2   relevant to the guilt phase determination?



3   A.  Absolutely.  I --



4   Q.  For the penalty phase?



5   A.  They are both.  If you testify in your trial as a



6   defendant, you're basically saying I didn't do it, I'm not



7   culpable, or I did it under some sort of infirmity, therefore



8   less culpable or I was a minor participant, less culpable, or I



9   was under duress, less culpable.  By taking the stand, you're



10   taking the position of relative culpability, okay.  Does that



11   make sense?



12   Q.  Yes, it does.



13   A.  Okay.



14   Q.  Does there -- does a problem arise of cross-examination of



15   a co-defendant?



16   A.  Yes.



17   Q.  How does that -- what happens there?



18   A.  Well, because -- because of that standard posturing, the



19   posturing that's going to take -- the necessary posturing



20   say -- and I'll use the example of not my defendant taking the



21   stand but the co-defendant or the opposing defendant taking the



22   stand.  The mitigating factors that are going -- that are



23   enumerated under the statute are equal culpability, minor



24   participation, duress, and it's basically posturing.



25            If the co-defendant is going to take the stand, I







                                            85



     David Wymore - Direct



1   would want to cross-examine him as to those issues that go to



2   the mitigation phase because I cannot allow him to succeed in



3   retaining or succeeding in having that posture of I didn't do



4   it, you caused me to do it, he caused me to do it, I was under



5   duress, all these other things that come out about my client,



6   state of mind, why he reacted, the reverse.  So therefore, I



7   have to cross-examine him, especially with the carryover effect



8   of guilt evidence into the penalty phase.



9            If the court protects him in cross-examination and



10   doesn't allow me to go into the issue of mitigation, the



11   evidence is going to be carried over into the penalty phase,



12   the impression.



13   Q.  Let me stop you there.  Couldn't -- can't you call him or



14   cross-examine him in the penalty phase?



