24   the problem is that you -- as you begin to cross-examine,



25   you're not limited or the co-defendant may not be limited in







                                            86



     David Wymore - Direct



1   the same parameters as the state is in terms of bringing out



2   certain things.



3            What may be important to you or your posture within



4   the penalty phase may be minor incidences of crime that have



5   some sort of effect upon your client's state of mind of why he



6   did or didn't do that that are not otherwise admissible.  So



7   the state may be limited in their cross-examination, but it



8   would be -- it would be tactically devastating to you if you



9   were because you weren't able to either attack and diminish or



10   remove that or put yourself into the better posture as it goes



11   into the penalty phase.



12   Q.  So you're forced as a co-defendant to cross-examine on



13   issues that have penalty phase relevance even -- even if they



14   are of marginal or no guilt phase relevance because of the



15   impact of the co-defendant's testimony at the penalty phase?



16   A.  Absolutely.  You're competing -- you're -- there's direct



17   competition between opposing defendants to be viewed better.



18   It's the reality of -- of death penalty litigation.  It's a



19   reality of jury sentence.  You've got to be less culpable, less



20   morally culpable than the co-defendant.  You cannot allow him



21   to live and be up there as a good person that was taken to the



22   cleaners by your guy.



