24   might very well be the nullification of that mitigating



25   evidence against the original defendant?







                                            89



     David Wymore - Direct



1   A.  Yes.  And what it is, is it becomes more of a -- of a -- of



2   a sideshow as to what is mitigating as opposed to what is the



3   burden of aggravation versus mitigation in the individualized



4   determination.  The co-defendants have to wage the battle in



5   the jurors' hearts and minds because you're asking for an



6   emotional connection to your mitigation case and then an



7   assessment from their own inherent moralistic values as to



8   whether or not you deserve to live or not.



9            So you now become in a contest as to really what is



10   mitigating.  And when the jurors are asking here -- and it also



11   plays to the advantage of the prosecution.  You heard it.  You



12   heard that was mitigating.  They will tell you two things at



13   the same time.  I mean, I can see myself doing it and I can see



14   it being heard in the argument.  Really, are any of these



15   mitigating?  The juror, after watching this display of attack



16   and parry and strike all the way through is going to say no,



17   there really is no mitigating.  There's only aggravation.



18   That's what we call nullification of mitigation.



19   Q.  And again, cannot that problem be solved by sufficient



20   judicial instructions?



21   A.  It's -- I do not believe in a realistic sense because you



22   ask for an emotional attachment.  You have jurors on your --



23   you need jurors who can hear your mitigation and the -- and



24   you're attempting to strike a semblance of mercy from them.



25   You're attempting to tell them yes, I have -- my client has







                                            90



     David Wymore - Direct



1   done a horrible thing.  And -- but your question is do you



2   decide that he dies and I want to tell you what his walk of



3   life is.  When you have two competing people with that, I mean,



4   you're basically showing -- or trying to attach and my



5   experience shows me that -- that jurors do attach emotionally.



6   Q.  Do they take their job seriously?



7   A.  Absolutely.



8   Q.  Are they trying as hard as they can to follow the judge's



9   instructions?



10   A.  Totally.  They do.  But here's the situation:  Say you go



11   second.  Say you're in seriatum --



12   Q.  Seriatum penalty phase?



13   A.  Right, in seriatum penalty phases where the -- the initial



14   co-defendant has gone through and already made the attachment



15   and received a life verdict from the person.  You're going to



16   ask that jury to reset their emotional clock back to zero.  You



17   can instruct, please reset your emotional clock back to zero.



18   The reality is not there.  They have made the bond and the



19   connection.  And you're going to tell them to reset their



20   inherent moral dial back to zero.  And it's just an unrealistic



21   burden on the jury.  It has nothing to do with the lawyers and



22   their ability.  It has nothing to do with instructions.  It has



