23   capital trials.



24            MR. THURSCHWELL:  Your Honor, we would tender



25   Dr. Bronson on the aspect of effect of joinder of capital







                                            101



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   defendants in a penalty phase.



2            MR. CONNELLY:  No objection.



3            THE COURT:  You may proceed.



4   BY MR. THURSCHWELL:



5   Q.  Dr. Bronson, let's talk about the two completed studies you



6   mentioned.  What was your methodology in -- well, let me back



7   up.  Was your methodology the same in both studies?



8   A.  Virtually identical.



9   Q.  Okay.  Could you describe to the Court that methodology.



10   A.  What I did was to -- in both of the studies, so I can



11   perhaps speak generically here.  I took the general scenario of



12   the case, each of which as it would happen involving three



13   co-defendants, all capitally charged.  I presented, at least as



14   written summaries of cases go, a fairly extensive factual



15   description of the guilt phase with instructions from the court



16   and -- and told my -- the people who participated in the study



17   that their jury -- that the jury in the case had unanimously



18   agreed that the defendants were guilty and then, given the



19   nature of California law, required to get to the penalty phase;



20   that the jury had also found them guilty of -- of what we call



21   special circumstances and we were now entering the -- the



22   penalty phase of the trial.



23            Then in order to test, which is the crucial



24   question -- in order to test as best I could the difference



25   between a joint penalty phase and a severed penalty phase, I







                                            102



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   then divided up my respondents.  And perhaps I should clarify



2   who my respondents were.



3   Q.  By "respondents," you mean the individuals who answered the



4   questionnaire --



5   A.  That's right.



6   Q.  -- that formed the underlying data for your results?



7   A.  Yes.  They were a mix.  Approximately 35 percent or so jury



8   pool members.  The other group were undergraduate students.



9   One set of students at Fresno State University, the other at my



10   university, Chico State University.



11   Q.  Judge -- I'm sorry.  Dr. Bronson, let me stop you there and



12   ask you:  Why did you use both jury pool members and students?



13   A.  Well, that's -- that's a fair question.  Most of what we



14   know in social science, in social psychology comes from the



15   study of students.  Students are the typical respondents in



16   various studies for two very practical, earthy reasons.  First



17   of all, they are a captive audience.  Second of all, the price



18   is right.  That is, you can do a study with limited resources.



19   But there are always questions arise, some of them very



20   appropriate, some of them less so about whether students -- any



21   results that you obtain from a social science study using



22   students can tell us anything about people who aren't students.



23            It may well be that given students' lack of exposure



24   to the real world, their relative youth, that they are -- they



25   tend to be an age cohort and many other factors, it's very --







                                            103



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   at least problematic about whether you can make that



2   projection.



3            Indeed, in the first study I ever did on juries when I



4   was still in graduate school here in Colorado, I was able to



5   use jury pool members given to me by jury commissioners to do



6   my studies, and I did it because I felt that there would be



7   some concern as to whether results obtained by testing students



8   would be viewed on as meaningful -- and being able to draw



9   general conclusions.



10            So in this case, I thought that -- it was much more



11   difficult to do the interviews of jurors.  And the way that I



12   got them was to get -- in both counties that I did my



13   experiments with, the jury commissioners furnished me very



14   gratuitously with the -- actually labels with the names and



15   addresses of jury pool members that had been selected for jury



16   duty in the one case in Fresno County and the other case in



17   Butte County so that I could paste those labels onto envelopes



18   and mail them, my questionnaires, with an appropriate cover



19   letter.



20            To get a big sample size was -- would have been



21   difficult to get -- the larger your sample size, the better



22   your -- the statistical power of whatever survey results you



23   get.  So I supplemented that actually with over half of the



24   respondents by using students.  But then I was able to separate



25   out the two groups, to look at students and how they dealt with







                                            104



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   the experiment and to look at how people who were jurors or at



2   least who were in the jury pool and to see if what jurors did



3   was more or less equivalent to what students did.



4   Q.  And we'll come back to your -- the total results in a



5   moment; but preliminarily, did -- what were the results of that



6   study?  Did the jurors' correspond to the students' results?



7   A.  They were very close.  In one of the counties, I think it



8   was the Fresno study, the absolute levels of support for the



9   death penalty were, as one might expect, a bit lower among



10   students than among jurors, but that wasn't of particular



11   importance to me.  What I cared about was the difference



12   between those respondents who looked at the case in a joined



13   scenario versus those who looked at it in a severance scenario.



14   And in -- in that element, the students and the jurors were



15   virtually the same.



16   Q.  Okay.  And I interrupted you.  You were just -- you were



17   describing questionnaires and saying you had sent them both to



18   a set of jurors and a set of students.  Please proceed.  What



19   did you do with the results of those specific questionnaires?



20   A.  Well, it wasn't very complicated at that stage.  I had



21   asked certain questions.  The -- the most crucial question



22   was -- on the questionnaire, the survey instrument was to ask



23   them to vote after they had been given a reasonable



24   instruction.



25            I should say also in terms of methodology that I did







                                            105



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   at least certain minimal steps to try and make my sample more



2   or less reflective of what an actual jury pool would be like.



3   Now, it -- for the jury pool members themselves, that was not



4   very difficult except that I added one further basis of



5   inclusion or exclusion, which was a simple death qualification



6   question.  It -- it was sort of a Witherspoon-type test, simply



7   asking them if they would always vote for the death penalty or



8   they would never vote for the death penalty or if they thought



9   the death penalty was appropriate in some cases, but not all.



10   And only those who were -- evidenced some open-mindedness on



11   that question by saying they thought the death penalty was



12   appropriate in some but not all cases were they included in the



13   analysis.



14            In addition, with respect to students, I had two



15   additional problems.  One was I didn't want anybody under 18,



16   for understandable reasons, so I excluded the few people in --



17   just a handful of college students who were not 18.  And then I



18   also wanted to exclude noncitizens to, as best I could, mirror



19   one of the important qualifications for -- for jury duty.  So



20   with those exclusions, then I analyzed the data as to the rest



21   of them.



22            You had asked me what it was that I analyzed.  The



23   first thing was I took a look at their penalty decisions.  They



24   were asked to then vote for life or -- and under California



25   law, it's life without the possibility of parole or death.







                                            106



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   Those were the only two choices and are the only two choices



2   that you have in a penalty phase in California.  Then I asked



3   them to explain why it was they had chosen that particular



4   decision, what factors had influenced them.  We can look at the



5   exact language if you like, but I think that's a fair



6   characterization.



7            And of course, some of them had a joint trial in both



8   of the experiments where they were asked to decide on life or



9   death for all three defendants.  Others were given, for each of



10   the other defendants, a separate scenario where they had the



11   same guilt phase, all the same evidence about guilt, but they



12   only heard the aggravation and mitigation that -- at least the



13   penalty portion of that that was presented during the penalty



14   phase and then asked to vote only on one defendant.



15   Q.  Dr. Bronson, could you -- did your questionnaire address



16   the reasons that the individuals voted for or against the death



17   penalty?



18   A.  Yes.  That was an open-ended question where I simply asked



19   people perhaps read what it -- what it said.



20   Q.  But since you're reading, are you reading from Exhibit E?



21   A.  This is Exhibit E.



22   Q.  Okay.  Could you identify for the Court what Nichols'



23   Exhibit E is.



24   A.  That is -- that is a set of questionnaires --



25   Q.  Is that the -- is that -- are those the individual







                                            107



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   questionnaires?



2   A.  Yes.  These are the -- these are the individual



3   questionnaires that were mailed -- this is only the -- the



4   juror questionnaire.  It's virtually identical to -- I think



5   maybe the only difference is that on the student questionnaire,



6   there was the citizenship question.  It's possible there's



7   another word or two, but it was virtually identical.  Also, the



8   students didn't have a cover letter explaining the purpose.



9   But this is the -- the actual questionnaire.



10   Q.  And before you go on, just to clean this up, in Nichols'



11   Exhibit F, is that the cover letter that you sent to the



12   members of the jury pool with the joint scenario that you --



13   questionnaire that you referred to?



14   A.  Yes.  Apparently, that is the -- so while I didn't look at



15   E carefully, I'm assuming that that's the -- the three severed



16   questionnaires and that F is the cover letter and joined



17   scenario, the composite version of the case that was sent.



18   Q.  Okay.



19            MR. THURSCHWELL:  Judge, we would move Exhibits E and



20   F.



21            MR. CONNELLY:  No objection.



22            THE COURT:  They are received.



23   BY MR. THURSCHWELL:



24   Q.  Okay.  You were about -- you were about to read from



25   Exhibit E the open-ended question regarding the basis for the







                                            108



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   jurors' or mock jurors' verdict?



2   A.  Yes.  It is simply what are some of the reasons you



3   considered in making your decision.  In other words, first,



4   they choose between death penalty and -- or life imprisonment



5   without possibility of parole.  They check one or the other of



6   those alternatives.  And then they are asked what are some of



7   the reasons you considered in making your decision.  Jurors



8   with a joint scenario were asked that three times.  Jurors in



9   the severed versions had only one.



10   Q.  Did you analyze those results, as well?



11   A.  Yes.  I used a content analysis that is systematic review,



12   looking at -- I focused on just one issue in -- in looking at



13   that, the extent to which those who explained their verdicts



14   gave as it affected social history.  In other words, did they



15   talk about those qualities which you've heard the other



16   witnesses talk about this morning?



17   Q.  The individual defendants' background and --



18   A.  Yes.



19   Q.  -- life experiences.



20   A.  All those things.  Bad childhood, their age and maturity,



21   other -- their prior record, history of violence and things



22   like that that would affect the case.  These were fairly



23   different cases.  So the kinds of materials that were brought



24   in did obviously differ.



25   Q.  Okay.  Dr. Bronson, I want to turn now to the results of







                                            109



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   your two studies, the Fresno study and the Butte study, and



2   directing your attention to what's been marked as Nichols'



3   Exhibit G.  Is this document a summary of some of the results



4   from those two studies?



5   A.  Yes, most of the results.



6            MR. THURSCHWELL:  We would move the admission of



7   Nichols' Exhibit G.



8            MR. CONNELLY:  No objection.



9            THE COURT:  Received.



10   BY MR. THURSCHWELL:



11   Q.  Turning first to page 1 of Exhibit G, Dr. Bronson, what do



12   the data represented in these tables represent?



13   A.  Well, the first part of this exhibit, which includes both 1



14   and 2 -- pages 1 and 2, simply look at a comparison of the



15   results from these two studies as to death penalty versus life



16   imprisonment, doing some comparisons between the joined



17   scenario and the severed scenario to see if that appears to



18   make some difference in how these respondents dealt with life



19   versus death in these two cases.



20   Q.  And what did your -- in laymen's language, what did your



21   results show with respect to the relationship between whether a



22   defendant was joined or severed and whether that defendant



23   received the death penalty?



24   A.  At least in the facts of these two cases, there was a very



25   large difference and from social scientists' point of view,







                                            110



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   statistically significant difference, I think, in -- in all but



2   maybe one or two cases where it was marginally statistically



3   significant, but in most situations, highly statistically



4   significant difference between defendants -- the same



5   defendants judged in a severed condition as compared with a



6   joined condition and in the direction that without exception,



7   those defendants whose case was considered separately -- that



8   is, in the severed version -- were significantly less likely to



9   get the death penalty than those who were judged in a joined



10   scenario.



11   Q.  And was that statistically significant difference



12   registered whether you looked at the verdicts in the aggregate



13   or looked at individually named defendants?



14   A.  Well, both because clearly, an aggregate difference, if you



15   say that there are -- you've got five people and their average



16   income is $200,000, it makes a lot of difference if you have



17   one millionaire and the others are all homeless.  You really



18   don't get a fair sense of what these people are like.  So it is



19   important not to look simply at the overall, but at the



20   underlying data because it could be unfair to average it



21   together.  So I did both.  And those -- page 1 has the results



22   in the aggregate, and then page 2 takes each of the defendants



23   separately and looks at them.



24   Q.  Referring to Nichols' Exhibit G --



25   A.  Yes.







                                            111



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   Q.  -- turning to page 3, which is titled, Lumping Effects,



2   could you explain to the Court what a -- what you mean by



3   "lumping effects"?



4   A.  Well, it's the job of a good social scientist to give



5   elegant phrases to things, so I came up with "lumping effects"



6   here.  By that, I mean the tendency in any process, but here of



7   those evaluating life versus death in a -- in a penalty phase



8   of a capital trial, their ability to separate out the



9   defendants, to judge them individually, to judge the defendants



10   on what appear to be independent criteria.



11            Obviously, if there's only one defendant, by



12   definition, that is, relatively speaking, going to be an



13   independent judgment.  You may look out at the world out there



14   and compare this defendant with others, but at least in the



15   given trial, you've only got one defendant that you are looking



16   at.  And indeed, in California, it's improper to -- to allow



17   the defense, for example, to bring in what happened to a



18   co-defendant.



19   Q.  Turning your attention specifically to Table 5 on page 3,



20   how do you measure lumping effect?  That's --



21   A.  Well, I just used a fairly straightforward statistical



22   technique.  It's almost maybe too high-powered to call it



23   statistical.  It's a very simple little thing.  If you want to



24   know -- as in my case, to what extent are you likely to get or



25   should you get, if each of these events was independent, would







                                            112



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   you get all three verdicts the same, all death, all life or a



2   combination of all three together.



3            If you want to know that kind of question, it's like



4   flipping coins.  If you want to know what are the chances that



5   you're going to flip with a fair coin three heads in a row,



6   then the technique, you multiply one-half times one-half times



7   one-half.  You would expect to get all three heads one time in



8   eight.  You would expect to get either all heads or all tails



9   twice that often.  That is one-fourth of the time.  That --



10   that means that they are independent, that the coin doesn't



11   have any memory, that they are operating separately.



12            So I did the same thing here and the -- the -- the



13   basis of determining what the likelihood is was based on what



14   my jurors -- and I use that to mean -- obviously, I'm not



15   talking about real jurors, but my respondents in this



16   experiment, to what extent they voted for death or life for an



17   individual defendant.  If they voted -- if it were like a coin



18   and in each -- each time one-half, then for each of the three



19   defendants, then I would expect that one-eighth of the time



20   they would always vote for heads, if you want to call that life



21   in the old Roman tradition, and that one-eighth of the time



22   they would all vote for death.  But I had real numbers because



23   I knew what my jurors had done in the severed condition.  And



24   that's shown on page 2 where I can look at each defendant



25   separately and see to what extent they voted for life and what







                                            113



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   extent they voted for death.



2            So, for example, in Fresno, looking at Table 2, 60.8



3   percent voted for death for defendant Ricardo.  62.9 -- no.



4   I'm -- yes.  62.9 voted for death for this Defendant Juan.  And



5   60.8 voted for Carlos.  They were pretty close.  In the Butte



6   County experiment, they were different.  It doesn't matter.



7   You take whatever set of numbers you get.  You multiply them



8   together, and that gives me the expectation that it would be



9   all death.  And in this case, it was 9.6 percent.



10   Q.  23.3 -- I think it's --



11   A.  I'm sorry.  In Fresno, it's 23.3.



12   Q.  Okay.  Now, what -- what does -- what were your conclusions



13   regarding the lumping effect of the joined capital penalty



14   phase versus the severed penalty phase?



15   A.  Well, as you see, what I found was that whereas the -- the



16   expected number of all three defendants getting death was 23.3,



17   on the scenarios that the respondents had, that actually



18   happened 61.1 percent of the time.  In other words, about three



19   times what -- what one would expect if these were independent



20   decisions was actually happening.



21            Now, if you got a coin that was coming up heads that



22   often, you might suspect that there was something wrong with



23   the coin, especially if you did it often enough as I did here;



24   that in fact, they were not independent; that there was



25   something else going on.







                                            114



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1            Furthermore, when you added the percentage who were



2   expected to vote for life to that, you found that all three



3   voting for all three defendants getting life or all defendants



4   getting death was 29 percent.  It actually happened about



5   76 percent.  Once again, about three times as often.  That



6   suggests to me that there is some process going on here.



7            In both scenarios, which were quite different, where



8   the levels of -- of culpability both in the crime and in their



9   background was -- was different, in the one situation and where



10   involvement in the crime was -- was different, ages were



11   different.  In the other one, there still -- in both of these



12   cases, about three times the expected level of all three



13   defendants getting the same verdict.



14            Now, of course, that doesn't mean that they sometimes



15   didn't get separate verdicts.  It just means that there is an



16   inordinate pressure for -- in my experience, at least based on



17   these experiments, for juries to intertwine their -- their



18   decisions, to consider relative culpability and things of that



19   sort.



20   Q.  Dr. Bronson, how do social scientists account for something



21   like these lumping effects?



22   A.  Well, I don't know about social scientists generally.  I



23   can talk about some of the things that -- that seem to me to be



24   responsible.  You -- you can get generalization.  That is



25   stereotyping, birds of a feather type of -- of thinking.  Guilt







                                            115



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   by association.  Making it very difficult to disentangle



2   what -- what one defendant did from another.  At least making



3   it more difficult.  I'm not suggesting that this is some sort



4   of automatic process or that all defendants will be found --



5   sentenced in the same way, either to life or death.  Only that



6   there are pressures that I would sus -- would -- I think are



7   probably unacceptable in a -- in capital case penalty decision



8   making in that direction.



9   Q.  Let me stop you there.  Might personal characteristics of



10   the defendants be among the factors that would tend to make



11   jurors lump them together?



12   A.  Yes.  And -- and the -- the problem with a -- a joint trial



13   is that it tends to reaffirm -- that is, to make concrete those



14   associations.  Such as a conspiracy, for example.  Here they



15   are sitting together.  That makes it less abstract than the --



16   the general charges or even evidence and contributes to that.



17   Qualities that they may share, whether it's their race, gang



18   membership, any one of a number of other qualities will -- will



19   go in the same direction.  If they are all perhaps the same age



20   are other factors that may tend to -- using that not-so-elegant



21   term, to lump them together.



22   Q.  Might -- might political perspective be among those



23   factors?



24   A.  Well, certainly.  To the extent that -- that we attribute



25   certain qualities to people who share a political perspective,







                                            116



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   what some social scientists have called a master identity that



2   may override other qualities of people.  The best example of



3   that, of course, the one we're most familiar with would be race



4   where there's a tendency to think that all people with a



5   certain racial background or ethnic background tend to have



6   more in common than people who are members of that group



7   believe is the case.



8   Q.  Dr. Bronson, let's talk briefly about your findings on



9   social history, the background of a defendant and so on that



10   you described earlier on pages 4, 5 and 6 of Exhibit G.



11            On Exhibit -- on page 4, Table 6, it's titled



12   Percentage of Fresno Respondents Mentioning Defendants' Social



13   History.  Could you describe for us the findings in these two



14   tables, Table 6 and 7.



15   A.  Yes.  I had been exposed to the same sort of understanding



16   of the importance of social history in capital defense that the



17   defendant -- the witnesses who testified this morning



18   expressed, and so I thought it was important to see if that



19   was -- was a factor.  So what I found was that, as you can see



20   in Table 6, that my respondents were far more likely to say



21   something about social history in the severed version than they



22   were in the joined.  By that I mean they say something he



23   suffered as a child or he's young enough to change or some



24   other quality, that his parents didn't give him a good start or



25   whatever it is that -- that might be considered.







                                            117



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1            And as you can see in -- it's about twice as -- as



2   often.  In fact, when you combine the three cases, in about



3   44 percent of the severed scenarios, social history was



4   mentioned as compared with about half that, 23 percent, in the



5   composite scenario.  And as you can see below, these results



6   are all highly statistically significant, meaning that this is



7   not just some random relationship.  This is something that's



8   real.



9   Q.  I'm -- now, turning to page 5 --



10   A.  And by the way, I was just talking about Fresno there.



11   Just quickly saying there that it's true with respect to Butte



12   County, as well.



13   Q.  A similar strong correlation between mention of social



14   history and severed scenario for the defendant was -- was shown



15   in the Butte study, also?



16   A.  Yes.  That doesn't necessarily show that that's helpful.



17   It sort of expresses a notion that at least from what defense



18   attorneys believe, that that factor was more often considered



19   or written down as a factor in the decision by -- in severed



20   conditions than in joined.



21   Q.  Well, let's -- let's find out what -- what your findings



22   were on the -- whether -- the mention of social history was



23   helpful, to use your word, for the capital defendant.  And



24   turning your attention to page 5, Tables 8 and 9, could you



25   explain to the Court what these tables represent.







                                            118



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   A.  Yes.  This -- this is showing -- dividing up into death



2   penalty verdicts and life verdicts.  LWOP is the phrase we use



3   in California for life without possibility of parole.  Among



4   those who noted social history, 63.3 percent gave death penalty



5   verdicts.  Among those who did not note social history, 72.9



6   percent gave death verdicts, a difference of 10 or 11 percent,



7   a difference that was statistically significant, and 10 or



8   11 percent, that's -- in baseball terms, that's 100 percent --



9   100 points higher batting average which maybe we can relate to



10   in Denver.  And in a jury, it's a little over one person per



11   jury.



12   Q.  Okay.  All right then.  Now, let's turn finally to page 6



13   and Tables 10 and 11 titled Impact on Fresno Respondents in the



14   first table -- Impact on Fresno Respondents of Defendants'



15   Social History Composite versus Severed Scenarios.  What do



16   these tables demonstrate?  What are they meant to -- to show?



17   A.  Well, while we've talked about social history in general,



18   whether in a severed or -- or joined trial, here I'm breaking



19   out the way social history was used at -- and comparing served



20   versus composite scenarios or joined trials to see if a joined



21   scenario affects the extent to which that will also affect the



22   ultimate decision in life versus death, which would seem



23   logical in view of other things we've said.  So as we look at



24   the defendants --



25   Q.  Let me just stop you there to clarify.  So what this table







                                            119



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1   demonstrates is the effect of joinder on the relationship



2   between the respondents' mentioning of social history and their



3   decision whether or not to give death?  Is that fair?



4   A.  Yes.



5   Q.  Okay.



6   A.  And what we see is -- if we look at the defendants, you're



7   looking at Ricardo first.  The -- in the composite scenario of



8   those voting for life who noted social history -- they did



9   both -- what we find is that 33-1/3 percent gave that decision



10   for him.  In the severed scenario, it went to almost a half.



11   48.6 percent.  That is, the severed scenario provided extra



12   force to the use of social history and the finding of a life



13   verdict.  The only one where that wasn't true in the Fresno



14   case is Defendant Juan.



15   Q.  Let me stop you there just to clarify for the record.  For



16   Juan, underneath where the -- the table where it indicates



17   whether the results were statistically significant, there's an



18   indication of NS where the others have a P, probability



19   indicated.  Does that NS mean not statistically significant?



20   A.  Yes.  There was no significance there, but I think it's



21   important to explain it because, to me, it adds validity to



22   everything else, which seems strange in view of the fact that



23   the results don't support my hypothesis, because with all the



24   other defendants, the -- the severed scenario and the use of



25   social history seems to lead to -- to life.







                                            120



    Edward Bronson - Direct



1            But the key thing is that in the Fresno scenario, two



2   of the defendants were young.  One was perhaps 19, the other in



3   his early twenties.  Juan, however, was 30-some-odd.  34 or



4   something like that.  But given the way I coded the data, if



5   somebody mentions the age of the defendant, then I use that as



6   a -- an element of the use of social history.  But clearly,



7   people who talked about Juan's age in this case meant that it



8   was, at least in their own mind, whatever the law might have



9   allowed was aggravating.  It didn't lead to life.  It led to



10   death.



11   Q.  So this is -- to use Judge Campbell's words, this is an



12   example -- age in your scenario was an example of a factor that



13   could be used either as a mitigator or aggravator depending on



14   the jury's perspective?



15   A.  That's right, but more than that, this shows the comparison



16   because I think what he was suggesting was that somebody might



17   want to take the fact that somebody was 21 and use it as an



18   aggravator.  I think that is a little unusual.  Ordinarily,



19   youth is a -- a mitigator and in fact, at least in my state, it



20   would be -- it is used that way, but let's not belabor that.



21   But here, they are using the -- the greater maturity, the older



22   age, the relative greater moral development or expected moral



23   development as an aggravator.  So in that limited circumstance,



24   social history is not helpful, but it really confirms the



25   hypothesis rather than undercuts it.







                                            121







1            MR. THURSCHWELL:  Your Honor, I have about four more



2   questions.  Would you --



3            THE COURT:  Well, I need to recess for other reasons.



4   We'll recess until 1:35.



5            (Recess at 12:05 p.m.)



