ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<P>In a three-day pretrial hearing, Oklahoma City Bombing defendants Timothy McVeigh and

Terry Nichols argued for separate trials. They also pressed the government to turn over

classified information that they said may prove Iraq was involved in the bombing. The

following is a transcript of the Oct. 2, 1996 afternoon proceedings.</P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>

<PRE>







 1                 IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT

                      FOR THE DISTRICT OF COLORADO

 2

     Criminal Action No. 96-CR-68

 3

     UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,

 4

         Plaintiff,

 5

     vs.

 6

     TIMOTHY JAMES McVEIGH and TERRY LYNN NICHOLS,

 7

         Defendants.

 8

     

 9

                          REPORTER'S TRANSCRIPT

10                  (HEARING ON MOTIONS - VOLUME II)



11   



12            Proceedings before the HONORABLE RICHARD P. MATSCH,



13   Judge, United States District Court for the District of



14   Colorado, commencing at 1:30 p.m., on the 2nd day of October,



15   1966, in Courtroom C-204, United States Courthouse, Denver,



16   Colorado.



17



18



19



20



21



22



23



24    Proceeding Recorded by Mechanical Stenography, Transcription

       Produced via Computer by Paul Zuckerman, 1929 Stout Street,

25       P.O. Box 3563, Denver, Colorado, 80294, (303) 629-9285







                                                                 124







 1                             APPEARANCES



 2            JOSEPH H. HARTZLER, SEAN CONNELLY, LARRY A. MACKEY,



 3   BETH WILKINSON, SCOTT MENDELOFF, and VICKI BEHENNA, Special



 4   Attorneys to the U.S. Attorney General, 1961 Stout Street,



 5   Suite 1200, Denver, Colorado, 80294, appearing for the



 6   plaintiff.



 7            STEPHEN JONES, ROBERT NIGH, JR., ROBERT WYATT, and



 8   RICHARD BURR, Attorneys at Law, Jones, Wyatt & Roberts, 114



 9   East Broadway, Suite 100, Post Office Box 472, Enid, Oklahoma,



10   73702-0472, and JERALYN MERRITT, 303 East 17th Avenue, Suite



11   400, Denver, Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant McVeigh.



12            MICHAEL E. TIGAR, RONALD G. WOODS, ADAM THURSCHWELL,



13   and REID NEUREITER, Attorneys at Law, 1120 Lincoln Street,



14   Suite 1308, Denver, Colorado, 80203, appearing for Defendant



15   Nichols.



16                            *  *  *  *  *



17                             PROCEEDINGS



18       (Reconvened at 1:35 p.m.)



19       (Edward Bronson was recalled to the stand.)



20                    DIRECT EXAMINATION CONTINUED



21            THE COURT:  Please be seated.



22   BY MR. THURSCHWELL:



23   Q.  Dr. Bronson, based on your research and knowledge, is it



24   your view that a capital defendant joined with other capital



25   defendants in a penalty phase hearing has a greater likelihood







                                                                 125



                         Edward Bronson - Direct



 1   of receiving a death penalty than the very same defendant who



 2   was tried in a severed penalty phase hearing?



 3   A.  Yes.



 4   Q.  Is it your opinion that a capital defendant joined in a



 5   joint penalty phase hearing will receive -- has a greater



 6   chance to be lumped with other co-defendants and therefore has



 7   a lesser chance of receiving the individualized consideration



 8   that the Supreme Court requires?



 9   A.  Yes.



10   Q.  Is it your opinion based on your research and knowledge



11   that a juror considering a joined capital defendant in a



12   penalty phase hearing is less likely to use that capital



13   defendant's social history in considering whether or not to



14   render a death verdict?



15   A.  Yes.



16   Q.  And based on your answers in particular to the last two



17   questions along with your research, knowledge and experience,



18   is it your opinion that a joined -- the verdict in a joined



19   capital penalty phase hearing is likely to be less reliable



20   than a verdict for a particular defendant in a severed penalty



21   phase hearing?



22   A.  Yes.



23            MR. THURSCHWELL:  No further questions.



24            THE COURT:  Mr. Connelly.



25                          CROSS-EXAMINATION







                                                                 126



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   BY MR. CONNELLY:



 2   Q.  Good afternoon, Dr. Bronson.



 3   A.  Hello again.



 4   Q.  I believe we first met back in Oklahoma City when you



 5   testified in the venue hearing; is that right?



 6   A.  That's right.



 7   Q.  Most of your career, apart from teaching at Chico State,



 8   has been spent trying to lend social science support to the



 9   cause of capital criminal defendants; is that right?



10   A.  It doubt it has had that effect.  I suppose we could differ



11   with the implications of the question; but I'm not going to



12   fight that -- you.



13   Q.  And you're personally opposed as a matter of personal



14   decision to the death penalty.



15   A.  That's correct.



16   Q.  And you have never testified on behalf of the prosecution



17   on any issue in a capital proceeding; is that correct?



18   A.  In a capital proceeding?  I've had murder cases, but I



19   don't think any of them were capital.



20   Q.  So you've never testified on behalf of the prosecution on



21   any issue in a capital proceeding.



22   A.  No, but I'm willing.



23   Q.  We'll get to that later.  Let's talk later.



24            You spent many years of your professional life,



25   especially the early years here in Colorado, trying to







                                                                 127



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   establish death-qualified juries were more conviction prone and



 2   hence unfair to the defense?



 3   A.  Well, when you say "trying to establish," if we could maybe



 4   characterize it a little more even-handedly.  I began that with



 5   a hunch that indeed it may be true in response to the



 6   Witherspoon decision that death-qualified juries are unfair;



 7   and then the research spoke for itself.



 8            But to say that I began to try and show that, it



 9   really isn't quite fair.



10   Q.  Okay.  Your work, in any event, in the form of attitude



11   studies was before the U.S. Supreme Court in Lockhart vs. 



12   McCree; is that correct?



13   A.  That's correct.



14   Q.  And in fact the Supreme Court summarily rejected your work



15   as unworthy of consideration; is that correct?



16   A.  No, they didn't do that.  In fact, the Chief Justice



17   assumed for purposes of the decision that the work showed what



18   it said it did.  I don't think he really believed that, but



19   that's what he said.



20            And then he said even if that's true, it wasn't enough



21   to make the death-qualified jury unconstitutional.



22   Q.  So the Supreme Court did not summarily reject your work as



23   unworthy of consideration?



24   A.  I don't think that's what they said.



25   Q.  Okay.  Professor, have you written a chapter in a book







                                                                 128



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   called Jury Work on the death penalty?



 2   A.  On death qualification.  I think that's what you're



 3   referring to.



 4   Q.  Is the overall chapter entitled -- Chapter 23, "Death



 5   Penalty"?



 6   A.  If that's what the title says, but it's not a general



 7   chapter on the death penalty.



 8            MR. CONNELLY:  Maybe I should mark this.  We've got



 9   No. 11.



10            THE COURTROOM DEPUTY:  What do you want it marked?



11            MR. CONNELLY:  11.  Government 11.



12            THE WITNESS:  Thank you.



13   BY MR. CONNELLY:



14   Q.  Professor, does that look familiar to you?



15   A.  Yes.  As you see, it's on death qualification.



16   Q.  And the overall Chapter 23 is entitled "Death Penalty"; is



17   that correct?



18   A.  Yes.



19   Q.  Could you flip to page 23.70 on that.  It's actually the



20   second page of the excerpt.



21   A.  Just the second page?



22            MR. THURSCHWELL:  Judge, I'm going to object to this



23   as -- on the basis that the Supreme Court opinion in Lockhart 



24   vs. McCree speaks for itself.



25            THE COURT:  I didn't know we were looking at a Supreme







                                                                 129



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   Court opinion.  I thought we were looking at a chapter authored



 2   by the witness.



 3            MR. CONNELLY:  That's correct, your Honor.



 4            THE COURT:  All right.



 5   BY MR. CONNELLY:



 6   Q.  Under the subheading A, could you read that first



 7   paragraph?  It's two sentences, I believe, and it's discussing



 8   the Lockhart opinion; isn't that right?



 9   A.  Yes.



10   Q.  Could you read aloud those first two?



11   A.  Yes.  That's exactly what they said:  "The court in



12   Lockhart started with 15 studies that had been introduced into



13   evidence and concluded that only one study was worthy of



14   consideration.  The attitude studies were summarily rejected."



15   Q.  And that was your words; is that not correct?



16            MR. THURSCHWELL:  Objection, your Honor.  If what's



17   trying to be established here is in fact that the Supreme Court



18   summarily rejected --



19            THE COURT:  No.  I think what's being established or



20   attempted to be established is what this witness said about the



21   Lockhart opinion at an earlier time.  Is that right?



22            MR. CONNELLY:  That is correct, your Honor.



23            THE COURT:  Okay.



24            THE WITNESS:  Yes.



25   BY MR. CONNELLY:







                                                                 130



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   Q.  Okay.  So your position as written in that work is that the



 2   Supreme Court summarily rejected your work as unworthy of



 3   consideration?



 4   A.  Well, they -- that's what the conclusion is; but that



 5   isn't, I think, accurate characterization.  In other words,



 6   attitude studies are different from conviction-prone studies.



 7   And what the court said was that a study testing attitude,



 8   which is what I did, pro prosecution attitudes in some of those



 9   early studies, did not prove the case in terms of conviction



10   proneness, so that it didn't address the question that was



11   directly before the court.



12            In that sense, this is true.



13   Q.  So is it true, or not, as you wrote in there -- is it your



14   opinion as you wrote in there, or not, that the Supreme Court



15   summarily rejected your attitude study as unworthy of



16   consideration?  Is that what you wrote?



17   A.  On the question of whether the death penalty -- the



18   death-qualified jury was unconstitutional.  To that extent, it



19   is true.  They were not irrelevant in terms of what they



20   purported to be.



21   Q.  Did the court's opinion in Lockhart -- and you've read



22   Lockhart; is that correct?



23   A.  It's been awhile, but yes.



24   Q.  Did the court's opinion in Lockhart speak more generally to



25   the uses and value of social science studies in evaluating the







                                                                 131



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   impact of jury decision-making in actual cases?



 2   A.  I'm sure it did.  I don't remember the exact language.  I



 3   think the court was somewhat skeptical of the value of such



 4   work.



 5   Q.  And is it a fact, Professor -- do you recall the court



 6   writing at page 171 of volume 476 that all three of the new



 7   studies were based on the responses of individuals randomly



 8   selected from some segment of the population but who were not



 9   actual jurors sworn under oath to apply the law to the facts of



10   an actual case involving the fate of an actual criminal



11   defendant?  Is that right?  Do you recall that?



12   A.  That seems consistent with the general approach, yes.  I



13   don't remember the exact words.



14   Q.  Do you recall the court writing that it had serious doubts



15   about the value of these study predicting the behavior of



16   actual jurors?



17   A.  If you're reading from the opinion, of course, I'm sure



18   it's accurate.



19   Q.  You recall that as the thrust of the court's opinion?



20   A.  The thrust, I do recall, yes.



21   Q.  I'd like to move on to the severance issue.  You talked a



22   lot, I think, in your direct examination and in your affidavit



23   about the Fresno and Butte County studies; is that correct?



24   A.  That's correct.



25   Q.  But actually, the first study that you did of capital







                                                                 132



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   co-defendants, severance, was in a San Diego case called Ayala;



 2   is that correct?



 3   A.  That's correct.



 4   Q.  And isn't it true, Professor, that your survey in that case



 5   showed, contrary to your testimony today, that respondents



 6   could make an individualized judgment in a capital sentencing



 7   proceeding as long as they were given the facts to



 8   individualize among defendants?



 9   A.  My testimony to that?  That would not have been what that



10   research tended to show.  It showed some tendency -- I think I



11   better just explain.  I don't remember exactly what I



12   testified, but let --



13   Q.  I guess if you could and the question:  Do you recall the



14   testimony showing that respondents could individualize in a



15   joint penalty proceeding?  Do you recall testifying to that



16   effect in that Ayala case?



17   A.  I would say the same thing today.  It's not precluded.



18   It's just interfered with.  It's made more difficult.  That's



19   all.



20   Q.  Didn't your study in Ayala show that the respondents, in



21   fact, did individualize as to the penalty phase?



22   A.  Well, I'd have to answer in the same way.  What I found was



23   a tendency for -- that case involved two brothers -- a tendency



24   to cross-attribute qualities of one defendant to the other;



25   that it muddled their decision-making.  They said things like







                                                                 133



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   as part of that little study that a -- they agreed with the



 2   notion that an older brother can influence a younger brother



 3   and that that would affect the way the younger brother would



 4   behave.  They had difficulty with that.  But that didn't mean,



 5   of course, that they were disabled from considering them, at



 6   least to some extent, as separate.



 7   Q.  The problem you identified in that case was that it was two



 8   brothers who happened to be of a minority race.  Those were the



 9   two key factors in your testimony there; right?



10   A.  That's right.



11   Q.  And your testimony there said that they could not



12   individualize as to the guilt phase but they could



13   individualize as to the penalty phase.  Was that not your



14   testimony?



15   A.  Yes, but I have to tell you that the study that I did



16   there, I would be the first to confess was a very limited study



17   done on the eve of the hearing with -- in a very, very



18   difficult way, using survey research, because it was the only



19   way that we could deal with it and where it was almost



20   impossible to present respondents with a scenario of the trial



21   over the phone in a way that would be useful.  So we had little



22   bits and pieces of attempts to try and get at this problem; and



23   it was very, I think, unsatisfactory.



24   Q.  You didn't tell the San Diego court in that case that your



25   study was flawed, did you?







                                                                 134



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   A.  Oh, it was pretty clear that it was a very limited study.



 2   The most powerful evidence in that case was not my study at



 3   all.  It was the testimony of attorneys who had tried joined



 4   defendants in capital cases.



 5   Q.  Well, if you could look again at Exhibit 11.  That, again,



 6   is your own work in the death penalty book.  Is that not



 7   correct?



 8   A.  This is Chapter 23, yes.



 9   Q.  23.  And Chapter 23.05 talks about severance motions when



10   the co-defendants are related; is that right?



11   A.  Well, if this is mine, I would not have written that part



12   of it.  Let's see.



13            This is chapter -- didn't I write chapter 22 in this



14   book, not 23?  I don't think I even wrote 23.



15   Q.  Okay.



16   A.  I wrote the one that preceded it.



17   Q.  Okay.  Could you look on your rsum.  Your CV is, I



18   believe, Exhibit A.



19   A.  I hope it says 22.



20   Q.  See Exhibit A.  I think it's on page 2, the



21   next-to-the-last entry on that page.



22            THE COURT:  Exhibit A, did you say?



23            MR. CONNELLY:  I think it's Exhibit A.



24            THE COURT:  No.  D.



25            MR. CONNELLY:  D.  I'm sorry.  His CV, in any event.







                                                                 135



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1            THE COURT:  Yes.



 2            THE WITNESS:  Chapter 23.  It sure says that.



 3   BY MR. CONNELLY:



 4   Q.  So that is, in fact, your writing, or at least it purports



 5   to be, under your CV?



 6   A.  That's right.  But the part that I dealt with would have



 7   been the portion that was the critique of the -- the decision



 8   in Lockhart.  That was my responsibility.  I'm a joint -- I



