20   part of the computation in an indirect way, but that's not



21   where I get that number from.



22   Q.  Well, if you look at Exhibit G, Table 5.  That's on page 3.



23   A.  Yes.



24   Q.  I thought your testimony was that in a joint scenario the



25   defendants were three times more likely to be sentenced to







                                                                 146



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   death.



 2   A.  No.  That's not what I said at all.  What I said was



 3   this -- and it is certainly confusing, so maybe I do need to



 4   explain it.  What I said was this:  In a joined trial, you can



 5   get a variety of results.  You could get death, death, death;



 6   you could get death, death, life; you could get life, life,



 7   death.  Those are all possibilities.



 8            Suppose you get death, death, death, for all three



 9   defendants.  Is the likelihood of getting that -- and that's



10   the only thing we're talking about.  That's the lumping I'm



11   talking about -- is that greater than statistical chance would



12   suggest?  And -- what I said was it was three times more likely



13   that all three defendants would get death -- death, death,



14   death -- than one would expect from the likelihood of what



15   respondents ordinarily decided was the appropriate penalty and



16   that the same thing to a lesser extent was true with all three



17   getting life.



18            In other words -- and I'm not sure if I've clarified



19   it.  It isn't just -- it isn't that they're three times more



20   likely to get death.  It's all three will get the same death



21   judgment is three times more likely than one would expect from



22   in severed versions those defendants got the -- in other words,



23   let's compare it this way:  If you had three severed trials,



24   Defendants A, B, C, and what are the chances that A will get



25   death in a severed trial, B will get death in a severed trial







                                                                 147



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   and C will get severed death?  What are the chances that will



 2   happen?  In severed trials, all three will get death.



 3            The calculation was in Butte that it was 9.6 percent



 4   of the time.  I don't know if you need me to explain where that



 5   comes from.  In other words, about 10 percent of the time in



 6   three severed trials all three will get death.



 7            But if you join those three together in the same



 8   trial, what did I find happened?  And I found that in fact all



 9   three got death 36.9 percent of the time.  It was much more



10   likely that all three would get that same death sentence when



11   they were joined.  That's what my calculation has to do with.



12   Q.  And you said it was like flipping coins; that you were



13   just -- if they were really independent, there would be no



14   relationship between one death verdict and another?



15   A.  That's correct.  If they're individualizing, to do that is



16   totally possible, I suppose; but this was pretty dramatic as



17   the extent to which all three got the same death sentence.  And



18   they also got life more often; so to that extent, it would be



19   helpful, I guess, from a defense perspective.



