25   Q.  Let me move on quickly to your opinions in this case, if I







                                                                 152



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   could.  Your affidavit stresses that you don't -- do not think



 2   that severance of co-defendants is required in every capital



 3   case; is that right?



 4   A.  That's right.



 5   Q.  Instead you suggest that it's only the special case with



 6   unusual circumstances in which severance is required even in a



 7   capital case?



 8   A.  Yes.



 9   Q.  I'd like to ask you if you would to give me hypothetically



10   a capital case in which two defendants could fairly be tried in



11   a joint penalty phase.



12   A.  It's difficult (1) because the more I work with it, the



13   more complicated it becomes for me.  On the one hand, for



14   example, if their penalty phases are different, advocating a



15   different theory of mitigation -- we talked about this morning



16   of competing theories.  One has an unblemished record as a



17   young person.  The other has a sorry childhood.  And in effect,



18   you're asking the jury to choose.  Obviously, that poses



19   difficulties.



20            On the other hand, if they have the same kind of



21   background, then -- then you get what is sometimes called



22   "dilution of mitigation," the notion that the first time a jury



23   hears a theory of "please save my life because I had a very



24   terrible childhood," the jury might be a little willing to



25   accept that, to feel special sympathy.







                                                                 153



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1            But when you go back again and ask that same jury to



 2   also save the life of the second defendant, then it might be



 3   more difficult.  And so you've diluted the mitigation theory



 4   that the defense offers.



 5            So my initial thoughts on that have gotten more



 6   complex; and so I guess my answer is that I have more



 7   difficulty with considering the myriad number of potential



 8   issues that complicate joinder in capital cases, because as I



 9   look at more and more of these cases where there are mutual



10   affiliations, confusion, etc., etc., relationships and so on, I



11   find fewer and fewer situations where I'm comfortable with



12   saying that joinder is okay.



13            Obviously, I would be inconsistent with the law if I



14   were to say that there ought to be some per se rule for joinder



15   in capital cases.  I don't think that's true, but it is surely



16   true that I have difficulty once I consider all the facts of



17   whether there are problems in a particular case.



18   Q.  So the short answer is if we want to hire you as a



19   prosecution expert some day, you can't tell me the case in



20   which you'd be willing to testify on behalf of the prosecution.



21   A.  It's really that I haven't thought about it.  The only



22   facts that I've been confronted with by and large have been



23   facts that seem to speak in favor of -- of severance.  But



24   maybe I do need to think more about -- think about what facts



25   that I haven't dealt with yet would not constitute a -- a







                                                                 154



                          Edward Bronson - Cross



 1   strong case for severance.



 2            And it's certainly true, and I don't want to back off



 3   of this, because it would be inconsistent with what I found and



 4   what I've seen:  Surely the fact that it's a capital case makes



 5   it a much stronger candidate for severance than anything else.



 6   And I've never dealt with any noncapital severances except in



 7   the case, for example, of some of those in New Mexico, where



 8   there were noncapital defendants joined with capital defendants



 9   and there were also issues of the severance of the noncapital



10   defendants.



