 8   Psychology; Law and Society Review; Memory; Memory and



 9   Cognition; Organizational Behavior and Human Decision



10   Processes; Psychological Review; The Psychonomic Bulletin and



11   Review, and Social Cognition.



12   Q.  And what is your role as a member of the board of these



13   professional journals?



14   A.  The thing that I spend most of my time on is reading papers



15   and reviews of papers that have been submitted for publication



16   and making decisions about whether to publish them in the



17   journal.  Probably I misspoke.  An equal amount of time is



18   spent reviewing the papers myself directly and advising other



19   editors about their publishability, acceptability.



20   Q.  Thank you.  Have you, yourself, conducted research in the



21   field of psychology?



22   A.  Yes.



23   Q.  And into what areas have you conducted research?  Or to



24   shorten this a bit, let me ask you:  What has been the primary



25   focus of your research and writing over the past 24 years?







                                                                 158



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   A.  I would say jury and juror decision-making.



 2   Q.  Have you ever conducted a study that attempted to measure



 3   whether or not a capital defendant was more likely to get the



 4   death penalty if -- in a joined trial as opposed to a severed



 5   trial?



 6   A.  No, I have not.



 7   Q.  Do you know of anyone who has?



 8   A.  I guess Dr. Bronson is the only one I know of.



 9   Q.  Have you attempted to research the literature to see if



10   there was other writings or research available?



11   A.  Yes.  I wouldn't commit to having absolutely thoroughly



12   researched it because I was called on this issue only at the



