15   Q.  You, yourself, have published many articles, have you not,



16   though, in the area of jury decision-making?



17   A.  Yes.



18   Q.  In a variety of journals all as set forth in your



19   curriculum vitae?



20   A.  I'm sorry.  I missed --



21   Q.  In a variety of journals all as set forth in your



22   curriculum vitae?



23   A.  Yes, they're all cited in the curriculum vitae.



24   Q.  After Dr. Bronson was identified by the Nichols team as a



25   potential witness in this case, you were contacted last week by







                                                                 159



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   the prosecution, Mr. Sean Connelly, to consult with the United



 2   States regarding this issue of severance.



 3   A.  Yes.



 4   Q.  And what were you asked to undertake?



 5   A.  I was asked to read the briefs that had been submitted by



 6   the various defense attorneys and the prosecution on this issue



 7   of severance; and included in that, of course, was



 8   Dr. Bronson's affidavit.  And that's -- and I was asked to



 9   evaluate specifically Dr. Bronson's research quality and his



10   conclusions.



11            And then was asked the more general question of did I



12   know of other research that would yield conclusions -- social



13   science research that would yield conclusions on the issues of



14   severance.



15   Q.  And have you undertaken that work?



16   A.  Yes.



17   Q.  And are you prepared to testify today with respect to your



18   analysis of Dr. Bronson's work?



19   A.  Yes.



20   Q.  Would you explain the -- what is meant by the term



21   "experimenter expectancy"?



22   A.  Yes.  It's a term that was introduced in the 1960's by a



23   researcher named Robert Rosenthal, and it's a summary label for



24   the biases that can sometimes occur when an experimenter



25   deliberately or inadvertently designs research that is biassed







                                                                 160



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   to produce conclusions that the researcher assumes are true or



 2   expects to be true before they conduct the research.



 3   Q.  Prior to consulting with the United States in this matter,



 4   were you aware of Dr. Bronson's attitudes with respect to the



 5   death penalty?



 6   A.  Yes.  I wouldn't say I was well acquainted with them; but I



 7   was involved in another hearing with Dr. Bronson, and I heard



 8   his testimony and I guess I have a view that he repeated



 9   earlier today about his opposition to the death penalty.



10   Q.  And you're aware through his testimony today that he



11   testifies in a variety of contexts with respect to death



12   penalty issues?



13   A.  Yes.



14   Q.  In your opinion, is experimenter's expectancy a factor in



15   your evaluation of Dr. Bronson's study?



16   A.  Yes.  It's a consideration raised by my examination of his



17   affidavit.



18   Q.  Could you explain that to the Court?



19   A.  Well, there is one definite signal of Dr. Bronson's



20   expectancy, and it's a bit of a technical signal that I think



21   almost any expert reading the affidavit would note.  He follows



22   a procedure to establish whether or not his results are



23   statistically significant or reliable called a "one-tailed



24   significance test procedure."



25            This is not a weird or totally unusual procedure, but







                                                                 161



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   it is certainly uncommon and unconventional and nonstandard.



 2   Several of the textbooks of statistics for behavioral



 3   scientists identify it as a procedure that is never, if -- or



 4   virtually ever justified.



 5            When the more, let's say, liberal textbooks discuss



 6   the conditions under which you might use a one-tailed test, the



 7   justification that is allowed is if before you conduct your



 8   experiment, you have a definite expectancy that result in only



 9   one direction or a no result is likely to occur, then the one-



10   tailed significance test procedure is warranted.  Otherwise, if



11   you are, if you will, more conservative or open-minded about



12   the results you expect might be produced by your research, you



13   would do the much more common standard two-tailed test.



14            And when I read Dr. Bronson's affidavit, I was



15   actually surprised to discover that throughout it, he followed



16   the one-tailed test procedure, so that the hypothesis, the



17   statistical hypothesis he was testing, was only whether the



18   joined groups would be more likely to convict or more likely to



19   confuse than the severed groups.  So by the choice of that



20   test, if he was an ethical researcher who follows the rules in



21   our statistics books, he is asserting to any social scientist



22   who read it that the result he is expecting and the result he



23   is testing for is either a no result or a result in the



24   direction of this -- you could call it "expectation" that he



25   stated on the stand earlier when he was cross-examined that the







                                                                 162



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   joined defendants would be convicted at a higher rate and



 2   confused more often.



 3   Q.  Dr. Hastie, have you had an opportunity to examine the --



 4   to the extent that you can -- the materials Dr. Bronson used



 5   and the questionnaires that he used in connection with his



 6   Fresno and Butte studies?



 7   A.  Yes.



 8   Q.  And do you have a judgment that you could share with the



 9   Court as to the realism of these materials and procedures that



10   Dr. Bronson used in his experiments?



11   A.  Considering the spectrum of social science research on



12   juror decision-making, mock juror decision-making, I would say



13   that they are towards the low -- low fidelity end of realism



14   for social science studies of juror decisions.



15   Q.  Why is that?



16   A.  Well, there are a list of conditions.  I think most of them



17   came out in his testimony, so I will try to telegraph the list.



18   First of all, there was relatively little control over his



19   subjects' behavior.  The questionnaires were made to them to



20   fill out, ad lib at home, and then return at will, or handed to



21   them in classrooms where they were not carefully supervised as



22   to time and attentiveness to the task.  So it was a relatively,



23   we would say, low controlled experiment.



24            Second, there were no obvious incentives aside from



25   the desire to be a volunteer, the desire to cooperate, and







                                                                 163



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   possibly the desire to have a vehicle to express a personal



 2   attitude about the legal system, to motivate subjects to



 3   perform the task.  Presumably, again, if the study was



 4   conducted ethically in the classrooms, the students were given



 5   the choice of participating or not.  That's a fundamental rule



 6   of all of our professional societies; that you can't coerce



 7   subjects into performing the task.



 8            And obviously, as I think it's clear from



 9   Dr. Bronson's testimony, there was no money incentive, no



10   authority figure, or other pressure to comply.



11            Similarly, as Dr. Bronson noted in some remarks and



12   especially in the affidavit with reference to research that has



13   studied jurors' capacity to comply with instructions from a



14   judge, this study is about as low pressure or low fidelity with



15   reference to the force with which the judicial instructions are



16   presented to the subjects.  I believe in the questionnaires



17   there was maybe 150 words at most out of 4,000 that were the



18   judge's instructions; and, of course, they were written in the



19   middle of this quite lengthy -- well, fairly lengthy for a



20   15-minute period questionnaire; so it was very low on the issue



21   of was there a motivation or a pressure to comply with



22   instructions from in this case the reigning judicial authority.



23            A fourth condition that has been referred to is that,



24   in my judgment, the materials are inadvertently or deliberately



25   designed to produce very high levels of confusability of the







                                                                 164



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   defendants.  The defendants were identified by proper names,



 2   sometimes by the same proper name and sometimes by what were



 3   obviously nonsense fictional proper names, Abel, Baker, and



 4   Charlie.  It's actually a total coincidence in this case, but I



 5   would say I'm the national authority on the issue of what makes



 6   people individuate other people.



 7            I would say the lead article ever written in



 8   psychology -- this surprises me; it occurred to me today when



 9   we were sitting here -- is the 1974 paper with John Anderson in



10   which we compare the individuating facts of proper names versus



11   other kinds of descriptions.  And among other things we



12   discovered that if you included a photograph, even in an



13   artificial laboratory study, it multiplied the individuate --



14   individualization of the persons being judged.  These were not



15   legal judgments; these were other inferential judgments.



16            So what Bronson inadvertently did was produce the



17   worst conditions, given research that I've conducted on



18   independent individuation of persons to produce unconfusable or



19   individuated people.  And that was consistent in both of his



20   experimental studies.



21   Q.  Do you recall what the names were of the hypothetical



22   defendants in the Fresno study?



23   A.  Alvarez, Alvarez, and Ricardo, I believe.



24   Q.  Three Hispanics, two of which had the same last name?



25   A.  Yes.







                                                                 165



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   Q.  And in the Butte study it was Abel, Baker, and Charlie?



 2   A.  Right.



 3   Q.  Was -- do you have any criticism in the manner in which the



 4   questions were posed to the subjects in Dr. Bronson's study?



 5   A.  Okay.  Well, this is really a two-part answer.  First of



 6   all, I would say it's a standard conclusion in survey



 7   methodology that when you want well motivated or complete or



 8   precise answers from subjects, whenever possible, you present



 9   them with alternatives.  We might call it a multiple choice



10   survey question and answer and ask them to choose among them.



11            But much of the -- I guess I would say all of the data



12   that Dr. Bronson used to draw conclusions about the lack of



13   attention to mitigating circumstances and so forth is taken



14   from responses to open-ended questions, which, in survey



15   approaches, are -- it's virtually an axiom of the field, a form



16   of question that will be likelier to elicit incomplete



17   responses.



18            So the first problem is -- and I could suggest



19   alternative forms of designing this questionnaire, but the



20   first problem is just the sole reliance on an open-ended



21   question to identify what factors subjects related to, to make



22   their judgments.



23            The second problem derives from the comparison between



24   joined and severed conditions, and it's already been



25   highlighted in the cross-exam.







                                                                 166



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1            We have subjects who are not very highly motivated, I



 2   would bet, to perform the task.  They're killing 15 minutes



 3   before class starts, or they're responding to a mail



 4   questionnaire, under what circumstances we don't know, talking



 5   to other people, watching television.  All of those are likely,



 6   I suspect, for some respondents.



 7            And we have one group of the subjects, the joined



 8   subjects, reading twice as much or one and a half to twice as



 9   much, very dense material, and then answering three times as



10   many open-ended questions, the questions that I've already said



11   are known to under-sample people's responses.



12            So what we have is a situation that's designed with



13   the combination of open-ended question and higher workload for



14   the joined subjects, is a situation where the joined subjects



15   are, under any principle of psychology or economics, going to



16   respond less fully and less completely.  They would have to



17   write three times as much, for example, to be as specific as



18   the severed respondents.



19            And I guess a lot of the responses in those conditions



20   that I believe Dr. Bronson interpreted as examples of confusion



21   or lack of individuation are very likely to result from



22   something else that's well known in survey research, and that's



23   known as the general sociolinguistic principle of responding



24   informatively and nonredundantly.  So, in fact, if a respondent



25   in the joined condition really did have similar reasons to







                                                                 167



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   apply or choose a penalty for two of the subjects, it's very



 2   likely they would respond by leaving the second one blank or



 3   using ditto marks or some other telegraphic remark just because



 4   of -- you might call it norms of everyday communication.



 5   Q.  One of Dr. Bronson's conclusions in his affidavit was that



 6   jurors in joint proceedings tend to ignore or underweigh



 7   mitigating circumstances.  Do you have a judgment about his



 8   conclusion in that area?



 9   A.  Yes, I do.



10   Q.  What is that?



11   A.  I'm not persuaded that his conclusion is reliable or



12   general.



13   Q.  What is the foundation for your judgment?



14   A.  Well, I've actually just commented on some of the reasons:



15   The fact that the open-ended questions is -- especially when



16   the question has to be answered three times in the joined



17   condition, are -- you don't have to be a social scientist to



18   figure this out -- are biassed to produce incomplete answers,



19   answers that don't express all of the actual considerations



20   that were thought about when the decision was made.



21            Another comment is that the way that someone would



22   establish whether a factor like a mitigating factor that might



23   be mentioned in the penalty phase was relied on or not, the



24   convincing way to study whether that factor is relied on or not



25   relied on or has an effect, is to manipulate its presence.  And







                                                                 168



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   in fact, many of the studies that Dr. Bronson cited in his



 2   affidavit and alluded to in court are studies of just that:



 3   The extent to which a mock juror relies on or does not rely on



 4   testimony that they're instructed not to attend to by a judge.



 5            And I'd say almost all of those experiments -- perhaps



 6   there is one exception -- included that manipulation in order



 7   to answer exactly that question:  Was the testimony that was



 8   stricken or limited actually ignored, or not?



 9            And the way to test that is to manipulate whether it's



10   present; and if it's present, you can compare it to the control



11   group where it wasn't present and see if it actually had an



12   effect.



13            In these studies, Dr. Bronson didn't try to study that



14   question; and I don't think his research gives an answer to the



15   question of whether the mitigating information is weighted more



16   heavily or less heavily in any particular groups of his



17   subjects.



18   Q.  Do you recall in Dr. Bronson's testimony that he draws the



19   conclusion that if the defendants are tried jointly, there is



20   more likelihood that they'll receive the death penalty?  And he



21   does that by multiplying the percentage of each individual



22   defendant by the percentage of the second defendant by the



23   percentage of the third defendant and reaches an overall



24   percentage of what one would expect if the three defendants



25   were tried separately, what the odds are that each of them







                                                                 169



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   would get the death penalty?



 2   A.  Well, I need to clarify.  There is one effect in his



 3   results and that is in the joined condition, there is a higher



 4   probability for a subject in the joined condition to give the



 5   death penalty to one of the fictional defendants as compared to



 6   the severed condition.  That's one effect.



 7            The other effect that you're referring to, actually,



 8   involves comparing those effects; and it's the issue that was



 9   referred to in cross-examination when Mr. Connelly questioned



10   him about the hypothetical triplets; and that's the extent to



11   which the mock jurors' judgment will individuate the



12   defendants, the extent to which the judgments appear to be



13   dependent on one another, at least statistically.



14            I actually think that Dr. Bronson's results and



15   possibly -- although I really think we need a higher level



16   probability theorist.  I've had quite a few courses in



17   probability theory, and this is a very complex calculation that



18   he does.  It's deceptively simple, and I'm not sure I fully



19   understand it.



20            But I'll accept at least conditionally that it



21   actually makes the point that there is a dependency in



22   judgments.  What I think is puzzling about that is that there



23   are different kinds of dependencies; some dependencies that



24   would be legally illegitimate: for example, if the mock juror



25   said whenever the defendant is Hispanic, I'm going to give them







                                                                 170



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   the death penalty, and in fact, I have three Hispanics here, so



 2   I'm going to go death penalty, death penalty, death penalty



 3   down the line because they're Hispanic.



 4            Or it would be illegitimate if the mock juror or the



 5   juror got confused about the defendants and remembered that all



 6   three of the defendants were sexually abused or were similar in



 7   age when they weren't.  So those would be illegitimate



 8   dependencies.



 9            But it seems to me there would be a lot of legitimate



10   dependencies, and that's what the triplets question, I think,



11   was designed to get at.  For example, I might believe that the



12   crime should be weighted not exclusively but more than the



13   mitigating circumstances.  And in Dr. Bronson's materials, the



14   criminal acts were virtually identical.  And so that would



15   produce a dependency, in my judgment, for these three



16   defendants; a reasonable, I think justifiable dependency.



17            Similarly, I might have a dependency that went the



18   other way.  I might have a very low personal appetite for the



19   death penalty.  I might not be a nullifier, but I might take a



20   very, very high level of conviction or threshold to produce the



21   death penalty.  And then for almost any triplet of



22   defendants -- certainly, for the defendants in these example



23   materials with the vast number of mitigating circumstances -- I



24   would come in with highly correlated or dependent judgments.



25            I can illustrate this point -- I'm probably going on







                                                                 171



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   too long, but I think it's an interesting argument -- with



 2   another hypothetical.



 3            Suppose we ran Dr. Bronson's joined condition so that



 4   we have one mock juror making all three judgments, but we run



 5   it over a nine-year period; so in the first administration, our



 6   mock juror hears the information and judges the first



 7   defendant.  Then three years later, we go back and we have the



 8   same mock juror joined in this hypothetical make the second



 9   judgment.  And then three years later, we go back and get the



10   third judgment.  I would expect there is a correlation within a



11   juror of those judgments but not a silly or an illegitimate



12   correlation.  They would have a habit of weighting the factors



13   the same way that I would assume for this example would persist



14   over nine years; they would have a level or a threshold for



15   administering or saying yes to the death penalty and those



16   would be consistent, I'm assuming, for the example; and they



17   would produce interdependencies in the judgments.



18            And in my hypothetical, I think confusability is an



19   unlikely possibility with the three-year interval.  I think



20   some of the other carryover effects or contamination effects



21   lumping-together effects would be very unlikely with that



22   interval, but I think we'd still get correlations in the



23   judgment.



24            So I'm not quite sure why the finding of a correlation



25   is necessarily a devastating problem.  I'm sure I spent too







                                                                 172



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   long on that example, but I've been struggling with the logic



 2   of it for a few hours.



 3   Q.  To what extent would you as a social scientist be willing



 4   to rely on Dr. Bronson's experimentations and his conclusions



 5   regarding the jointly tried capital defendants?



 6   A.  Well, I regret to say that I don't believe that these



 7   studies provide a substantial basis to draw any conclusions



 8   about what would happen if the McVeigh/Nichols defendants were



 9   joined or severed.



10   Q.  I'd like to ask you a few questions about the term



11   "external validity."  Would you explain to the Court what that



12   term means?



13   A.  It's another sort of background term in psychological



14   research, and Dr. Bronson uses it himself several places in the



15   affidavit.



16            It refers in my vocabulary to the -- if you have a



17   finding in one setting -- and let's take the experimental



18   setting -- so if we've got a conclusion that we believe is a



19   valid, correct conclusion about our experiment, to what other



20   situations can we generalize that conclusion?  To what external



21   situations does the result that we're sure is correct in our



22   original situation applicable?  And that's what external



23   validity refers to.



24   Q.  So even if we were willing for the sake of argument to



25   accept Dr. Bronson's conclusions were validly drawn based on







                                                                 173



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   valid methodology and valid experiments, do you think that



 2   those studies would have any external validity to the facts of



 3   this case?



 4   A.  Emphasizing that it's hypothetical as to whether the



 5   original results are valid, reliable, I would say that the



 6   external validity with reference to the Nichols/McVeigh



 7   situation is extremely weak, perhaps -- well, extremely weak.



 8   Q.  Did you -- I think Dr. Bronson indicated that he had never



 9   attempted to publish any of his work except in this criminal



10   defense publication in California.



11            Based on your experience in serving on all of these



12   various editorial boards for the professional journals that you



13   testified to earlier, would a manuscript such as Dr. Bronson's



14   be publishable in a recognized peer review refereed



15   professional journal?



16   A.  If it was the same article or was an article based closely



17   on the affidavit, I would say the probability is extremely low



18   for any of the 50 or so journals that I've worked for or



19   reviewed for.



20   Q.  Why is that?



21   A.  Well --



22   Q.  I don't want you to repeat everything.  If it's a



23   repetition of what you've already told the Court, then just say



24   so; or if there are some additional reasons, please identify



25   them.







                                                                 174



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   A.  It's essentially the reasons I've mentioned before with a



 2   further comment that the -- one of the critical editorial



 3   functions of these relatively conservative scientific journals



 4   is that they're, again, fairly conservative on what conclusions



 5   the author is allowed to draw beyond the data.  And so I'd add



 6   a little speech about how I believe Dr. Bronson has gone very



 7   far beyond what his data implies in the conclusions in the



 8   paper.  So both with reference to the quality of the research



 9   and the logic with which he's drawn conclusions, I think the



10   paper would have a great deal of trouble.



11   Q.  We've talked about Dr. Bronson's studies and the fact that



12   you believe those are an insubstantial basis to draw



13   conclusions.  I'd now like to turn to the more general subject



14   of behavioral science literature and ask you if there is any



15   behavioral science literature that impacts on this question of



16   joinder.



17   A.  Well, Dr. Bronson is absolutely correct that at least he



18   and I don't know of any studies aside from his that look at the



19   specific mechanism or issue of joinder or severance of



20   defendants at trial in the empirical social science literature.



21            There are related literatures, and Dr. Bronson and the



22   defense attorneys in their brief have cited them.  The closest



23   literatures, I would say, are literatures of research about



24   joinder of charges for a single defendant and then literature



25   on the effects on a juror of making repeated judgments in







                                                                 175



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   completely separate trials of different trials with different



 2   charges.  And then there is the literature that is also, I'd



 3   say, relevant on mock jurors and jurors' willingness and



 4   capacity to comply with instructions to limit the use of



 5   evidence or to disregard evidence.



 6   Q.  Without asking you to review all of that literature, let me



 7   ask a general question:  Is it possible to draw conclusions



 8   from this body of behavioral literature as to what impact



 9   joinder will have on capital sentencing and the jury's ability



10   to give individualized consideration to each defendant?



11   A.  I have to say that the literature yields a lot of



12   conflicting implications.  My reading of it is extremely



13   different than the summary in the defense briefs; that, for



14   example, the literature is unanimous in finding jurors'



15   capacity in regard to following instructions to disregard



16   evidence -- is severely limited.



17            My reading of the literature -- and it included quite



18   a different collection of citations, but it also included some



19   that the defense cited -- found a much more mixed picture, not



20   a unanimous picture at all.



21            In almost half of the studies on the issue of capacity



22   to comply with the instruction to disregard or limit from the



23   same journals as the other studies, the result was that,



24   apparently, the mock jurors could comply.



25            My own research -- and I guess it's one reason I stay







                                                                 176



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1   in the business that I'm in -- has found that jurors and juries



 2   are conscientious and, if anything, lenient in their decisions



 3   with regard to defendants.



 4            I also think that in these situations, the possibility



 5   of confusion or failure to independently individuate in a



 6   realistic trial or in the trial that's going to occur here is



 7   of extremely low magnitude and, in my view, almost



 8   discountable.



 9            So speaking very generally, I think there are



10   tentative conclusions from a thorough balanced review of the



11   literature; and my tentative -- well, I have a tentative



12   conclusion.



13   Q.  What is your tentative conclusion?



14   A.  It's -- I guess my best judgment is that the issues of



15   independent individuation, confusion and failure to comply with



16   the judge's instructions at both the guilt and the penalty



17   phase with reference to limiting use of the testimony that I've



18   been told is or has been foregrounded in the briefs and the



19   issues that are -- could possibly arrive at the penalty phase



20   when the defendants need to be independently individuated are



21   not a major threat in this trial.



22            MR. RYAN:  That's all I have, your Honor.  I'll pass



23   the witness.



24            MR. TIGAR:  I don't need a recess, your Honor, unless



25   you plan to take it at this time.







                                                                 177



                           Reid Hastie - Direct



 1            THE COURT:  No.  Let's go ahead.



 2                          CROSS-EXAMINATION



 3   BY MR. TIGAR:



