10   that case.



11   Q.  Well, let me just ask you this, because it's only related



12   to this "jurors' following instructions" question.  You



13   concluded in your article, didn't you, that initial questioning



14   can so taint an eyewitness identification as to make it



15   unreliable; correct?



16   A.  Yes, I did.



17   Q.  Now, in addition to that, sir, you're aware that sometimes



18   judges change venue in cases; correct?



19   A.  Yes.



20   Q.  And that has to do with a lack of confidence, doesn't it,



21   at least in part, that jurors can be trusted when they say I



22   can put out of my mind what I've read in the media; correct?



23   A.  Yes, that's right.



24   Q.  You've also in the literature talked about something called



25   "The Story."  Is that right?







                                                                 185



                           Reid Hastie - Cross



 1   A.  Yes.  That's right.



 2   Q.  Well, what do you mean by "The Story"?



 3   A.  I'll try to keep it really brief.



 4   Q.  Yeah.



 5   A.  My general theory about the typical juror's decision



 6   process is that he or she spends most of the time during the



 7   guilt judgment phase -- and if I had thought about it harder,



 8   probably during the penalty phase, but the phase I've studied



 9   is the guilt phase -- trying to construct a story that they



10   believe that summarizes the facts that they think are credible



11   and that is internally coherent.  And once they've constructed



12   that story, they use it to make further inferences; for



13   example, whether the defendant is guilty of a crime that the



14   judge describes to them.



15   Q.  And that -- that notion of "The Story "-- that's -- that's



16   a theory of human cognition, isn't it?



17   A.  Perhaps that general; but in this example, it's a theory of



18   how the typical juror makes a decision in a civil or a criminal



19   case.



20   Q.  And do you attribute that theory that you've told us about,



21   "The Story," in part to the gestalt theories?



22   A.  Well, no, but that's beside the point.  It's a kind of



23   gestalt theory, but it doesn't derive in any simple way from



24   the historical tradition of gestalt psychology.  But I don't



25   think --







                                                                 186



                           Reid Hastie - Cross



 1   Q.  Doctor, I'm not going to try to follow you down that road



 2   even if you wanted to go there.



 3            Let's come back to the story.  When jurors read about



 4   aggravated crime that's had a lot of publicity, they're likely



 5   to come to court with a story partly formed, aren't they?



 6   A.  Yes.  That's one possible effect of pretrial publicity, for



 7   example.



 8   Q.  And there sure has been pretrial publicity in this case,



 9   hasn't there, sir?



10   A.  Yes.



11   Q.  In fact, before you ever heard about you were going to be a



12   witness in this case, you had some views about it, didn't you?



13   A.  Well, I'm virtually out of contact with any media.  I've



14   never seen a report of this case on television.  In fact, I've



15   never read a newspaper article about the case.



16   Q.  Then you're an exception.  I'll go on to something else.



17   A.  I'm unusual.



18   Q.  So our average juror who has read a lot comes with a kind



19   of a story?



20   A.  Yes.



21   Q.  Now, in the guilt phase of a trial, jurors are trying to



22   make sense of an event that happened in the historic past; is



23   that correct?



24   A.  That's the way I describe it.



25   Q.  And if the alleged participation of two people in the







                                                                 187



                           Reid Hastie - Cross



 1   historic past is very, very different, jurors can have trouble



