                                                                 196



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1   that they under -- sort of gain their -- my understanding of



 2   their understanding of the various aspects of the case and



 3   to -- we did it for the purpose of improving our skills as



 4   prosecutors and try and be sure that our -- the prosecutors



 5   that worked for me that were -- were doing the best job they



 6   could.



 7   Q.  And did you do that in the single defendant case -- capital



 8   cases as well as the three capital -- joint capital cases



 9   you've spoken of?



10   A.  Yes.



11   Q.  Can you draw any conclusions with respect to following your



12   interviews with these capital jurors as to their ability to



13   recall details of the case or to separate the facts with



14   respect to various defendants?



15   A.  I was always very favorably impressed with the intensity



16   with which the juries concentrated on the various aspects of



17   our cases and their ability to recall sometimes even two and



18   three weeks later the facts and circumstances that were -- that



19   came through the evidence that was presented to them from



20   the -- from the witness chairs.  I thought they had good



21   ability to recall it, and obviously, they -- they cared very



22   much about trying to reach the right result.  And consequently,



23   they really did listen and pay attention and try to remember



24   and -- and try to reach the right result.



25   Q.  Did they frequently express to you the importance of the







                                                                 197



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1   decision that they had undertaken regarding deciding whether or



 2   not a capital defendant should live or die?



 3   A.  Yes.  In my view, the -- the obvious most difficult



 4   decision any juror is called upon to make is the death penalty



 5   decision.  And you could tell that they truly in many cases



 6   agonized over that decision.  And that if there was a good --



 7   good reason -- they could find some good reason not to -- to



 8   invoke the death penalty, quite often, they did not or at least



 9   some of them did not.  And that was tantamount to the whole



10   jury not invoking the death penalty.



11            They really, again -- I feel like jurors in all cases



12   really try to do the right thing, but obviously that is



13   heightened to some degree in death penalty cases.  They live



14   and die with their verdict and they live and die with the



15   testimony that is there and they carry it with them even years



16   afterwards.



17   Q.  Did you get calls at night from capital defendants --



18   excuse me -- capital jurors?



19   A.  Yeah.  Not, obviously, during the trial, but sometimes



20   later, people would call me up and -- and ask to talk about,



21   you know -- mostly they want me to hear them.  It wasn't they



22   were really trying to get anything from me as much as -- they



23   were retrying the case in their mind and they were -- they were



24   wanting to discuss it with -- something that was still living



25   with them.







                                                                 198



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1   Q.  Following the -- their decision, did they come to your



 2   office?



 3   A.  Most -- occasionally, although mostly it would be the



 4   hallway.  Our jurors were there for, like, three weeks for a



 5   jury term.  And so if they tried the case in the first few days



 6   of the term, quite often, they would stop me in the hall later



 7   and -- and/or visit with me about the case and talk about it.



 8   And again, mostly, it was a matter of their telling me, you



 9   know, what they remembered about it and what was important to



10   them and that -- that sort of thing.



11   Q.  Did you hear the testimony of Dr. Bronson?



12   A.  Yes.  I did.



13   Q.  Did you hear him describe the 15 minutes in which students



14   and other citizens filled out a -- read a questionnaire and



15   filled it out with respect to whether they would give the death



16   penalty?



17   A.  Yes, I heard that.



18   Q.  How do you think -- how realistic do you think that type of



19   experiment is when compared to real-life capital cases?



20   A.  Well, of course, I just heard about it for the first time



21   today, but it did occur to me that the thing that I found from



22   jurors, that in talking, and the thing that seemed to me



23   obvious was that when they sit in a courtroom for three or four



24   weeks or five weeks and they look at the defendants, they



25   really become people to them.







                                                                 199



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1            And it seemed to me that the flaw in that study was



 2   that it does disregard to some degree the -- the human elements



 3   of the people identifying with and seeing a person there that



 4   they are trying for a heinous crime and they -- they are there



 5   with them and they see them walk and talk and laugh and they



 6   become a real person.  And I think that -- I think it's a good



 7   thing about the system because it makes it that much more



 8   difficult to assess the death penalty.



 9            But I think it seems to me that reading some papers



10   off a script somewhere and -- and trying to compare that to the



11   process of sitting there, hearing able counsel extol the



12   virtues or talk about the mitigation of a person and seeing



13   that person in their real persona and -- and being exposed to



14   them for a long period of time is such a substantially



15   different thing that I don't know how you could credit the



16   other very much.



17   Q.  Are you familiar with Stephen Jones?



18   A.  Yes, sir.



19   Q.  And again, this line of questioning will cause me great



20   pain, but I'll do it nonetheless.  Would you regard Mr. Jones



21   as a very competent trial counsel?



22   A.  I do indeed.  I had the privilege of trying a case against



23   Mr. Jones some years ago, and we handled two or three other



24   things together.  And that was a -- quite a number of years



25   ago.  He just continued to grow in stature.  I think he is







                                                                 200



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1   clearly one of the finest, if not the finest criminal defense



 2   lawyer in Oklahoma, certainly a gifted advocate, able lawyer,



 3   and certainly one who will do a great job in defending any



 4   client that he undertakes to represent.



 5   Q.  Do you know Mr. Tigar?



 6   A.  I do.  By reputation mostly.  And -- although I have been



 7   in situations -- a litigation situation which he was involved



 8   some years ago, I -- I argued a case in the Tenth Circuit right



 9   behind him arising out of a similar fact situation in Oklahoma



10   City.  And again, he is nationally known as an extremely able



11   and -- and brilliant trial lawyer and, again, a gifted advocate



12   and, certainly, one who would be a formidable opponent.  I



13   don't think that Judge Russell, if he made the appointments,



14   did the Government any favor by selection of counsel in this



15   case.



16   Q.  Do you have an opinion as to whether Mr. Jones and



17   Mr. Tigar are capable of differentiating the proof for the



18   benefit of the jury against their client from the proof against



19   the other in a joint trial?



20   A.  I wish all the questions I had to answer were as easy as



21   that one.  I have no question at all that those gentlemen will



22   clearly differentiate themselves and their clients from each



23   other in the minds of the jurors, the spectators, the judge, or



24   anybody else that's in the vicinity; that they will indeed do a



25   remarkable job of representing their clients as I think all







                                                                 201



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1   people can already see through the early stages of this trial.



 2   And I don't think there will be any question there will be any



 3   confusion in anybody's mind about the clients or the lawyers in



 4   this case.



 5   Q.  Did you -- have you also interviewed noncapital juries with



 6   respect to their ability in joint cases, joint trials, to



 7   differentiate the evidence as to each defendant?



 8   A.  Yes, I think "interview" is probably too strong a word.  I



 9   have talked with them, and, of course, I have seen their



10   reactions and been in so many of those cases.  And juries



11   invariably, I think, judge each person on their own merits and



12   clearly differentiate between defendants and the people accused



13   of crimes.  They quite often convict some defendants and turn



14   some away, acquit some.  They -- they quite often have various



15   judgments in terms of severity of the punishment as between



16   defendants in the same case.  I -- it just goes on all the



17   time.  I've never seen situations where I felt the juries did



18   not make a differentiation, if one was properly deserved, as



19   between joint defendants.



20   Q.  In this case, as you're aware, an argument is being made by



21   the defense that in a joint trial where there is a capital



22   sentencing hearing, there's a greater chance of a death



23   sentence than if the trial were severed and the defendants were



24   tried separately.  Do you agree with that hypothesis?



25   A.  No, I don't.  I think that the -- the jury in this case







                                                                 202



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1   could very -- and would weigh each of the people involved here



 2   on their own circumstances based on the evidence they hear.  I



 3   think they would be -- would listen carefully to counsel and to



 4   the witnesses if they choose to testify, and I think they can



 5   make individual distinctions and determinations.  I don't know



 6   of any reason to believe that they are more apt to give both



 7   the death penalty or one the death penalty or both life than



 8   they would be if they were tried separately.



 9   Q.  Prior to your coming to court today, did you ask to look at



10   some information with respect to capital sentencing in



11   federal -- in the capital federal cases?



12   A.  Yes, I did.



13   Q.  Did you also ask to look at some information that the



14   attorney general from Oklahoma could provide with respect to



15   joint capital trials?



16   A.  Yes.  In both cases, I was curious to see if there was any



17   pattern, and so I asked your office to file -- look at the



18   joint -- joint tried capital cases in federal courts and the



19   joint tried capital cases in Oklahoma, which is where I know



20   something about jurors.  And that information was provided to



21   me.



22   Q.  And were the results -- after looking at that data, federal



23   data and the Oklahoma data, did you draw any conclusions with



24   respect to whether, in fact, there was a pattern?



25            MR. TIGAR:  Excuse me, your Honor.  I object to the







                                                                 203



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1   witness opining about a study which -- in which he didn't



 2   participate, didn't have anything to do with.  All he did was



 3   read it, and he's going to tell us about it.



 4            THE COURT:  I didn't understand it to be based on a



 5   study but simply reported data.  Is that right?



 6            MR. RYAN:  That's right.



 7            THE COURT:  Do you have --



 8            MR. RYAN:  It's just simply the cap -- results of



 9   capital cases in federal court and Oklahoma.  Do they show --



10            THE COURT:  Well, you said both federal and state, I



11   thought.



12            MR. RYAN:  Federal and Oklahoma, your Honor.



13            THE COURT:  Oh, all right.



14   BY MR. RYAN:



15   Q.  And did you see any pattern with respect to whether the



16   defendants -- it was a march to death, if you will, as the



17   defense has insisted upon in this case?



18   A.  No.  From the information furnished to me, I could not



19   discern any pattern.  There were a number of cases jointly



20   tried.  In those cases, there would be some in which both the



21   defendants got -- or two defendants, they both got death.



22   There were some in which both got life.  There were quite a



23   number in which some got the death penalty and some -- and some



24   joint defendants did not and in some, when we get life and



25   something even less than that.







                                                                 204



                           Andrew Coat - Direct



 1            Both of the federal cases that I saw, I -- my



 2   recollection is that there were, like, 15 and there were six



 3   death penalties and nine not death penalties of jointly



 4   acquired -- jointly tried defendants.  And in Oklahoma, some



 5   such to the same numbers.  And there was no pattern that I



 6   could see one way or the other.  It seemed to me it was pretty



 7   clear that jurors decided the issues based on the evidence of



 8   the case and the -- and the circumstances surrounding each



 9   defendant.



10   Q.  So in a larger scale, that information simply mirrored



11   your -- the results of the three cases that you were involved



12   with?



13   A.  Mine were split out, and I think it's sort of -- confirmed



14   what I -- I think had believed all along, that jurors can do a



15   good job if properly handled by the trial judge and properly



16   presented the -- the case properly presented to them in making



17   individual determinations.  I think that they really would try



18   to do that and they will be able to do that.



19            MR. RYAN:  Thank you, Mr. Coat.  No further questions,



20   your Honor.



