                                                                 207



                           Andrew Coat - Cross



 1   Q.  You want to see justice done, don't you, sir?



 2   A.  I do.



 3   Q.  Now, in 1976, that was an important year in the Supreme



 4   Court's decision-making in capital cases, wasn't it, sir?



 5   A.  It was, indeed.



 6   Q.  Because the court upheld a number of state statutes that



 7   had reinstituted the death penalty after Furman; correct?



 8   A.  That's correct.



 9   Q.  But, in fact, sir, the Eddings vs. Oklahoma hadn't been



10   decided by the time you left office, had it, sir?



11   A.  That's right.



12   Q.  And Eddings was the case in which the Supreme Court told us



13   some very important things about the treatment of mitigating



14   evidence and the breadth that was to be given to the defense;



15   is that right, sir?



16   A.  That's right.



17   Q.  All of your capital cases are pre-Eddings capital cases;



18   right?



19   A.  That is true.



20   Q.  Now, you said you tried approximately 14 capital cases?



21   A.  I think so.  Something like that.



22   Q.  And what was the quickest verdict you ever had in a capital



23   case?



24   A.  A matter of -- a number of hours.  Three, four, five hours.



25   Q.  What's the quickest verdict you've ever had in any case?







                                                                 208



                           Andrew Coat - Cross



 1   A.  I've had some where they hardly left the box, but -- both



 2   for and against, I might add.



 3   Q.  So certainly, under 15 or 20 minutes?



 4   A.  Yeah.  We had some very short ones, yes, sir.



 5   Q.  In other words, in the real world, it sometimes happens



 6   that verdicts are just as quick as Dr. Bronson's hypothetical



 7   verdicts; right, sir?



 8   A.  I would think so.



 9   Q.  Now, the last time you ever spoke to a juror about how they



10   dealt with the evidence in a capital case was in what year,



11   sir?



12   A.  Oh, it would have been '79 or '80.



13   Q.  So prior to Eddings against Oklahoma?



14   A.  Absolutely.



15   Q.  And prior to Penry vs. Lynaugh, obviously?



16   A.  That is so.



17   Q.  You believe, sir, don't you, that sometimes evidence can be



18   so prejudicial that even a judge's cautionary instruction is



19   not enough to keep the jurors from making improper use of it?



20   A.  I suppose there are some circumstances like that.



21   Q.  Well, in fact, sir, wouldn't you have said that the



22   deposition of Mr. Kohley in Marsee vs. United States Tobacco 



23   Company was a -- something in which it should have been



24   excluded, should be -- was properly excluded from the jury's



25   consideration?  In fact -- excuse me.  Just a minute.  Let me







                                                                 209



                           Andrew Coat - Cross



 1   finish my question.  Because the jury was likely to give it



 2   greater weight than it was due?



 3   A.  We were certainly concerned about it.



 4   Q.  Well, you got Judge Russell to say that, didn't you?



 5   A.  Yes, sir.



 6   Q.  And you got the Tenth Circuit to affirm it, didn't you,



 7   sir?



 8   A.  Absolutely.



 9   Q.  So there's one example in which jury instructions are to no



10   avail; correct?



11   A.  I wouldn't say they were to no avail.  We were successful



12   in getting the evidence excluded.  We were glad we did.  We



13   thought it should have been excluded.  I'm not certain that the



14   effect would have been with the proper precautionary



15   instruction; but you're certainly right, we did get it



16   excluded.



17   Q.  And have you ever tried a case or been involved in a case



18   in which a jury is considering a capital sentence under a jury



19   sentencing weighing statute?



20   A.  Well, ours were like that.  I mean, we had a -- an original



21   trial, a guilt phase, and then a -- then a sentencing phase in



22   which any kind of evidence would -- could come in about the



23   defendant.  So we did have those two-stage proceedings.  We had



24   it in not only capital cases but a number of other cases.  So



25   to that degree, yes.  They all were.







                                                                 210



                           Andrew Coat - Cross



 1   Q.  But again, you're talking about that period before the



 2   Supreme Court made it clear to the State of Oklahoma what was



 3   and was not the scope of a mitigating evidence; right?



 4   A.  Well, except that the fact is that our judges would let



 5   almost anything in in mitigation that the defense wanted to



 6   offer.  I mean, I don't think that anybody -- I don't recall



 7   any objections to any evidence coming in, and I don't recall



 8   any circumstances where everything, psychological workups on



 9   the person accused, family matters, that sort of thing, all



10   came into evidence, which is, I think, pretty much like what



11   you would expect to find today.



12   Q.  In the -- you said the Oklahoma statute.  Is each



13   individual juror able to decide what is and is not mitigating



14   and that becomes mitigation for that juror?



15   A.  I think that's the fact.



16   Q.  I didn't ask if it was fact.  I asked whether the statute



17   resembles the federal statute.



18   A.  It may have been a little more restrictive at that time,



19   but it was still an open question as to what mitigation was.



20   Q.  Now, in your discussion with Mr. Ryan, you were careful to



21   say some nice things about me and Mr. Jones.  Do you think that



