 4                         DIRECT EXAMINATION



 5   BY MR. MACKEY:



 6   Q.  Mr. Grant, tell the Court where you reside.



 7   A.  I live in Brighton, Colorado.



 8   Q.  And how long in Colorado?



 9   A.  I've been in Colorado since 1973.



10   Q.  Would you outline for the Court your educational



11   background.



12   A.  I grew up in the East, in Connecticut, went through schools



13   there.  Started at the University of Rochester in the mid --



14   '60s.  Decided that's not really what I wanted to do.  Joined



15   the Army.  Spent a few years in the Army, including a tour of



16   duty in Vietnam.  Came back to Connecticut.  Matriculated at



17   the University of Connecticut, graduated there in 1973 with a



18   B.A. in political science.  Graduated Phi Beta Kappa.  Came



19   from Connecticut to the University of Colorado.  Went to law



20   school at CU.  Graduated in 1976.



21   Q.  And during the past 20 years, then, have you practiced law



22   in this state?



23   A.  I have.



24   Q.  Where?



25   A.  I have -- in January of 1977, I joined the staff of the







                                                                 213



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   district attorney's office in Adams County.  Brighton is the



 2   county seat of Adams County.  Adams County is just to the north



 3   and extends to the east of Denver.  I have practiced as



 4   prosecutor since then.  Prior to that, while I was in school, I



 5   was an intern with the law firm of Leonard Chesler for all



 6   three years of my -- of my law school career and the first two



 7   months of my legal career.



 8   Q.  Have you held different positions with the Adams County



 9   district attorney's office over those some 20 years?



10   A.  I have.  I started as a deputy district attorney, worked in



11   just about every phase of the prosecution business.  As a



12   deputy, I worked traffic misdemeanor and juvenile cases.  Then



13   became a chief trial deputy in the felony division.  Became



14   assistant district attorney in 1983 and was elected as district



15   attorney for my first term in 1992.  I am up for reelection



16   this November for my second term.



17   Q.  You are currently, then, the district attorney for the 17th



18   Judicial District?



19   A.  I am, sir.



20   Q.  Mr. Grant, over those 20-some years, have you had occasion



21   to supervise, participate in, or otherwise become familiar with



22   prosecution of homicide cases in Adams County?



23   A.  I have.



24   Q.  Could you outline that experience, please.



25   A.  I think I tried my first homicide case -- it was a 1979







                                                                 214



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   case, probably tried in 1980.  Since then, I've personally



 2   tried 17 or 18 first-degree murder cases.  As a chief trial



 3   deputy, beginning in 1980 or '81, I had supervisory



 4   responsibility for those homicide cases in my division.  And



 5   then as an assistant district attorney from 1983 on and as



 6   D.A., all of the homicide trials would have been under my



 7   supervision.



 8   Q.  Since 1980, have you supervised approximately 200 homicide



 9   cases in that judicial district?



10   A.  Yeah.  That's an estimate.  Based on about -- we get



11   anywhere from 12 to 15 a year in Adams County.



12   Q.  And have you served as assigned counsel to six cases in



13   which the death penalty was declared?



14   A.  That's correct.



15   Q.  Could you tell the Court what you mean by "assigned as



16   counsel" in those cases.



17   A.  I was assigned -- generally assigned myself as lead counsel



18   in those cases with the concurrence of the district attorney at



19   that time.  Two cases were actually tried.  The other four were



20   not, for various reasons.



21   Q.  And what two capital cases or death penalty cases have you



22   tried in Adams County to death-qualified jurors?



23   A.  In 1987 I tried the case of People vs. Gary Lee Davis.  His



24   case is currently pending before the Tenth Circuit Court of



25   Appeals.  And in 1993, I tried the case of People vs. Robert 







                                                                 215



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   Harlan, which is just beginning its sojourn through the



 2   appellate courts.



 3   Q.  Each of those cases involved a single defendant at trial?



 4   A.  That's correct.  The Davis case, there were two defendants



 5   originally charged.  However, the death penalty was sought



 6   against only one of them, and they were tried separately.



 7   Q.  Do you currently hold any positions with the Colorado



 8   District Attorneys Council?



 9   A.  Yes, I do.  I've been with the District Attorneys Council



10   since 1983.  I am the president-elect of the District Attorneys



11   Council, will take office next October.  I'm also a member of



12   the legislative committee and have been for a number of years



13   and am chairman of the capital litigation committee of the



14   Colorado District Attorneys Council and have been for a number



15   of years.



16   Q.  And are you a member of the Association of Government



17   Attorneys engaged in capital litigation?



18   A.  That's correct.  That's a national association that has an



19   annual seminar somewhere in the United States.



20   Q.  Over the years, have you been invited, Mr. Grant, to



21   testify before the Colorado legislature concerning the death



22   penalty in this state?



23   A.  I have.  And I tried to count the number of times and I



24   couldn't.  It's six or seven, around that.  I've been involved



25   with legislation in the death penalty area in Colorado since







                                                                 216



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   about 1986.



 2   Q.  And similarly, have you offered the prosecution



 3   perspective, if you will, on capital litigation in this state,



 4   either to college courses or to other prosecuting bodies?



 5   A.  I have.  I speak regularly and have spoken regularly at the



 6   annual District Attorneys Council conference, which is a



 7   three-day conference held every year.  The subject generally



 8   has been involving the death penalty.  I have been on numerous



 9   panels and debates around this state at various college and



10   school functions.  I also am invited annually to give a



11   different perspective to Mr. David Lane's class at the



12   University of Denver School of Law regarding capital



13   litigation.



14   Q.  And have you made it your practice over the years to follow



15   capital litigation in the state even when your office or



16   your -- your judicial district was not involved?



17   A.  I have, particularly with my role as -- as chairman of the



18   capital litigation committee and on the legislative committee



19   of the CDAC.



20   Q.  Based on that experience as a whole, then, do you feel



21   qualified to render opinions about capital litigation in this



22   state?



23   A.  I do.



24            MR. MACKEY:  We tender the witness as so qualified.



25            MR. TIGAR:  No objection, your Honor.







                                                                 217



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1            THE COURT:  All right.  You may proceed.



 2   BY MR. MACKEY:



 3   Q.  Mr. Grant, you were in court earlier today when Mr. Wymore



 4   testified?



 5   A.  I was.  As a matter of fact, Mr. Wymore and I were



 6   classmates at the University of Colorado law school.



 7   Q.  And with that in mind, because it's the end of the day and



 8   I don't want to duplicate, could you give the Court an overview



 9   of the application the Colorado death penalty statute as it



10   existed at the time juries made that decision.



11   A.  Certainly.  In brief, your Honor, the -- the statute in



12   Colorado involves four steps and a four-step deliberation



13   process.  That's been a hallmark of the -- the statute for many



14   years.  The qualification, obviously, is that a jury has to



15   find guilt as to a class-one felony, first-degree murder,



16   before the capital stage is invoked.



17            The first step is that the jury must find beyond a



18   reasonable doubt whether at least one aggravating factor as



19   listed in the statute exists.  If they find one or more



20   aggravating factors, then they are to consider the existence of



21   mitigation.  The difference between the state statute here and



22   the federal statute is that there is no burden of proof with



23   respect to mitigation.  It's simply a burden of persuasion to



24   the extent that they find it exists or doesn't exist.  How they



25   weigh it is up to them.







                                                                 218



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1            The third stage is then to weigh the aggravation that



 2   they have found beyond a reasonable doubt against any



 3   mitigation that they are considering and make a determination



 4   as to whether or not the mitigation outweighs that aggravation.



 5            The fourth and final step is given that weighing



 6   consideration, do they believe that the death penalty is the



 7   appropriate penalty under all the circumstances of this case.



 8            THE COURT:  And is there a requirement that the



 9   mitigating factor be found out to whatever level unanimously?



10            THE WITNESS:  No, your Honor.  There is no -- no such



11   requirement.



12            THE COURT:  Okay.



13            THE WITNESS:  Each juror is allowed to consideration



14   mitigation in their own individual consideration.



15   BY MR. MACKEY:



16   Q.  In your judgment, Mr. Grant, are there any other material



17   differences between the Colorado death penalty statute again as



18   one supplied by the jury and current federal statute?



19   A.  Sure.  There -- there are -- some of the aggravators are



20   different.  Some of the mitigators are different.  There is



21   the -- both of them are similar in that it's open-ended



22   mitigation.  Anything that the court considers to be mitigation



23   is allowed in as relevant.



24            The certification upon the finding of a verdict was



25   interesting.  That is not part of the Colorado statute.







                                                                 219



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   Certification having to do with the fact that the verdict was



 2   not rendered in a racially-biased or gender-biased,



 3   religious-biased means.  I don't think that there are any other



 4   major differences, sir.



 5   Q.  Mr. Grant, in your practice, have you -- would you say that



 6   Colorado courts, trial courts routinely provide an



 7   individualized instruction to a Colorado death-qualified jury



 8   before giving that decision to them?



 9   A.  Yes.  It's -- that's been my experience.  There is not a



10   stock instruction.  In fact, the State of Colorado does not



11   have stock jury instructions with respect to the death penalty.



12   I also sit on the Criminal Jury Instructions committee.  And



13   although we have debated that for a number of years, we



14   essentially gave up because of the -- the makeup of the



15   committee was not able to agree.  And then, of course, last



16   year, the legislature took that decision from jurors.



17            But that lack of stock instruction has not really



18   affected the practice.  Colorado, the statutory scheme requires



19   that the decision be made based on the facts of the crime and



20   the individual characteristics of the defendant, character,



21   background and history, given that tendered instructions from



22   defense counsel are routinely given, individualizing that



23   decision.



24   Q.  Just to bring the record complete to present, could you



25   tell the Court what the current version of the Colorado death







                                                                 220



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   penalty statute provides?



 2   A.  As of last year, the legislature changed the statute to



 3   allow for judicial sentencing.  The statute is the same in all



 4   other respects except that a three-judge panel now will make



 5   the death penalty after a verdict of guilt is rendered on a



 6   first-degree murder charge.



 7            That panel will be chosen randomly in a -- the chief



 8   justice of the Supreme Court has set out different regions from



 9   which the judges will be chosen, and the two other judges in



10   addition to the trial judge will sit and listen to the penalty



11   phase and render a decision.  That decision, if it's to be



12   death, must be unanimous.  If one of the three judges votes for



13   life, then the sentence is life.



14   Q.  But the four steps that you identified earlier would be as



15   applicable to the three-judge panel as to the twelve-member



16   jury panel previously?



17   A.  That's correct.  I kind of envision it as a jury of three.



18   There haven't been any cases tried under that system yet.



19   Q.  Mr. Grant, prior to your testimony today, did I ask you to



20   reconstruct an accurate history of death penalty jury trials in



21   the state of Colorado?



22   A.  Yes, sir.



23   Q.  Did you endeavor to do so, you and your staff?



24   A.  Yes, I did.



25   Q.  Would you describe to the Court just briefly what steps you







                                                                 221



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   undertook to ensure its completeness.



 2   A.  Sure.  Many of the cases I was familiar with, Judge, from



 3   having talked to a number of prosecutors and being a



 4   participant for as long as I have been.  In those cases that I



 5   did not know the particular answers to the questions that



 6   Mr. Mackey asked me, I made contact, either myself or my



 7   assistant district attorney, Stephen Bernard -- made contact



 8   with the individual jurisdictions.  We also did make contact



 9   with each judicial district in the state of Colorado to



10   ascertain whether there were any other cases that we were not



11   aware of.  And that was the basis for preparing the charts.



12   Q.  Did you, in fact, compile your research into a summary



13   exhibit?



14   A.  I did.



15   Q.  Do you find one before you marked Government Exhibit No. 7?



16   A.  I do.



17   Q.  Directing your attention, Mr. Grant, to Exhibit No. 7.  Is



18   that one entitled Results of All Death Penalty Hearing Jury



19   Verdicts in Colorado by District and Trial Site?



20   A.  I have that, sir.



21   Q.  Could you tell the Judge what information is meant to be



22   captured on Exhibit No. 7.



23   A.  Your Honor, the headings kind of speak for themselves.



24   This represents all of the jury verdicts in the state of



25   Colorado from 1979, which is when the post-Furman statute was







                                                                 222



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   enacted, through 1996.  The total at the bottom is a



 2   compilation of each judicial district that has had a tried case



 3   to the death-qualified jury.  And then the second column is



 4   those who were, in fact, convicted of capital crimes,



 5   eliminating those that were convicted less than first-degree



 6   murder.  The third is the life verdicts returned, and the



 7   fourth is the death verdicts returned.



 8   Q.  Incidentally, Mr. Grant, how many counties are there in the



 9   state of Colorado?



10   A.  63, I believe.



11   Q.  How are they organized in terms of judicial districts?



12   A.  There are 22 judicial districts in the state of Colorado.



13   There are some judicial districts that are single counties.



14   The majority of them are multiple counties.



15   Q.  Based on your research and as reflected in Exhibit 7, did



16   you find that some nine or less than half of those judicial



17   districts have seated death-qualified juries in that time



18   period?



19   A.  That's correct.  From my research, this is all of the



20   judicial districts that have ever tried capital cases to a



21   death-qualified jury.



22   Q.  Between 1979 and last year?



23   A.  And 1996; correct.



24   Q.  Thank you.  For the record, what was the total number of



25   defendants tried by death-qualified juries in the state of







                                                                 223



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   Colorado during that time?



 2   A.  38.



 3   Q.  And the number of defendants who proceeded to the death



 4   penalty hearing?



 5   A.  27.



 6   Q.  And the number of life verdicts by jury?



 7   A.  19.



 8   Q.  And the number of death verdicts by jury?



 9   A.  Eight.



10   Q.  Let me turn your attention, Mr. Grant, to Government



11   Exhibit 8.  Do you have that before you?



12   A.  I do.



13   Q.  Does the information reflected on No. 8 correspond with



