22   will, about -- or some important points about those particular



23   cases.



24   Q.  You've attempted by footnote in Exhibit No. 8 to offer



25   certain material history about the particular case or more?







                                                                 224



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   A.  That's correct.



 2   Q.  In your survey, did you identify the number of cases in the



 3   Colorado modern death penalty history that had more than one



 4   defendant facing the death penalty in the same trial?



 5   A.  That's correct.



 6   Q.  And how many such cases?



 7   A.  That were actually tried together, there have only been



 8   two.



 9   Q.  And how many such cases were there where more than one



10   defendant faced an announced or declared death penalty in



11   Colorado?



12   A.  As far as I could determine, there were five.



13   Q.  What were the two cases that proceeded to trial in Colorado



14   where more than one defendant faced the death penalty?



15   A.  In 1981, Edgar Durre and James Manners were tried together



16   in Weld County.  That's in Greeley.  And in 1987, Mr. Borrego



17   and Mr. Lucero were tried together in Jefferson County.  That's



18   the case that Mr. Wymore represented Mr. Borrego.



19   Q.  And is additional information about each of those joint



20   trials set forth in Government Exhibit 6?



21   A.  That's correct.



22   Q.  Is that accurate information as it relates to those two



23   cases?



24   A.  That is.



25   Q.  What were the results in those two jointly tried cases in







                                                                 225



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   the state of Colorado?



 2   A.  All of the defendants were sentenced to life.  There is



 3   somewhat of a -- an errata with respect to Mr. Durre.  An



 4   interesting case.  And I've set forth the Colorado Supreme



 5   Court citation to that case.  Mr. Durre, when he was tried, the



 6   jury was asked to return a verdict on a verdict form that



 7   indicated that they were to say whether or not there was



 8   sufficient mitigation to outweigh aggravation and, therefore,



 9   justify a life sentence.  The jury foreman signed that verdict



10   form no.  However, when that jury verdict was rendered in



11   court, the jury foreman also passed a note to the judge that



12   said there -- there is not unanimity in the jury with respect



13   to the penalty of death.  Seven of the juror members would



14   agree with the court if the court were to sentence Mr. Durre to



15   death.  Five of the jury members would not impose the death



16   penalty.



17            The judge in that case regarding -- or disregarded



18   that note to the extent of sentencing and sentenced Mr. Durre



19   to death.  That death sentence was overturned by the Colorado



20   Supreme Court in the 1984 decision noted here.  So it's listed



21   here as a life sentence.  And in fact, since it was not a



22   unanimous death verdict under Colorado law at the time, it's



23   fairly obvious that it could not have been a death sentence



24   upheld.



25   Q.  So neither of the two Colorado juries that faced joint







                                                                 226



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   death penalty defendant trials rendered unanimous votes of



 2   death on any of the four defendants?



 3   A.  No.  They both gave life sentences, including the -- for



 4   the defendant that Mr. Wymore represented.



 5            MR. MACKEY:  Your Honor, I would move into admission



 6   Government Exhibits 6 and 7 and 8.



 7            MR. TIGAR:  No objection, your Honor.



 8            THE COURT:  They are received.



 9   BY MR. MACKEY:



10   Q.  Mr. Grant, perhaps for reasons similar to Mr. Coat's



11   description earlier, have you made it a practice over the years



12   to talk to jurors that have tried -- heard trials involving



13   death penalty cases?



14   A.  I have.  And I've been warned against it numerous times,



15   but I never heeded those warnings.  I've talked to jurors in my



16   entire prosecution practice.



17   Q.  Can you quantify for the Court what background you have



18   with regard to that practice?



19   A.  With respect to death penalty jurors, I've talked to, I



20   would say, anywhere from two dozen to 25 to 30 individual



21   jurors.  Some in groups.  Some individually.  The Gary Davis



22   jury was somewhat unique in that they had a reunion that they



23   invited me to the year after the verdict was rendered.  I spent



24   some time talking with them there and had previously.  I've



25   also talked to jurors in other jurisdictions about cases that







                                                                 227



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   were tried in other jurisdictions that were of interest to me,



 2   particularly involving changes in legislation.



 3   Q.  Without being specific at this point, have jurors in those



 4   sessions described to you in their own way, their own words,



 5   what it's been like to sit in judgment of another individual?



 6   A.  Yes.  And I've particularly asked those kinds of questions.



 7   One of the things that a district attorney does in making a



 8   decision whether to seek the death penalty is determine the



 9   likelihood of such a verdict.  I also felt it was important to



10   talk to people that had been in that situation after they



11   deliberated to make future judgments about the likelihood of



12   verdicts.



13   Q.  Mr. Grant, have you formed an opinion about the sense of



14   responsibility Colorado potential jurors carry to the task of



15   deciding life and death verdicts?



16   A.  I have.



17   Q.  Is that based at least in part on your experience of



18   interviewing those jurors?



19   A.  It is.



20   Q.  And your study of the Colorado death penalty history?



21   A.  It is.



22   Q.  And your own practice in trying those cases?



23   A.  It is.  Specifically within that last regard with respect



24   to jury:  In questioning jurors in Colorado and in the cases



25   that I've been involved with, it's an individual voir dire







                                                                 228



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   situation that has taken place over a period of many, many



 2   days.  And talking to jurors in that setting also gives you a



 3   good flavor for their degree of attentiveness.



 4   Q.  Would you tell Judge Matsch at this time, Mr. Grant, what



 5   that opinion is and the basis for it.



 6   A.  Your Honor, it's my belief and opinion that jurors in this



 7   case or in this state that I've been in contact with are



 8   extremely conscientious.  I have been impressed repeatedly by



 9   the gravity of the decision-making process that they related to



10   me.  Many of them have expressed the opinion that it's the most



11   monumental decision they have ever made, including getting



12   married, buying houses and things like that.  They have all



13   reflected a degree of focus and concentration and severity of



14   judgment that is unique, at least in my experience, with



15   respect to any kind of group dynamics.  It's -- it really



16   stands out.



17   Q.  Mr. Grant, after 20 years of serving the people of Adams



18   County, have you come to recognize more than one school of



19   thought among prosecutors about the relative tactical



20   advantages or disadvantages of multiple defendant death penalty



21   cases?



22   A.  I have.  That's fair.



23   Q.  And what are those two schools of thought as you observed



24   them?



25   A.  Well, to -- to the extent that jurors may combine thoughts







                                                                 229



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   about multiple defendants, I am of the school of thought that



 2   believes that -- that jurors do not want to impose the death



 3   penalty.  They start with an inherent bias against the death



 4   penalty which, you know, is -- is very basic, very



 5   foundational.  Killing is wrong.  That's what we believe as



 6   human beings.  They start with that bias.  They are looking for



 7   reasons not to impose that penalty as opposed to the other side



 8   where they're, you know, blood-thirsty, blood dripping off



 9   their teeth kind of folks.  That is not my view of them.



10            In that regard, the one school of thought is that a --



11   a defendant with a lesser degree of culpability, a lesser



12   degree of involvement, a more regular or more seemingly



13   appropriate upbringing, that feeling might tend to bleed over



14   into one with the opposite background.  And if death is not



15   going to impose on that lesser culpable defendant, then the



16   likelihood is it would not be imposed on the more culpable



17   defendant.



18            There is, of course, the other school of thought that



19   would go the other way.  I think the third school of thought



20   has been expressed here today as well, and that is that jurors



21   can and will make individual determinations without bleeding



22   over into each circumstance.



23   Q.  These theories and schools of thought as you've described



24   them condense in your experience to a single confidence that



25   juries that have that duty will follow the court's instructions







                                                                 230



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   and give individualized consideration to the defendants?



 2   A.  I'm convinced of that.  I -- my own experience with the



 3   Davis case underlines that for me.  In the Davis case, Gary



 4   Davis was charged and -- and we, in fact, sought the death



 5   penalty against Gary.  And his wife, Becky Davis, was charged



 6   with first-degree murder and the same basic crimes, but we did



 7   not seek the death penalty against her.



 8            She was tried first.  In her trial, of course, the



 9   defense was Gary did it all.  Gary made me do it.  She was



10   convicted, sentenced to life.  In his trial, that defense was



11   reversed.  And the -- the consideration at the penalty phase



12   was very heavily weighted against if Becky Davis didn't get the



13   death penalty, then Gary shouldn't, either.



14            In speaking with the jurors in both of those cases and



15   specifically in Gary Davis's case, they said, well, wait a



16   minute, we had to look at Gary Davis's situation and



17   circumstances separate and, in fact, did that to the degree



18   that -- that they separated out Becky's actions -- what they



19   knew about Becky's background, and her testimony was admitted



20   at his trial and Gary's actions and Gary's background.  I was



21   impressed with that.



22   Q.  Mr. Grant, did you hear earlier today Mr. Wymore's



23   testimony where he used the phrase "mitigation-impaired"?



24   A.  Yeah.  I did.



25   Q.  Could you summarize for the Judge what you understood







                                                                 231



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   Mr. Wymore to mean on that point.



 2   A.  Well, my understanding, not only from his testimony but



 3   from having tried cases against the public defenders and



 4   talking to others who have, is that their theory is that a -- a



 5   person is disqualified from juror service if they will not give



 6   appropriate weight to whatever mitigation fact they are



 7   presented.  I think he used age.  Alcohol has been used before.



 8   And the theory is we can challenge for cause -- the defense can



 9   challenge for cause a juror who says, well, okay, I'll listen



10   to your testimony about alcohol, but that's not going to make a



11   difference to me.  To my knowledge, that theory has not been



12   accepted by any appellate court in the state of Colorado.



13            Obviously, the jury selection standard is the same as



14   the federal standard, the Wainwright and Witt standard.  And



15   that has to do with their ability to -- to render a verdict in



16   accordance with the law and whether or not that ability is



17   substantially impaired.  It doesn't have to do with whether or



18   not they give any weight to a particular mitigator or a



19   particular aggravator.



20   Q.  Certainly, Mr. Grant, did you hear Mr. Stevenson testify



21   earlier in the day about the presumption of death in highly



22   publicized cases with very aggravated circumstances of crime?



23   A.  Sure.



24   Q.  And did you apply that notion against your own experience



25   here in the state of Colorado?







                                                                 232



                          Robert Grant - Direct



 1   A.  I did.  As I listened to him testify, I thought immediately



 2   of three cases that -- that would mitigate against that



 3   assertion.  One here in Denver, the James King case, which was



 4   a -- a very highly publicized case, and the tenure of the



 5   publicity was very heavily weighted against Mr. King's guilt.



 6   Mr. King was acquitted even though he killed four security



 7   guards, allegedly, during a bank holdup.



 8            Two other cases that come to mind involved the death



 9   of -- of law enforcement officers, one the Templeman case out



10   of Colorado Springs in 1984 where a state patrol officer was



11   killed, and the other, the Marvin Walker case in Adams County



12   in 1988 where a -- a police officer -- a policewoman in Aurora



13   was killed.  In both cases, both of which were highly



14   publicized, sensationalized, if you will, in the state of



15   Colorado -- in both of those cases, the jury returned verdicts



16   of first-degree murder against the defendants and rendered



17   penalty decisions for life as opposed to death.  That seems to



18   me to be fairly contrary to what was testified to earlier by



19   Mr. Stevenson.



20            MR. MACKEY:  I have nothing else, your Honor.



