                                                                 235



                           Robert Grant - Cross



 1   Q.  And you agreed with her to the extent that you did not seek



 2   a death penalty on her; is that right?



 3   A.  I did not seek the death penalty on her, but there were a



 4   lot of different reasons for that.  That being one of them.



 5   The available evidence at the time of the trial, yes, sir.



 6   Q.  And you -- as a prosecutor, you understand there's no joy



 7   in getting a death verdict, is there, sir?



 8   A.  I would agree with that.



 9   Q.  There's no joy on the part of jurors in returning one, is



10   there, sir?



11   A.  I would agree with that.



12   Q.  Your job as the prosecutor in Adams County is to get



13   verdicts that are just and then hold onto them on appeal;



14   correct?



15   A.  That's one of them, yes, sir.



16   Q.  And can you just share with us as you were thinking about;



17   are you going to stand in front of a judge in Adams County and



18   you're going to be real strong opposing Mrs. Davis's motion,



19   not so strong, were you thinking about is trying to work real



20   hard to get just one trial here worth the hassle I might face



21   on appeal?  Is that something that ran through your mind?



22   A.  I -- I suspect it probably did.  I don't latch onto that as



23   a major reason.  I suspect that's something that was a matter



24   of consideration, yes, sir.



25   Q.  Well, you believe that the death penalty is a deterrent to







                                                                 236



                           Robert Grant - Cross



 1   willful murder, do you not, sir?



 2   A.  I believe that.



 3   Q.  And its deterrent effect is seen when trials are held that



 4   command the respect of appellate courts; correct?



 5   A.  That's one facet, yes, sir.



 6   Q.  Now, you also told us, sir, that juries don't sentence



 7   anymore in Colorado; is that right?



 8   A.  That's correct under the current statute.  That -- of



 9   course, there hasn't been a case tried to the three judge panel



10   yet.



11   Q.  Now, the three judge panel, that was a Senate bill; is that



12   right?  Was that SB-54?  Have I got that wrong?



13   A.  I don't know.  It went through -- it went through both



14   houses and was signed by the Governor.  I'm not sure whether it



15   originated in the Senate or the house.



16   Q.  But you and Mr. Ritter and Mr. Suthers went up there and



17   testified for it; is that right?



18   A.  We did, yes, sir.



19   Q.  And why do you think that jurors in Colorado were not the



20   best people to be sentencing people in these capital cases?



21   A.  I don't think I'd agree with that statement, Mr. Tigar.



22   Q.  I'm sorry.  I -- I withdraw it because it assumes something



23   that I just don't know.



24            Tell us why you were in favor of Senate Bill 54 that



25   would have substituted the three-judge panel for juries.







                                                                 237



                           Robert Grant - Cross



 1   A.  There -- there were a number of reasons.  I actually was



 2   not a proponent of the change.  One of the reasons that I



 3   thought it was appropriate was consistency and I believe that



 4   was the thrust of my testimony before the legislative hearing



 5   and I think I told the legislative hearing that they should not



 6   vote for this bill in the expectation that it would increase



 7   the number of residents of Colorado's death row.  But rather,



 8   they should be impressed with the fact that judges make



 9   sentencing decisions on a regular basis and that if they were



10   seeking consistency in capital sentencing, that that would be a



11   by-product of judicial sentencing.



12   Q.  Did you have in mind any cases that had been tried in Adams



13   County, although perhaps by prosecutors from Arapahoe County,



14   that informed your judgment on that?



15   A.  I am certain that you're talking about the Allen Thomas



16   case and one of the -- one of the backgrounds to this



17   legislation had to do with our consideration of trying to pass



18   a nonunanimous verdict statute in the State of Colorado.



19   Q.  What happened in the Thomas case was that -- well, you tell



20   me.  Why didn't you get a death there?



21   A.  Actually, I was hoping to be able to try the Thomas case



22   myself and --



23   Q.  Why didn't they get a death there?



24   A.  The case was tried by the Arapahoe County district



25   attorney's office and in speaking with jurors after the case,







                                                                 238



                           Robert Grant - Cross



 1   the jury was essentially hung, 11 to 1, in favor of death with



 2   one juror who declined to participate in the deliberation



 3   process from the beginning.



 4   Q.  And you thought that that was not a good thing to have



 5   happened; correct?



 6   A.  I thought it was inappropriate that the jury felt that they



 7   could not even deliberate together as a whole but rather that



 8   one of them removed them -- themselves from the deliberation



 9   process.



10   Q.  So that's a juror who did not obey the judge's instructions



11   to deliberate; correct?



12   A.  In fact, I didn't agree with the judge's instructions,



13   either, Mr. Tigar, and the judge's instructions and comments



14   during the voir dire led the jurors to believe that they did



15   not have to deliberate.  That they did not have to take part in



16   any discussions in the jury room.  So in fact, that juror felt



17   that she was following the judge's instructions.



18   Q.  But that was just a misunderstanding then?



19   A.  I -- in my view, it was an error of law.



20   Q.  The Congress of the United States has said that with



21   respect to what is or is not a mitigating factor, each



22   individual juror is sovereign in the penalty process; isn't



23   that right?



24   A.  I haven't read those words, Mr. Tigar, but I agree with the



25   concept that jurors are allowed to give whatever weight







                                                                 239



                           Robert Grant - Cross



 1   individually they ascribe to particular mitigation.



 2   Q.  So under the law as passed by the Congress of the United



 3   States, each individual juror, as you understand it, can say I



 4   find X and Y and Z to be mitigating and I'm going to use that



 5   even if no other juror agrees that that's mitigating; is that



 6   right?



 7   A.  I believe that's correct.



 8   Q.  And if that juror holds onto that view under the statute as



 9   passed by the Congress of the United States, then that would



10   prevent unanimity with respect to death; is that correct?



11   A.  In that scenario, it would.



12   Q.  And that, of course, is the system -- that's something like



13   the system that used to exist in Colorado; correct?



14   A.  It very much is in terms of individual jurors being able to



15   give what weight they particularly ascribe to mitigation as



16   long as they participate in the deliberative process.



17   Q.  And that system that the Congress of the United States has



18   instituted does increase the risk of inconsistency as compared



19   to a system where judges alone sentence; isn't that right?



20   A.  Increase the risk of inconsistency -- I guess I'm not so



21   sure I would talk about risk of inconsistency.  I would say



22   that judges who make sentencing decisions on a daily basis are



23   more likely to be consistent in those sentencing decisions over



24   time than jurors who are recruited to make that decision once.



25   Q.  Let me put it in the context of Colorado then, sir.  The







                                                                 240



                           Robert Grant - Cross



 1   cold -- the old Colorado system that you were opposed to was



 2   more likely to create inconsistent results in death cases than



 3   the -- the new system where judges are doing it; isn't that



 4   correct?



 5   A.  Well, first of all, I was not opposed to the old Colorado



 6   system.  In fact, over my career, with due respect, I've always



 7   had more luck with jurors than with judges.  I think, again,



 8   judicial sentencing is more likely to be consistent given



 9   similar facts over time than juror sentencing.



10   Q.  And the federal courts have chosen jury sentencing;



11   correct?



12   A.  As did the Colorado courts for 100 years of its history.



13   Q.  Until you argued the legislature into changing it?



14   A.  I was one of those folks, that's true.



15            MR. TIGAR:  Nothing further.



16            MR. MACKEY:  Nothing, your Honor.  Thank you.



17            THE COURT:  You may step down, Mr. Grant.  I take it



18   he's excused.



19            MR. MACKEY:  Please, your Honor.



20            THE COURT:  You're excused.



21            THE WITNESS:  Thank you, sir.



22            MR. MACKEY:  Your Honor, we have no other witnesses.



23   We would move into admission certain other exhibits tendered to



24   the defense --



25            THE COURT:  All right.







                                                                 241







 1            MR. MACKEY:  -- I believe without objection with one



 2   exception.  Government Exhibit Number 1 being an affidavit of



 3   Ann Roberts that attaches the results of her search on federal



 4   capital sentencing set forth in Exhibits 2, 3, 4, and 5.



 5            THE COURT:  Yes.  Those being attachments 1, 2, 3, and



 6   4; right?



 7            MR. MACKEY:  Yes, your Honor.



 8            THE COURT:  And you filed this on -- yesterday?



 9            MR. MACKEY:  Yes, we did.



10            THE COURT:  Okay.



11            MR. THURSCHWELL:  No objection to those exhibits, your



12   Honor.



13            THE COURT:  All right.  They are received then as a



14   part of -- and the affidavit of Ms. Roberts.



15            MR. THURSCHWELL:  That's correct.



16            THE COURT:  All right.  Which is simply foundational



17   for the exhibits.



18            MR. MACKEY:  Precisely, your Honor.  In addition, we



19   move to admit Government Exhibit No. 9, that being a multi-page



20   declaration of Joseph Hoffman and would consent to the requests



21   of defense to supplement Mr. Hoffman's presentation with one



22   article referenced in his C.V.



23            MR. THURSCHWELL:  Your Honor, pursuant to Federal Rule



24   of Evidence 806, this article is somewhat inconsistent with



25   some of the assertions made in the affidavit itself.  It's







                                                                 242







 1   authored by the same individual.  It's admissible on that



 2   grounds.  With that objection, we would offer that.



 3            THE COURT:  So that's agreed to.



 4            MR. MACKEY:  It is, your Honor.



 5            THE COURT:  Where is the --



 6            MR. THURSCHWELL:  Your Honor, I thought we had brought



 7   it with us today.  We did not.  With the Court's indulgence, we



 8   can bring it tomorrow.  First thing tomorrow morning.



 9            THE COURT:  All right.



10            MR. MACKEY:  And in addition, and finally, your Honor,



11   offer the declaration of Dane Gillette, tendered this afternoon



12   to defense, setting forth that lawyer's research concerning the



13   results in California's death penalty cases.



14            THE COURT:  I don't think I've seen that.  Is that



15   submitted?



16            MR. TIGAR:  Shall I stand here or at the lectern?



17            THE COURT:  It'll be easier at the lectern for



18   everyone to hear.



19            MR. TIGAR:  Thank you.  Your Honor, this document was



20   faxed to the Government today and tendered to us after lunch.



21   I have -- it purports to contain research conducted on a



22   somewhat informal basis by a senior assistant attorney general.



23   I would --



24            THE COURT:  Do you want to look at it overnight?



25            MR. TIGAR:  I'd like to look at it overnight before I







                                                                 243







 1   take a position.  Maybe we can consent to it.  We'd like to



 2   look at it.



 3            THE COURT:  All right.



 4            MR. MACKEY:  I apologize for the late delay.



 5            THE COURT:  All right.  We'll take it up first thing



 6   in the morning.



 7            MR. MACKEY:  That will be all the exhibits we'd offer



 8   at this time, your Honor.



 9            THE COURT:  Any rebuttal type witnesses here?



10            MR. TIGAR:  No, your Honor.  We're -- we're quitting



11   as promised.



12            THE COURT:  All right.  Well, the evidentiary record



13   with respect to these motions then is complete.  And I propose



14   to argue -- hear argument on them first thing in the morning.



15            I don't see Mr. Kelley here.  We didn't notify him



16   that we might have 20 minutes left to consider his motion to



17   unseal.  So by the time we get him notice and get here, I think



18   it'll be 5:00, so I would propose that we recess.



19   Mr. Hartzler?



20            MR. HARTZLER:  One brief matter regarding scheduling.



21            THE COURT:  Yes.



22            MR. HARTZLER:  I understood we would hear evidence on



23   the severance motion at the conclusion of our meeting.



24   Mr. Tigar indicated that he would like to call witnesses on the



25   Nichols motion regarding the conditions of confinement.  He has







                                                                 244







 1   two witnesses that he's proposing.  It is not clear to us why



 2   those witnesses would be necessary.  One of them is the warden



 3   and the warden has plans to be out of town both tomorrow and



 4   Friday.  So I'm -- I would invite the Court to solicit from



 5   Mr. Tigar some indication as to what information we need and if



 6   truly we need testimony, then possibly reach a stipulation or



 7   something.



 8            THE COURT:  What was -- can you advise us on that?



 9            MR. TIGAR:  Yes, your Honor.  And I would like the



10   courtesy of when I'm told Government counsel witnesses would be



11   there and an objection is to be made that they are not going to



12   be here, that I be told about it beforehand.



13            MR. HARTZLER:  To that extent, I apologize, but I



14   didn't know until we contacted the witness.  So I mean, we were



15   told yesterday afternoon.  I apologize for not communicating it



16   to Mr. Tigar.  But this is obviously late notice.  These



17   motions have been on file for some time.



18            THE COURT:  Let's not go back and forth on that.  He's



19   not available.



20            MR. TIGAR:  Your Honor, in connection -- he's in



21   Aspen, your Honor.  The motion has -- their reply that they



22   filed yesterday had Warden Perrill's affidavit connected to it.



23   And Mr. May has relied upon for things that Warden Perrill



24   wants to tell the Court.  What's happening here, your Honor, is



25   that in a capital case in which prison discipline can be







                                                                 245







 1   admissible in the punishment phase of the -- of the trial -- if



 2   we ever get there -- things are being done at the prison that



 3   are, in our view, improper.  Warden Perrill says things in that



 4   affidavit that are flatly not true with respect to his



 5   involvement on Mr. Nichols' ongoing discussions with the prison



 6   about getting an adequate diet.  This is a situation in which



 7   Mr. Nichols has blown the whistle on a Government contractor



 8   who has been cheating the prison and being punished for it.  I



 9   think that Warden Perrill ought to be in here to explain this



10   because I don't think he's leveled with the Court.



11            Mr. May has also had conversations directly with



12   Mr. Nichols, has been involved in this kangaroo court



13   discipline out there and we think that he has some explaining



14   to do.  Sooner or later, Mr. May, who is the man who we have to



15   deal with every single day, your Honor, to see Mr. Nichols and



16   prepare this case, is going to have to account for somebody --



17   to somebody about the behavior.  We don't intend to harass



18   these witnesses, but we do think there are some questions that



19   they should be required to answer.



20            THE COURT:  Well, there are two things involved here,



21   then, as I understand it.  One is whether this Court should be



22   taking any action with respect to any remedy now.  The other is



23   whether the disciplinary record, if there be a disciplinary



24   record, should be admissible at some time in the penalty



25   hearing if there be one.  Those are two different --







                                                                 246







 1            MR. TIGAR:  Those are two different issues.  With



 2   respect to the Court's taking action, the only basis upon which



 3   the Government says this Court should not take action is the



 4   citation of an irrelevant portion of the Prisoner's Litigation



 5   Reform Act of 1996, which imposes administrative exhaustion



 6   requirements on civil suits not on motions made in criminal



 7   cases.  Other than that, I'm prepared to argue the -- the law.



 8   I could do it first thing in the morning to show your Honor



 9   there's a motion to be heard here.



10            THE COURT:  But I'm asking whether the warden's



11   testimony is necessary for this question of whether some



12   remedial action is appropriate.



13            MR. TIGAR:  Yes, your Honor, it is because the warden



14   has in his affidavit incorrectly characterized negotiations



15   that preceded Mr. Nichols coming to Colorado, incorrectly



16   characterized the punitive nature of the restriction of the



17   access of these two defendants to commissary rights,



18   incorrectly characterized the way in which Mr. Nichols has been



19   exercising his commissary rights, in --



20            THE COURT:  Well, you're in disagreement with his



21   declaration.



22            MR. TIGAR:  I'm sorry, your Honor.  I'm getting



23   carried away.  But those are the matters in which I'd



24   interrogate him.



25            THE COURT:  I don't know that I've read the







                                                                 247







 1   declaration.  It was filed yesterday and that -- that motion



 2   was down on my schedule later.  He's not available at all on



 3   Friday?



 4            MR. HARTZLER:  I could find out and report to the



 5   Court tomorrow morning.



 6            MR. TIGAR:  It's not a long ways to Aspen if there's



 7   no snow on the Pass, your Honor.



 8            THE COURT:  Well, find out what his schedule is and



 9   whether it's possible for him to be here Friday.



10            MR. HARTZLER:  I will.  Thank you.



11            THE COURT:  Thank you.  Back on the schedule then with



12   this additional matter of an exhibit, we'll be prepared for



13   argument on the motions at 9:00 in the morning.



14            MR. JONES:  Your Honor.



15            THE COURT:  Mr. Jones, we haven't heard from you all



16   day.



17            MR. JONES:  You were almost lucky, your Honor.  But



18   I'll be brief.  In our meetings with the Court from time to



19   time and in comments that have been made in Court, it occurs to



20   me that at some time, the Court may want to hear from counsel



21   for all parties with respect to the issues concerning the



22   composition of the jury, the amount of voir dire, whether the



23   jury will be anonymous, all those types of issues and



24   sequestered --



25            THE COURT:  Yes.







                                                                 248







 1            MR. JONES:  -- and I simply would take the opportunity



 2   to ask if the Court would think about that, about setting a



 3   schedule by which the matters would be presented to the Court



 4   in advocacy form through the appropriate written motions.



 5            THE COURT:  Well, it's not something that has escaped



 6   my attention that these things will be necessary, but I think



 7   this question of severance has an influence on those



 8   questions -- those issues.  Certainly.  But I will hear the --



 9   those matters in open court and in an adversarial procedure



10   because I'm sure there will be some disagreements.



11            All right.  9:00 in the morning.



12            (Recess at 4:44 p.m.)



